I Wanted To Like It....but...,"Here's the thing. I wanted to like the Fire Stick. I really did. I was drawn in, like everyone else, by the low price. Can't be beat. However, there are certain drawbacks.The first is that the Apps seem to be dropping off Fire TV like flies. Here are two streaming apps I enjoy: VUDU and Youtube. Sometime in the last two years Amazon stopped supporting VUDU and the app was discontinued. Last year Amazon decided not to sell Google products, so as of Jan 1 2018 there is no longer a Youtube app on Amazon Fire TV. My concern is: What app is next to go? I don't want to live with that uncertainty.Second, speed. The stick itself is very fast. However, the 1.3GhZ Quad core processor, which doesn't have enough RAM, can only handle one app at a time. So in order to switch between apps it must close the current app and reload the desired app. The low amount of RAM causes glitchy/delayed operation. For example, when it loads a screensaver there is a momentary grey screen. Sometimes system sound effects do not function consistently. Also, this causes apps and menus to run glitchy and lag from screen to screen.Third, Alexa. She just isn't very smart. I believe she is designed that way. She really only functions well with Amazon content. But it's actually easier just to use the buttons on the remote than tell Alexa to do it, takes less time. And when you tell her to do things, such as ""skip 30 seconds"" or play a specific episode, she won't always do it. Sometimes using these features will even cause the system to glitch/crash. She is very tempermental. Alexa does nothing within any of the other apps besides Amazon Prime. She can simply launch other apps, but she only does it 50% of the time. The other 50% she doesn't understand you. And you have to say the exact app name or she won't open it. For example, to open the CBS app you have to say ""Launch CBS Full Episodes and Movies"" in those exact words or Alexa will not be able to understand what you want. Suffice it to say, Alexa's voice recognition software needs a lot of work. Also, I really don't care if my Fire Stick can order a Pizza or show me movie times. There are much easier and more efficient ways to do that.Fourth, the controls in streaming apps. They are all different from app to app. One will let you seek for rewinding and fast forwarding. The other will have you scroll through a clumsy thumbnail timeline. Netflix for example. You are supposed to be able to skip forward and back ten seconds by clicking the left or right buttons. It even shows a 10 with an arrow pictograph on screen but it doesn't do it. It just shows the thumbnail timeline screen. Other apps are similar. The only app that runs, to any degree, the way it's designed is the Prime App.Fifth, LAN. The Firestick does not come with a LAN port itself. If you want a wired connection you must buy a separate LAN adapter from Amazon. They do not keep them in stock in any great quantity. So they are often out of stock. So if you need one in order to get a connection, you may be without streaming for quite some time. As long as a month. Also, the adapter is only capable of 100Mbps speed. So if you have a decent internet service, mine is Gigabit (1000mbps) you are essentially throttling your connection speed on the Fire Stick by using the LAN adapter. You might as well go with shaky WiFi if it's faster. With 100mbps you'll probably experience Picture Quality drops anyway.Sixth, the Alexa remote constantly freezes. You have to unplug and replug the stick to reset the remotes connection. That is just unacceptable.One last note, this is the third Fire Stick I've purchased since December 2017. The first two were from Target and both went back. The first one stopped working after about a month. The second stick never worked. The third stick I bought directly from Amazon, at their suggestion. It was touch and go the entire time. I ultimately decided to return that one too. A warning: if you have a power outage or if the signal isn't perfect 100% of the time (impossible), your Fire Stick will have panic attack. The remote will become temporarily slower and less responsive (menus and buttons respond slower) and will eventually resolve itself. The WiFi connection will get slower and weaker. Nothing resolves this (resetting your router, restarting the Stick), you just have to wait it out. And if you had it connected to 5G WiFi, forget it. The Fire Stick seems to be allergic to staying connected to that, especially if there is a power interruption. My guess is a weak/underpowered WiFi antenna in the Stick. Also, everything I've read says that placing a Wifi device behind a tv, which is what you have to do to connect the Stick, will muffle the Wifi signal, combined with the weak Wifi antenna makes it have an unreliable signal most of the time. It will lose the connection, or it will drop to a very weak connection at random. I have an excellent WiFi connection. None of my other devices have this problem. A power loss can also cause the remote to stop working. So get ready to have to talk to tech support over something that should be a simple fix but isn't. And then possibly have to exchange your Stick for a replacement, that is if the short 30-day return policy hasn't expired. So you better hope you don't have any issues with it after one month. Most companies guarantee their devices for 90 days and have a One-Year Warranty.Like I said, I really wanted to like this product. Just too many drawbacks. I ended up shelling out the extra money and getting the latest generation of Apple TV. It is well worth the extra cash. The picture quality is much better. The general quality of the apps is better. The Wifi is much stronger. The remote is nowhere near as primitive as Amazons, in both design and functionality. The device itself functions much quicker and much more smoothly. Siri CAN do voice search and voice commands in every app. She also understands a lot more, and you can be far less precise and she knows what you want. Also the streaming apps all have the same uniform interface/controls and function the same. You can switch seamlessly between apps you've been using without it having to reboot them. Cuts down on time. No, The ATV can't order pizza for you or check showtimes at the movies...oh well...",1,0,positive,0.4852909445762634,0.4852909445762634,0.3425074517726898,0.17220160365104675,0.3131,5,6299,0,1
Amazon customer service agents not following thru with promises,"This rating goes for Amazon Customer Service – 1-star. The Fire-Stick with Alexa would get at least 4-stars if not for the 6 Amazon customer service agents I had to deal with for over couple hours on customer help-chat-line.The problem began when I decided to try Amazon Music and cancel the other music service I have been using. I already ordered the Fire-Stick which came with 90 days free Amazon Music Unlimited which was a bonus.No problem installing Fire-Stick on my TV except Amazon Music program would not load. So, I had a chat with a customer service agent whom told me that it would not work on Sony. This TV is 2017 model so technology is up to per. Such a disappointment it was to be told that they are not comparable.Next step was downloading the music app on iPhone which was easy enough. But then music app used up over 2.5GB on cell with music download which caused problem due to using too much memory. I had to use my laptop to download all the music instead of cell to resolve the problem.Couple days into this music thing, the Music app all of sudden appeared on my TV screen. Excited when it began playing My Playlist talking into Alexa. The next day, switched my car radio to iPhone music app and it began playing nicely.The old music service I had would loose signal while driving under tall trees that are plenty in this region. Now music keeps playing unless navigator talks. I like that.Then annoying thing started to happen – every time I switch devices, from iPhone to TV or vice visa, or laptop searching for new songs, Amazon Music prompts me saying that “Another device is in use. You have been subscribed to Individual plan. If you want to stream music on more than one device at one time you need to subscribe for Family music plan.” appears on screen even though only one device is in use.It got so annoying that I got on customer service online-chat again to complain that their system thinks I got more than one device going but I do not or have not had more than one device playing at same time and better not find extra charges on my account.Wished now that I DID NOT get on that chat-line. Wasted couple hours for one, two, I was transferred to 4 different agents, and, one of the agents did something during this time and disabled Alexa voice command.I know this happened because I had to log back in to reactivate Alexa/Fire-Stick on my TV while on chat. Once logged back in Alexa program, only buttons worked, not voice commend. Is this device broken? I doubt it. Whatever one of the agents did, somehow disabled voice part. Why? How?This is what should have happened due to this new problem:Rahul Kumar: Okay.I will go ahead and create the Free replacement for the alexa voice remote and send the Information on your email address for youIs there anything else I can assist you with today?Do you think I got new replacement device? No. Instead I got credit for my old unit without replacement. I AM STILL WAITING for new unit. I didn’t want credit, I want what Amazon agent did to my unit replaced as promised, not paying increased $15 extra dollars for the same unit.The 1st agent Archak, 2nd agent Vincenzio, 3rd agent Vijay, 4th agent Selva, on this chat, another agent about Sony TV not comparable, and yet another agent I talked with whom promised me that I will not be charged for Unlimited saying that my account indicating 90days free trial activated so not to worry about extra charge also proven wrong since I was charged already.Do you know Amazon Chat cannot be saved like other companies chat-line do when you end the chat? Well, I saved our chat so I know what was discussed and what was promised.Still waiting the $10 I was promised for my trouble. Still wanting for new replacement unit, Still waiting for charge placed on my account dropped, an error during 90days free trial which should last until mid-March.The last agent on chat stated that my Alexa device is no longer on my account. That was before credit appeared on my account a day later. So, if I play music, are they going to charge me adding more errors on their action? It is a huge mess that they created only because I wanted them to be aware that their system is not working correctly and their customer, me, is annoyed with repeat warning, upon false indication their system telling me that I am on more than one device when I am not. Also a chance that extra charges may appear due to their incorrect detection system, a charge for Family Plan.Ship me replacement unit ASAP as promised!___________________________________________________________Update: Jan 28, 2019Still no sign of replacement unit nor any type of communication from Amazon Customer Service.Should I post the chat-room conversation again? A REPLACEMENT UNIT WAS PROMISED which I have not received yet. I DID NOT ask for refund nor agreed to.So you have a very upset Amazon Prime customer! Dare you charge me back the refund for the unit that was some how DISABLED/DAMAGED by YOUR AGENT.You will not get rid of me until you honor what you promised.__________________________________________________________",1,1,neutral,0.5430134534835815,0.3552590310573578,0.5430134534835815,0.10172748565673828,0.2535,2,5101,0,0
"If you don't mind giving up privacy, go for it! Silk Browser killed Fire TV for me","Be prepared to give up privacy. I'm so sad to give this previously 5-star item a 1-star review, but SILK browser is a major privacy and security hole. I tried on 4 different occasions to work with Amazon customer service (various transfers and departments) to no avail. So here's my 1-star justification, with plenty of detail so you have enough information to make an informed decision.I own 4 Fire sticks, my first acquired in 2015 and they are used A LOT. There have been many changes in programming, what's accessible and what is not, but we have been happy with their functionality overall. THEN, Amazon made the Silk browser available for installation. I installed it and played with it a little. Using Silk, went to Amazon.com and discovered that, BY DEFAULT, I am logged in to my account! I delved further and, yes, I could see every purchase i ever made, going back to 1999. I could buy anything I want from this browser window. In other words, anyone who has access to your Fire TV stick can access every bit of your personal Amazon information. Anyone can unplug the stick from one of my 4 TVs and walk out of the house with it. And plug it in where they want, and access my information.I logged myself OUT of Silk. I exited the App, went back into it and, yes, I was still logged out. Whew!I went to another Fire TV stick in my house and repeated the actions. Installed, by default each was logged into my account. I logged out of each. So far so good. Until the App needs to update. Then, after said update, I was involuntarily logged in again BY DEFAULT to my personal Amazon account on each Silk browser. Arrgghh!!I contemplated this for a couple days and decided that it was completely unacceptable to me and decided to contact Amazon Fire Customer Service. Here is the final advice I was given the first time I advised Amazon of this (and I had contact w more than one person): &#34;I would like to bring this to your kind notice that, at present we do not have an option to hide/restrict the purchases made on any account. I'm sorry for the disappointment caused in this regard. I would request you to understand my limitations regarding this issue. However, as an alternative, I request you to please create a new account for your family members/self, only for the restricted content, so that, others will not be able to view your purchased content. You can access your purchased content this way and once done, sign out of the account from Fire Stick. Once you logout from the account on any device, no one will have access to your account.&#34;So, a completely unacceptable and inconvenient solution, created by a design flaw. IF I create a new, independent account, how do I use the paid Apps currently associated w my main account? How many hours do i get to spend installing all the free apps associated w the account which was just logged out? How do I access the purchased media on the other account? Hmmm.... no solution for that!After a week, I made another attempt. Again, contact with more than one person. This time I was told to set up the 5-digit parent control password protection to limit access/usage to Silk. Can I block access to opening Silk? Yes, but not without blocking access to opening every other App. I can create password requirements to install and open Apps (and was advised to do that by one customer service rep), but once that is done it is needed to install and use ANY App, thus rendering the Fire TV stick useless for anyone else in the house. When I told them that, the rep said: &#34;I apologize for any inconvenience this may have caused. I've forwarded this issue to my internal team with high priority.&#34; And I am sure she did. But I haven't heard from anyone.I have been an Amazon customer since 1999, that's 19 years of buying. I've had Prime since there's been Prime. I'm not changing my Prime settings because of this (I have my shared settings the way I like them, and it will change our usage of my account). Amazon needs to fix this. There is ZERO reason that Silk needs to be logged into anyone's personal Amazon account on default. There is ZERO reason that I should concern myself with privacy issues that didn't exist a few months ago.Everyone has different circumstances- if you live by yourself or share your single Amazon account with a group of people, this may not bother you. But if you have Fire sticks installed on TVs in rooms where house guests stay, if you have kids or kids' friends that are over, if you have made any purchase in 20 years you don't necessarily want just anyone to see, then this may be a problem for you. For myself, I can say this- it needs to be fixed or all of these sticks are coming off my Tvs. And I'm not happy about that either.",1,2,negative,0.7536820769309998,0.023813968524336815,0.22250398993492126,0.7536820769309998,-0.7299,2,4740,1,0
"Time consuming, stressful, and disappointing","This is an update to my original review below. Still haven’t been able to link Fire Stick to Alexa, once I installed the Fire Stick, Alexa who had been accessing my Prime Music Library, stopped? After four wasted calls today, including a very nice but useless guy in Costa Rica; who admitted after reviewing his instructions, that there is no Fire Stick App under Alexa Settings Apps?? Additionally the 3rd Amazon Rep, Stateside, was rude, demeaning, condescending, completely childish and unprofessional, thus the transfer to a Supervisor. More than 2 hrs to get the Alexa running, numerous attempts to get help from Amazon including 45 min/four reps today, and still no connection between the two devices. Oh, according The the condescending Amazon Rep #3 today, “They ARE different devices, they aren’t supposed to link up”, well, so much for all their advertising, and the Alexa menu on my Furestick screen. All these adds showing Alexa as all able and Firestick connecting you to all your Prime viewing... 6 months later all Alexa does is tell me weather and run a kitchen timer. I purchased 20 Seasons of a series, do u think I can access them in my Fire Stick, not Seasons 1-6, but 7-10 I can, I guess that’s Amazon products and Service in 2017. Oh and I get admonished for writing a “mean” review that they wouldn’t print. Will someone tell me when the truth about BAD BAD Service became mean??Original Review: purchased the Fire TV Stick with ALEXA voice remote from Amazon. It arrived in good condition promptly with all items present. Additionally, I ordered Gen 1 Echo, NEW, from an Amazon partner. It too arrived with everything present, in good condition and in a moderate time period. To get the best use out of the Firestick, the Echo should be fully &#34;adjusted&#34; using the menu on the app. The app cannot be downloaded on your laptop? If you have been on the phone with Amazon a great deal, you will be unable to use the app until your phone recharges.. The Firestick is used on a separate TV input accessed either thru voice command, or remote.The Echo would not configure following the instructions. I contacted Amazon and was helped by Brian who was terrific, and the only person who appeared aware and genuinely apologetic for the time that was involved. The process to get to the point where I could download the Amazon Alexa App, not set it up it is still not set up, was incredibly long. There was a system code that was missing that was not allowing the unit to appear as belonging to me, or assigned to me. That had to be corrected. Then the two speeds on our modem(4.2 MHz and 5MHz) had to be separated this required calls to the Internet provider, then to the Modem Provider as we own our own modem. In then end I was on the phone with Brian from 8:30 am till11:30 pm on October 1, 2017. After all that Alexa's menu settings remain undone. My Echo purchase from the third party came with three additional items, to attempt to resolve Brian transferred me within Amazon. Long story short I was kept on the phone another three hours on Monday, and then one of the same Amazon Reps called again Tuesday. On Tuesday nothing was accomplished except that another several hours were wasted. The Amazon Rep who initiated the final three way call with me actually disengaged her own call without any word to me. I found this to be surprising conduct. At present I am unable to access that second input using my remote, which I was able prior to these Amazon devices, and neither Amazon device works as advertised, and the last &#34;perk&#34; remains in limbo. When I wrote a more passionate review it was disqualified. This time I simply stated the facts. A purchase of technology greatly hyped by Amazon; made by me to make my life easier as my health deteriorates due to Systemic Lupus has in fact taken a great deal of my time and been stressful and disappointing. To mention that the Amazon rep who made me join her on the multitude of phone calls for two days, disconnected without a word is not mean or insulting (except that it was insulting to me) it is a statement of exactly what occurred and the level of service I received. I fully expect this review to be posted in it's accurate form.",1,3,negative,0.7649387717247009,0.014241847209632397,0.22081942856311798,0.7649387717247009,-0.7507,2,4223,1,0
Fire TV Stick with Alexa leaves much to be desired!,"My Roku device was getting extremely hot on the living room TV and the sound was terrible, so I moved it to the bedroom (where it is no longer hot and the sound is fabulous - so it must be the TV). However, in moving it, I now wanted a device on the living room TV, and since this was a Prime Day special, I purchased the Amazon Fire stick with Alexa. I had read the reviews and talked with a few people, and thought I was making a great choice. Personally, I will stick to the ROKU - far and away a better device! And Alexa is an idiot. I'll keep this because I want a device on the TV in that room and the price was excellent, and it is OK. I've watched the &#34;how to&#34; a few times to see if I can get rid of any of my cons. Nope. Still was not helpful.PROS - if you are a fan of FIRE and Alexa, you will like this. It came in a fancy-schmancy box with an extender, etc. (BTW _ the extender thing is FABULOUS!), It is easy to stick in. It plays a &#34;how to&#34; thing (that I found to be lacking, but ok). It looks nice. The back and the batteries are not going to be easily lost or loosed.CONS - it took me 15 minutes (literally) to prize the back open using a knifeblade to put the batteries in! I have since tried it three other times, hoping to &#34;loosen&#34; the back or figure out how to open it easily, and it still takes 15 minutes! You get to enjoy (sic) commercials that will NOT go away! The Home is awful - you can't find anything. You have no idea you are going to pay for something until you hit play and then surprise! The menu is worse than awful. The options are not options; they are settings and the settings are very limited. Alexa will not go to the show that I previously watched nor can she find the free version in Prime Video of anything that I want to watch, only the pay for it one; the menu doesn't allow you to search and type in a name, or go back to the show you were watching, either! In fact, I have yet to find a spot that allows you to type in something and actually search. Holding the microphone button while you speak (and hope Alexa will get it), takes as much or more time than typing in the show or picking the show on the ROKU device. My fumble fingers consistently hit the home button (which is NOT in a good location on the stick) instead of the pause or back or forward button when trying to control what I'm watching which sends it back to &#34;home&#34; where you can't find anything and Alexa does not understand &#34;go back to the show I was watching!&#34; I will stick with ROKU. Much better layout, a far and away better HOME and menu - more &#34;intuitive&#34;. Unless you are an expert with Alexa, I wouldn't use this stick. It does what it was made to do; however, it is not something I would recommend and is not as easy to use as the Roku.***UPDATE AS OF 8/13/18 - dropped one more star. Purchased on Prime Day July 17th. Began using it on July 20th (?). Used it maybe once or twice that week. But let's just say, I used it ONCE per day, every day beginning July 20th (maybe). The included &#34;new&#34; batteries died - yes - died (used a tester on it as well) August 6th, and I had to put new batteries in it. Seriously - the batteries lasted less than 2 weeks?!! I had told the Amazon customer service guy who called me (and was very nice and needed to know more about the technical issues) that when the batteries failed, I might throw it away simply because it didn't work like it should and getting the back off was far too frustrating and difficult. Well - after some colorful metaphors, I found a way to get the back off in less than 15 minutes and I put new batteries in it. It seems to be working a bit better; however, if these brand name batteries fail in 2 wks, I will know there is some major issue with the stick. It still cannot search for items, Alexa still doesn't get it right - however, the last video I watched is (for the most part) now showing in the line up at the correct spot, and the closed caption option is great.",1,4,neutral,0.3825216293334961,0.2877863049507141,0.3825216293334961,0.3296920657157898,-0.0419,5,4010,0,0
Amazon Pin Scam --- if you have children read so you dont get screwed,"I loved the Fire Sticks for the six months I had them. However they should come with a big warning if you have children. Although my master account, my phone's, and my apps on my PS3, PS4, Smart TV, Blu-ray players, or any other device require a pin in order to order a video the fire-stick does not. In fact Amazon supposedly cannot figure out how to transfer that feature. They can however transfer all your personal information and make that feature work on everything except the fire stick. So here I am for 6 months thinking there's no harm in letting my children control what they're watching. Fortunately for me it was not too bad but I saw a weird purchase yesterday and looked into it further.Amazon does not keep the video purchases in the same spot as all the others so you have to do some research to realize your accidentally ordering things. I found out I was ordering HBO for 6 months. My young children had apparently watch something on HBO and that authorized me to be charged 14.99 for 6 months.First I complain on chat and they basically told me this is all my fault because I should have set my pin when I got the fire sticks. That yes it transfers to all devices but not to a fire stick. They were willing to reimburse me the month I didn't use of July so far and the movie I accidentally ordered using Alexa. I told him it wasn't good enough and they basically said well if you don't have any more questions then have a nice day.So I sent an email. Explain the situation. Complain about the fact that I'm being treated like this is my fault when they have the ability to transfer all my personal information and passwords but apparently can't transfer a pin. Seems convenient for them doesn't it. Anyway, in the end a bunch of emails end up with the same thing that it's been happening so far. Then they have the nerve to ask me how they did in a survey. When I rate them terrible they ask if they can call me to discuss. So I say yes. I explained it to the first person who tells me don't worry we'll get this refunded to you. Sounds great I'm about to get my six months of fraudulent charges by Amazon back. Nope. Transferred again then again and finally given only two months because they can't do more than that for me. It's not like the $50 will break the bank but it's a dirty trade practice that anyone would children should be aware of. Even if you have locked all your apps and accounts and haven't had to do it individually you must lock each fire stick individually. All of your settings except this will transfer. Seems convenient for Amazon huh. Just seems like a shady method of making more money. Well they lost here.I was about to buy an echo. Cancelled that. I was about to buy an echo for my brother for his birthday. Cancelled that. It would be very irresponsible for me to send a gift to my brother who has three young children that apparently they can just order anything they want with Amazon related products because they have no filter. Apparently they can only transfer your PIN requirements apps or phones. So I had to cancel out of the worry that my children can talk to Alexa and order something. Especially since Amazon device as have no protection that sets itself up like it does on all their other apps. I Was about to renew audible but don't want to get nailed there too now that they took my money for no reason. And this is left a very bad taste in my mouth. I've had Amazon a long time and use it a lot more than most people I know. Buyer beware. If you do buy this make sure to set your settings right away if you have children.",1,5,positive,0.7043552398681641,0.7043552398681641,0.2325415015220642,0.06310328841209412,0.6413,2,3587,0,1
"JUNK two of my three sticks have went bad , one more on the way out","This is JUNK. I have a brand new $900 yamaha RXA870BL receiver and I thought it was bad but it's been two of these junk sticks crashing it all along. 2 of three of my sticks are now bad, won't even start and the other one is going bad.Wait there is more: I jsut ought a USED gen 1 Fire TV box on Ebay and it is working fine. there is no white specs in the pictures, it looks a lot better, it has a quad core 1.7 Ghz processor and it baffles me how Amazon is claiming less is more. The sticks are down to like 1.3 ghz quad cores but they're supposed to be faster? And NONE of them are 64 bit .They are 32 bit, which I have to say IS SO 1990s it's (Amazon) freaking pathetic.I actually ordered another stereo because it was cutting off while I was trying to watch TV from the antenna or the Fire Sticks. it has not cut off all morning now with my gen2 sticks removed from the system! the bluetooth for other devices nor the mirroring EVER worked on either stick, the remotes become discombobulated and won't repair without resetting them and There is no useful information on the amazon site to address ANy of the plethora of issues this junk causes in an entertainment system, Oh they start of fine, but keep running them awhile and you'll see what i mean. I can't believe Amazon sells this junk and put's it's name brand at stake.Two, about a year old started not working on their own power supplies. First they stopped working on other brand power supplies, Then finally had to connect both to their respective TV USB ports for power to get them to work. I had tried every Amazon power supply in my house with them, every cable and none would power them adequately until I connected them to the TVs. Now one stopped working at all connected to even the tv USB. The third I bought in the middle of last year and set up for a friend and put it back in the box for her to take to Egypt with her. I gave it to her last xmas and this week it quit, same issue, not even a start up screen no matter what she does or where she plugs it inObviously amazon is selling junk. supposedly they are supposed to replace them even thought hey are out of the paltry replacement window of like 60 days. I suspect that is so they don't have to face lawsuits and make amends for selling millions of pieces of junk or a mass recall of this garbage product, that didn't even work correctly out of the packages (read below)original review: Everything works as advertised EXCEPT the screen Mirroring and the Bluetooth tethering of anything but it's own remote. Blue tooth and the supposed mirror casting of phone screens do not work at all, even with other AMAZON devices. I tried doing both with my android phones and they won't connect, and even if they did, all i could do is mirror my phone contents because direct WiFi takes over the connection so I cannot browse the internet with my phone. So it's hardly worth the trouble to me even if it did work.And this stick simply WILL NOT Bluetooth tether to ANY of my devices including my NEW FIRE TABLET and my two MotorolaAndroid phones. & i know the issue is with the Fire sticks because all of these devices will tether to each other!Well I was made a liar, SORT OF. I have been able to mirror my [phone screen easily to the tv through the Fire Stick BY USING THE feature from within YOU TUBE! , which to me is a DISGRACE and AMAZON should be ashamed!I mean it's been making this thing for how long and it still refuses to network with other devices including OTHER AMAZON devices!!!??? WTFudge?",1,6,negative,0.7804900407791138,0.04551302269101143,0.1739969402551651,0.7804900407791138,-0.735,7,3524,1,0
Great for six weeks...now I'm throwing them out,"We received a couple of these as a Christmas gift, but didn't start using them until we moved in April. At first we loved them. Our cable bill was cut in half and we were able to access all of our favorite channels with Hulu live TV, plus all of the Prime content, and a few other apps. Then, after about six weeks, things stopped working. We had the most trouble accessing Hulu, so we contacted their support team and they told us Amazon had done an update to their software and now several Hulu customers were having trouble connecting. They said they were working on a patch and credited us for a month while they it got worked out. We looked online and learned that this was a common problem. We decided to stick it out because we had been SO happy with it up to that point, and I come from the tech industry, so I know these things sometimes do happen with updates, but I felt that a bug fix would get it taken care of pretty quickly.By the time we got to the end of our one month credit, we were able to access Hulu, but not without trying 2-3 times each time we tried to launch the app, and when it finally did open it would only partially load (we could see the text of the menu, but not images). We also often experienced a connection failure while we were watching something.Since we were having trouble with Hulu, we began trying the other apps more, and we noticed that our other apps were having just as much trouble. We even had trouble accessing Prime content.When watching Prime content, we would sometimes get an error stating that our internet speed did not support streaming, even though we have the fastest speed available, and we live in the L.A. area, so it's not like we're using countryside infrastructure. That made us think we were being throttled but our ISP, but speed tests never showed this and their customer service assured me that there was no throttling with the service package we had purchased (if you can trust ISPs).We kept troubleshooting and the kicker came when we had successfully logged into Hulu on the Fire Stick one morning (after two attempts), and we were trying to watch a show. While the status bar was going across on the TV, waiting for the show to start, my husband was able to search for and download the Hulu app on his phone, log into our account, set his mobile app preferences, then launch the show and start watching it, all before the Fire Stick even started playing the program. Both devices were using the same internet at the same time. The Fire Stick action had been started first and we did not even pick up the phone until after the Fire Stick had already been showing us the status bar for a couple of minutes.The next day we bought a Roku stick for one TV, and we cannot believe how much easier life has gotten on that TV. We turn it on and it works. The menus automatically load, right away, WITH all of the images. We hit the Hulu button and the app launches within seconds. We have zero delay in anything. And the Roku remote also turns the TV on and off, plus controls the volume, so we don't have to fumble with two remotes. The Fire Stick issues have still not been resolved, so we just ordered another Roku stick for the bedroom today.I love Amazon and I was excited to get my Fire Sticks, but after only three months of using them, I guess I am going to throw them in a box. I can't even give them to anyone knowing all of the problems they have. I feel guilty having asked my mother-in-law to buy us these for Christmas. She wasted her money.",1,7,positive,0.8208658695220947,0.8208658695220947,0.16297169029712677,0.01616246998310089,0.8047,7,3519,0,1
High hopes dashed,"I've been using an old Roku for many years and wanted to upgrade to a new device to get better performance and better features. After reading about the Amazon Fire TV Stick, especially the voice integration with Alexa, I was excited about it and was looking forward to using it.Unfortunately to my unpleasant surprise I discovered three issues shortly after setting up Amazon Fire that have caused me to decide to return it and get a newer Roku instead:1. Google Play app/channel is not in the Amazon Fire TV store. We have purchased many movies on Google Play, which I can easily watch on our old Roku since it has a Google Play app/channel but Amazon Fire TV does not have it. I searched online and there is some convoluted way to hack the Amazon Fire TV to get Google Play on it. I realize that it's Google that's to blame for not making an app/channel on for the Amazon Fire because they don't want to support their competition and would rather people get Google Chromecast instead. But as a consumer convenience is king, and I prefer to just plug and play, which I can do with Google Play on Roku, instead of having to hack together a solution. If this were the only issue I had with the Amazon Fire TV Stick then I would just do the hack and live with it instead of going through the hassle of returning it.The other two issues are particular to the MLB.tv app/channel, which is the one I watch and care about the most:2. Audio overlay - With Roku you can watch each MLB game's TV feed but choose to overlay the radio feed or sounds from within the ballpark in place of listening to the TV announcers. Whenever I watch my favorite team (Cleveland Indians) play I listen to the radio feed since their radio announcer, Tom Hamilton, is the best broadcaster in baseball on TV or radio IMHO. With Amazon Fire I can only listen to the radio feed without watching the game or watch the game and listen only to the TV announcers. This is a deal breaker for me.3. Inning chapters - With Roku when you watch a MLB game that is in progress or over you have the ability to select the top or bottom of any inning that has been played and start watching the game at that point. This feature is very useful, and I use it all the time. For instance, if I see from the box score that my team has scored in the top of the 3rd and 5th innings then I can go directly to each of those half innings and watch them to see how they scored their runs. Or when I want to re-live the catch of the year by Austin Jackson then I can go to Cleveland's game against the Boston on 8/1/17 and click on the Bottom of the 5th Inning. With the Amazon Fire you have to fast forward or rewind to the particular inning, which it does shows on the bar when each half inning approximately begins, but it takes longer to get there and also is more difficult to start precisely when the half inning begins without including any of the commercial break time. The inning chapters in Roku is just so much easier to navigate.I'm sure there are other issues I would find if I continued to use the Amazon Fire TV Stick but after running into these three right off the bat I decided not to waste any more time on it. Since the newer Roku devices do not have any of these three issues I will be returning the Amazon Fire and getting a newer Roku instead.",1,8,positive,0.8863462805747986,0.8863462805747986,0.10251515358686447,0.01113860309123993,0.8752,5,3310,0,1
If I could leave 0 stars I would,"Works good when it works.... but mine had constant problems and finally died just after the warranty period. No kind of compensation was offered. Customer service stinks - they tell you they will call and will only call you if you harrass them.Here's a transcript of the chat:Me: Previous issue has not been resolved case ID: 0168769113You are now connected to Shruthi Sai from Amazon.comShruthi Sai: Hello, my name is Shruthi Sai. I'm here to help you today.I'm sorry to know about that. Allow me 2 minutes while i check with this for you.Working on this for you.Thank you for staying connectedI'm sorry to know about the issue. May I know have you tried de registering the device please?Me: i cannot get past the initial amazon logo. I presume the device is not bootingNo i did not deregisterShruthi Sai: Okay. As a part of troubleshooting would that be fine if i go ahead and de register the device and register it back for you?I don't mean to rush. I hope we are still connected?Me: yes still connected. I have deregistered. How do i re-register?Shruthi Sai: I have gone ahead and registered it back for you and now i request you to unplug the device and plug back after 30 seconds and try accessing the device and do let me know if you still face the issues.Me: ok unpluggedThe amazon logo comes up .....and that's it, no change after 30+ secondsShruthi Sai: Okay. Checking with this for you.Allow me 2 minutes.Thank you for staying connected,I have checked with the details of the ticket and the device and can see that as the warrenty has been expired, In this case we cannot go ahead and replace this for you but can go ahead and add the promo value for the order. Would that be fine for you?Me: When did the warranty expire?Shruthi Sai: The Warrenty has been expired on Expired on : Sat 05 Aug, 2017I don't mean to rush. I hope we are still connected?Me: I have gone through my emails and found a previous issue with this device - Mon, Jun 11, 2018 07:46 PM I recieved email regarding this deviceShruthi Sai: In this case would that be fine if i go ahead and arrange a cal back from our end for you for better understading?Me: okShruthi Sai: Thank you. Can I have your mobile number please?Me: yesShruthi Sai: Can I get the number please so hat i can go ahead and connect you now.Me: 9089173120Shruthi Sai: Thanks for the details and your call is now connected and our agent will help you further.I don't mean to rush. I hope we are still connected?Is there anything else I can help you with?Me: on phoneShruthi Sai: Is there anything else I can help you with Max?I don't mean to rush you, but we've been idle for 1 minute. I want to make sure our chat's still connected. If you aren't able to respond in 1 minute, this chat will close.Since we've been idle for 3 minutes, I'll need to disconnect this chat. We hope to see you again soon! Thank you for contacting Amazon. Have a nice day!Shruthi Sai from Amazon.com has left the conversation.",1,9,negative,0.7920944094657898,0.024936409667134285,0.1829691082239151,0.7920944094657898,-0.7672,2,2951,1,0
Hardware OK - Interface the worst on the market.,"The hardware side of things is acceptable. The software side of things however makes this streamer one of the worst devices for watching Amazon's Video service. How could that be you ask? Well let me tell you about it.We have been cord-cutters for years now. We started with the very first Roku device and Netflix on it's release date. Then came several generations of Roku Players and many, many purchases of content from Amazon Video. This was before Amazon's Prime service so you either rented or purchased every TV episode or movie you wanted to stream in. During this time we also purchased our first Apple devices, iPads and iPhones and eventually an Apple TV. We purchased a small bit of content from Apple but made the decision to go all in on Amazon Video with the release of Prime Video.So fast forward a few years and we now have two Fire TV units and four Fire Stick units and a massive amount of purchased content to watch in addition to Prime Video content. So what could be the problem? Well for one thing Amazon's own devices have the worst interface for viewing purchased Amazon content of any device out there. The Apple devices all let you sort your content into TV and Movies. Amazon Fire devices, nope not there at all. Amazon website, hey you can sort your video library all kinds of ways. TV or Movies, A - Z, Z- A and most resent to oldest. Amazon Fire devices, no they can't sort at all. Just one long ribbon of icons in the your video section that mixes TV and Movies together and maxes out at around a thousand items. Suckiest way to display content every developed by anyone in the history of UI design. If you choose to scroll from one end of the list to the other end it will take you what seems like forever and makes you want to puke watching all the icons go by but eventually you get to the end only to find that one thousand items cuts off most of your Video Library because a TV series with fourteen seasons gets fourteen icons on the list, one for each season.So the only way to get to all your content is to go to the Amazon website and add content that doesn't make it to the fire device UI to your watch list. We add all movie purchases to the watch list and leave all TV content in the Your Video Library list for now on Amazon devices witch is a really stupid way of having to do things to get to your PAID content.My family prefers to watch our Amazon video content, purchased or prime, on their iPads rather than on the big screen TV's and Fire devices that hang in every room of the house just because it sucks so bad to actually buy content from Amazon. Sure if all you do is watch Prime then there is no problem since that content is divided up in so many ways it's actually overkill. But if you give Amazon more money to purchase content you get treated like a second class citizen.I'm seriously considering replacing all the Fire TV devices with Apple TV's so I can get a better interface for my Amazon content and start purchasing content through Apple instead.",1,10,negative,0.7333564758300781,0.025668010115623474,0.2409755289554596,0.7333564758300781,-0.7077,5,3011,1,0
"BE CAREFUL - FORCES PRIME ON YOU WITHOUT ASKING! - Also, terrible WiFi reception.","The firestick activation/video process forces a new prime membership on you, even if you don't want it. I have Prime through the household account my wife and I share. I got the firestick, plugged it in and after struggling to get the thing to connect to the Amazon servers for an hour seemed to be working OK. I got an email a short while later thanking me for joining Prime, even though my account was already Prime.Took about 45 minutes to straighten it all out via Amazon help chat, but they told me yes, activating does force a Prime subscription, it doesn't even appear to ask you if you want it. Amazon is becoming very sketchy. Help finally told me - I cant watch any Prime content and next time I click on &#34;Watch with Prime&#34; I will be rebilled for Prime. This is VERY unethical.Chat text:-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Thomas: Hello, my name is Thomas. Please give me a moment to review the previous correspondence.Me: okThomas: Okay I see that you were charged for prime although you share prime with your wife, Please let me just look into thisMe: OK - Im wondering how it was done, and now that I cancelled - will my firestick still work?Thomas: Okay I see that A refund has been requested from our end for the amazon prime.which was ordered through Fire stick.Please allow me a moment to check on the amazon fire stickMe: Odd thing is - I dont remember the firestick asking me to joing primeThomas: Sorry for the wait. From what I understand after checking with my team is that you will not face any problems without prime just that certain shows or serials that comes with prime will not be available.Sometimes there are shows which are available on prime many customers just see the series without checking that you need prime for it.Me: Thats very bad. Like I said - I am prime via a shared account.I guess I'll register it under my wifes name or return it. Bad business practice.Thomas: I understand what you are getting at however customers who are unader joint prime sharing benefits may have only certain access to benfites like prime delivery sefices etc.It may be that you are not registered to receive the prime video services that may be why when you tied to use fire TV it automatically selected prime in your steadMe: And to be clear - if I am Prime via a shared account - I CANT watch prime content on the firestick without being subversively charged for another prime account?OK - Sounds like a yes. Thank you - and please pass on that this is very unethical, I wasn't even asked to join prime first.Thomas: I understand. I will take this as your feedback, for this fire TV device.Thank you for contacting Amazon.com. We hope to see you again.",1,11,neutral,0.7440649271011353,0.1857714056968689,0.7440649271011353,0.07016368955373764,0.1156,2,2787,0,0
Definitely worth the upgrade...,"I've dropped my review to 1 star because Amazon has started treating me the same. I've been a cord-cutter for years and my entire house is immersed in the Amazon ecosystem. I estimate I've saved about $4500 over the last 4 years with about $800 invested in at least 20-30 Amazon devices across my home. What do I get for this loyalty?1. Deregistration of devices every month. Evidently this huge company with all its talent cannot differentiate me from a criminal that is reselling their devices with pirated software.2. Dropped support of 1st generation Fire TV box. Directv Now is no longer supported and has a pop-up message that says that I need to upgrade my device. There is literally no explanation anywhere on the Internet as to why this would be. Shame on AT&T and Amazon for colluding on an early retirement as this device is absolutely not obsolete.3. Fire TV devices that will no longer register to my Amazon account. Amazon can literally not tell me why this is. I have had to use a second gmail email address to register some of my devices.4. Subpar customer service. I have never seen customer service drop so fast in the 4 years that I've been using Amazon Fire TV devices. You are treated like a criminal just for calling them and even then they are useless with no answer other than to offer a meaningless credit toward another device because they cannot fix your issue.5. Ads gone wild. I'm sick of being fed ads at the top of my user interface. It has gotten so bad that it is virtually impossible to differentiate whether you are highlighting an ad to watch or are interacting with the menu bar.My advice to anyone that is considering cord-cutting and that will need a large number of devices is to consider another ecosystem. I have heard that the Nvidia Shield and Apple TV devices are far superior. Yes I love Alexa but I definitely regret the marriage for the points made above.____________________________________I cannot describe how much better this Fire TV stick is compared to the first generation. The first generation does not have near the horsepower necessary to run all of the apps that we use and seem to have wi-fi issues that cause it to drop/lose connectivity very easily. I honestly should have sent them back when I first got them but now they will be relegated to the junk pile and/or our travel bag. The new Fire TV stick also includes a voice remote which is also a nice bonus. We have 8-10 Fire TV devices and with this latest version, I cannot tell the difference in performance/speed between the all-new stick using wi-fi and the boxes that are plugged into the wall.",1,12,positive,0.5866554379463196,0.5866554379463196,0.3674853444099426,0.045859195291996,0.5408,7,2614,0,1
"Firestick is Great, Remote is Useless - Updated Review","Update to my review below: I continue to have problems with the remotes for my two Fire Sticks and one Fire TV box. To Amazon's credit, I was contacted and offered help as a result of my initial review. They sent me, free of charge, two replacement remotes which was impressive. Unfortunately this did not solve the problem as even the replacement remotes quickly stopped working. So the current &#34;scorecard&#34; is, I have five Fire remotes and only one actually works. Even the phone app can be &#34;glitchy&#34; and it doesn't always work. The other issue with the app is that it is very touch sensitive so a slight touch of the screen will cause it to scroll down about 15 rows and then you need to carefully scroll your way back up to where you wanted to be. the Two Fire Sticks are being used in a second house which we don't live in full time so we don't have cable, just internet, therefore the Fire Sticks are the only source of entertainment. When they don't work it's even more frustrating since we don't have another option. Bottom Line: Despite having made a pretty significant investment in Amazon Fire (about $160), it looks like we will have to ditch the Fire Stick and Fire TV altogether and try Roku. This serious remote issue is a real shame because when the system works it's very, very good (4.5/5), but as it is, I have to change my rating to 1/5. Amazon, if you're listening, refunds would be very much appreciated.Original Review: Let me clarify my rating. First, I have two Firesticks and a Fire TV box. My rating is based almost entirely on the remote control which is virtually useless for all three. The picture, ease of use, connection to the internet, lack of buffering (I have a very fast internet connection) are all excellent. The weak (very weak) link of this product is the remote control which stops working constantly. I had to download the Fire TV app on my phone and usually can only use my phone to operate the Firestick. Yes, I went on YouTube and followed all the various methods described to &#34;reset&#34; the remotes. None of them worked. This problem is not isolated to a specific Firestick or the FireTV. All three have has serious remote control issues. So you may say, what's the problem? Just use your phone. It's not as simple as that. Once you get it all set up on the service and channel you want, you must leave your phone on or the Firestick will disconnect. For the life of me I can't figure out how Amazon could make a sell such an excellent product with a remote that simply doesn't work. If this is the best they can do, they should ship it with a cell phone rather than a remote control.",1,13,negative,0.7699283361434937,0.025774406269192696,0.2042972892522812,0.7699283361434937,-0.7442,7,2651,1,0
"Device is physically good, menus really suck","The Stick itself is very good. Easy to set up. Around 5 minutes. and it seems to work very well. The problem is, and the the reason for 3 stars, are the apps. They are terrible. Have the unit for about a week and a half and still can't sign into the NBC app. Keeps asking for the code and no matter how many times I put it in, it just recycles to asking for the access code. Finally gave up. I like the voice feature for searching. Works pretty well and quickly.Another annoying thing is when you're in an app, if you make a mistake or select the wrong thing using the buttons, you cannot go back and select something else in that app.You have to go into another app, then select something in that app, then go out of that app and go back to the one you originally wanted and try again.Let's say I'm in my CBS All Access app and I selected something by mistake. It goes to that page. Now, I realize my mistake and want to go back the CBS Access menu. You can't. You have to go into another app, not just select it, but actually enter it, back out of it by going to the 'Home&#34; screen, re-enter the CBS app and try again. This is horrible and a waste of time and is of great frustration to me.I had a Roku 2 which was similar. This should not be a hard thing to fix. But since it happens across devices, I guess they figured they got some of right at first, so fixing anything is not a priority.If they had to they, I imagine they could charge a few dollars more, hire someone to rework the remote and everyone would be happy. There is no excuse in this day and age for this horrible interface.And maybe tell us in advance when a program or movie is going to cost something to view.But like I said earlier, the device itself is great.Too bad they are so 'over it&#34; that they won't fix the interface.7/04/2018 Even worse than originally thought. ABC and NBC apps need a cable connection to function. Can't fast forward through commercials, buffer overflows and freezes the unit. On PBS, keeps wanting to play an episode I already watched and would not let me pick another show. If you want to watch something on PBS, you'd better know the exact title and the date. If you just go through episodes you're in for a long trip. I like Antiques Roadshow, so I was looking for a show called 'Vintage Tampa.&#34; Unfortunately, All I get is the word &#34;Vintage.&#34; I have to stop at each show square with word Vintage in it, open it and see if the it's the correct episode. If not I have to go back and keep searching, inspecting each and every one until I stumble on the correct series. This unit is going in the trash.",1,14,positive,0.6721606850624084,0.6721606850624084,0.1840924471616745,0.14374688267707825,0.5284,3,2621,0,1
hero to zero,"8/2018 update - still freezing on all channels periodically no matter which router, band or settings I use ... does anyone have a real technical explanation!? contacted Amazon tech support - was transferred 4 times within India at various representatives - final suggestion after I explained that XBOX works fine, Roku works fine was &#34;reset your Amazon device to factory settings and reload your applications&#34; ... before I had a chance to ask what the success of that procedure was going to be on 3 of these devices which would be extraordinarily time consuming their overseas call center disconnected and did not call back ... I would say that's terrible customer service and even worse tech support since they have no real explanation for what's happening with their devices ...================================================================================================not sure what's happening but a few weeks after purchasing and using these went from hero to zero - freeze every 20 min on any streaming channel with no changes to network and router - just started suddenly with no specific symptoms and now will result in a quick return after one more attempt in a few days with a brand new ac3200 router - very disappointed - seems a pervasive problem with no good explanation and lots of hypothesis ... can't explain how i went from super speed and consistent streaming to freeze frame - I hate all these devices no matter who makes them - too much technical overhead to tweak non-stop - I wish we'd all stop being tech support and just be able to use these devices ...===================================================================================================These fire sticks (2) are replacing Rokus which I am super annoyed with since their performance for whatever reason has basically degraded to a point where it is impossible to use them without wanting to take a hammer to them. So - bought 2 fire sticks on Prime Day for $20 each which I can tell you was an amazing deal. They come with everything you need - power brick, power cord, HDMI extension - and are basically a plug and play deal. Bonus surprise they have 5ghz connectivity to my router which makes them real fast. Only slight complaint there is some bloatware you can't uninstall and they are only 8gb which means that you'll have to be very judicious in choosing your apps. At the $20 price point these were a great deal and I now wish I would have bought 6 ... highly recommended.",1,15,negative,0.7745427489280701,0.012970691546797752,0.21248653531074524,0.7745427489280701,-0.7616,7,2480,1,0
So Amazon wont sell me anymore of these? please explain,"I ordered two of these fire sticks to try and overall I am really happy with them. Its only been a couple of days but I like them. I can't attest to their reliability due my limited experience with the device. My issue is that I ordered two a couple days ago and yesterday I tried to order two more but was not allowed to. Every time I attempt to check out a warning message appears stating that I have reached my limit and the system automatically changes my quantity to zero. I called customer service three times yesterday and wasted over two hours of my time. I received three different and conflicting ""solutions"" from customer service. first rep told me that I can only have two fire sticks ever. According to him I am never allowed to own more than two fire tv sticks. the second rep said that I can order any more because there is a limit on how many I can buy now due to the offer. I stated to him that on this page it only states limited time offer and when i click on the link it takes me right back to the same page. Nowhere on this page does it state that i can never have more than two fire sticks. why wouldn't Amazon provide me this information before i purchased these items. maybe i would have not wasted my time buying them, installing them, teaching my wife how to use them, and time and money wasted contacting customer service. So now i have four TVs two of which can not access the internet because of some limitation that now one apparently working at Amazon can help point to in writing anywhere. i read the terms of use and it does state that amazon my limit discount items at their discretion but nowhere does it say i cant buy an item as many times as i want. I even was told by rep to just try again in 7 days. really Amazon this is acceptable. no one working there could tell me if when i could buy more if any or when i can buy them. so im suppose to wake up every morning and hope i can order two more. maybe i want five of them. maybe i dont want to wait three days for shipping if one breaks. this is the only time i tried to buy the same item within a week. maybe i never notice this before. so do i have to watch what i buy at Amazon. if i buy anything will i be able to reorder it. this makes no sense to me. what else to they limit. Amazon reps are wrong i can have as many devices linked to my account as i want just cant use more than two devices on amazon prime to watch the same show. i am hoping anyone working there will respond publicly to my concerns.",1,16,positive,0.9016630053520203,0.9016630053520203,0.07927371561527252,0.019063318148255348,0.8826,2,2497,0,1
Annoying bloatware-like home screen; Inferior to Chromecast,"I've had a Chromecast thing for years and was looking for another for our other TV. Amazon no longer sells them so I got a Fire TV Stick instead. I've had it for a few months now and while having a separate interface for apps can be nice, I prefer the flexibility (and privacy!) of Chromecast. Big reasons: -------&#62; It doesn't work with my Android or MacBook.Unlike Chromecast, which requires an external device like a phone or laptop to play media on your TV, the Fire Stick holds apps you can select with a remote. In theory, you should also be able to cast or tap into those apps with a phone or laptop. Most of the time, however, the Fire Stick does not show up as a device I can cast to from my phone. There is no way to cast from a MacBook to the Fire Stick without a third party app (you have to pay extra for). In contrast, with Chromecast I've rarely had trouble connecting to Youtube, Netflix, or Spotify through respective apps on my phone or in mirroring tabs with Chrome on my MacBook (my primary uses). Amazon and Google are in some dispute also, so the Youtube app is no longer on the Fire Stick (though it had always been very mediocre on it anyways). -------&#62; I'm not interested in Amazon Prime ...so I'm really annoyed by the home screen filled with Amazon Video options. Netflix, Spotify, and other apps I choose to download are icons near the top. The rest of the home screen is filled with rows and rows and rows of video suggestions, ads, and other irrelevant offerings. It feels very spammy and busy. Sometimes you have to sift through their recommendations to get to the apps you had chosen to download. There is not an option to quiet down the screen. Chromecast is less clunky - there are only photos until you cast your media. I don't feel like I need TV suggestions, so I appreciate the calm and autonomy of it. -------&#62; The Fire Stick has (?) to be tied to your Amazon account.When I first plugged in the device, my name and account information popped up on my TV. If you don't select &#34;gift&#34; upon purchase, Amazon personalizes your device by pre-logging in for you. This made me very uncomfortable. Tied to the push to use Amazon Video and services through the home screen, I disliked that in-app purchases could be made without my consent by people with whom I share the TV. You can turn off in-app purchases, but &#34;ON&#34; is the default option and it is nestled a bit in the settings.",1,17,neutral,0.5627774000167847,0.14280064404010773,0.5627774000167847,0.2944219708442688,-0.1516,5,2439,0,0
I wish I had known about the problems with Netflix before I purchased this product.,"With the exception of issues when trying to watch anything from Netflix, this is a good product. If you are a Netflix user, this is a nightmare. First of all let me state that the problems trying to view anything on Netflix are not with my network or ISP. I can stream Netflix over other streaming devices without any problems at all. When trying to stream anything from Netflix with the Fire TV Stick, it will buffer somewhere around 20% to 25% and will just hang at that point. I can back out by using the back button on the remote and try to load the video again but it will once again freeze when buffering at either the same percentage or around 15%. The only way I can watch something on Netflix is to go into the settings of the Fire TV Stick and then into the installed applications part of the settings and clear both the cache and data for the Amazon (yes, I said Amazon) streaming Video app. I then have to clear just the cache (not the data though) for the Netflix app. I then have to go into the device part of the settings and chose to restart the device. Once the device has restarted I need to immediately go into the Netflix app, chose what I want to watch and it will immediately start and play without any buffering issues or problems. If I want to watch something else through Netflix I need to go through that whole routine again. I have found threads on various forums on the Internet about this problem that go back to 2015. People have been communicating this issue back to Amazon since 2015 and they have been aware of it since at least 2015. The steps I outlined to solve this issue (for one viewing) came from an Amazon customer support agent. The fact that they have not been able to solve this issue in 2+ years and that part of the solution lies with clearing the cache and data from their own video app points to suspicious behavior on Amazon's part. Could this be that Amazon would rather have Fire TV Stick viewers view movies through Amazon Prime rather than Netflix? I do not know if that is the case but it sure looks like Amazon is trying to make it painful to view movies via Netflix with their device in hopes that the customer will dump Netflix and subscribe to Amazon Prime instead. If that is what is happening, Amazon should hang their head in shame. If that is not what is happening, Amazon should fix the issues with the Netflix streaming app. Why has it been this way for 2+ years? Your customers deserve an answer.",1,18,positive,0.524025022983551,0.524025022983551,0.3290795087814331,0.14689549803733826,0.3771,2,2461,0,1
Be aware that the range on this is very low and buffer is small* Problem solved,"I purchased this product on recommendation of Amazon Prime Video customer service reps after complaining that my Sony Blue Ray device was apparently causing repeated pauses and disconnects from my WiFi. The Fire Stick is no better, maybe worse because I have to go back to home and restart the movie where it stopped. I've been fighting this problem for many months and Prime Video Tech support had no answers. A customer service rep for our cable provider (Spectrum) taught me how to do a speed test on the signal from the Fire Stick. A computer with only 2 G capability was getting 35+Mbps and the Fire Stick only 7. The antennas on the Sony device and the Fire Stick is so badly designed that it won't pick up the signals. We know that phones have much better antennas. So now I have to purchase a WiFi extender for another $25 that hopefully will give the Fire Stick or Sony Blue Ray enough to stop the pauses and drops. Netflix on the other hand can easily be run with a dongle and NetCast. Amazon Prime Video is losing business to Netflix because of the crappy devices Amazon is selling to put streaming onto TV sets that aren't doing a good job if your set is more than 5 feet away from the WiFi transmitter and lower. WiFi transmits up and bounces of ceilings like an umbrella. My computers and other WiFi devices upstairs get better signals from the modem which is downstairs.Additionally the buffer is too small for continuous streaming when Amazon's upload speeds are cut because of high traffic. Amazon has yet to acknowledge this issue and some are blaming throttling by the server companies. That isn't true.After months of problems streaming Amazon and no useful help from Amazon support for either Prime Streaming Videos or Fire TV Stick Customer service, a Spectrum tech came in and checked the WiFi signals. There is a predictable dead spot behind the TV where the Fire Stick resides. I purchased a 3' HDMI extension so the stick would be out in front of the TV. My signal strengths are now good enough so we aren't having problems with streaming. Our Sony Blu Ray still doesn't work well because it isn't 5G capable and the 2.5 G signal near the TV is too low to stream without interruptions or poor quality picture.Bottom like is that I'm not adding stars back because a Spectrum tech and I, not Amazon support, figured the problem out and I figured the solution out.",1,19,negative,0.8563891053199768,0.011691349558532238,0.1319195032119751,0.8563891053199768,-0.8447,4,2387,1,0
Incredible Hardware Plagued by Poor Interface Features,"The second generation Fire TV Stick has a lot going for it with two extremely big problems that area deal breakers.The stick offers excellent overall picture quality. Most content played via Amazon Video, Netflix, Hulu and SkyTV looks really good with very few artifacts and solid color fidelity. I had been using a Roku but experienced some issues with audio after FF or RW video in some apps which is never an issue with the Fire TV Stick. The AV performance of this very small device is remarkable.The user interface is Amazon centric which should not be considered a negative being the Stick is priced so low and Amazon's strategy is proudly NOT content-agnostic. Competing apps are cumbersome to reach but it's not horrible by any means.Okay, now for the bad which, I think, ruins this product.1. The previews at the beginning of each piece of Amazon produced content are extremely annoying. Not only will a user often see the exact same preview (commercial) with each episode of an original series, the volume level is VERY loud. I'm sure the product team would claim this is a value add but viewers enjoy moving from one episode to another without these commercials. The commercials can be skipped after a short period but come on!!!!2. X-Ray has to go. Again, this only applies to Amazon produced content but X-Ray is a blatant insult to viewers and to the artists who created the content. For example, the stellar good &#34;Man in the High Castle&#34; series has some of the best cinematography of any series I've seen. Truly visually stunning. But, when the X-Ray &#34;feature&#34; blocks the lower 1/3 of the screen, viewers and artists are absolutely cheated. Again, this can be removed via the remote but it's just plain obnoxious. Let's watch the content that hundreds of people created instead of blocking the screen. Think about the logic - if a viewer presses play to watch a piece of programming do they want to immediately stop watching it and go listen to a song or research one of the actors? No, they want to watch the program. It makes no sense whatsoever. What's next? How about as soon as we start watching a movie, we can stop watching and post to Facebook?Amazon creates some of the best hardware in the world and arguably the best original programming but this product gets in the way.",1,20,positive,0.9412747621536255,0.9412747621536255,0.05015769973397255,0.008567548356950283,0.9327,5,2313,0,1
"Plain & Simple, it sucks!","The remote NEVER works!!! It says “needs new batteries” as soon as I put brand new ones in. I’ve tried more expensive and cheaper batteries and they all do the same! Also, my “older” firestick, I’ve had for about 3 years, works faster and better than this one! This one just disconnects from the internet and stops working. I will have to reset the whole firestick, and even sometimes disconnect and reconnect my router and all. It’s so frustrating. I know it’s not my router or internet because my other fire stick doesn’t do that and neither does our phones, iPad, printer, and tablet. The biggest thing that really makes this go down two more stars is the remote. I thought this was going to be so much better than the original fire stick because it’s newer. However it’s been probably a year or so since I’ve replaced the batteries out of that remote. And the batteries last about a year or two years in that one, but this “newer one” I’ve had to replace batteries weekly or more and the remote still don’t work. I have to take the batteries out for 30 seconds or so, or just use the app on my phone which can be very inconvenient considering I don’t always have my phone on me. So frustrating. I’ve been having this problem since I’d say end of 2018. But for some reason I thought I had had this one longer (probably because of the amount of batteries I’ve been through with it), if I knew I still to this day, June 20th, 2019, haven’t even had it a year, I would’ve done tried contacting someone or writing a review. It’s literally been a horrible experience all around. If I knew it would be this bad, I would’ve bought the cheaper, older version because it’s been working fine in the bedroom. This one right here though, is in my living room, and hands down I wouldn’t give $10 for another one. Maybe mine is faulty or something. I don’t know, but I know it is definitely worse than the first generation firestick I have. It would get 2 stars instead of one because I do like the firestick setup and display, but it would be nice if I could actually use it when it don’t randomly disconnect from my internet or the remote decides to just quit working. ALL THE TIME! Would recommend the older version without Alexa (I don’t use it anyways). Maybe the newest one, but I haven’t tried it. So can’t give an opinion on it. But I can give an opinion on this one, and IT SUCKS!",1,21,negative,0.9050176739692688,0.01480796653777361,0.08017430454492569,0.9050176739692688,-0.8902,7,2378,1,0
or just an extremely bad run of luck,"So I ordered this product 3 times.The first time I ordered this product, I got the firestick and set it up after taking it out of the box. I was so excited to try this product. I was exploring all the features and especially being an Amazon Prime member I was excited to utilize the full potential of my product. After I used it the first time, the product did not go into &#34;sleep mode&#34; and over heated. Which caused the product to over heat and lose connectivity to the wireless remote.I then managed to talk to IT support located at a Call Center in India to reach the conclusion that my firestick remote was not connecting and it should not overheat. Waited another 3 days to get my Second Firestick. This time when I got the product, the remote did not connect right out of the box. I thought this was a sick joke, or just an extremely bad run of luck. But I decided to try one more time. After another call to an IT support center in India, they reached the same conclusion. After mindless walking me through the same, &#34;troubleshooting&#34; techniques listed online.So this time after 5 days, I finally got my third Amazon Fire Stick. With no information on how to return the previous two defective ones. I opened it up immediately to make sure it worked. This time I connected like a charm, explored the apps and logged into my favorite apps. All was going well, then I even made sure that this Firestick would successfully go into sleep mode with out heating up. Everything was going as planned and I thought, &#34;Third Times the Charm!&#34;.FALSE! My firestick remote will not connect and &#34;wake up the firestick&#34; because its no longer connected. I even changed out the batteries to brand new ones, not the amazon brand that comes with it to be 100% sure. I pressed the home button for 10 seconds to reconnect the remote, I pressed every button repeatedly and even walked up within 2 inches of the the slick black stick.Ladies and Gentleman, I am going to return this clearly glitched and problematic device and look into roku or chrome-cast. Which hopefully will give me a better experience. Im just glad I did not have to pay shipping each time. Even though I technically paid $100 since I am a prime member.",1,22,positive,0.956200122833252,0.956200122833252,0.041377078741788864,0.002422736957669258,0.9538,5,2237,0,1
Difficult To Put Together And To Operate -- Plus Features Are Too Limited,"The Fire Stick keeps rebooting itself at odd times for no obvious reason. The remote is very awkward to use manually. Then Alexa kept telling me that she was unable to perform that operation or that she didn't understand what I meant. The Miracast app won't work on my Kindle HD 8 (7th Generation) so I can't display any of my own pictures, listen to my own music, or run any of my own videos. Display mirroring is also disabled on the Kindle HD 8 (and I assume the HD 7 also). You can't run either the Audible app or the Kindle app on the Fire Stick (it might seem stupid to want that ability, but I was hoping to use it to help my aunt, who is going blind, to read large print on her TV). They keep saying that Alexa will read your Kindle books to you, but there are no instructions on how to make that work (and I did search the web). No matter how I set up the display settings on my TV, some of the Fire Stick display is too large (so it won't calibrate) and the picture goes outside the TV screen so I can't see it. The small end of the USB power cable will not fit into the Fire Stick because it has a male fitting exclusively for a &#34;power only&#34; connection. The Fire Stick has a female slot for a regular charging USB cable so it is a smaller size than the one used only to supply power. The instructions say that we should use the cables and plugs included in the package, but the male cable end doesn't fit the female slot on the Fire Stick! When I chatted with your Support Assistants, the last thing they told me is that a power cable does not come with the Fire Stick and that I could buy it from Amazon on line. However, if you refer to the picture of what is included in the package, you can see that it really DOES come with a cable and an adapter plug. That kind of answer from Support implies that I don't know what I am talking about, which is an insult and not any help at all. So I am very disappointed and am returning the Fire Stick to Amazon. The only thing it does better than my existing setup is run Amazon Prime Video content. Why does Amazon have to make everything relating to Kindle Fire and now the Fire Stick so VERY EXCLUSIVE that the functionality goes down with each new generation they design? It is so frustrating!",1,23,negative,0.8720057606697083,0.0069067166186869144,0.12108751386404037,0.8720057606697083,-0.8651,4,2259,1,0
"Poor video quality, You get what you pay for!","Video quality is poor, in fact it was much darker than my Ruku 4 when I tried it on my Panasonic plasma TV. I also tried it on my Samsung LED TV and it wasn't as dark but it was definitely grainier. I know maybe its not a fair comparison because the Ruku also supports 4k but it was annoying enough for me to stop using it for everything except Kodi. Most people will probably be okay with it but I'm used to having quality stuff. I already own a Roku 3 and 4 but they don't support Kodi. I will just keep this in my room for now but I'm not going to use it on my main TV. If you don't use Kodi I would recommend spending a little extra for something like a Roku 4 because the picture quality is much better and the user interface is much faster and friendly-er. A even better alternative would be the Nvidia Shield and it supports Kodi but it cost around $199 and the remote is an extra $50, its on my Christmas list.The pros: its cheap, it works with Kodi, Wifi connection was good, and it was pretty responsive, I didn't notice any lag except when Kodi was first updating. I did enjoy using the remote and the fast forward options such as 4x, 8x, and 16x. The remote worked really well with Kodi too. I'm not sure if Alexa is a pro but it did help me one time when I couldn't find my favorite Red Bull app to download in any of the categories. Red Bull channel shouldn't be that hard to find and it should of been listed under sports apps or top apps.I'm sure a lot of people are getting this for Kodi and there's a lot of how to you-tube videos but unfortunately most of the links in the videos are dead but they are always posting new ones. I also have Kodi on my desktop computer which is hooked up to my living room TV, I have a video card that supports 2 displays. I have a USB flirc IR sensor so that I could use my harmony universal remote to navigate Kodi. Its a nice setup if you have movies on your hard drives and if you want the best audio and video quality but it cost a lot more than the Fire TV Stick. If your looking for something cheap to stream stuff than this Stick is for you but just know your not getting the best video quality.Good Luck and I hope my review helps.",1,24,negative,0.7854892611503601,0.02144390530884266,0.1930667757987976,0.7854892611503601,-0.764,4,2190,1,0
Avoid at all costs!,"I love amazon - it’s where I have purchased virtually every item I have had to buy in the past five years. Customer service has always been excellent, very efficient. This is the first and probably last review I’ll ever post about a product I purchased on this site because... I don’t like to complain and I doubt that anything I do buy in the future can compare to this poorly created device. IT IS HORRIBLE. My advice is to run back into the arms of Roku, or literally any other streaming device out there besides the Firestick. I work from home and my husband and I were looking to save money on our cable bill and after a modest amount of research, we chose the Firestick over all the others mostly in part because we both love Amazon and like to support their products whenever we can. I work from home and so I keep a couple of our TVs on throughout much of the day to catch up on news, watch Bravo, and play background music on Youtube. All of this has become basically impossible to do on any type of a regular basis after we switched from cable to the Firestick. I consider myself a fairly patient and go-with-the-flow consumer as well as pretty knowledgeable re: tech stuff who doesn’t get disgruntled easily. Fast forward to present day, about three months after the date of purchase, and you would find someone who is quite the opposite of what has just been described. I HAVE TRIED EVERYTHING to try and get this thing(s) to work properly as well - I added the (s) to emphasize that I not only bought one but THREE of these useless things and they all have basically the same issues - at least this reinforced the fact that maybe it’s not just me and this wasn’t just a fluke of bad luck where I happened to purchase a lemon. Currently, I barely ever watch tv anymore even the silly reality shows on Bravo that I so enjoy because I just don’t have enough free time every hour on the hour to sit and try all the tricks I have taught myself to get the horrible channel apps to stream live tv for ten mins before it randomly shuts off. Steer clear of this disaster of a device if you want to keep your sanity. I ordered a Roku from Amazon that will be here tomorrow... it can only get better from here.",1,25,positive,0.9211063981056213,0.9211063981056213,0.04354601725935936,0.03534761071205139,0.8858,0,2212,0,1
More like plug and pray,"Extremely annoyed nothing seems to work. The apps page is more annoying and busy than vegas on new years eve. And NOW I have to place a flipping call to customer service to get it working? While I admit I'm being a little entitled. The LEAST you could have done os pit the damned number on the error screen. Im running 300 mbps internet the damn thing has excellent signal and i still get degraded picture and buffering.**UPDATE**Steve from amazon just called. He offered to credit my account 30 dollars and have my buy a new one... why not just SEND me a new one with a return mailer? Totally inefficient! I certainly hope that someone sees this and then i hope that Steve was thorough with his notes. I countered with Telling Steve... That i would go and find the Customer service number ( my main annoyance is the lack of the number on the screen especially with older tech - these little things should be ironed out ) call up the number and if they cant get it running id return it for a full refund. Steves offer of &#34;here take some money and get a new one was pretty ridiculous. his further claims that he had reported the phone number thing and hed report it again is SOP. I get it. And while i DO appreciate the attempt &#34;i cant just send you one&#34; seems pretty lame. I mean you cant just send me a new item that AMAZON OWNS and HAS THEIR LOGO all OVER. but i bet if i asked for a return mailer id have gotten that... Again inefficient. I have lost confidence in the product. and im losong confidence with Amazon overall. its just becoming the US version of Aliexpress- hells i could have gotten a firestick knock off unlocked for half the price. This is what i get for goping legit hahah!Final Update - I have utterly lost confidence in Amazon overall 4 &#34;techs&#34; for a simple fix- not being listended to BY the techs may have averted a lot of these issues to begin with, the fix took exactly 30 seconds. utter nonsense. in my frustration i have requested a return label and will re visit this issue after the weekend. I realize that as a frustrated customer i have been turse and surly and even an a-hole. but 4 people for a thirty second fix? CMON!",1,26,negative,0.9030816555023193,0.011591782793402672,0.08532649278640747,0.9030816555023193,-0.8915,7,2174,1,0
Cant download Netflix,"I hate giving bad reviews.I got a promo credit added to my account so this is what I spent that money on. I was kinda tricked by cs but that's irrelevant. We already have a &#34;stick&#34; kit by another company in use at home. But I figured since this had a voice remote this might be better.I AM HAVING SO MUCH TROUBLE WITH THIS.First off, it's not really clear whether the apps are downloaded or not in your menu. It was hard to keep track of whether I just owned an app or it was actually downloaded. There is a setting to remove just owned apps from the main menu.For example: Netflix was on the main menu so I clicked on it. I had owned it but it wasn't downloaded on the device. I didn't know that at the time because it said nothing about downloading. It was just confusing. Once I figured out how to download it it gets stuck installing.I successfully downloaded other apps but there were like 3 apps that I attempted to download many times. They just say installing forever and eventually say they are unable to download. There is enough space on the device and I reset the router 2 times. I also used the extension for the HDMI which apparently gives the wifi more strength. I still to this day can't download the number one app we use. We ended up switching back to our other &#34;stick&#34; device. And I'm really disappointed because I found the voice remote to be very helpful. I also liked all the setting options in the fire stick! But it's ALL useless if I cant access the apps I want.I'll pull it out another time eventually when I want to set it up again. I'll probably reset it and start again but for now it's just collecting dust. I unfortunately can't send it back for a refund or exchange... That's how the promo credits work lol. I might contact support at some point to get this fixed but I really doubt they will know what's wrong. They'll probably say it's my internet connection but if it is all I can say is our other device works fine with our internet connection. I wonder if anyone else is having this problem. I never thought I'd be giving a bad review on a device purchased with credit haha!",1,27,negative,0.8510611057281494,0.014066440053284168,0.1348724067211151,0.8510611057281494,-0.837,7,2127,1,0
The Fire Stick is a Kid's Toy,"This is the slowest device I have ever had! I purchased it to replace my aging Apple TV V2. Might also mention my TV has chromecast imbedded and will run via my phone apps, but that is kind of clunky to to. I should also mention that I have my son's 6 year old PS3 connected to the same Visio 4K TV. I'm running Xfinity wifi with an average speed of over 100MB download. I figured since I have solid broadband and good TV i might as well have a new streaming device.Boy did I pick wrong! Since I got it 2 months ago, it has had almost daily connectivity issues and 3rd party app loads (hulu, ESPN, etc) can take easily over a MINUTE TO LOAD! The whole interface is designed around Primes content (and paid upgrade services) of course and it will only allow voice search to find things that come from Amazon, not other types of content from other providers. As what I feel is an insult to the consumer, at the top of the search area is a SPONSORED COMMERCIAL!!! Come on Amazon!! I paid you for the device, I pay you for Prime and you are still going to shove commercials at me top of screen???My final straw was the update Amazon made yesterday to the software. Basically, the only content that will play is their own Amazon prime stuff. The 3rd party apps aren't functioning. Pretty sad they would drop an update like that. And on a college football Saturday! Support has said they are working on the apps and that the problems are likely with my wifi. Of which speed tests ran on average 130MB while I had then on the phone. Also while on the phone I could stream the ESPN app on my phone with no problems. After a SOLID HOUR on support (they were very nice, I will give them that) they had no solution and simply told me that the Fire Stick doesn't have a strong of a processor as the Fire TV box. Thanks guys!!The Fire Stick is a KID'S TOY. If you really love prime and nothing else due the the interface, then perhaps dropping the extra dollars on the Fire TV would make sense. But I'm going to have to pass.... For now, I'm back to streaming on my really, really old Apple TV until I figure out what to do with this junker.",1,28,negative,0.7611818313598633,0.03989537060260773,0.19892287254333496,0.7611818313598633,-0.7213,5,2128,1,0
The Fire Stick is a Coin Toss,"I don't think I've ever had so many problems with a mainstream device as much as I had with the 5(going on 6) Fire Sticks I've owned.I have a Fire TV in the living room, and 3 Fire Sticks in each of my bedrooms. I don't have cable/satellite so I use streaming as my main source of entertainment, which means these Fire devices are practically used on a daily basis.The first Fire Stick I had for 6 months. Within those 6 months I bought 2 more Sticks for my remaining bedrooms upstairs. One of those Sticks would no longer connect to my Wi-Fi after 2 WEEKS. It would load and load until I got the &#34;Home is Unavailable&#34; screen even though everything else in my house worked just fine. I thought it was a fluke so I returned it and got another one. So far so good even though it's been about a month and a half since I got that replacement. Same goes for that 3rd Stick which has been about 2 months since I've had it and no hiccups yet.Now that first Stick I bought had the SAME ISSUE with the &#34;Home is Unavailable&#34; 6 months after I bought it. This couldn't be a coincidence as I just had that problem with my other Stick not too long ago. I contacted Amazon and Amazon honored the replacement Stick even though I bought it at a different retailer (thank you, Amazon. I love your customer service). Not even 10 DAYS LATER my replacement Fire Stick no longer turns on. I just get a blank screen with my TV saying there's no signal. Again, I contacted Amazon and they are now sending me a 3rd replacement Stick which will be here on Tuesday.Meanwhile, my Fire TV that I've had for 2 years probably gets the most abuse and has never so much as FLICKERED with all the content I put into it. I don't know if it's just the Sticks that are this defective or maybe I'm just unlucky, but I don't think I will continue using Fire Sticks if this replacement Amazon is sending me fails to work in the near future. I might just switch over to a Fire TV even though I don't want the bulkiness in my bedrooms. But who knows. I'm trying to give Amazon the benefit of the doubt. I'll update this review if anything else happens...",1,29,neutral,0.5272389054298401,0.3323283791542053,0.5272389054298401,0.14043276011943817,0.1919,7,2128,0,0
No one should ever buy this.,"Rarely works, and when it does, you'll be overwhelmed with ads. No one should get this, ever, for any purpose.Edit: I was contacted by Patrick from Amazon about my review of this product. Patrick knew what I had installed and what I have watched on the device. He shared this information unprovoked and without my say so. It seems even low level employees at Amazon have access to everything you do with their devices, so caveat emptor when buying ANY amazon electronic device, they freely share this information with anyone in their company, and who knows who else.apps on the amazon store are frequently broken, and amazon has nothing in place to fix this or maintain quality. Sideloaded apps are your only chance at getting anything to work, and those are frequently broken in other ways.Many of the videos available on prime video are free for only a few shows or seasons, and you have to buy the rest, so it's bait and switch. You won't really know when you're watching a show that you'll be surprised you're paying for.This device has no built-in ability to correct overscan. This is extremely easy to fix, they have not.This device is bad at connecting to wifi when it has to connect to more than one network.This device will force you to watch ads all the time, and I mean all the time. Your home screen has an ad, if you watch a YouTube video, you'll get ads, if you watch amazon video, which you are PAYING FOR, you'll get unskippable ads. If you watch anything on Hulu, and you definitely should not, you'll get ads. On a device you paid for, to watch videos you paid for.The only reason I can think of to own this is to stream your own library to your TV. Too bad. Streaming is broken on VLC, I imagine to the utter delight of Amazon, and is busted on Kodi as well.Some alternatives to this device are the Roku streaming stick, and Google's excellent Chromecast.Do not buy this. If you own it happily, just remember Amazon is freely sharing what you install and watch with all its employees, and consider returning it if possible.",1,30,negative,0.7407481074333191,0.019839292392134666,0.2394126057624817,0.7407481074333191,-0.7209,5,2042,1,0
I liked it when it worked,"I liked it when it worked. I purchased TWO fire sticks on December 1st, and they were delivered DECEMBER 5TH 2017. One remote stopped workin after a few weeks....so I used my phone as a remote, and then the Firestick itself stopped working. I looked online and in the AMAZON TROUBLE shooting FAQ....tried ALL OF THEM. Tried it on a different TV....nothing. So the first week of FEB , I contacted AMAZON, but I was at work, but then I was told the &#34;window&#34; for returns, credits, pretty much anytime of help...was JAN31st. So to be clear....the &#34;window&#34; that they cover this product is 2 months. Here is the conversation I just had with AMAZON customer service, today 2/15/18. (Habeeb is on the special team I was transferrer to)hank you for being a Prime member.Sorry for the typo.Me: You are welcome. I am a little frustrated I have to pay for another Firestick for my TV, when I ordered TWO, and one stopped working after a month and a few days.I tried everything, THEN contact AMAZON, when I was told the 30 day window had closed.Habeeb: I can truly understand that and do feel sorry for the same.However, I see that the return window for this has expired, let me see if something can be done about this.Yes, that has been closed on Jan 31st, 2018.Me: SO that means you do not stand behind this product longer than a month? Thats not very encouraging. The remote stopped working a couple weeks before the Firestick.Habeeb: Unfortunately the return window has expired, we're unable to help you with the return for this item and any other credit.Me: I had to use MY PHONE to control the Firestick.ok thank you. please do not be shocked to see this on a review of the item and amazon. VERY disappointed in AMAZON.Habeeb: I can truly understand that and we'll take this as a feedback and forward to the concern team and see if something can be done about this.Me: I will be cancelling my prime, as well as my kindle unlimited. wow. 40 dollars to your company is NOTHING. 40 dollars to me...after a product worked 2 months...is a LOT.",1,31,neutral,0.4858122169971466,0.3699224591255188,0.4858122169971466,0.14426536858081818,0.2257,7,2047,0,0
Unbelievable you can't customize a PRIME menu and see only PRIME,"Love hate relationship with this stick.Setup is easy. There is some customization where you can move some tiles on the home page. Navigation and searching is tedious for me. I can't believe it is 2018 and you can't create a custom menu of what YOU want to watch. I spent 15 minutes and could not find MONK, RIFF TRAX, or a host of other shows I watch using PRIME.You spend more time SEARCHING poorly navigating menus littered with shows and channels to BUY.Seriously we can't split BUY from FREE (or included with PRIME)I do NOT want to use Alexa.It is easier and cheaper to connect your laptop with an hdmi cable.If anyone knows how to set up a PRIME menu that YOU want to watch please commentI downloaded Crackle App and the QUALITY of Just Shoot Me was horrible..Prime quality was as expected, very goodEDIT: Amazon contacted me, but they force you to either PHONE or CHAT. I don't have time for that and to sit on hold.I love PRIME and the selections are fine and streaming is fine. The stick is fine.I want to set up MY Prime watchlist and tiles of shows I am interested in. NOT what amazon 'recommends'. That is fine to have that as an option. It is 2018 and you can't have multiple 'watch lists' or move the tiles of your shows, or sort by year?You can't assemble a playlist of individual episodes from different shows? You should at least be able to do this on a billion dollar web site and be able to access from the Fire Stick.Edit: Today i wanted to watch One Step Beyond in PRIME. Had to go to laptop find it, which moves it up in the watch list. On the Firestick i go to watch season one and PRIME is COMBINED with OTHER WAYS to watch!!!! Now i have the episodes listed more than once.Seriously, I am in PRIME and I want to watch ONLY PRIME and SEE only. Give the option to see ONLY PRIME and COMBINE things on another menu. Dropping this back to one star.I love five stars Goliath, Man in the High Tower, Sneaky Pete. But this isn't a review about content. It is a review about usability.",1,32,negative,0.7365809679031372,0.08051373809576035,0.18290534615516663,0.7365809679031372,-0.6561,0,2002,1,0
"Rebooting. Hoped it was just 1st unit. Unfortunately, both units I've tried have been duds. Quality Control is a thing, right?","Revision: Okay, I still hate it AND I hate getting stuck with two of the bloody things because of the way Amazon handles returns on these (see below).However, by eliminating the flexible extender AND moving it to a TV where the wifi signal is 86%, I can frequently use it now.I have received two duds in a row and am revising my review. This simply does not work, which stinks. It should be a great device. Obviously, thousands of other owners are really pleased with the new version.I am knocking it down to one star because of the return hassles. 1) This requires communication with Customer Support in order to initate a return. 2) Writing an email is completely insufficient. 3) One has to call or chat with support to authorize a return. DIRECT QUOTE from Support Email so don't blame me for the error, &#34;You can replace your Fire TV stick at any point of time unless{sic} it is under warranty.&#34;To replace your device I kindly request you to contact us back via live medium because all replacement/Refund decisions and actions are taken through live medium (Phone/Chat) due to the limitation over email. We require to confirm a few security questions like your current shipping address and credit card details. Due to the sensitivity of such information, we do not ask this information over email.I apologize for redirecting you to our chat or phone technicians, however, please understand that certain steps cannot be performed via email support due to system limitations.&#34;The first surprise is the mic on the remote is heard by Alexa/Echo (as expected) and the FireTVStick (which I expected to be controlled by the new Echo). I get weird results like &#34;You can only pause music when you are playing music&#34; from the TV while the Echo continues blasting tunes.I'm giving up on them because they both kept rebooting. I just scrolled through until I found a great movie. Then I clicked to play the movie and got the blue screen of death followed by the FireTVStick booting up after having obviously crashed for the tenth time tonight.",1,33,negative,0.8881006240844727,0.02006138116121292,0.09183795750141144,0.8881006240844727,-0.868,2,2055,1,0
Poorly engineered and tested device with firmware issues galore.,"This is quite possibly the worst piece of electronics I have ever owned. I have gone through 3 or 4 devices (I lost count) due to them arriving DOA or failing within a few weeks. The last one I received actually lasted awhile, but still had numerous problems that I had hoped would be fixed with software/firmware updates over time. Nope.I had mine plugged into my home theater receiver, not directly to the TV, so I could get the best sound and also switch HDMI output on the receiver to go to an outdoor projector. This is a pretty typical scenario for any media device (cable box, bluray, etc) with this kind of setup. The biggest headache with the device is that the HDMI output on it goes to sleep after awhile, and it does NOT like to wake up. It often takes a large number of random button presses on the remote and several minutes for both video and audio to reappear, with various stages of awaking in between (small black box in the middle of the screen because it is sending one resolution but advertising another, blank screen with clicking sounds when pressing buttons or audio if it decides to play something, etc). Sometimes it refuses to wake up no matter what and needs to be unplugged from power and HDMI to reboot. It does not like when I set the receiver to output to both HDMI (TV and projector) at the same time, though I have never had any problems with other devices. I sometimes wonder if this thing has HDCP handshake issues causing all of these problems. It also often loses connection to wifi, even though it is 6' from the router and everything else in the house has no problems. The interface has always been laggy, sometimes freezing up entirely for several seconds or even permanently, requiring a power cycle. Other times apps just randomly close and must be restarted.Perhaps this is the price you pay for going with the stick over the higher-priced box unit, or perhaps that has the same issues. Regardless, my latest one has met a tragic end with a tile floor, and while I may try the new 4K version, I do not have high hopes for much improvement in the firmware.",1,34,negative,0.8563838601112366,0.0185527466237545,0.1250634342432022,0.8563838601112366,-0.8378,5,2099,1,0
Return yours until Youtube app works!,"I own three Firesticks starting with the first gen when it came out. I'm revising my review because of the recent announcement that came up on my stick saying that Youtube app will no longer work on my Firestick after Jan. 1, 2018. That's why I will be returning this Firestick on Jan.2, 2018. I am a Prime member for years. I have a garage full of Amazon boxes like many people. I have purchased content from my Firestick.But I really enjoy Youtube on the big screen and my couch and spend many hours getting an education and not watching cat-flushing-toilet videos. But now I'm caught in this PIS**** contest between Amazon and Google and guess who loses? Right. The consumers again.Why blame Amazon? My research shows this schoolyard battle has been going on between these two giants for years.This latest round was Google pulling content from Firestick because Amazon has stopped selling all products related to Google such as Chromecast, etc.on it's site. Come on guys! You both already own the world! I use Youtube to research the products first, then go to Amazon to purchase.Now I will have to go to Ebay and purchase an android box from - wait for it- China so that I can watch my Youtube from my couch. Who wins? China!Amazon please put your competitors products on your site and end this before it escalates farther and hurts us all. Chromecast is no competition to Fire TV or stick. Don't be afraid of competition - it's what makes the business world go around. You both are at the top of your fields.If you want to spends some extra couple of your millions then get some lobbyists to our Congress and fight to keep Net Neutrality (title 2) before the ISP's decide to charge us extra to visit either of your sites. Then where will you be? Who will control where we're allowed to visit on the web? If you think they won't, you know they already have. And you both can offer all the streaming content you want but if it's blocked or throttled by my one choice of ISP how will I use your services? I've purchased 7 Firesticks but no more until you get your stuff worked out. Thanks.",1,35,neutral,0.5121837258338928,0.4658154547214508,0.5121837258338928,0.022000804543495178,0.4438,5,2091,0,0
"Poorly executed software, glitchy hardware.","No YouTube as of 1/1/18. Get a Roku instead. Since Amazon can't cooperate with Google, this and the Chromecast kinda stink. I wish I hadn't bought either.It's not as intuitive as I'd like, and comes preloaded with lots of garbage apps and links. It took me an hour or more to figure out how to remove the garbage and then get it done.Even after that, getting to use the apps you want to use (for me, that's Prime Video, Netflix and YouTube) is more complicated than it should be. They're never &#34;front and center.&#34; I'm forever digging to get to what I want to use this for.Browsing Prime Videos is a mess. It's easier on a phone or PC than this thing. The silly thing is that you can't use your voice to type, so if Alexa doesn't understand you, you're forced to use the directional pad on the tiny remote to &#34;hunt and peck&#34; each letter in a title. That's a bigger problem than you might think since Alexa isn't that bright. No one in our family can get it to understand &#34;Play Baby Einstein.&#34;The remote is nice, but is tiny and black, so it's easy to lose.Alexa is a moron. Even though the time is set properly, and displays properly, if you ask Alexa what time it is, she never gets it right, always giving us the time in California. We're in Atlanta. The commercials where people get Alexa to do neat tricks must be using a different version of Alexa. I have several playlists on Amazon Music, but Alexa and the FireStick can't seem to access them.No matter what we stream, we get random audio glitches where the audio is muted for a few seconds. Our Internet isn't the issue. We have among the fastest connections in the nation.We're still using the FireStick, but I use the app on my phone to control it. After a couple of days fighting with this thing, we went back to using our Chromecast for most of the functions you might use the FireStick for. The only thing we really use it for now is watching Prime Videos... which is a nightmare on this thing.",1,36,negative,0.8744245171546936,0.012201867997646332,0.11337356269359589,0.8744245171546936,-0.8622,5,1980,1,0
"A sad disappointment, No customer support what-so-ever on this device.","I cannot get this device to work/connect to my WiFi. It does not recognize the WiiFi no matter what I do yet my Samsung Smart TV is connected already. I don't understand, I'm using the same access code. I went through the set-up procedure a dozen times using my password, Then the advanced set up with IP addresses etc. Nothing!Replaced my older Wifi router! Thought it might help?I work on electronics and hate sending stuff back so my fiddled with the power adapter and tried another usb power supply and the device came to life. Consequently, you may find that the power adapter on yours could be the culprit if it doesn't work. Happily I may not have to return the fire stick and I now have it seeing my WiFi. Very easy and straight forward! But now the remote only works intermittently.After some fiddling I realized my Samsung TV remote will operate the fire stick. Now I can search the channels and view whatever I want. It works, finally! Wish Amazon would send me a new power supply and remote though. Guess I will not be returning the Fire-stick after all. Great programming and Amazon has a variety of programs without commercials. Love it! Wish I had done this years ago as I have been a Prime member since the very start.Update:I've now owned this product for six months, the remote never worked from the git go, bought a new replacement power supply that didn't work with the Fire Stick even if it was labeled as a replacement. The Fire Stick continues to go in and out, on and off. What makes it do this is anyone's guess at this point. Brand new WiFi which is on all the time and works all the time for all our other devices. I've tried everything, should've returned it when I had the chance. Love Amazon TV but there is NO CUSTOMER SUPPORT for this device. I've tried everything. Now I'm looking at buying something else which will get my Prime Amazon TV.Probably the most regretful purchase I ever made from Amazon. $40 down the tube, not to mention the extra power supply I bought.",1,37,negative,0.8358469605445862,0.01301365252584219,0.15113934874534607,0.8358469605445862,-0.8228,7,2001,1,0
YouTube TV not supported!!,"I would like to say first off that I'm a huge Amazon supporter. I am a Prime member and 95% of the time Amazon provides great customer service and I am able to successfully return products when the situation warrants. This review is more about Amazon's fight with Google than the product itself. A few facts before I continue: 1. I purchased the Fire stick at Best Buy. 2. I did not purchase it for YouTube TV. 3. I switched from Roku to the Fire stick because of Akexa.Now on to my rant. My son subscribed to YouTube TV and added me to his family plan. He said &#34;Dad, you'll be able to see both in market and out of market baseball games. More baseball than you'll ever have time to see!&#34; I was excited!! So I go to my Fire stick and try to load YouTube TV. Guess what?? The Fire stick does not support Google products. I come to find out that Amazon and Google are both acting like two spoiled kids and their public feud prevents little guys like us from enjoying programming that other companies like Roku are providing their customer base. So I call Amazon support to voice my concerns. Sure enough, Amazon's Firestick or any other Fire device like the Fire HD, of which I also own, is not compatible with anything Google. But they say, you can watch YouTube TV with our silk browser. To which I reply with, why would I use a browser to watch your competitor's product when I can just go back to using Roku?? I got the virtual shoulder shrug.So long story short, my love of baseball FAR exceeds my loyalty to any billion dollar company, so I went back to Roku where I can see just as much programming if not more than the Firestick. I put the Firestick in the guest bedroom where no one is looking at the Blockstick, I call it, and where Alexa waits in purgatory. Poor Alexa.So if you don't care about Amazon's fight with Google and don't care about quality TV programming like YouTube TV, then the Blockstick should meet your needs where you and Alexa can live and love happily ever after 😁😁😁",1,38,positive,0.8322399854660034,0.8322399854660034,0.1534951627254486,0.014264858327805996,0.818,5,2004,0,1
Not that great,"Terrible, honestly. The features are extremely limited, and there's no Youtube app. Here are a few of the most annoying aspects from my perspective:Alexa: The Fire TV stick is supposed to work well with prompts to Alexa, like asking Alexa to pause, play, fast forward, etc. But, rarely does this integration actually work. Like when I say, &#34;Alexa, play Masterchef on Hulu&#34; it will say, &#34;playing Masterchef on Amazon.&#34; First of all, I wanted to play it on Hulu, but worse, it doesn't even play after it says that. It just opens the Amazon app.Advertisements: I payed for this TV stick, and it is really annoying that there are advertisements within the platform. They are annoying, and overtake a lot of the screen, which is already full of too many things in the first place.Speed: It takes a long time to load things, and when Alexa does work, there is a large time gap between the command and the action. If you decide to plug the power cord into the usb port on your TV, it will take significantly longer for anything to work. It takes at least 30 seconds from turning the TV on, until anything is functional on the Fire TV platform.The &#34;apps&#34; section of the device is possibly the worst part of all. You can't even type the name of an app that you want to download. You have to scroll through their list of random apps that you don't want. I would really love to download the Vudu app, but I am not even sure if it's on the Fire TV stick platform, seeing as that I can't search for it. I tried using the voice search on the remote, but it didn't do anything.I opened the Vudu app on my phone in hopes that I could cast a show to the Fire TV stick, but it didn't show up in the devices which could be cast to. I know there is some way to mirror your phones screen to the stick, but that is a complicated process, and would drain my phones battery anyway.I just really, really hate the Fire TV stick. I am going back to my Chromecast.",1,39,negative,0.8690771460533142,0.014157808385789394,0.11676505953073502,0.8690771460533142,-0.8549,5,1960,1,0
"""Includes Special Offers"", and is as buggy and crash prone as Windows ME.","TLDR: Cheap , buggy junk that crashes all the time and has advertisements they didn't tell you about!Perhaps I received a lemon, or maybe my experience with my Roku 3 spoiled me, but the only good things I can say about this buggy crash ridden piece of junk are that it does let me use 5.1 surround sound with Netflix and prime video (with some fiddling), and does seems to improve the image quality a bit over my old Roku 3. It also mostly works(when it isn't crashing), and is fairly cheap, so, given the price I'd probably rate it in low to mid 2 star territory in my book, were it not for the fact that it is an &#34;Includes Special Offers&#34; device, but isn't sold as such. In other words, they don't tell you that it puts advertisements on the home page and prime pages, and there is no way to turn them off.In addition to the unadvertised inclusion of- advertisements on menus, it crashes daily, needs regular rebooting, loses sound, and won't support surround sound in Plex ( which the roku 3 actually *does* do, so even the one advantage over a several year old roku is questionable), not that it can run plex reliably without crashing.Also, the &#34;Amazon Focus&#34; is much more annoying in practice than I expected it to be. Since voice search always returns prime options, and the main menu is prime, you have to go to the home screen (with it's advertisements) and use the remote wheel to navigate to the netflix app every time. In theory I believe that you can load netflix with voice remote, but that is clunky and causes crashes and sound drops like crazy.Pros:-cheap-good image quality-remote pairs well with the unit ( no pushing buttons 5 times at different angles)-small footprintcons:-Includes Special Offers, but doesn't tell you it does that!!!!-needs to be rebooted at least once a day-freezes up regularly-sound will drop when switching between menus (about a 5-10% chance per menu switch!)",1,40,negative,0.7098188996315002,0.07333867251873016,0.2168423980474472,0.7098188996315002,-0.6365,3,1920,1,0
Poor remote and help for getting local stations.,"The remote kills batteries in 3-4 weeks even when not being used. replacement remote cost as much as a complete new stick if you can get one. Tried to contact Amazon which seems to be impossible and there help is useless. Dropped my rating from 2 stars to 1 star. If there was a - star I'd use it. This seems to be a common problem. The stick is great when working but if you can't access it because the remote will not work it is useless.Worked good at first, easy set up. After having for a few months the remote started locking up. After taking a hammer to the remote to get the back off I rebooted it, took one of the batteries of for a while, and it started working again. Now that seems to be a recurring problem. I also tried replacing the batteries and that didn't help. I didn't actually take a hammer to it but I was close. This is the worst remote I have ever seen to try and get the back off. These problems seem to be a common complaint. If the remote had continued to work properly and wasn't so hard to get into I would have given it a much higher rating.There also seems to be a lot of complaints about not being able to get local channels with the stick. It wasn't made for local channels. All TV stations now broadcast in Digital HD. I still have my old antenna on the roof and connect the 75 ohm coaxial connector to the antenna input on the TV and get just as good a picture as I do on my Dish DVR. It's the station that makes the signal digital not the antenna. An old set of rabbit ears might give you just as good a picture as one of these fancy digital antennas as long as it has a 75 ohm and not twin lead output. And yes all your new TV's still have the old 75 ohm antenna input. Just don't have all the capabilities as the DVR. I checked on Amazon and there are quite a few DVR's that you can hook the antenna to and then hook the DVR to the TV still have the same capabilities (record, pause, fast forward, etc.). I hope maybe this helps some people.",1,41,negative,0.7889924049377441,0.031739890575408936,0.1792677491903305,0.7889924049377441,-0.7573,3,1978,1,0
"Buyer Beware - a few months in and, like many of us, you'll have a useless stick.","I’ve left only a handful of reviews over the years, but this product requires a BUYER BEWARE sign attached to it. The Fire Stick, and perhaps more importantly, Amazon's [total lack of] support for the Fire Stick, is junk. The nutshell version: the only problem with the Fire Stick is the Fire Stick in spite of Amazon’s ‘support’ which only allows for the possibility that it’s a connectivity problem with your network. This device will work like a charm for a few months until one night when you'll turn on your television and instead of getting the Fire Stick’s home page, all you’ll get is a black screen with this message: &#34;Home is unavailable. We are unable to connect to Amazon services. Network connection has been lost. Go to Network Settings.” I did everything suggested: I checked my network connections and found nothing wrong, all the other apps and the browser on the TV worked perfectly, and re-booting my router, making sure the router was within a foot or two of the flash drive, using the extender provided in the box, and re-booting the Fire Stick, made no difference: the only thing that didn't work was the Fire Stick. I even tried different HDMI ports, including the one I was positive worked - the one directly connected to my router - and my connectivity continued to be fine, with all other apps working as long as I accessed them though the TV software, not through the Fire Stick. I’ve spent hours in the Amazon forums where all indications are that while it happens to lots and lots of people (confirmed by the enormous number of postings on this issue in the Amazon forums and other tech forums), there is no known ‘fix.’ My advice on this is that when reading all the glowing reviews, keep in mind that the majority are written in the first couple of weeks after someone gets one of these things. It’s awesome while it works, but then it simply fails and there is zero support from Amazon beyond screens that tell you to check your connectivity. Don’t waste your money.",1,42,negative,0.7044914364814758,0.044931236654520035,0.25057730078697205,0.7044914364814758,-0.6596,7,2002,1,0
My Worst Amazon Experience (FireTV Stick),"Possibly the worst experience from any Amazon device so far. I ordered it as a replacement for my older FireTV Stick. But it started giving me buffering problems within days. Many videos would play for some time and buffer for a long time. This happened mostly with Amazon Video, but also sometimes with Netflix and Youtube etc. I went through all the trouble shooting steps (like re-setting the device, un-plugging / plugging it, re-setting the router, doing speed test on my internet connection), and none of it was the problem.As if this was not sufficient, then came the worst and most unexpected part - a poor customer service, and that too from Amazon !! I have been a big fan of Amazon and its customer service for several years, but the FireTV staff was surprisingly unhelpful, and did not know their product very well. After spending 45 minutes with the first representative, trying to debug the problem (and basically doing the exact same steps that I had done), he logged in a ticket. Nothing happened for 5 days, so today, I called again. The new agent just refused to acknowledge the fact that I had gone through this once, and made me do all trouble-shooting steps again (at one point, when I complained, he also threatened me that he will not help me if I am unwilling to trouble shoot with him). Anyway, after spending 1 hour with him, and doing almost the same things again, he thought he had fixed the problem. That's when I understood that he did not understand my problem at all, that my device stopped working intermittently.I actually lost contact with the 2nd agent, since my battery ran out. And no I did not have the patience nor the time to call Amazon again and explain this to a 3rd agent. Not only did Amazon NOT follow-up on an open ticket after 5 days, it appeared that they had no plans to follow-up (Even Comcast actually calls you back if the call drops for some reason, but apparently not Amazon).I am returning this device.",1,43,negative,0.8973455429077148,0.009476438164710999,0.09317803382873535,0.8973455429077148,-0.8879,2,1959,1,0
And I am so horribly embarrassed!,"If I could just pick no stars, I wouldn’t do that. But since you have to pick at least one to be seen.... So I have had a Roku for a couple years now. Just a little Roku stick that I use in the main family room TV or when my kids aren’t home I take to my TV in my room at night. A friend of mine up north suggested that I get a fire stick with the Alexa remote for my kids and their friends. So I did. And I am so horribly embarrassed!!! We all have Spectrum TV here, formally bright house networks, and we all have a spectrum app on the Roku and our portable devices. But this great, wonderful, crap fire stick doesn’t allow that app!!!!! I could almost suck it up and deal with all the kids disappointment if that were the only problem. But two of the fire sticks I bought shut down and reboot constantly. Several times in the middle of a single movie. I’ve tried all four of the fire sticks that I bought on the same TV, but two of them constantly shut off and reboot. Thank God I had more than one here at my house on Christmas Day because everyone was here to watch the Strelers kick butt, and my fire stick kept stopping and rebooting over and over. So I got one of the other ones and it worked fine. I gave one of my daughters the one I was using so she could watch something else in her room, and she came out and told me it was garbage because it kept rebooting. I’m so disappointed. I got one for my daughter to give to her boyfriend, and of course that was the other one that kept rebooting itself. So no ability to get any local channels, or use our local app, and two of the sticks constantly reboot. Yes, I gave my friend up north an earful (of course joking around because she was lucky enough to get one that worked and allowed her local cable companies app to download.So be warned if you have spectrum and plan to use the spectrum app. It will not work. In fact, just stick with Roku. You’ll be far better off in a far happier customer.",1,44,neutral,0.558336615562439,0.06282361596822739,0.558336615562439,0.37883979082107544,-0.316,7,1954,0,0
My new report for the Fire Sticks,"I was buying this for my nefu I was seating it up it didn't work at all I so sad .I wasted two of my check I earn bye work on just Amazon this is how I get repaid not even my Alexa work and I have internet at my house. Oh I don't even want to return it didn't even come with batteries are back cover and I just found out and I can't believe I just did that it required a plug to be connected to the fire stick I really don't want to buy the stuff separately but if I have two I guess as you're young adult customer telling you the truth I already almost gave you three of my checks. And if you ask me to return that firestick that looks like it was work buying on sale I haven't decided to get rid of it or throw it away, but I am not going to return it because it took me this long to figure out the truth about this fire stick I thoughtI am not giving you a new start becauI gave it time and time again for firestic to work. Yes you all sent me a replacement but remote didn't want work well so I was able to place it in the app then about three days later remove stop working completely. So I was thinking I should guess troll it away because they already sent me a replacement.Other bad news I gave that firesick lots of opportunities GUST like a regular human being would get in there lifetime. It already a month in that the firesick is messing up before it was the remote two that remote messed up now it firesick. It messing up my cable TV from spectrum and also messaging up when I turn it on hdm3 I see firesick on display for on second and then it starts making noise like if the firesick is popping every time it tries to display it self .when it doesn't I sometimes a press home button I go to app from firesick. Remote on my phone.That is why I stop being your young member here and amazon.even if I had loved spending all my check here I don't like that a young costumer had to leave because of same issue and a new issue.",1,45,negative,0.8908911347389221,0.010458511300384998,0.09865037351846695,0.8908911347389221,-0.8804,7,1937,1,0
I am really disappointed in this device!,"Was looking forward to using it since my Roku 2 was not compatible w/Hulu app, kept having issues watching it. So I thought why not try something new WRONG answer!Pros:Compatible with Netflix and Hulu - the only real plus about this device is that I had no issues using the Hulu app!Cons:Remote control is defective - changed the batteries 3 times! Even though it came with brand new AAA Amazon Basics batteries they lasted only 3 weeks!! Had to use old batteries from my other remotes but they died instantly. I then put in new batteries again and they lasted barely 2 weeks!!!Had my Roku 2 for almost 2 years and I maybe changed the batteries once!Not very compatible w/SlingTV it buffers too much when I rewind a couple of times and I have to restart the device every time to get it to work again, which is a pain in the ass!Lay out is not that great have to prefer the Roku simple lay out instead.This device might be great for people who really love Amazon Prime Videos. I am an Amazon Prime member, but I hardly watch Amazon Prime Videos, so for that reason this isn’t the right device for me personally. I guess you have to try a couple devices before you find what works for you. But I never had any issues with my Roku 2 device until I got Hulu.I don’t use the voice command on the remote cause it never really show me what I want. Plus now I can’t even use the remote!I regret not getting the Roku Stick instead. Now I’m told that I can’t get a replacement remote b/c I used a promotion from SlingTV to get the Fire Stick for free. They did say that I could buy a Roku stick and then once it’s ships they would reimburse me.Now I have to wait a while to buy the Roku Steaming Strick + then hope that they will reimburse me for it.So buyer beware hope you don’t get a defective remote like I did! GOOD LUCK!",1,46,negative,0.6094078421592712,0.09628737717866898,0.29430481791496277,0.6094078421592712,-0.5131,6,1816,1,0
Extremely Frustrating Device - I am returning,"I am incredibly frustrated by this device. I originally bought the package that comes with the stick, power adapter, remote, etc.. I was excited that it was same-day delivery and I received the device in probably about 8 hours. However, while I was able to access the home screen and could access some of the Apps, none of the other pages worked (e.g., Dashboard, etc.) as the screen told me that the device was unable to connect to the servers. I spent about an hour on the phone with customer service and we tried several things to trouble-shoot (unplugging / re-plugging in the device, resetting my internet server, etc.) but nothing worked. The service representative quickly sent me a replacement stick, which came two days later. However, I was only sent a new Firestick and now the problem is that the device cannot pair / locate the remote at all, so the device. I spent another 30+ mins on the phone with a new representative who tried several things to trouble-shoot (unplugging / re-plugging in the device, pressing the back button, menu button, and left button on the ring at the same time for 40 seconds, pressing the home button for 40 seconds) and after several rounds, it still did not work. I decided I no longer want to deal with the trouble-shooting hassle of the device, so I asked to return the device for a full refund. I then waited ~5 mins to be sent to a new representative, who actually only dealt with replacements, so I had to wait another ~3 mins to be sent to a retail representative, who quickly understood my issue and immediately started working on a refund. She asked if I would request a refund to my credit card (which takes 3-5 business days) or as a gift card amount (which takes about an hour), so I requested a gift card refund. I'm currently still on the line (~45 mins in). Customer service is fine, but I'm incredibly frustrated with time this whole ordeal has taken and I wish I never purchased this device at all.",1,47,negative,0.4518505036830902,0.17381171882152557,0.37433773279190063,0.4518505036830902,-0.278,7,1958,1,0
this device is about 1/4th as useful as it used to be,"Without YouTube, this device is about 1/4th as useful as it used to be. Many of the TV apps falsely suggest they provide access to TV content with a fee. However, you eventually find out that if the cable provider you have doesn't already provide you with access to that content, then the app(s) won't either. Whats the point of that? If I had the content on cable, why would I also need it on FireTV except for additional convenience of on-demand access. Many of the app interfaces are lame. The main screens keep track of recently used apps but don't keep track of recently viewed content (except for amazon content). So, you can't in one step return to an HBO movie you were last watching or a YouTube video you last viewed or a photo you were last browsing in your photo collection, etc. I've puchased A&E content (Leah Remini's Scientology and the Aftermath) from *Amazon Prime*, only to find out several episodes were instead streamed via the A&E app and NOT via Amazon's app. Why does that matter? Because A&E's app sucks! It frequently hangs and restarts. It forces you to watch commercial content and they can never find a way to insert commercials such that they don't screw up the main content stream. In any event, I *paid* for that content. Why they heck do I then need to be forced to watch commercials during it too? Finally, I frequently wind up having to re-boot the device and/or the cable modem it connects to. Otherwise, it buffers constantly even when other networking apps on other devices in my home are running fine. They don't offer bandwidth saving audio-only modes or accelerated play modes (often useful for documentary or reference content). The NetFlix and Amazon apps have been pretty good. But, the fact is, I probably watch YouTube content about 80% of the time. Without, the device is pretty worthless. I suggest anyone else with similar opinion either return their device to Amazon for a full refund or sell it on EBay.",1,48,negative,0.5423493981361389,0.0494229719042778,0.4082275927066803,0.5423493981361389,-0.4929,5,1954,1,0
"Prime Member, No Prime Video. Not a Cord Cutting Device","I’ve been a Prime member for years, my wife signed up over 5 years ago and added me as a spouse / household member. On Prime Day 2018, I decided to buy a Fire TV stick to explore if I could use it to “cut the cord” with my cable company. I set everything up, signed up with my Amazon username as usual and started adding apps. Then I decided to explore Prime Video and add some stuff to a watchlist. While doing this, I discovered that my Fire TV stick did not recognize that I was a Prime member. When I tried to explore why the Fire stick did not recognize my Prime account I reached a page which asked me to ‘Explore more’ and it signed ME uup for Prime. I don’t need Prime. I already have it. I have not been able to figure out how to correct this. Perhaps Amazon has designed it this way on purpose, to force every person to have a Prime account even though they supposedly allow spouses/family members to share a Prime account. Sneaky, sneaky. Now I have to cancel MY prime without killing the one my wife signed up with. I wonder what percentage of households have more than one Prime account?My second complaint with the Fire TV stick is that it is not a true cord cutting device. Many of the Apps force you to login with your cable company ID to watch programs. For example, if you have cancelled your cable TV, you can’t use the Fire TV stick to watch a lot of History channel programs because you have to sign in with your cable provider ID. If you are no longer a cable customer, you are stuck. I tried creating a History ID and paring the device, and it still forced me to sign in with my cable TV ID. So much for using my Fire device to cut the cable cord if I can’t still enjoy a few of my favorite cable channels, even if I create a login ID on their App and allow them to track my viewing and monetize me another way.Probably can’t return the Fire TV stick at this point. Probably won’t be using it anymore.",1,49,neutral,0.694145143032074,0.29501599073410034,0.694145143032074,0.010838836431503296,0.2842,0,1924,0,0
Meh. Remote EATS batteries,"I have a love-hate relationship with this Fire TV Stick. I'll start with what I like. I like how Amazon Fire TV devices integrate the various services into the Home screen. I have and have had Roku and AppleTV devices so I have something to compare with and I prefer this over both the Roku and Apple home screens. I like that I bought this on a very good deal on the bottom end of what you'll ever see them priced because it's not worth any more than that.Unfortunately that's about where my love ends. The remote devours batteries like no remote I've ever had for any modern device. I'm now over my one year replacement point by a few days, maybe I should have taken this up with Amazon before. Maybe they should have made the remote a tiny bit larger so that larger capacity AA batteries could be used instead of AAA? Not sure how much extra life that would give since I have other remotes that use AAA batteries and the remotes can go well over a year with batteries. I get 3 months if lucky on this. Also remote feels really cheap. Sometimes when I use it even though the batteries are fresh/good it will refuse to respond to commands from the remote. It just did this in Plex and prompted me to write my review as my frustration was high and reminded me I wanted to write this. Speaking of Plex, which I use not nearly as much as Prime Video or Netflix, it does not work nearly as nice on this as it does on my also low end Roku device. It works maybe better than the Plex app on my 4K LG tv but that's not saying much. Both are always high frustration. Why? Because they are so skimpy with the specs on these things. They need twice the RAM and at least twice the storage capacity. While you can download a lot of media apps for your Fire TV you'll eat up your storage space if you have many installed this really impacts performance it seems. I'd be really happy if they offered devices with better specs and I'd be willing to pay more for that value. They offer the better 4K Stick and Fire TV Cube but the specs on those aren't what you'd expect for the premium you pay but then I'll admit I haven't used one because my only 4k TV is using other options.I also don't care for how quickly it will go into screen saver mode and no ability to change this behavior or even set your own screen saver unless you are subscribed to Amazon Photos apparently. I absolutely hate how fast it will drop out of whatever you have paused, go into screen saver and then drop back to the Home screen. Checking this I see that now there is the ability to change how long before it goes into screen saver which was not there when I looked before, not sure how long it's been there. Rather unforgivable how this is all locked down previously. I was really thinking I'd get a 4K Stick for my LG 4K TV until I used this enough. Come on Amazon, you can do so much better. Not only that but a couple months after I got this model the 2nd gen voice remote came out for the same price. The only difference is the new remote but it'd be nice to have the volume controls on the Fire remote, that is if the efficiency has improved so the batteries last longer than 2-3 months.New reasons to not be happy. I'm about 2 weeks past one year on this and now suddenly it just works terrible. It's locking up too much, needs to be restarted up to a few times a day. Amazon I think you should take care of me on this and replace it. I took off another star due to the behavior the device has exhibited since it's year anniversary. Something needs to happen with it or I'm def not going to buy another Fire TV device of any kind.Feb 2020, that above issue was apparently tied to some update it did as it resolved. All of the quirks these have remain though. Then today a new issue appeared, it would connect to wifi fine as usual but would not indicate a connection to the internet. I've got many devices on our extensive home network and it was the only one that had this issue. Had to make it forget the current wifi setup and then redo it exactly as it was. I'm tech savvy, it's my business, I've never had any device be able to connect to my wifi connection but refuse to see the internet until the old connection setup was forgotten and a new one replicating it was set up. Strange. But then strange surrounds the behavior of this device. I was initially thinking it was somehow dead with some update having corrupted it's ability to connect to Amazon's servers that would likely not be resolvable without an Ethernet connector if even that would do it. Luckily this issue seems common for Fire TV devices where a wifi connection setup must for some reason need to be forgotten and then set up all over again. SMH New experiences in frustration with this thing every week.I won't buy another Amazon Fire TV device. Period. I suggest you buy a Roku for something in the same price ranges. If you really want a good streaming device look at the other more expensive options that include a much more capable Apple TV (especially for 4K owners) or Nvidia Shield for similar ease in plug and play type device. If you're more capable and want the ultimate in flexibility even a PC based solution using an Intel NUC as a starting point or even a suitable desktop or laptop drafted into use as a streaming device directly connected to your TV. I was using this Fire TV because it was all that was needed for my older 32"" 720p Samsung in my office. I definitely prefer the Roku Express+ we have in a similar setup on a 1080p set in a bedroom. That works day in and day out with no suprises without needing to be restarted and fiddled with constantly. The remote on that doesn't eat batteries like this Fire TV stick does either. I really expect more Amazon and it's not just those of us using the low end Fire TV device that have these complaints.",2,50,positive,0.8844513297080994,0.8844513297080994,0.09673336893320084,0.018815262243151665,0.8656,5,5814,0,1
Amazon removed calibrate display adjustments. Serious harm to usability. Otherwise great improvement!,"In addition to the 2nd generation Fire TV Stick (FTVS2) I've previously used the 1st generation model Fire TV Stick (FTVS1). Right off the bat, the FTVS2 fixes my main complaint from the FTVS1. The first gen. stick was a good product, but it lacked the processing power necessary for a consistent smooth user experience; It's slow, ancient (in computer time) dual core processor and anemic GPU were not quite enough to run the Fire TV software + apps. While this new device is an all around improvement, Amazon removed the calibrate display option which is why I've only awarded 2/5 stars. (see below for detail)The FTVS2 (being reviewed here) is dramatically faster thanks to its more modern chipset (Mediatek 8127D). This chipset is nearly identical to the one used in the [[ASIN:B00TSUGXKE 7&#34; Fire tablet]] so if you are familiar with that device the performance is similar.Navigation throughout the Amazon Fire OS interface is no longer a chore; the various pages load much quicker and without causing the rest of the system to hang as was common on FTVS1. Additionally, in apps such as Hulu, NBCSports, YouTube, etc. loading times and graphical stutters are greatly reduced. With the previous model I often found that long load times, and interface choppiness deterred me from using the FTVS1. Luckily with the FTVS2 this is no longer the case.More games are compatible with the new more powerful FTVS2 than the FTVS1, but selection is still lacking compared to whats compatible with the [[ASIN:B00U3FPN4U Fire TV 4K Box]]. If you are looking to use the FTVS2 for games, I would recommend spending the extra $ for the 4K Fire TV box. Games that the FTVS2 can play (ex. [[ASIN:B00QW8TYWO Crossy Road]], [[ASIN:B012GOSOD2 PAC-MAN 256]] amongst others) are much more fluid and enjoyable on the FTVS2 compared to the FTVS1. Unlike FTVS1, Crossy Road is actually worth playing on FTVS2.Compared to the non-voice remote included with my FTVS1, the [[ASIN:B00NO8JJZW Alexa Voice Remote]] is a nice improvement. The directional buttons provide greater resistance which I like, and the 6 buttons below are now rubberized instead of hard plastic. Alexa/voice control works better than I expected, which is crucial because typing anything using the 4-way directional pad is seriously aggravating now that I've seen the voice control light. Compared with the old remote, the Alexa remote seems to pair much quicker than the old simple remote. User reports suggest that the durability of this new remote is sub-par, however I have not owned it long enough to comment on its reliability.Overall this new device is improved in nearly every way compared to the old one. Basically it is a faster version of the same Android based media streamer Amazon released last year. I would highly recommend anyone with FTVS1 consider upgrading to this new model.REASON for 2/5: The FTVS2 ships with a newer version of Fire OS (5.2.2.0) wherein Amazon has removed the &#34;calibrate display&#34; adjustment settings. This setting allows the Fire TV to scale its output to compensate for overscan induced by the TV. My Sony TV (older model) does not allow for adjustments to its default overscan settings, so the outside ~5% of the image from the FTVS2 is cut off. FTVS1 had an option to correct for this by shrinking the image in all dimensions, but FTVS2 does not. Normally this is not a problem as most professionally produced content is aware of typical overscan and therefore does not place any critical content in the outside edges. With the FTVS2 however I am finding it to be a problem as many amateur producers (those on YouTube) assume that their content will be watched on a screen that does not overscan (computers, mobile phones, etc) and therefore place critical elements in the bottom corners/edges where they are cut off by overscan. Users who've talked to Amazon suggest that they will reimplement this feature soon, but as it stands overscan compensation is not available as it was on my previous FTVS1. This may seem like a minor issue, but it makes many youtube videos much harder to watch as tickers, scores, etc are cut off. Additionally, some apps will place toggle switches on the far right of the screen where they are occasionally cut off (ex. ES File Explorer settings). YouTube is one of my main uses for the FTVS, and the overscan compensation option was the main reason I used FTVS1 over the Chromecast I also own (Chromecast has never allowed for such adjustment). I hope Amazon re-adds this feature in an update soon. I will update my review (likely to 5/5) if this is occurs.It should be noted that I am fairly comfortable with consumer tech products. This device to me seems like it would be more difficult to use for those less tech-inclined than rivals like Roku.",2,51,neutral,0.6674113273620605,0.2689553499221802,0.6674113273620605,0.06363328546285629,0.2053,5,4779,0,0
"Bad quality control, bad tech support. Decent product.","For transparency, I'll state that I received a &#34;bad&#34; unit, and Amazon is replacing it. It was on back order for three weeks, so obviously their manufacturing couldn't keep up with the holiday demand.The unit kind of / sort of worked, so I feel comfortable giving a review. Amazon did, however, lose 3 stars right off the bat because they sent me a defective unit and made is so hard to get a replacement. Their manufacturing quality control needs improvement, and their tech support is horrible (more below).This unit has a built-in 802.11 radio (Wi-Fi), and the same circuitry also provides the Bluetooth interface, which is what the remote works on. Mine was faulty, so when the remote worked, it worked great, and when it didn't work, neither the network nor the remote work. Somewhat heat related, but it was out in the open, so either bad manufacturing and / or bad design.Pros:* I've been using my Logitech Revue (Google TV) for the past 5 years, primarily to watch Netflix, and to stream movies from a SAMBA (Windows) network drive share. It has worked great for that, but Amazon stopped supporting live streaming to Google TV, and turned the service off. This unit supports Amazon Live Streaming, and it works great for that (when it works).* Install was very easy. Plug in to an open HDMI port, and plug in the microUSB power adapter. Put the batteries in the remote, and you're all set.* Set up started out nice. My remote kept dropping, but going through the setup was painless. It was already set up for my Amazon account, so all I had to do was sign in to my wireless network.* GUI is intuitive and straight-forward. I didn't read any manuals, and it only took a minute or so to find a show and start streaming it.* The Android app for your smart phone is a nice touch, although your smart phone doesn't make that nice of a remote.* Voice recognition works great. This is what makes the device so easy to use. If you can't figure out how to do something, just use the voice recognition feature.Cons:* No off button. This thing is on 24/7. No way to shut it off.* Cannot control TV / Audio Receiver with the remote. With my Logitech Revue, I could control the TV, Audio Receiver, cable box, etc., all with one remote. Now I'm back to having 3 remotes sitting on the side table. It would have been so easy to include an IR transmitter on the remote.* In the GUI itself, when you click on a Netflix show, it just takes you to the Netflix app. It doesn't start playing that show. You have to then manually search for the show.* Cannot listen to music with the TV off. If you turn the TV off, since the audio streams through the TV, you lose audio. Technically, if you have an HDMI ready audio receiver, you can plug the unit into the back of the audio receiver and then listen to music with the TV off.* Music experience was only so-so. I wasn't impressed. If you were listening to music, went back to the home screen, and tried to go back to the music, it would stop the song and start playing another.* Buttons use symbols instead of text. I know, Amazon is trying to make this universal globally, but usability suffers, especially at first.* It's almost impossible to get a replacement if you get a bad unit. First you have to email customer service, and then you have to go to tech support, and then you have to escalate to a supervisor because tech support isn't allowed to make that kind of decision. Ugh.* Customer service / support was terrible. First of all, you're speaking to someone in India, or recently from India, so you have to work through that heavy accent while they read from a script. (Feels like you're talking to a scam person, because they are generally from India as well, and are just reading from a script). Nothing against people from India as I have several friends from India, but I do wish Amazon would support US jobs instead of sending them offshore to India. Second, tech support really doesn't know much about the device, and nothing about electronics. They were totally lost when I said the radio (Wi-Fi / BT) wasn't working. &#34;Radio? This is for a TV, not a radio.&#34; All they can do is read (barely) from a script, and ask you to go through all of the troubleshooting steps, even if you've already gone through them yourself, multiple times. Honestly, it was worse than talking to tech support from Verizon, and that's pretty bad. Finally, after wasting 15 minutes on the phone with them, they agree to send a new unit, but then say it will take 3-4 weeks to send it. Seriously? Someone really screwed up when planning the manufacturing. They didn't have a clue what the demand would look like.",2,52,negative,0.7271466851234436,0.03035658597946167,0.24249668419361115,0.7271466851234436,-0.6968,7,4654,1,0
It's ok... but app support is what kills it,"I have been using a Roku device for several years now. I've upgraded to different rokus over the years to suit my needs, including the roku stick for easy portability when I travel. I received the Amazon Fire Stick for my birthday and I'll be honest, it feels very sub-standard to today's standards.My experience from start to finish:1: unboxing - this actually felt really nice! the way that it was packaged and everything just felt amazing. almost as good as unboxing a new iphone or ipad.2: connecting to TV - When I first plugged it in to my Samsung Plasma TV's HDMI and USB port, I was greeted with a not-enough-power message. So I was forced to use the power adapter. No big deal, just annoying as a plug-and-play feature.3: first run - I expected some sort of boot updates to happen, but it took about 30 minutes to get to some sort of setup screen where I could properly interact with the device. My speed is over 200Mbps, so that was definitely not the issue. Then it took another 30 minutes to an hour to get the device finally ready to use after many tedious configurations and additional updates and reboots.4: security - this is one feature I am sort of happy about. The ability to need to input a pin every time an app is going to be run is good for preventing kids from using the device outside permitted time frames. it's annoying that I have to enter it every single time I need to enter each and every app while that feature is enabled. But it is a good step in the right direction.5: parental control / child profiles - this is interesting and I actually appreciate it. However, when I enabled it, everything slowed down to a crawl, device kept on crashing and there were no visual queues of what was going on, so the remote felt unresponsive multiple times without any idea of what was happening. I like the idea, but the method of switching back and forth is too hidden and needs a better UI and UX.6: app support - there are many apps and that is good. some work better than others. some just work almost the same across platforms, but others..... others just have the annoying requirement of being a trial version and must be purchased or your experience will end there. I have probably been too spoiled by roku as the same apps I use on these other devices don't require a payment or subscription.6.2 app support | emby/plex - so, I use my emby home media servers to stream to my devices. Everything was great and felt mostly the same but then the trial notice was very obvious. I was too used to never seeing it on my roku. When I went to emby's site, the firestick does indeed require a separate purchase just to work past its trial. I am not going to do that for this and the other channels that require it.7: remote control - it feels nice on the hand, but to be honest, I don't like microphones on my remotes and I cannot find any option on how to completely disable it so I am checking as many options to block it. Even if it supposedly only works after the button is pushed, I don't want it. It is not a feature I want at all. But that may just be me. The other issue that I have had with the remote, is that in the middle of watching a movie, when I wanted to pause, the remote suddenly stopped working and had to search various sites to figure out why it was not working. After a while, I found that pressing the HOME button for 10 seconds would link it again... but that is just too inconvenient.Final Words:While the amazon firestick is fast, works relatively well and has a good amount of streaming channels to choose from; unless you have a prime account or spend extra on some channels, it just doesn't wow me enough. I'm going to buy a new 4k roku stick to replace this one and just hook it to one of the extra tvs around the house.If I were to compare it to the roku, apple tv and my lg smart tv, or even my brother's samsung smart tv... the Roku is the absolute winner from start to finish in user experience. Unlike all the other options above, I was able to use it within 5 minutes of unboxing it. Also, when I travel to south america, the fire stick is just a lifeless stick with very limited channel support, making it less than useless for international travel to Ecuador.I would not recommend it, but if you already have it, for basic streaming it should be good enough.",2,53,positive,0.6251716613769531,0.6251716613769531,0.35297197103500366,0.021856434643268585,0.6033,5,4317,0,1
"Was a Great Toy, now Amz/Google Fight makes it Annoying.","[[ASIN:B00ZV9RDKK Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote | Streaming Media Player]]01/08/18 - Update: I've taken off two stars. I no longer like this device and will likely replace it. Amazon and Google got in a tiff and we customers are the losers. Google has taken away from Amazon support for their YouTube app. In order to access YT now with your Fire you have to download a web browser (Silk or Firefox are currently recommended), and navigate to youtube.com. Using the site instead of the app is different. I find the video playback is poor with lots more stutter and streaming issues. Navigation of videos is more difficult than it used to be. And worst of all, I can no longer use the YT app on my portable devices (phone, iPad, etc.) to control the YT app on my Fire. Doing that was a great way to use the Fire, namely because searching via the virtual keyboard on my device was super easy, and I could easily take YT links I'd acquired on my device in Facebook, texts, emails, etc., push them through the device app, and play them on my TV through the Fire. I used to do this a lot. I can no longer. Disappointing. Note: You *can* activate Youtube for TV which gives you some access to your Google YT account on your Fire's browser, so that's nice, but it's not as good as it was.Original Review:Works great, but not perfect (ie 4 stars). Minor imperfections:1) For no apparent reason, about 1 in 5 times, it takes a subjectively long time to open an app (like YouTube, Netflix, or CBS All Access). I'm fairly certain there's nothing wrong with my WiFi or ISP during these times (I'm an IT Professional by trade, I run a tight ship, and I don't see any failures in those areas during these long loads.). It's probably only 20-30 seconds, so not really that long, but when compared to the otherwise apparent instant app opening, one tends to notice these slow opens.2) This device's voice commands/search are unimpressive. Too many times, I'm given a &#34;does-not-compute&#34;-like response or given results that have nothing to do with my request. Navigating by the click wheel is smooth/fast, though. This is my first Amazon voice device, so it is possible we've got some user-error going on here, but I'm well-versed in (and LOVE!) Google Now and Siri (Overrated, IMHO) voice tech, and do great with those, so to have to re-learn how to speak to this device is annoying.3) I once noticed the audio was out of sync while watching an Amazon Prime The Tick episode. I tried a few things to sync up the audio, what finally worked was that I stopped the episode, started another, and then went back to the previous episode, and the audio was synced. All other content I've watched (including the rest of The Tick series, and a couple dozen hours of other material throughout several apps) has been fine.4) There's no way to Turn Off the device. It's just always on (though it will go into a sleep mode eventually). The minute electrical consumption worries aside, I can't help but occasionally feel I need to wear my aluminum foil hat, like I'm being Watched (uh Listened To) 24/7. LOLUpsides are that it's normally fast and responsive (the above notwithstanding) with bright and colorful, easy-to-navigate menus. It is small (the remote is actually bigger than the device itself). Mine came with a couple-inch-long extension cable, and using that, I've got it hooked directly into an HDMI port on the back of my receiver, and I &#34;tune&#34; to it, by changing inputs as I would when switching between my Cable, PS3, or BD player. It also has a separate A/C power adaptor cable that connects to it and the other end to a standard outlet on my AV Power Strip. So it's easy to install physically. Once on, the onscreen setup was simple, too (the &#34;hardest&#34; part was navigating the onscreen keyboard to type-in my obnoxiously long and complicated WiFi password, lol).Don't let the above imperfection list be a turn off. It's a good device, and for the price, well worth it if you're in the market for such a toy. It's just a couple hiccups away from perfection. Thumbs Up. -- 01/08/18 Edit - I'm really annoyed with this toy after the YouTube debacle. Thumbs Down.",2,54,negative,0.7199407815933228,0.018070923164486885,0.2619883120059967,0.7199407815933228,-0.7019,5,4177,1,0
4x2 inch slice of hell,"The Amazon Fire TV stick is not a horrible product, I find it nice because I am a Prime member, and I have subscriptions to Hulu, Netflix, and Crunchyroll (if you don't already subscribe to streaming services, you probably won't find this product useful). Having all these apps available for me to use on my tv instead of on my computer is great, and if the Fire TV stick actually worked, I might really like it. But it just doesn't.I received my first Amazon Fire TV stick in December, it broke within three weeks, and I am currently on my second, which has also stopped working after 2 months. The issues between the two, while not exactly the same, are similar enough for me to consider a similar cause.The first TV Stick would halt in the middle of playing any type of video, the picture would skip, a ringing noise would come out of the speaker, and then it would shut down and disconnect from the tv completely. From that point it would take hours (usually done over the course of a week, because I would want to break something after 30 or so minutes) of plugging the stick into different HDMI ports, unplugging the power and reconnecting the power, using the HDMI extender or plugging the stick directly in to just get my tv to recognize the device again. If I was able to get this far, the device usually had reset to factory settings so I had to start registration again, re-install and log into apps before I could use it. Then, the whole entire process would begin again after about five hours worth of use. After three weeks of this, I finally called the help line, which of course, while friendly, was absolutely no help. So I was sent a new Fire TV Stick.This second Fire TV stick actually lasted about twice as long as the first (but really, is two months worth of use something to get excited over) before it decided to fail. The issues with this stick began with the device disconnecting from my tv in the middle of being used, and then my tv was no longer able to recognize the device. For a week this could be fixed with about thirty minutes worth of effort of disconnecting and unplugging the device to let it restart before trying a different HDMI port. But still, I had to do this every time I wanted to use it, so I stopped using it. Because I was annoyed with being unable to use something I purchased, I tried using the force restart and force reset through the fire tv stick remote, which actually had the device working for a full two days. After this, the new issue popped up, where the fire tv stick would suddenly reboot while a video was playing and go back to the home screen. After a day of this, the next time I tried to use it, it got stuck in the &#34;boot-loop&#34; either staying on the white Amazon logo screen or the FireTV screen. This issue has now added this nice order of events ... I try to connect to the device and the tv says &#34;no signal&#34;, after a couple of minutes it boots to the white Amazon logo screen, this screen is in place for about a minute and then I get the &#34;no signal&#34; reading again, this then goes back to the white Amazon logo, and we finally end on the &#34;Amazon system recovery&#34; command line screen, which does not go away. After getting in contact with the Fire TV help people who were once again, very pleasant but absolutely no help (I mean really, its real hard to keep your cool when the questions you get asked are &#34;is the HDMI cable connected, but not connected too tight?&#34;, &#34;is it plugged in?&#34;, &#34;did you select the correct device on the tv?&#34;, &#34;do the batteries in the remote work?&#34;) I am now being sent a HDMI extender, because this should solve the problem (100% certain that this will not help the issue in the slightest, but whatever).If this does not work, I will be sent my third new Fire TV Stick. I do not want a new fire TV stick, I never want to see one again in my life, I am probably never going to be able to use a streaming device again because it will lead to PTSD-like flashbacks of all the downtime that was consumed by this little 4x2 inch slice of hell.",2,55,positive,0.6711651682853699,0.6711651682853699,0.2338002324104309,0.09503462165594101,0.5761,4,4098,0,1
A Customer Service Nightmare,"Amazon Fire TV Stick.Overall I like this little Android operating system device. But, that being said. The warranty that is not listed on their page is only 90 days. I bought four of these devices and for the most part was happy with their performance. Till one decided not to turn on. I called customer service, in the Philippines, and after a few minutes of trying to figure out which one failed and then going through a list of troubleshooting steps, they finally told me it was out of warranty. I asked how long the warranty was. The lady on the other end told me that it was 90 days. She then proceeded to apologize for the problem and offered a 15% discount and asked if I was all right with that. I told that I guessed that I had no other option than to accept that offer. She then apologized again and said that if I ordered now she would give me a 25% discount on the device. I told her that I really could not afford to replace it now. She then said it would only be about $20. Well that was do able and I agreed to stay on the phone with her while I placed the order. She told me the discount would automatically apply when I got to the review order screen. When I finally got to the review order screen the total was over $41 and I told her that I could not do that right now. She told me that they have seen that before and that the discount would be applied after I placed the order. I asked if she was going to guarantee that the correct amount would come off my card. She said it has worked for other customers. I asked to speak with a supervisor and she had go through all the steps for placing the order. Same total came up. She told me to go ahead and check out and if it was wrong she would give me a refund of the over charge. If you have ever gotten a refund back on a credit card then you know it can take at least 10 days to process. Now, during all of this they kept saying on an item fulfilled by Amazon. Well, right there in blue letters it said Amazon. It did not say Joe's Electronics or something to that effect. Well, I asked her if she was going to guarantee that the correct amount would come off my card. She said yes. I placed the order. My credit card let me know through email when a charge goes through and for how much. My cell phone alerts me that a charge went through for over $41. I am pissed at this point and asked for someone in the States. She transfers me to a gentleman in Georgia who is a customer service manager and told him everything. He then told me after looking at the order that they could not give that type of discount on the order since it is not 100% fulfilled by Amazon. He then told me that the blue letters are the clue, and, that if they had been properly trained they would have known this. He then told me that he would personally take care of it and if he had to he would give me the $20 personally. That was August 14, 2018. Have not heard from him since. I get an email from Kathi Raven at Amazon giving me a 100% discount on the Fire TV Stick and to use the attached link to place the order. I click on the link and it takes me to the same item, I select it and go to my shopping cart to complete the order. When I finally got to the review order screen the total was over $41 again. I cleared my cart and started over again just in case. Same result. The email stated that they hoped that this would resolve the problem. I replied to the email and told her that the discount could not be applied to this item, and that the only way I would be satisfied would be to ship me another for free with no strings.Now, to be fair, I would have just ordered another when I could afford it at full price and been done with it. It would be hypocritical of me to belittle a warranty. But, after the crap I was put through I felt my time involved with this was worth more than a Fire TV Stick.Still like my remaining devices.",2,56,positive,0.6092957854270935,0.6092957854270935,0.30212897062301636,0.08857524394989014,0.5207,2,3885,0,1
Has a long way to go for the basic features I was looking for. Doesn't play well with others yet. UI looks like a giant ad.,"I've had some version of Apple TV for at least 5 years and when they added the voice button in the Gen 4 I was super excited thinking I was finally going just be able to tell Siri what I wanted to happen on the TV &#34;Siri: Open Netflix, pause, resume, search for 'X'&#34; etc. Alas, that's still not possible and with my self-proclaimed luddite mother about to be watching my 2 year old regularly I wanted a TV that could take voice commands that I could just write down for her. Enter: Fire TV Stick with Alexa.Now this actually wasn't the first Alexa enabled device I've purchased. I purchased an Echo Tap for my wife's birthday a few months earlier and we just use it like a regular Echo by leaving it in &#34;hands free mode&#34; and constantly plugged into the wall, but we COULD take it on the go if we wanted. The Alexa I had come to know through that device more than capably handled interfacing with every member of the family, managing my music and playing it back through a (surprisingly) nice compact speaker. Not so with the Fire Stick.First complaint: No Youtube App. I got this just as the whole Google/Amazon drama was coming to a head and wasn't super versed in the situation at the time I placed the order. As a parent of a small child who can only be immobilized by certain youtube videos in emergencies, when I got it out of the box and saw that it no longer had the Youtube app and they had instead replaced it with a shortcut to the desktop version of the site I almost sent it back right then and there. With my wife's first day back at work after having our son fast approaching I decided to keep trying despite this massive deficiency right out of the box.Second complaint: No &#34;hands free mode&#34;. You must push the button on the remote to talk to Alexa. Now, to be fair, I knew this going in, but I also knew that you could use a Dot or other Echo device to control the Firestick if you set it up right. This is maybe 20% accurate. Yes, there are settings on all the devices I've mentioned that should allow Alex to take commands from any speaker and run them on any connected, Alexa-enabled device, but ultimately the Fire Stick controls were SEVERLY lacking. The syntax needed was far too specific, there were few if any skills available for our most-used app applications... basically, it technically worked, but it never really &#34;worked&#34;.Third and final complaint: The advertising. In an age where every TV comes with Netflix, Hulu, HBO Go, and Amazon Prime Video apps pre-installed out of the box why in god's name should I spend $50 extra dollars on an additional piece of equipment (no matter how small) to access all of those COMMERCIAL FREE services over a device that has so many ads built into the UI it's hard to tell what's an app and what's an ad that's going to launch you down a rabbit hole of product advertisements. The whole interface was just so overwhelmingly littered with banners and unsolicited trailers and advertisements that I dreaded returning to the home menu for anything. This was truly what broke the camel's back for me.In my opinion, the Fire Stick is only going to satisfy a small subset of people who meet one or more of the following criteria: 1.) don't have a smart enough TV to run streaming apps natively 2.) Hate Apple and/or don't have the money to spend on a new Apple TV 3.) Have accepted that our world was turned into a capitalist hellscape long ago and have had the part of their brain irritated by a constant barrage of advertising callused over permanently. 4.) Monsters who like to renew their Amazon Pantry &#34;Tuck's Medicated Hemorrhoid Pads&#34; on the largest most public screen in their house instead of via the Amazon phone app like the rest of civilized humanity.",2,57,positive,0.6709215044975281,0.6709215044975281,0.2700442671775818,0.05903424695134163,0.6119,5,3763,0,1
"Great hardware, but choked to death with ads","Well, the good news is that the hardware works fine. Setup was easy, it streams very well over a not terribly fast WiFi connection. So I'd happily give the hardware 5 stars. Amazon's software deserves zero stars.The system menu was apparently designed by the Marketing Dept. You have to wade through dozens and dozens of things Amazon wants you to watch in order to find what should be right on top.Be aware that every different channel seems to have entirely different standards for logging on. Some will just play. Some make you go to their website on a computer to enter a code before the channel will play. Some force you to sign up (giving out an email address that will result in spam). At least one channel demanded my cable account number and password. Guess what? I don't HAVE a cable provider! My landlord has a cable provider. So, apparently no one who rents an apartment is allowed to watch that channel?Be prepared to spend hours trying to set up individual channels. Be prepared to sit through just as many commercials as over-the-air TV. Plus being forced to sit through previews for stuff you may not even want to see. Be aware that some channels will only allow you to see the episodes that they pick out, rather than the ones you actually wanted to watch.BTW, Fast Forward only works on the shows and movies, not the commercials. You WILL watch the commercials, whether you want to or not. The remote doesn't have a Mute button. Some of the commercials are coded so you can't even use the pause button to shut them up.This device could be improved about 1000% if Amazon designed the control layout to act as a TV remote instead of using it to try to push sales of other channels. The Internet Streaming experience could greatly improved it Amazon and Google called a truce long enough to come out with a common standard for logging on to Internet streams, etc. This would benefit everybody.Overall, I'm glad that I got the cheapest Firestick that Amazon makes. I don't regret buying it, but once my Prime subscription has expired I will happily replace it with something, anything, that has a less obnoxious interface. Seriously, the more that I use this device, the more that I despise it. Amazon and the various internet Channels have the thing so choked up with advertising that you can't use it. You literally sometimes cannot navigate to a channel or show you want to watch, because there are so many ads in the way.I've been using various Android devices for years, and this is hands down the worst interface I've ever used. Again, the hardware does a great job of playing streaming video. The underlying Android system is not the problem. But you have to fight your way through at least two or three commercials before you can do ANYTHING. I would not recommend this product to anyone, unless they had no other way to watch TV.Oh, and yes, I understand that ad supported devices are cheaper because the advertisers pay the costs. I don't object to watching a few commercials before a movie or TV show. I DO object to being forced to watch several commercials before I can even locate the show to watch. I object to the menu system being so cluttered up with ads that you can't find what you're looking for.",2,58,positive,0.8338286280632019,0.8338286280632019,0.12904329597949982,0.03712806478142738,0.7967,0,3231,0,1
Fails to work with Amazon Drive service properly (Review will be updated),"This was my 2nd Fire Stick. I have the original model one. While the original one works great, this &#34;all-new&#34; one has significant issues for those people who use the Amazon Drive service.I currently have 107,000+ photos/videos and 1400+ folders on my Amazon Drive. My original Fire Stick displays all items in my Amazon Drive. However, this 2nd Fire Stock only lists there being 20,000 or so items in my Amazon Drive and only about 700 folders. I noticed that this new Fire Stick came with a newer, 5.2.2.0, OS than my old Fire Stick. I did a factory reset on the unit and tried again; same amount of missing items. I called Amazon support on 11/25/16 and spoke with Corey R. I explained to him my issue and he gave me some basic troubleshooting steps; all of which I had done previously. He said he was going to contact the Fire Stick tech team for more support. To Corey's credit, he's been calling me every 2 days with an update. Unfortunately the updates are &#34;The tech team has not found anything wrong or have been unable to replicate the issue.&#34; On 12/8/16, the Fire Stick received a new OS (5.2.4.0). I checked my Amazon Drive on the Fire Stick and the same limited amount of files are listed. Meanwhile, my original Fire Stick works just fine and displays all Amazon Drive contents. NOTE: My original Fire Stick is still on an older Fire OS (5.2.1.1). It doesn't report needing a new OS. Furthermore, the new Fire Stick will not authenticate to my 5 Ghz wireless network, only my 2.4 Ghz wireless network. It will connect to the 5 Ghz network, attempt to authenticate with my supplied WPA key, and then connect/disconnect multiple times and then report &#34;Failed to authenticate.&#34; My older Fire Stick (and all of my other devices) works fine on both (and is primarily on the 5 Ghz network).I will attempt to update the review as long as this issue occurs or until it is resolved (which I feel won't be for a long time). Everything else works fine on this new Fire Stick except for accessing Amazon Drive files completely.UPDATE: 12/16/16 - Corey R., from Amazon, has placed an exchange order on my behalf for a replacement Amazon Fire Stick. When it arrives I'll test it out with my Amazon Drive account.UPDATE: 12/23/16 - I received the replacement Amazon Fire Stick. Same exact issues (as expected) with my Amazon Drive files and the Fire Stick. I returned the original &#34;all new&#34; Fire Stick and have the replacement one hooked up. In speaking with Corey R. I asked if the Fire TV uses the same OS as the &#34;all new&#34; Fire Stick; it does. The problem is definitely the OS and not the hardware. Amazon tech support just isn't understanding that. Corey R. stated he will follow up further with Amazon Fire tech support.UPDATE: 12/28/16 - No real update from Amazon. I still get the same email from Corey R. every 2 days (&#34;It is taking longer than usual to resolve your issue. Please wait another 1 - 2 business days for more information&#34;). I then get a call from Corey R., he tells me the same info, and that he'll call me back in 2 days time. It is like clockwork. The other consistent thing is that the problem has still not been fixed.",2,59,neutral,0.4699360132217407,0.10581652820110321,0.4699360132217407,0.4242474436759949,-0.3184,7,3188,0,0
Cord Cutting that (almost) worked,"This will be a somewhat lengthy review of my firesticks, which I've had for almost a year now. After deciding to cut the cord I've saved a ton of money and the sticks paid for themselves in less than a month. If I had written this review when I first purchased and began using the firesticks, I have no doubt I would have given them 4 if not 5 stars. They were responsive, easy to navigate, and having access to my music and videos through my entertainment center was fantastic.Then Amazon pushed a software update.Since that update, 2 factory resets, continual clearing of the devices' cache and application data, and constant restarts, I can honestly say I am more than a little peeved about their performance. The sticks were working GREAT before, video was crisp, it loaded fast, and the voice remote was responsive and usually only took a couple of seconds to reveal the results of my searches. Now, loading my streaming TV service (I use PlaystationVue) can take several minutes... just for the home screen to populate. The guide takes another several minutes to fill and switching between channels makes it almost prohibitive to do so. This was never a problem when I first began using the firesticks. (By the way, my internet speed is 50Mbps download on wireless and 100Mbps hardwired... there's no issues there). What frequently happens after an hour or two of watching TV (primarily sports) is that the service will freeze, my firestick no longer recognizes my internet connection and I have to go through the incredibly annoying process of deleting the application cache, restarting the device, and sometimes even restarting my router to get my service back. Again, my internet is NOT the problem. This service never behaved like that before the update.Next, the voice search isn't usable anymore. More often than not the search query will lag out after a minute of thinking. I don't bother anymore. This wouldn't be a big deal if it weren't for the fact that it's the easiest way to search for a movie, tv show, or music I want played.Hulu, Netflix, Prime video, and any other streaming service are laggy, take forever to load, and have frequent service interruptions - all new issues (sensing a theme here?).In an effort to combat the issues that have popped up since the software push (assuming that's the issue and if it is SHAME ON YOU AMAZON!!!!!! You're no better than Apple if you're pulling that crap - and don't think I didn't notice that the firetv cube came out around the same time.) I have deleted everything from my firesticks except my TV service, Netflix, and Hulu. It hasn't helped.I LOVED my firesticks before, which is why I was willing to grab the FireTV when it went on a surprise sale the other day. Hopefully the faster device will return my services to the way they were before. I'm giving Amazon ONE chance. If Amazon pulls this ""drop an update prior to a new device and kill the performance of their old devices, thereby forcing users to buy new equipment they didn't need or want"" stuff (like Apple) I will cancel Prime. Big deal, right? Maybe I'll write someone like Senator Warren of MA who actually cares about consumer protection, too.",2,60,positive,0.8766731023788452,0.8766731023788452,0.11440669745206833,0.008920187130570412,0.8678,7,3178,0,1
"Underwhelmed, at best","I purchased an Amazon Fire TV stick a couple months ago, mostly because it was cheaper than a new Roku and because I was enticed by the Alexa voice control. I've had a Roku for the past few years and have been very happy with it, but I moved it to another TV and thought a Fire stick, thinking it might be just as good, if not better. Sadly, I've grown very frustrated with it. Here are some of the main reasons:1) Many of the apps won't load or function properly. Sometimes they work fine, but other times they lead to a blank gray screen or just fritz out upon trying to load and return you to the Fire stick's main menu, despite multiple attempts. Certain apps have this problem more than others. The most notable ones I can think of off the top of my head are Pandora, Newsy, WatchESPN, FOXNow, HBONow, PBSKids, and occasionally Netflix. Normally I might think it was a problem on the app developer end, but with so many different ones having issues, it seems it must be an Amazon problem. All the same apps are consistently working fine on our Roku.2) The font size on many of the apps is annoyingly small. As in, I can barely read some app menus from 10 feet away (and I have 20/20 vision). And my TV is 48&quot;, so it's not like the text is shrinking to fit a small screen.3) The main menu is cluttered and annoying, often shoving Amazon content down my throat when I just want to be able to get to my self-selected and downloaded apps. It is not nearly as simple or intuitive as the Roku's main menu. I get that Amazon wants to frontload its own content, but it's just causing resentment.4) Certain apps are requiring me to activate them almost EVERY time I try to use them. They ask me to put in an activation code with my cable provider info nearly every other day. WTF? Why can't it retain my cable provider info?5) Some apps I can't even get on the Fire stick. In particular, I've searched and searched for the AMC app, but it doesn't appear to exist for Amazon (or they are withholding it?). Accordingly, I have to switch rooms when I want to use the AMC app, which is annoying. The Roku has the AMC app, which works without issue.6) Music apps keep playing even when I exit them. Perhaps some people would like this, but I find it annoying and distracting. If I've exited the music app, it's because I want to do something else and don't want/need the music to continue.To be fair, when things are working smoothly, the Fire TV stick's video quality is good. And the Alexa voice control is a sometimes nifty shortcut. And the Amazon Music app is notably better than on the Roku (no surprise there). And the remote is sleek and works well. But overall, there are just too many inconveniences and drawbacks for it to be worthwhile. I'll probably put up with it for a little longer, in hopes the issues will straighten out. But if they don't, I might have to go back to the reliable Roku.Anyway, I love Amazon for many of its other services and online shopping, but this Fire TV stick is just not cutting it. Might need to give it to my dog as a chew toy.",2,61,positive,0.42901432514190674,0.42901432514190674,0.39855343103408813,0.17243227362632751,0.2566,5,3067,0,1
Worked alright for awhile but...,"I now need to hard-restart the unit at least once a day every day now because the video playback straight-up does not work. Everything about the menus -- all the menus in all the apps I use regularly, including the autoplay trailers in Netflix -- is always totally fine. But, once I actually click a show or movie, one of two things happen: Either the audio still plays fine but there's just a blank black screen (most common), or the images play fine but the audio comes through at like 1/10th the speed its supposed to so everything sounds all garbled. Restarting the unit makes everything work again for 3-12 hours, but it's still a huge pain in the ass because (a) the menus *stop* working perfectly fine after clicking on a video so the only way to restart is to manually pull the plug on the hardware which is extremely inconvenient given the product's form factor and how my TV is mounted; and, (b) it takes 3-4+ minutes for the thing to restart. Maybe that last part is just a problem with my device, but either way it sure seems like a product *designed to play audiovisual material* should reliably do that. For those reasons I gave the product 1 star for stream quality: although it's fine when it works something that consistently doesn't work is not ""quality"" in my book.That's all I was originally going to say in this review, but since it also asked me to give stars to its voice recognition and Alexa integration I'll touch briefly on those things too. To start with a major caveat that almost certainly affects my user experience: I hate Alexa as a concept. I think the idea of an always-on microphone in my *bedroom* that one of the world's largest conglomerates can listen to whenever they want is terrifying and dystopian, and I do not trust Amazon to ethically, effectively protect and respect my data or personal space. I have therefore only very rarely used the voice features, and only when I first got the stick and was more trusting of the tech. I therefore acknowledge that it never got a chance to build a substantial database on my voice, which almost certainly impacted the accuracy and utility of those features. That said, the few times I did use it were frustrating and dumb. Part of that is due to the fact that it really seemed to have a hard time accurately transcribing what I was saying (even though I have a standard American male accent). The other part of that is because Amazon's search feature just kind of sucks, which is still a problem even though I use the remote to manually type out my searches these days. Searches often return irrelevant or tangentially-related results, and gives no preference to titles I've purchased and put in my library (e.g. I've bought several films that include bonus features and not only do I hate having to scroll through a bunch of other search results to find the one I own, but my wife often doesn't know or recall which version I've purchased or whether I've purchased something which has resulted in us owning a couple versions of some things).",2,62,negative,0.7559655904769897,0.03413863480091095,0.20989570021629333,0.7559655904769897,-0.7218,5,3028,1,0
"Problems since day one, not even a year old purchase.","At first it worked fairly well (by the way my current device isn't even a year old so that should give you some perspective) then it quickly started to just restart itself during full length movies or shows. Nothing seemed to be the cause though I would feel the HDMI stick and I found that it was extremely hot for a simple plug in device. Part of the issue is that there is no way to shut it off or restart it manually when it starts messing up, one time I was stuck in a pure freeze, the device literally locked up and I had no real way to shut it down or anything short of completely removing the device from it's power source and the HDMI outlet. That seemed to help but the problem would continue unless I kept the thing unplugged all the time until I was ready to use it, not much of a solution if you ask me, what's the point of having something like this if you have to first plug the thing in every single time?Now I just wanted to watch a 30 minute show or something, I turn it on and suddenly it just says ""Optimizing system storage and applications.."" and as it turns out this seems to be a fairly common error. I attempted to fix this but there also appears not to be any constant fix for it and the normal means of stopping the Firestick from doing things that you don't want (unplugging it) failed to fix the problem. I've tried a few different tips but so far nothing, currently it is out of the HDMI port and on my couch. Upon plugging the device back in and powering it back up after about 10 minutes it still went into the ""Optimizing system storage and applications.."" loop so I'm fairly confident that the Firestick is a loss..When you just want to watch some TV and the device consistently bugs out, freezes, has some kind of an infinite loop and goodness knows what else I'd say you have a major quality control problem. If you do buy this thing get ready for a lot of problems as it seems Amazon, a billion dollar company, can not seem to get simple parts and QC done properly so as to deliver a reliable product to their paying customers. There's nothing quite like having a rough night, getting out of bed to watch a show or two before you try falling back to sleep again only for the device to cause you to stay up for 2+ hours trying to troubleshoot it, unsuccessfully I might add.*edit* after talking to Amazon support for just 15 minutes I was told that ""we've expended all of our premade steps and found that your device is past warranty therefore we can only ask you to rebuy the device with a 15% discount"". What a joke! What's the warranty period 10 days after purchase? and you want me to just rebuy a device thinking that you, Amazon, deserve my money again when you can't even guarantee me that your ""new"" device will function any better then my original one?!",2,63,neutral,0.5310785174369812,0.37963607907295227,0.5310785174369812,0.08928537368774414,0.2904,7,2798,0,0
"Good start, leaves a horrible taste in your mouth.","When I first bought this item, the product seemed promising. It contained all the software like Slingplayer, Netflix, Plex, and so on that I needed all at a relatively low cost. It felt suprisingly sprite, in comparison to my old (revived) Apple Tv 2nd gen (more on this later). After a year and a half, the firestick has become unuseable. The wifi receiver has never really been that great, but it seems that over time it gets worse? The software updates have made the fire stick unuseable, and it is buggy with jumpy frame rates. It takes so long to respond - each touch of the button is delayed so much - that you often wind up selecting the wrong app, movie, etc. This was used primarily on my office tv, and I have not watched anything reliably for a year or so. I can get the firestick to work around 20% of the time to stream something. It isn’t a wifi issue as I have done a number of diagnostic tests and we have a high strength signal with substantial bandwidth.Then, I plugged my old Apple Tv 2nd gen in and viola!!! It connected superfast to the wifi, and was updated instanteously with Amazon Prime video. The Apple Tv 2nd gen felt super fast and most importantly - I could navigate with no delay - connect with no problem - and watch on demand.I want to be clear, I love Apple products - but I am not blind to their problems. Amazon’s vision of getting cheap products in our hands to maximize their retail margins have been largely hit or miss. I love low cost tech that does a lot (see Echo), but sometimes you pay a price when a company is spread too thin. Their Kindle products are fine - just wish they created a larger format. Echo line is good. Wish their video cameras were more transparent abour security (still uncomfortable with putting their camera in my home as of now). Their firestick is simply a letdown. Google searches will tell you the reason the Apple Tv (older gens) last longer than the Fire stick is simply Amazon’s commitment to cheaper thus inferior components. You pay a cheap price for something to last a year or so.Here is my Apple fanboy coming out - Apple makes products that last. I know there are a lot of haters - but I use both PC’s and Macs daily (largely due to work). I have found that Mac’s make the most reliable PC. I know their laptops do not have touchscreens (this still sucks!) but their products are workhorses. I have a 2012 Macbook Air that I cannot replace because it is still killing it. Same with their Apple Tv. Do yourself a favor, pay a little more. You will be thankful you did. (This goes for the Apple Tv 4K - I have it - it works as it should. It may not overcome the evils of cable companies though)",2,64,positive,0.5211575031280518,0.5211575031280518,0.3740963041782379,0.10474617779254913,0.4164,5,2671,0,1
Not a finished product,"So here it is, the Fire TV, and well I have to give it 2 stars, here is why.The product is ok (let us say 3 stars) for the basic user a little Netflix, Hulu and some Prime Video in the mix, but stray but a little and you will find a unfinished and very poorly designed product.First of all, the remote, as much as it feels nice and light in your hand, it lacks the premium features I would want in a remote these days, no headphone jack, the &#34;fake&#34; wheel on it is nothing more than four buttons trying to resemble a wheel.Alexa is well not really born yet when it comes to the Fire TV. It can find some stuff sure, but the integration is nothing of what Amazon is trying to push it as, there is a poor integration between the Echo's and Fire TV's as in you assign ONE Fire TV to individual Echo's which then becomes &#34;TV) to that Echo, so no &#34;Alexa turn on Main TV and tune to PS VUE&#34; only hope you reach the right Echo and hope the TV integration works, not impressive. There is also no integration of Alexa routines with Fire TV (yet at least) which fior me was sort of the point, &#34;start my day, yes that includes turning on CNN along with the lights, meh I will do it myself as I did with the Roku&#34; poor poor poor.The interface is sleek but insanely overcrowded with Amazon channels, content and stuff with no relevance to me, no thanks, love the sleep minimalist tiles, hate the insistence on &#34;YOU CAN ALSO TRY THIS&#34; mentality. Boooooooo no thanks.But this is where the wheels really come off the wagon. The video quality is, poor, at least compared to other streaming sticks/players. It always felt like watching SD quality on everything (incl. Prime Video/HBO GoT) and was meh, this uggo. And Audio is an utter mess. The codecs the device can do passthrough with is hit and miss. There is NO DTS passthrough whatsoever so don't even try to those BLU'RAY's you put in your PLEX archive, it will mess up everytime and more often than not zero audio, other times hello transcoding hello PCM hello why did I get a DTS X/Atmos equipment? Dolby Digital was somewhat more able to passthrough (no Atmos though of course, don't trust the 4K version claims, there is no content available to test it on anyways) and with the lack of VUDU in a native app you cannot access many of your titles (Movies anywhere does no have all UV titles yet at least)This is an unfinished product not anywhere close to the maturity of ROKU (has its own issues with TrueHD and DTS MA-HD) or anywhere near nVidia Shield in terms of capabilities/power, pay a little extra and get a real player.",2,65,negative,0.4828975200653076,0.14531436562538147,0.3717881441116333,0.4828975200653076,-0.3376,5,2603,1,0
I am returning mine to the store,"It pushes their own pay content even if you do not have Amazon Prime. As in there is Prime stuff on the main screen even when you do not have Prime which is odd. It is geared toward Prime people.I am probably going to return mine to the store. What I do like about it is It is fast (faster than my Roku 1 which has refused to update) and has an internet browser app called Silk which I only got when I did a system re-install. Which was odd.There are banner ads for products right on the home screen like for cereal. And I do not eat cereal so that is also odd being I have been an Amazon customer over 10 plus years since and you would think they know this being they have tons of my info.and they do not show you what are free shows. With the Smart Tv Amazon app and Roku Amazon Apps? They have a &#34;Prime&#34; labe banner across the shows which means it is a free show. But...they do not have this and I read this was done on purpose. So, it literally is like click-bait I believe to make you click-click-click on shows and if you like the show that is a pay one then they hope you will...pay!It literally can take hours to find the free ones. This is shady and not user friendly.It visually reminds me of the Amazon app. So, it is kinda like I bought the app which I already have for free on my Smart tv and my old Roku.And they will not and do not tell you the Alexa talking remote does NOT work with Netflix. I called the tech people and was told yes. true. it does not on &#34;3rd party apps&#34; which Netflix I guess is. Simple commands like trying to rewind or turn the volume up will not work with the talking Alexa remote watching a show on Netflix. But does apparently with Hulu?If you need Accessibility features? You need go elsewhere! They obviously did not test these features. Ask my cat...because they are the opposite of accessible! Ironic eh? I was literally almost crying trying out the zoom and talking stuff. The froze and the directions were so convoluted and ridiculous. LIke and entire long list of up down. hold this and hold that and pause plus play and. It was almost like a joke. but not!See photo below of how the app has the &#34;prime&#34; banner label to show free shows but how Fire stick does not. shady. I told them too and they told me? Do factory reset. smh. Online told me in articles that they did this on purpose.",2,66,neutral,0.6587399244308472,0.23279905319213867,0.6587399244308472,0.10846100002527237,0.1243,5,2358,0,0
Completely disappointed.,I have really tried to like the the Fire TV Stick but it just plain sucks.Trying to think of where to start. First off I am comparing this to a 2016 Roku Streaming Stick and Xbox One.Pros:Apps like Netflix and Pandora work as expected but feel a tad slower than my other devices.I like the ability to side load apps though I have not tried this feature yet.PS Vue app looks nicer but is noticeably slower than the Roku app.The device works if you don't mind being pigeonholed to the way Amazon wants you to use it. (Not sure this is a pro but wanted to add it)Cons: As a Amazon device I expected Amazon Video to be just as simple or better than on my Roku and Xbox. Instead it just complete throws it in my face with content I don't care about. My watchlist doesn't even tell me what is prime and what is not prime. The only way to tell if it is prime or not is to open the video and see if it says watch with prime. The app on the other devices works almost perfect. But now I just feel overwhelmed with amazon content that I am not even sure I have to pay for or not.Amazon sells Blu-Ray's with Ultraviolet yet I cannot watch my Vudu library on their device without side loading and app. Amazon should have a warning that your Ultraviolet library will not work on this device. My Google movie library won't work either. Shows me my movies but won't play them.I never plan on using amazon photo yet I am stuck with it in my app list as well as any other amazon app I have that works on the fire tv stick.The over all device just feels slow compared to my Roku. It wants to do to much at the expense of performance. I just want to watch my content and not have to wait for it to slowly load. I love the simplicity of Roku. It just plain works well.I have decided to keep the device since the shipping cost and time out way what I paid for it. Maybe I will side load apps to see if it helps it any and update my review.Edit: 4-7-17 Went to use the Netflix app for 6 kids under the age of 4 to quite them down. Took 15 minutes to get it to work. I had to delete app and redownload. Even went looking for something on the Amazon Prime Video which is a total mess. The more I use this device the more I hate.,2,67,negative,0.7440189719200134,0.044952038675546646,0.21102897822856903,0.7440189719200134,-0.6991,5,2204,1,0
Used to Be a Great Product,"It pains me to write such a negative review, as I was one of the Fire Tv Stick's biggest supporters, most ardently arguing in its favor each time the subject of streaming services or cable bills came up. This used to be a great product. Now it's mediocre at best when compared to other streaming products. What made the Amazon fire TV stick stand out was the ability to access all streaming services from one device. This is no longer the case now that Amazon has ended access to ultraviolet video copies through the use of the Vudu or Flixster apps. As an Amazon user, I now purchase digital movies through Amazon, but this does not negate the numerous copies I already owned or DVD copies I purchase that contain a digital copy.Why in the world does Amazon think that their customers would be willing to spend their money on something they had already purchased, just because it wasn't purchased from them? I have an ultraviolet collection of at least 30 movies that are no longer accessible because of these changes. The cost of purchasing these movies again is significant enough to make me consider ditching the fire TV stick for a Roku stick and using the Amazon app to access my Amazon content.As frustrating as this may be, it is not my only concern with this product. The Amazon fire TV stick through no reason I can fathom, periodically times out while streaming. According to the customer service FAQ's this could be because it is not plugged into the correct HDMI port or is plugged into an unsupported device. I have checked both of these possibilites, followed all the instructions in the online troubleshooting guide, yet I continue to have problems. The black screen timing out issue has continued to worsen the longer I've had this product. And I've owned by Fire TV Stick for less than a year. There are lots of great features of this product: being able to stream all my Amazon content is definitely a plus, and I love the interface. The software is easy to use and pleasing to the eye. It has the potential to be a great product. It used to be a great product. But if having access to your ultraviolet collection or being able to stream without constant interruptions is important to you, then stay away from the Amazon Fire Tv Stick!",2,68,negative,0.6231479644775391,0.10706649720668793,0.2697855234146118,0.6231479644775391,-0.5161,5,2254,1,0
This should be fun......but its not.,"Got a couple of firesticks a few days ago. Looking forward to streaming and enjoying movies and tv. I have several devices that can do this but these stivks will let me consoladate apps in one place. Other devices are preloaded. I have combination of wired and wireless connections with 400mb speed from spectrum (used to be time Warner). I usually opt for wired as it is more consistent.Have been streaming and not at all pleased with quality. SD isnt that bad but anything high def is blotchy and always buffering. Testing speed I am getting anywhere from 15 to 55 MB with wired and 8 to 26 with Wi-Fi. This still should be ok as most sources suggest 10 MB can get hd and amazon says 2.5 Will get hd. However fire stick isn't. Customer support suggests that my internet speed needs to be upgraded and/or I have too many devices connected and need to walk around house disconnecting stuff if I want to watch with fire stick. I asked how that would matter since other devices arent suffering from loss anywhere close to that. Support stated that they have people that call with these same issues and Only have 6 devices connected to internet. I asked how the fire stick could possibly be geared towards households where the expectation is there would be less than 6 connected devices and have internet speeds more than 400 MB as I only know 1 family personally that has less than 6 devices (they have 3) and no family with more than 400 MB download speed.In any event, not Happy with something and that something is the fire stick.Update: shortly after original post a manager called and told me they have been having issues with specific isp and routers. I told him mine and surprise.....i am one of those affected. The issue is lost packets during stream so engineers are working on solution. 6 weeks later same issues. A wired connection clocking 300 plus can only pull 15 to 20 mbs and even though that is supposed to be enough to stream hd and even 1080 it still buffers. The signal degradation enough points to an issue with the stick but of course customer support has blamed everything else but a hardwear issue. The manager was nice though so it did get my hopes up. Wish I had waited to buy when they were cheaper so I wouldnt feel as cheated.",2,69,positive,0.875813901424408,0.875813901424408,0.11841379851102829,0.005772314965724945,0.87,7,2253,0,1
Spotty streaming/buffering,"Ignore the bad reviews complaining about YouTube not being available. The YouTube APP is no longer available, but you can still log in to YouTube on the Firefox browser on the stick. It literally looks and operates exactly like the app.My low rating is because the audio drops out for several seconds every ten minutes or so. Amazon support said it was my WiFi connection, except my laptop, Ricky stick, ps4, WiiU, and other UHD smart TV can all stream without issue on the same WiFi network, so there is apparently no reason for this problem. However it is too late to return it, so it is collecting dust plugged into the back of my tv.This is not a universal issue, but it is prevalent enough that there are several threads in online forums with people asking about this problem, with no solution found yet.If you don’t have connection problems this will be a good inexpensive streaming device.Notes:(1) Unlike the Amazon app on other devices, you don’t have to enter a PIN to buy anything, so anyone using your fire stick can purchase anything on Amazon video with just a click. I’ve had roommates purchase entire TV shows by accident on my account.(2) It does work with an Echo, but it’s not worth it. It takes a good 3-5 seconds for a voice command to an Echo to register on the fire stick, whereas using the remote is immediate. I ended up disconnecting the fire stick from Alexa since I often accidentally control the fire stick while trying to play music on the Echo.(3) You cannot use the voice controls to pick up a tv series you are watching where you left off. If you say “Play Grey’s Anatomy on Netflix” it will start at the pilot. In order to resume watching where you’ve left off, you have to open Netflix and manually go to the TV show to resume it.(4) This device ONLY works on WiFi. There is no way to directly connect it to your router using an Ethernet cable. It also must be plugged in to a power source to work - there is no internal battery.Overall, if this worked for me, I would give it 5 Stars, but the streaming audio dropouts make this useless to me when I can just use my WiiU to stream from all of the same services without problem.",2,70,negative,0.766958475112915,0.03201589733362198,0.20102564990520477,0.766958475112915,-0.7349,5,2162,1,0
Its flaws disrupt any convenience. Very disappointing.,"I've been using (or trying to use) this product for about two months. I got it because I wanted to use my prime account more and I can't cast amazon easily with a chromecast. On paper, this is a big step up from a chromecast for a similar price. It turns any TV into a smart TV and feels more like a streaming device than a casting device. However, this thing has some very frustrating and surprising flaws that has left me still preferring the chromecast.1) When the fire stick goes to sleep, I almost always have to restart it manually - meaning go up to the TV, unhook the power cable, and then put it back in. It doesn't respond to the remote when asleep except very occaisionally. The Google Chromecast (which I've had for years) is always ready to go, even when I'm not on the right input. As soon as I begin casting, it switches to the right input. I barely have to do anything. The fire stick seems to struggle to turn itself on much less automatically make the TV show the right source input. I don't want to go reach behind my TV and play around with wires everytime I want to use the thing. This is huge disappointment.2) This one blows my mind - No volume control. You read that correct. How did that get through the design and production process? It's so simple and basic. It even comes with a physical remote.3) The Fire TV app (it's is like a remote on your phone) constantly disconnects. If you put your phone down for 5 seconds it's probably not connected anymore and may not see the firestick as available anymore. And no, this isn't a WiFi issue. My wifi works fine. I even have a WiFi extender. There are similar connection issues using the prime video app and telling it to connect to the fire stick.Once it works it's fine. The remote is basic, but is good enough. The voice control seems fine. Lots of ads and it pushes pay-for content on you a lot. But it gives you access to stuff you don't get easily via Chromecast and you don't need another device (ie phone, computer) to control it (when it actually works).I had high hopes, but it's a frustrating device to use for issues that should not exist. I still prefer my simpler Chromecast.",2,71,positive,0.6248837113380432,0.6248837113380432,0.33535265922546387,0.039763592183589935,0.5851,5,2162,0,1
AMAZON POLICY and CUSTOMER SERVICE $UCKS for FIRE PRODUCTS,"So, this is a double edged review. Part one is on the fire stick/fire tv product and performance, part two relates to Amazon Policy and customer service. So, for part one.. I give the product a 5 star review (when it's working), and for part two, I'd give it zero starts if I could... hence the two star overall rating.First, the product, works great, voice recognition is great, movies with prime are good and we've begun to build an online library of movies we've purchased, mostly classics that we know we'll watch over and over. It's nice because you can take a stick with you when you travel, and have your own movie library with you without having to carry much with you at all.But, I'm going to spend more time on part two... Amazon Policy and customer service. At this point, I have about 10 fire sticks/fire tv boxes through my house and one in a travel case. I use them all as I don't want to have to move it around with me depending on where I am. So, here's THE BIG PROBLEM. Apparently, you can add other apps to the fire stick and people do this and resell them. BIG PROBLEM is that Amazon arbitrarily decides you ARE a RE-SELLER if you own too many of them. Now this is where the fun begins. If you talk to the first line phone support people about this, they claim to know NOTHING about. If you google this problem, it's easy to find. But they know nothing. I believe they are told to say that. After getting really hot on the phone, I was transferred to a TECHNICAL SUPPORT person in the fire tv group, which indeed DID know about this and said I was flagged as a RE-SELLER. I was told this would be noted and removed. SURPRISE, two weeks later, my fire sticks are DE-REGISTERING AGAIN. I really believe that Amazon believes their customers are stupid. I would NEVER buy another FIRE TV product from them again and will start to look for alternatives and update this review when I find suitable alternatives. As for AMAZON, I am going to become the BIGGEST PAIN IN THE REAR, as I'm going to push for a refund on all of my FIRE products, including a refund on all of the movies i have purchased to date (my collection is around 60 at this writing).",2,72,positive,0.48025229573249817,0.48025229573249817,0.47592779994010925,0.04381990805268288,0.4364,2,2163,0,1
Constantly have to re-authenticate :(,"This works nice when it works. But when it takes 15 minutes to re-authenticate an app such as ESPN, CNN, TNT, etc. it gets old really quickly. It's hard to say where the problem lies; the fire stick code, or my cable provider (Suddenlink). I wanted to be able to see the different courts on the ESPN app but ESPN had trouble remembering I was a Suddenlink subscriber with access to ESPN! I had to reset my stick to factory defaults and re-load ESPN app to continue. I've messed around with this trying to figure out the best way to authenticate since the stick cannot remember I have these channel providers via my cable. For example to see CNN live, it tells me I am not authorized to see the show. I've figured out I have to:a) log out of my provider on the CNN apps setting screenb) go to home/settings/applications and stop the CNN appc) clear datad) clear data again just to make sure it clears the cachee) restart the firestick press select and play for about 5 secondsf) go back into CNN settings screen and log in with my providerNow, things will work. But this is a lengthly process and points to something not ready for prime time. Like I said, i don't know if this is FireTV stick or my provider (Suddenlink) but the only benefit I get out of this is now as a prime user I can listen to Prime music (a plus.) All Amazon prime functions are easy; I'm just complaining about the apps and how they authenticate with the cable provider. So all I get out of this is Amazon prime music. Netflix? well, it works fine, but I get better Netflix through my PS3 since there's more buffer area and a really hot cell processor in it.So like I said, I'm not sure. Is it the fire tv stick or the provider (Suddenlink)? My guess is Suddenlink since so many of you fine people rate this thing really high. But with all these authentication hassles I really am not enjoying the Fire TV stick. I hope you all have a better experience than I have had with this thing. I got this on a sale day but I can honestly say I wish I had bought a Chromecast or a Rokku or something that works better than this thing!",2,73,negative,0.6062300205230713,0.031636811792850494,0.3621331751346588,0.6062300205230713,-0.5746,0,2098,1,0
So... buggy...,"I originally thought this was pointless for people with smart TVs, but it has some things my smart TV doesn't, particularly integration with Alexa. It should be super nice to be able to link the TV Stick to your Echo and control shows with your voice without even having to touch the remote... but it always takes Amazon 5 seconds to forward your commands to the Fire Stick, even if they're in the same room, and Alexa usually can't understand my voice while the TV is going.The centralized search feature should make it easy to find shows and movies in all of your streaming services at the same time. On my smart TV I'd have to search Netflix, Amazon, and Hulu all separately. Unfortunately, half of the time you'll get some stupid error like &#34;sorry, I can't search for science fiction&#34;.Alexa voice control is very buggy. It frequently fails to open apps, either giving a generic error or claiming the Fire Stick is offline. Sometimes Alexa opens the wrong show, or just doesn't respond to your commands at all.You have to dig deep into the menu to find the command to put the Fire Stick to sleep, and of course you can't do this with voice commands.My girlfriend and I bought this at the same time. Setup went fine for me, but with my girlfriend's Fire TV Stick setup was a huge hassle. She plugged it in, spent 20 minutes installing apps and linking her accounts, and then we realized that half the features didn't work because it couldn't connect to Amazon's servers. So we spent 30 minutes installing a software update, which didn't fix the issue, then had to spend another 30 minutes doing a factory reset, then another 20 minutes installing apps and linking accounts again. At least it worked properly after all that, but nobody should have to factory reset the device right after receiving it just to get it to work.The CEC on my Fire TV Stick doesn't work. I can control other HDMI devices (such as my Blu-ray player) using my TV remote with CEC, but the TV will not detect the Fire TV Stick even though CEC is turned on at both ends. Not a big deal, but it's a little annoying.",2,74,negative,0.5163607597351074,0.07978279888629913,0.403856486082077,0.5163607597351074,-0.4366,4,2096,1,0
"Once great device's fall from grace. Evaluate your options before hitting ""Add To Cart""","Here is my comprehensive review of the Fire TV Stick after having had one of each generation since 2014.1. Quality of Video and AudioThe quality of the picture and audio has generally been pretty good. I have used these devices on TV's ranging from 720p to 4K with UHD. These 720/1080 devices have been reliable at producing a clear picture and smooth audio playback when the connectivity supported it. For those instances where the bandwidth was constrained, the apps that run on this device do a pretty good job of stepping down the resolution before allowing it to become choppy. More on app performance later.2. Quality of InterfaceThe FireTV interface is fairly easy to use, but is not great at remembering preferences. Whether the feature exists or not, making your 'favorite list of apps' show up when you launch the device on a daily basis. There are performance issue however. Each of my devices, from the oldest to the newest, have been slowing down. The drop in performance has been most notable over the last few months. This has caused the interface to also slow down.3. Overall Performancethe FireTV Stick has become a source of frustration rather than entertainment. Other than the stick installed on a TV that only plays one show while I walk on the treadmill, the rest of the devices are slow or borderline inoperable. I have had apps &#34;talk over each other&#34; and apps crashing. I tried to isolate the issues to one app, but cannot find correlation. Often, I must force quit apps to recover performance.Final Thoughts:The idea of the FireTV Stick is solid. In the past, these devices were transparent in how they delivered the content and and afterthought with regard to the magic of streaming media. Recently, however, the performance has degraded and has lead me to start replacing them. I have had good experiences with the more advanced 4K FireTV, but even that has been slowing recently.Recommendation: Evaluate the streaming devices that are available. I may recommend an alternative to the FireTV Stick that is in the same price range.",2,75,positive,0.8791812062263489,0.8791812062263489,0.11704938858747482,0.0037694184575229883,0.8754,4,2065,0,1
"Its great when it works, but I've had a lot of problems with it not working...","This is my second of this model of Fire TV Stick. The first one worked great for about 2-3 months. And then one day it just wouldn't come on. So Amazon told me to return it and they'd send me a new one. When I got the new one, Hullu wouldn't load. However, Netflix and other apps work fine, but the whole processing speed of this new stick seems slower than the first. I ran a download speed test on my internet, and it was not the problem. I can watch Hulu just fine on my lap top, so I think that this particular device is just a lemon. I got on to the customer chat and after over and hour there was no resolution, and I had some place to be so I let it drop temporarily. Then one day not long after I tried to get help on the chat, I was using it to watch Netflix and the stick did an auto update. I was then able to use Hulu two or three times, but then, for no reason, it once again stopped loading one day. So I tried to call customer service this time. They said to call Hulu. Hulu said it wasn't their fault. Hulu was really cool though, and even though I could use my laptop to watch Hulu, they gave me a one month credit. So I called Amazon back. This time they said it was a system problem and they had tech services working on it and to be patient and eventually it would work again. Over the holidays when I was home a lot I had my laptop hooked up to my computer, but that's a hassle to just watch one show. So yesterday I tried the Fire stick and got Hulu to load, but it kept stopping and starting and finally I was kicked off and couldn't get back on. I haven't tried to contact anyone again yet, but am getting really annoyed. The people at Hulu said I should try Roku. I had a Roku box about 5 or 6 years ago and had all kinds of problems with it, but I will try the new Roku stick and see if that works better. Seriously frustrated with Amazon and Amazon Fire TV Stick. My advice? If yours will work, you'll be happy with it, because my first one was awesome until it quit working. But, I have had such bad luck, I don't know if I'd recommend you try one.",2,76,negative,0.596078097820282,0.07017595320940018,0.3337460160255432,0.596078097820282,-0.5259,7,2076,1,0
Becomes useless brick when internet is down....,"I've been running this for some time and have had my ups and downs. I recently ran into one issue that's really soured my opinion on the device though. I'm going to run over the points I've found so far.Pros:1.) Great entry device for Amazon Prime members. Prime videos are front and center and easy to access.2.) Good integration with a few services. Netflix, Hulu, HBO, etc. Integrated applications are very easy to work with. Search is federated so you can find movies and shows across a variety of apps.3.) Alexa integration. Handy...but I have an echo dot nearby so I don't use the TV one much.4.) *plays games (see con)5.) CHEAP!Cons:1.) No youtube. Seriously! Unless you want to load a browser...there's no youtube. Amazon and google need to get over themselves.2.) A bit underpowered. While it'll play games...don't expect much, but at this price point that's ok.3.) Plex client isn't great IMHO...but that's not Amazon's fault. Wish there was better search integration on plex.4.) No way to block content. Seriously...this is needed. I want a content blacklist that I can add things to and edit. Videos my kid's seen 100 times of somebody on the internet playing Lego City Undercover or Splatoon..... he's five, we don't own a Nintendo, and he can't read so he can't game....yet he want's these games and systems. I keep removing them from the recent list...but he keeps finding them!5.) **** BIGGEST ISSUE YET **** - Becomes a BRICK when the internet is out. You can change settings, but NOTHING works. PIN codes verify against the internet so you can't access anything (can we cache the pin locally?!) and you can't access locally installed games, or network resources. I have PLEX for local access media and TV!!!!! I can't even check the weather on my local broadcast when the internet is down because I run TV through PLEX!!!!! FIX THIS!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! There's NO FREAKING NEED for the internet if my LAN is up for this!",2,77,neutral,0.44381847977638245,0.2840155363082886,0.44381847977638245,0.27216601371765137,0.0118,5,1969,0,0
Freezes on Apps.  Very frustrating.,"I bought the previous version of Fire Stick last year and had to return it due to it freezing on apps (Netflix, Plex, etc.). I purchased the new version and, like the previous version, it plays Amazon Prime movies perfectly but it is freezing on Plex and TubiTV. It's really frustrating because when it works, it works well. Still, I've only had this for a few days - less than a week - and I have had to call customer service twice. Amazon is replacing the remote, but that will take two weeks to get. I WANT this to work, but I have to say, my old ROKU NEVER had these issues. Also, as an Audible subscriber, this is the other reason I want this to work. Through &#34;Alexa&#34;, you request Audible to play a book from your Audible library. However - this is only working with SOME of my library selections. Very frustrating.My last criticism....I believe there is more Amazon oriented advertising on this version of the Fire Stick than previously. This is another issue I have, almost reminiscent of Microsoft forcing you to use their products. I do not see that I am able to customize the home screen to eliminate the MANY (IE: ROWS) of suggested subscription channels, etc., from Amazon....leaving my home screen more cluttered than it is on my Roku. Also, when utilizing PRIME via the Amazon Fire Stick, the little corner logo showing that a movie/tv is a PRIME selection, is missing. So if I search for all movies starring Jeremy Sisto, and a selection comes up, I have to actually click on each one to find out if it is PRIME or one that I need to pay for. When I utilize Amazon Prime on my Roku and do the same actor search, I have the Amazon Prime flag displayed in the upper left corner which makes things much easier. This ticks me off. Hello? Already a paid member. Buying your stuff. For the love of chocolate Amazon, are you trying to make me buy more things?? Well, I guess you are. But you are detracting from my PRIME user experience as opposed to adding to it.Oh - and the Alexa addition is pretty cool.",2,78,negative,0.6686570048332214,0.04203708469867706,0.28930598497390747,0.6686570048332214,-0.6266,5,2023,1,0
Remote defective. Customer service experience,"I want to love this firestick so bad, but the remote doesn't work reliably. The app on my iPhone works every time. I contacted customer service about the sporadic usefulness of the remote, tried every trouble shooting suggestion they provided. It worked for a min., and then started working off and on again conviently after my return date passed. I wish I had returned it and waited on the next version. They do updates on the remote, and when it does work, It recognizes it as a &#34;new remote.&#34; It's obviously still a work in progress. If you haven't purchased one yet, I'd wait on the next one they release when they've worked out the bugs. Great streaming quality though.*update* after I wrote this review, an employee read it and started a replacement/return without contacting me to see if this was the solution I wanted. Very strange to read a review and act without consulting the customer, am I right? After I wrote this review, having no idea an employee had ordered a replacement through my account without asking, I contacted customer service myself after seeing many people had the same experience as me. The associate was VERY helpful and sent me a code for a replacement remote. Exactly what I wanted. One from a new batch, I'll have to wait a couple months, but hopefully they have made improvements on the design. This was all set to go until the code I was given didn't work! I worked with 8 different reps through chat and over the phone. For almost 4 hours! No one could figure out how to get the promo to work, until, someone finally realized another employee had taken the liberty of making my purchasing decisions for me and had ordered an entire new system expecting me to ship back my whole system, again, without consulting me, resulting in a huge amount of confusion for their coworkers and for me. I hope it will be worth all the hours I spent chatting and on the phone! If you wrote a dissatisfied review, I'd check your email bc they may have made your shopping decisions for you and just sent you an email!",2,79,negative,0.7529217600822449,0.05148407816886902,0.19559410214424133,0.7529217600822449,-0.7014,7,2043,1,0
but any modern smart TV will run most of,"The Fire TV Stick is really slow. I have 125 Mbps fiber internet and the Fire Stick constantly loses network connection. (My Fire Stick is 10 feet from my router with no obstructions.) I constantly have to reboot the Fire Stick to regain the dropped network connection. When it is connected, the streaming is slow and constantly buffering. Amazon sells add on equipment to connect directly via EtherNet, but I don't want to buy more equipment nor have another wire.To utilize Alexa with the Fire Stick, you have to press the mic button on the severely limited remote. If I have to pick up the remote for Alexa, why not just use the remote. Alexa will not control through echo devices.The free content available on Amazon Prime Video is very outdated and limited. Have a look at Amazon Prime Video on your computer to see the available content. People are stating claims of money savings by using subscription based apps on the Fire Stick, but any modern smart TV will run most of, if not all, those apps. The YouTube app has been removed and now you have to use the browser to access YouTube. (The browser itself is an additional download that isn't easy to accomplish) Searching for content is cumbersome and frustrating. You will need to be somewhat technically savvy to do anything beyond browse suggested content.I dislike the cable company just as much as the next guy but the Fire Stick has a long way to go before it's the way to go. If you're going to be using Fire Stick as part of your cable cutting process, get ready to watch a bunch of YouTube videos on how to fully utilize the device. Amazons suggested troubleshooting is basically turn it off and back on, or restore to factory settings.Before purchasing a Fire Stick I suggest:Checking out Amazon Prime Video online to see what free content is available.Checking the cost of the subscription services such as HBO, Sling, Netflix, etc.Verify what apps could be used on a regular smart TV without Fire Stick",2,80,negative,0.8247627019882202,0.017700906842947006,0.1575363576412201,0.8247627019882202,-0.8071,5,1972,1,0
"Per ""Amazon's Internal Communications,"" FireStick is NOT designed to be used with computer monitors [not in product description]","Got this thing, which does NOT say anywhere in the product page that it is NOT designed to be used with computer monitors, per the specialist I spoke to when I asked for help since it was doing periodic random black screens. After THIRTY MINUTES of back and forth and TWO (2) reps, I got to the third rep who told me pic related. It took another THREE (3) representatives to finally get a return.The pertinent part of the conversation, in case the picture somehow (((does not load))) are the following:Dilip: Hello, my name is Dilip. Please give me a moment to review the previous correspondence.Dilip: Have you connected the Fire TV Stick with the computer monitor?Me : yesMe : two monitorsDilip: I am sorry but Fire TV Stick is not designed to be used with the monitors, you can only use the device with Smart TVs and connecting with HDMI Port on TVMe : uh whatMe : I might have missed that in the product page hold onDilip: SureMe : a quick google gives me this, DilipMe : https://www.amazon.com/ask/questions/Tx...(See full link)Me : I mean I am seeing an output, it's just that it goes black randomly then comes up againDilip: I am sorry but officially its not supported.Me : show meMe : also why am I only being told this now after two reps have spoken to me and knew that it was being used with a monitor?Dilip: I am sorry but its not documented anywhere. However it is internally communicated.Me : can you show proof of this internal communication? For future referenceDilip: I am sorry but we would not be able to provide that information on chat.Me : very good. Start return procedures immediately.Me : I would *not* have bought this had your &#34;internal communications&#34; were made publicDilip: I understand its quite frustrating but Fire TV Stick is designed to be used with the Smart TVs and not with the computerMe : I got that a few sentences ago, Dilip. I want this returned",2,81,negative,0.7263363003730774,0.015376362949609756,0.25828737020492554,0.7263363003730774,-0.711,2,1894,1,0
"Does not do well with WiFi, Clunky Interface, and not Alexa friendly","We purchased a Fire Stick after six years of using Roku. We loved our Roku, but they wear out after a while and we wanted something Alexa compatible.Well, we hooked up our Fire Stick, got it running and we found that it disconnected from our Internet a lot. We did not have this problem with our Roku (located in the same place), but we were having some slow internet issues (having recently moved/changed internet providers) so we looked into those and discovered that our Router was to blame. We replaced our router and now several internet speed tests have shown that we get blazing fast internet. (We get around 100 mb/s.) The Roku internet issues stopped. All our internet issues stopped, except for the FireStick. It still disconnects frequently. Says the Internet is down (it isn’t). Roku and Apple TV work great (in the same location/distance from the router).We could also never get our FireStick to be recognized by Alexa/work with Alexa. We could use the remote button to get the Fire Stick’s Alexa to work, but our Echo and Dot could not connect to it ever. My husband is a software engineer—he’s pretty good with devices and even I had no problem setting any other smart devices up to Alexa but not this one.I also didn’t love the user interface of the FireStick — both Roku and Apple TV have better ones. Heck, even my blu ray player has a better one. The issue is that it’s all about Amazon movies. The homepage basically just takes you back to Amazon stuff with options for other apps. I prefer the home pages that take you to all your app, are easily organized, easy to add, etc. This feels like having other apps is an after thought, and while we do use PrimeVideo A LOT, we still use other apps and this just isn’t the easiest way to do so.So, we’re not stuck on our FireStick. I’ll keep playing around with it and see if I can get it to work better, but right now I’m only keeping it because we got it on sale so it’s really not worth returning it.",2,82,neutral,0.503841757774353,0.28720515966415405,0.503841757774353,0.20895308256149292,0.0783,4,1968,0,0
Lacks the features it touts,"I loved this initially. I thought the idea of putting Alexa in the remote was convenient and communicating with it through my Echo made it even easier. There are however, a few problems that make this really frustrating.First, on the box it says you can communicate through the remote to “fast forward 30 seconds”. This totally works... with prime only. Try it on Netflix or Hulu and you’ll only get a pause out the command. Second, want to watch a specific TV show without having to open Netflix, find your show, find your episode and hit play? According to the box you just hit the Alexa button and say, for instance “play The Office”. At the very least you’d expect it to open the office and start playing where you left off right? Wrong. It first comes up with both the UK version and the US version. Ok, I get that. But when you select say, the US Office, it starts the first episode of the series... every time!. Ask her to play ANY tv show and you will always be played the first episode of the first season.Add on top of that the fact that the Echo will rarely actually communicate with the fire stick, and it makes for a frustrating experience. Also add on the fact that it still experiences lag in opening apps. How that’s possible with the new processor is beyond me. It’s also very specific in regards to how you phrase things. You can pause the show or movie you’re watching by telling your Echo, “Alexa, Pause”. But if you say “Alexa, Play” it does nothing, because you actually have to say “Alexa, RESUME”. I did find it very convenient that when I asked for a random tv show or movie I was looking for, it would give me results on every platform it could find it on.Unfortunately, that was about the only positive experience I could find with the 2nd generation Fire Stick. I expected so much more out of this. It’s a bummer, every other Amazon product I’ve bought has been stellar. Hopefully changes will be made in the future.",2,83,positive,0.6392945647239685,0.6392945647239685,0.25344350934028625,0.10726189613342285,0.532,5,1944,0,1
5 Stars When It Works...,"I had been using my Bluray player to steam from Amazon for several years. When I saw the stick go on sale I decided to buy it.Set-up was easy and straight forward. I was also able to access titles from my watchlist faster and scan trough shows when needed more efficiently.Shortly after my first hour of streaming, my video froze with a partial circle spinning in the center of the screen. When I checked the settings, I found that the Fire stick had lost it's internet connection and was saying I should reboot my router. I did this the first timer and was able to continue watching the video (after about five minutes for the reboot). about thirty minutes later, it happened again. With the same instructions. I once again rebooted my router. After this reoccurred a third time, I went into the settings and reset the Fire Stick. This had the same affect as the reboot but did not require me to go into another room and wait for the reboot process. It was still a couple of minutes and interupted the experience. This continues to occur at least once per day. after two times i often get disgusted and move on to something else or will just watch it on my laptop.I have the stick connected to the front of my AV receiver to minimize obstructions, amdmy router is less than 25 feet away. I do not have this problem with any other devices. When I stream to my Suface in the kitchen (one floor down and on the other side of the house) i never have an issue. I have even streamed to another laptop in the basement. I have checked twice while streaming to two other devices placed further away, (where i could still monitor them) and when the video from the Fire Stick froze, the other devices kept on playing.As i stated above, it is five stars when it works. Even if it only froze once or twice per week I could begrudgingly give it 3-4, but when it happens every time I use it for more than an hour, I feel two stars is being kind.",2,84,positive,0.6278430819511414,0.6278430819511414,0.35477620363235474,0.017380742356181145,0.6105,7,1931,0,1
The Previous Version Fire Sticks were Much better,"I have had the old fire sticks which I loved and decided to upgrade to the new voice remote. I've only used it since December and have had to change the batteries 4x now and it's only Feb. 1st!! I've never had batteries run out so fast! I don't even use the microphone button much. I've epecially layed off using the Alexa Mic. Button since the 1st time the batteries were replaced thinking they would last longer, nope! My old fire sticks only had to be replaced 1x each in at least a year and a half the amazon batteries that came with, lasted the whole while. Also the picture zooms in and freezes quite a bit on this new one for seemingly no reason and to get it off we have to Google how to get it back to a normal screen! There is a screen calibration option in the device settings, which is useless, you cannot even read what it says when zoomed in! I had to write this review after trying to use it to workout with the beachbody app (which I love that It's available on the firestick) it froze, changed the batteries (for the 4th time in 2 months) still did not work, so I unplugged it, and upon coming back on it's zoomed in. Tried changing my tv pic size settings, and that is not the problem, there is an orange frame around it which means it's the firestick.. found how to zoom out by using the remote buttons via internet search, does nothing but freezes again!!!! The remote makes a pulsing electronic sound like it’s trying to do something, so I had to take the batteries out to reset the remote. All I want to do is workout, get it over with and go back to work. This is beyond frustrating and I'm writing this wasting my time. When it works it's fine and dandy, excpet for the fact that I cannot utilize the only reason I bought this new one (for the microphone) out of fear of replacing the batteries again. I guess I'll have to do my workouts on one of the old sticks, because today's workout is gone because of this.",2,85,positive,0.5446526408195496,0.5446526408195496,0.30543363094329834,0.1499137133359909,0.3947,7,1936,0,1
"Low price, interesting remote, performance lacking","I own a Roku, and Apple TV 4th generation, and this Amazon Fire TV stick with Alexa Voice Remote. I have never had anything to complain about either the Roku or the Apple TV, so I expected the Fire TV Stick to be at least as good as the others; I was wrong.The Fire TV Stick has all sorts of streaming problems. I frequently get the message &#34;having trouble streaming this title right now, please try again later or select another title&#34;. When I would get this message with the Fire TV Stick I would try again and get the same message; then I would switch to my Roku and have no trouble watching the show that would not stream on the Fire TV Stick. I have never had a streaming issue with Roku or Apple TV.In addition, apps (like Acorn TV) that work flawlessly on Roku and Apple TV and are full of bugs and/or are missing features in their Fire TV Stick versions. I'll give the product 2 stars for the price and for the voice remote (although it's a bit creepy to talk to a remote).If you can afford a REAL streaming device and not a &#34;stick&#34; model, I highly recommend buying a Roku (not a stick) or an Apple TV. Maybe Amazon will eventually release a firmware update for the Fire TV Stick that will resolve the streaming issues, and release some updated apps that catch up with the functionality provided by the ones for Roku and Apple TV, but until then the Fire TV Stick lags behind.By the way, I did try to use the voice remote a few times, but when I did say &#34;skip ahead two minutes&#34;, I would get the message &#34;I can't perform that function right now&#34; and the Fire TV Stick would kick me out of the app I was using and return me to the main menu. I would have to restart the app and start the program I was watching again from the beginning. Nice idea, poor execution. I assume this function does work with some apps, just not the ones I wanted to use it with.",2,86,neutral,0.5626417994499207,0.21954703330993652,0.5626417994499207,0.21781118214130402,0.0017,4,1894,0,0
Cumbersome and Lacking Effective Parental Control,"There are some significant issues with Fire Stick that should be addressed. The poor parental control system is not just Fire Stick, but it is Amazon in general.The first issue is, the lack of a good parental control system. As far as I can see:• You can only select one pin to control access to content on Amazon/Fire Stick/Prime Video, etc.• You can only select one viewing restriction settingThis is extremely inadequate for protecting children from inappropriate content, while at the same time offering flexibility and ease of use to access other content.If I give my child the pin so they can watch something appropriate, there’s nothing to stop them from watching something inappropriate or unapproved. That’s ridiculous. This is a no-brainer and should already be part of Firesticks/Amazon’s parental control system.The solution is, to be able to set up multiple pins/passcodes for:• Different levels of content• Different types of content• Different apps• Different usersI may have no issue with my child viewing one app in Fire Stick, but have a major issue viewing another. Right now, there’s nothing that I see that I can do about that. Once they have the pin for access, they have access to everything regardless of how the viewing restrictions are set. The pin simply bypasses all parental control settings. THAT IS NOT HELPFUL! It’s really pointless…unless a parent is going to sit there the whole time and monitor or watch with them.The second issue is: There should be an easy way to return a previous app. Right now you have to go back to the Home button/screen, find the previous app and start over.The third issue is: Alexa should work when using other apps. If I’m on Hulu, it doesn’t work. If I’m on Silk, it doesn’t work.These are rather obvious issues and should have been dealt with long ago.",2,87,negative,0.8861151933670044,0.006996637210249901,0.10688816756010056,0.8861151933670044,-0.8791,5,1817,1,0
"Unless you're married to Amazon, explore your options.","It seems like the love of this device comes from a lot of people who have never used another TV streaming device. We previously had an Apple TV that we replaced with this, since the Apple TV was older and no longer supported and certain apps (You Tube) were no longer available.We have the previous generation Amazon Fire TV Stick, but that is no longer available, so commenting on it is not useful to anyone. Compared to Apple TV this thing is incredibly slow, takes forever to load the home screen, and often takes a while to load apps. The interface is far less clear as well.However, my biggest problem is that the Apple TV functioned as a wifi base station as well, meaning that I could stream directly from my computer to my TV or stereo through the device. I used it stream music from my laptop, mostly from Google Play since that's the subscription we have. This thing doesn't have Google Play installed, instead it has Spotify and Amazon Music. We learned how to &#34;Sideload&#34; apps through an Android device and installed Google Play that way. Worked great for a couple of days. Then Amazon must've detected the new app, and the stick refuses to load it anymore. Instead, we get an error: &#34;this app is not associated with your Amazon account.&#34;I'm sure there is another way around this problem, but how much time do I want to spend screwing around with every new device we bring into the house? Less than this thing takes.We will get a Roku. We won't be buying any more Amazon technology, until such time as Bezos buys every tech company in the US, and we no longer have a choice in the matter.Update: watching Netflix streaming at 9:30 on a Friday night and get a notification that updates are ready. Would we like to install now or later? Later please. Later means every 5 minutes we get the same notification. Are they sadists in there?",2,88,neutral,0.41080304980278015,0.3468605577945709,0.41080304980278015,0.24233634769916534,0.1045,5,1860,0,0
"Audi Features, Geo Metro Engine","I'm sure once the next one comes out it will hopefully be better. Amazon is focused on making this affordable, which makes sense.. but I'd rather pay more for a device that actually works as the UX developers intended. The lag... OH GaWD the LAAA- A - A - ...... (spinning circle) -A A G!!! This thing just does not have enough horsepower to run the Fire Stick OS smoothly. The Apple TV 2nd Gen (2010) would run laps around this thing. Crossy Road?? Forget about it. You're lucky if you can navigate the menus and browse through Netflix without this thing hanging up. Constant freezing and unresponsive user interface kills this products. I'm using the supplied USB adapter and I've done multiple factory resets as well as software updates. I think my watch has more memory than this thing.I've disabled auto-play previews and set the resolution to 720p and uninstalled / disabled all background apps that might hinder performance and this thing is &#34;functional&#34; at best..Amazon needs to boost the horsepower (CPU) and find away to make the OS run more efficiently because this thing just simply cannot handle all the animations and graphics found in Fire TV OS.With all that said... it IS functional as a streaming device for a bedroom TV that hardly gets used.. but man I will not hesitate to toss it in the garbage as soon as the new one comes out.Last note: the device will work fine (720p and no auto-previews) when it first starts up.. but once that CPU gets hot enough it will thermal throttle (to prevent overheating) and then you're back to what above. Poor engineering.UPDATE: Amazon did reach out to me although I haven't yet responded (but I appreciate them taking the time to try and make it right) Not sure much can be done its just what you get for a $39 computer in a stick. I'm giving up on it and going with a Roku Premier+ instead.",2,89,positive,0.4616236686706543,0.4616236686706543,0.3493046164512634,0.18907172977924347,0.2726,5,1857,0,1
"it's just ok, needs a stronger processor and a responsive remote.","Update: after longterm use:Bad:Remote is atrocious and consistently non-responsive.Wifi only (no ethernet) means pixelated videos, netflix streams at 720p at times even though i have very fast wifi over 5ghz channel and fast internet. My other devices that use netflix over wifi do 1080p without issue.No Youtube app because of stupid fight with google. DEALBREAKER! for me.Can't play 10bit h265Kodi menu performance is very labored.It's mostly a way to sell you Amazon services. I don't subscribe to those so the majority of the homepages are wasted space.Needs frequent rebooting because it's Android based.Processor struggles a bit with keeping up with the interface. That is you hit right and it takes two seconds to go right.Netflix etc all run well though. I don't have a 4k tv so don't know how that works or if it's even a feature honestly.The remote is tremendously laggy. Remote often is completely unresponsive. Remote is designed fine it just needs to respond when i press the button. I look forward to an updated version.Alexa is not great on it in that it does very little. It's not as useful as an echo and it won't set timers which really sucks. You can ask it questions though. I think you can order things off of amazon and possibly things like starbucks coffee but i haven't connected my account and would prefer to wait till i get there before ordering cause who likes cold coffee and it's a bit gimmicky. Will say the A.I. seems better than Siri on my iphone when it comes to understanding conversation.Bottom line: For me this is behind a Shield and a Roku. It's just lacks the power, performance, remote and options. Nvidia Sheild would be my next purchase. I'd put a Roku ultra in before almost any Firetv device as well. Also No youtube app is a dealbreaker for me.",2,90,negative,0.8842639327049255,0.011820859275758266,0.10391523689031601,0.8842639327049255,-0.8724,5,1790,1,0
Using directv now so I have no choice,"At least it has directv now or else it would be one star.The fire tv interface is pretty useless, just ads for amazon content. They have a few good shows, emphasis on few. I've watched them, now I'm greeted with ads for them everytime I turn on the fire stick.Good luck if you're coming over from an apple tv, the voice features were much better. I am totally spoiled apparently.You kind of expect the following to work as they do on apple tv but they don't: &#34;What did they just say&#34;, &#34;Who's in this movie&#34;, &#34;Install the TNT app&#34;Alexa will basically say 'hmm what device is that'? Maybe apply some context since I'm talking to a tv.Apple tv also allowed you to use voice to spell things out, like usernames and passwords! Do not expect the same luxuries here. Welcome to scroll and click a letter hell.But I guess voice here is just designed for the modern person wanting to reorder Tide and adjust the thermostat by talking into a remote while everyone is trying to watch game of thrones.The home screen has a series of horizontal lists organizing god knows what. Most of these apps and shows are junk. No review integration, or top imdb picks. Just sift through and hope something in the top 10 popularity is interesting.Your app list will include apps you've installed on your kindle fire that are available on fire tv and have supposedly to been installed to the cloud, whatever that means. So for you kindle app lovers out there that have installed tons of apps.... thoughts and prayers.So rejoice, for $40 you've cut the cord and subscribed to directv now, sling, or playstation vue instead. Do not expect any more than that and you will not be disappointed. Looking for a new home to install a few apps for on demand content, pump your brakes you did not buy an apple tv or roku.",2,91,negative,0.6577069759368896,0.08447980135679245,0.2578131854534149,0.6577069759368896,-0.5732,5,1810,1,0
"Stutters, chucks, freezes unlike my computers, it simply cannot handle high speed, but erratic internet. Reboot over and over an","I love Amazon and do a lot of shopping using their service. It pains me to give such poor feedback to one of their in-house products. However, using this Firestick is among the most disapointing products I have ever purchased. I actually watch much less TV now, just because it is so frustrating to rely on. It cannot handle the high speed, but erratic, internet service providers (such as Time Warner) to deliver a steady stream. Instead, it freezes often on Amazon movies, Netflix, Amazon Music, Sling, NFL Sunday ticket and Spotify, during which time it requires me to reboot the stick, or if I am lucky, just kicks me out of the App. During a college football game, I will typically reboot once each quarter. (I am already using a replacement Firestick, verifying it is not faulty, per se).As I mentioned earlier, the issue isnt entirely the fault of the Firestick. My ISP has 100MPS speed (verified), but the signal does drop from time to time. However, I have two laptops and a desktop that don't seem to mind. At the most, I will simply reload a browser page. But the Firestick is far more sensitive than PCs, and far less capable of coping. So the typical inconsistencies bring it to its news. I think this is something Amazon can fix with a firmware update or a re-design. I am pulling for them to do so, as I absolutely LOVE the cable free life. Regardless of the headache with Firestick, I have a weight lifted from not having to worry about my discounts expiring from Verizon or TW-- and hiking my bill to $250/ month for standard cable packages.I am giving 2 stars instead of 1, because I dropped cable (though I will be switching to Roku) until Amazon upgrades their unit.EDIT- during the time I wrote this review, the college football game (SLing) has dropped out not once, not twice, but three times.",2,92,negative,0.7744042873382568,0.0737433061003685,0.15185248851776123,0.7744042873382568,-0.7007,0,1816,1,0
Try It,"I thought you would be able to view a lot of the older movies, sitcoms and game shows. There are a few. Also you don't have the ability to schedule programming that you want to watch ahead of time so that the program will automatically change to the program you set. I usually set programs for my father who is 90 years old so that I don't have to constantly come into his room to change the channel to the programs he likes. Also there aren't a lot of free programs. You have to subscribe and I'm not clear if when you subscribe it is permanent as long as you have the Fire Stick or if you have to subscribe every time you want to watch. I currently have Verizon Fios and I thought getting the Fire Stick I would be able to chose the programs I wanted rather than having to be locked into a package that I may only watch a channel once or twice a year. For example my father loves the Game Show Network but Fire Stick does not offer it. So I hope they will have more programming. With regard to operation, it is easy to set up and the programming is clear. Another example my father likes Superman with George Reeves. You can see one free and then you have to subscribe. I'm not sure if it is for all seasons or for just a couple of programs. I wish they had a section you could go to that explains how everything works. I like the idea that you don't need a box with a monthly fee. It's really hard to get into paying for everything because the old generations just turned on the television and watched. Now you have to pay even though you have commercial advertising. Would I recommend the Fire TV Stick? Yes because I know they will be improving and Amazon is customer oriented, making things easy for the customer and giving them the best. I would have given 5 stars but some of the programs I wanted were not offered yet.",2,93,neutral,0.6553434133529663,0.04039883613586426,0.6553434133529663,0.3042577803134918,-0.2639,0,1827,0,0
Not as good as 3rd Gen Apple TV or Apps on DVD player - for me,"My first impressions of the Fire TV are not good - not worth even the Black Friday discount price. I was hoping it would be be better than my 3rd generation Apple TV. The UI navigation is overcrowded - too much granularity. The voice navigation just doesn't grab what I want. I can't even reliably select from my handful of installed apps. It'll find Netflix but not launch it. It won't find my installed Acorn TV app, just a handful of titles - not the app, and not any of My content in the app. That's just about the definition of useless, as far as I'm concerned. I was hoping the MLB TV app would be better that the one on Apple TV or my DVD player, but not even. There is no way to jump to the next inning/chapter like I can with the older devices - just a really crude fast forward. That's no good for me. But, the thing that really ticked me off, maybe enough to return it Amazon - was that it instantly signed me up for another (redundant/duplicate) Amazon Prime account - we already have one in the family. I think I was able to cancel it. I hope it didn't ruin the shared access I already had.We have a housefull of Dots and an Echo and we sort of share access to Prime content by &#34;switching&#34; accounts. It's kind of lame, because all of the the SmartHome devices are recognized on my Amazon account, and can't be accessed while we're switched to my wife's Prime account. But at least we can get to her audio content. It's considerably better than having to &#34;deregister&#34; the Fire TV and re-register it. In fact, I dislike that idea so much I'm very inclined to return the Fire TV. That, coupled with the instant Prime membership duplication and I'm really tempted. I was expecting to like the Fire TV with the same enthusiasim that I have for Echo and Dot. But, so far it's been very disappointing.",2,94,negative,0.8943227529525757,0.011766665615141392,0.09391064941883087,0.8943227529525757,-0.8826,5,1823,1,0
Pointless if its not going to be an open ecosystem,"The controller is really nice, Alexa is Awesome and it is pretty fast but...Complete waste of time until ultraviolet &#34;digital copies&#34; can become accessible. I still enjoy buying physical copies of movies, and I spend the extra couple of bucks to buy the versions that have the DVD, Blu Ray and Digital copy....oh and I buy these off of Amazon!!!!! So the fact that I can't watch the digital copies on my Fire Stick TV is even more infuriating. Now, being a valued amazon customer, I do have plenty of digital content on Amazon, but currently it is mostly TV shows and music, with a few movies. I was under the impression that the Fire TV Stick would be able to integrate all of my files into one ecosystem where I could just ask Alexa to play Star Trek and viola...it plays. Now...I have a smart TV that has a amazon app, and all the other apps that I need to watch my digital library...I also have an Xbox one that can do the same exact thing....so what's the point of the Fire Stick TV. I am not about to loose my entire ultraviolet video library just because I love the amazon ecosystem so much. Come on Amazon, put on a pair of big boy pants, stop being selfish and start being a little more accepting. Thanks.Also, I am a little bugged by the interface. In the little intro, learn about your Fire Stick TV video, all of the apps were shown in this wonderful grid pattern that occupied the entire page. I have yet to find where that happens in ones actual use of the thing. Instead, on the home page the is one horizontal band that you are supposed to scroll left or right on until you get to the app that you want.....really.....is that the best way to do this. I want to be able to see all of my apps on one page and all of my movies on one page and etc etc in the grid format.",2,95,positive,0.6742537021636963,0.6742537021636963,0.2120347023010254,0.11371161788702011,0.5605,5,1791,0,1
I can't understand why this has so many good reviews. It works,"For the life of me, I can't understand why this has so many good reviews. It works, and does what it is intended to do for the most part, but I have found it to be a completely unenjoyable product and deeply regret purchasing it. Why? Simply because of the sheer amount of ads on it. I pay $60+ for Amazon Prime and then paid $40 for this Fire TV Stick, equaling out to $100+. Then they have the audacity to toss ads on this thing that I paid for? When I'm a paying Prime subscriber? I think it's insane. I don't know if it's maybe because I've been using adblock half my life or what, but I just don't get why everyone seems to be OK with the sheer amount of ads that dominate this platform. Every time you want to watch an Amazon Prime video? You get an annoying ad. Every time you go to your home page? A giant ad banner takes up literally over half the screen, and starts playing loud trailers if you accidentally hover over it.I've included a picture that demonstrates this. The actual content I want to see takes up maybe like 30% of the screen. The rest is pure advertisement. This is blatantly awful and I am frankly disgusted by the way Amazon treats their paying customers. I contacted support about this and was basically given the middle finger, despite being an Amazon supporter for years.We were going to buy Fire TV Sticks for the rest of the TV's in our house, but after seeing how covered in ads these things are we've decided against it. I don't like ads. I don't appreciate being advertised to on a product that I have spent a rather large amount of money on. If there was just one little tiny banner ad at the top, I'd be fine with that, but there's way too much and the fact that there's an ad before videos is ridiculous.Highly recommend purchasing another product.",2,96,negative,0.8428303599357605,0.028372399508953094,0.128797248005867,0.8428303599357605,-0.8145,5,1787,1,0
Not very happy.,"So, there are some cool things with this, but some very very bad issues I have been having make it something I loathe.1st: If I don't exit to the home screen, it will constantly turn on my TV. Very annoying to come home to see your TV on when you know it was off upon leaving.2nd: The remote and delay. I am not sure if this is a lag thing, but I feel it is not. The remote will sometimes work, and sometimes not. It really is annoying when something is playing and you need to pause and it just won't work. Sometimes taking the batteries out and placing them back makes it work, sometimes that doesn't. Sometimes sitting there spamming the buttons will make it work. Sometimes holding the buttons down will make it work. I felt at one point that it might be an internet lag issue, but then why does it happen when something is playing. (Maybe it's an Amazon battery issue? I replaced the Amazon batteries that came with the remote with new Amazon batteries from a pack and still have the same issues *shrug*).3rd: The quasi YouTube functionality. Trash. It will constantly, like every time, need to confirm if I want to open Youtube with Firefox or Sling. Really got old by the third time. Now I have to do that at least once daily.4th: This may not be there fault, but the stupid rewind/forward functionality in the Netflix app. Seriously, why the doesn't it just work like the 10 sec forward and 10 second back function when watching Prime shoes. Like I said, probably Netflix's issue, but still crap.If I didn't need Prime for my business I would have dropped this and returned the stick and never looked back.I gave it two stars because when it works it is okay. It is definitely not a replacement for a tablet and a Google ChromeCast.",2,97,negative,0.8593932390213013,0.016770457848906517,0.12383630871772766,0.8593932390213013,-0.8426,5,1740,1,0
Installed in 5 minutes with no problem but oh the heat,"It looked beautiful - so why you might ask did I only give it 2 stars. Because I could use it as a toaster but that, unfortunately is not what I bought it for. In case there's a question in your mind, I brought a 2nd gen Fire Stick with Alexa Voice Remote from Amazon July 25, 2018. I finally set it up on August 7 with no problem using the included power cord. Easy setup after working an hour to get my Panasonic TV to turn on it's HDMI 3 port. I started a Netflix movie, downloaded a game - no problem. It had good picture and sound and the remote worked smoothly. All of that would have gotten a 5 star rating from me - until I touched the stick. It was hot (as in VERY HOT). I started looking around on the Internet and sure enough there were MANY reports of this stick overheating, and this affected the quality of picture, stuttering, pausing for data and even one melting when pushed on data. Well, mine didn't do any of that but it did get HOT. I have had a lot of devices over the years and every once in a while I come across one that overheats. Folks, that's nothing you want to risk in your house. There are actually very handy people who put out videos of how to open the little case and drill vent holes or make a better heat sink and even built enclosures with fans. Hey, I don't want this that badly. It should be safe to use, period. I am returning it and ordering a fire cube. It's bigger so the hope is it will not overheat the way this did. If any of you have a recent fire stick that is not hot to the touch, you might want to jump in on this review and let me know. Electronics should never get this hot to the touch and it would have been easy to design a bigger enclosure with a better heat sink and vents. Anyway, I'll let you know about the cube when I try that out.",2,98,positive,0.7716196775436401,0.7716196775436401,0.19603602588176727,0.03234428912401199,0.7393,7,1793,0,1
"Designed to be replaced annually, typical ""Waste-ware"".","Let me just be frank and get right to the bottom. This is the product you most likely have to throw away just after year of use replacing it with newer version.Here is why.Amazon periodically pushes software updates for Fire Stick. These updates always bring more features or more stuff with it, however it comes with price. Which is that your stick will gradually becomes slower and lagging. This is because the software they push gradually requires more resources from your stick eventually pushing its performance to the limit. Since you are stuck with the FireStick you purchased it slowly becomes a bottleneck for larger and more demanding software updates.I purchased my stick about a year ago from Amazon and now it is almost useless. Yes, I did factory reset but that does not help of course because the latest software immediately makes your older stick slow and laggy again as soon as device boots up.I also have Fire TV box for less than a year and this one still works but not as fast and swift as it used to be. But I know in another year or two my FireTV would most likely also need a replacement unless Amazon stops executing it's designed in obsolescence by pushing those updates which don't do any good at all except messing up your stick and FireTV if you happen to owe one.Unfortunately this type of practice is common nowadays in world of modern electronics and include smartphones, smart appliances and other communication devices to ensure you are forced to upgrade these periodically so it's manufacturers make extra bucks and sell newer model over and over again.So if you agree with this scheme, go ahead and buy the product. If you however do not, stay away from it.",2,99,negative,0.6711674332618713,0.026737742125988007,0.30209481716156006,0.6711674332618713,-0.6444,6,1692,1,0
All-New Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote,"First let me begin by saying this review is based on having more than one Fire TV device or having this device and a Amazon Echo. If you will only have one Fire TV device and NO Echo products, then this would be a five star review. Now, let me explain: 1. First, this device works well as access device to a wealth of Amazon content as well as other app access. It has great video and audio streaming. The first rub comes when you have MORE than one device. Amazon will ONLY allow streaming audio to one FIRE device!!!!! So, if you buy more than one of these and think you will be able to stream music to more than one location in your home, forget it. ONE location ONLY!! This is REALLY LAME since if you have more than one echo product (Touch, Dot, Echo) you can stream the same or different audio channels to all devices! However, as soon as you try to use the Fire TV device to stream it will turn OFF streaming to your Echo devices if you want to stream music to your Fire TV. You should also know that there is a limit of TWO video streams allowed per prime account! So, if you have three TVs with three Fire Sticks, you can only stream video to TWO of those TVs!!! This should be stated in the ad for this device so that people understand the limits!!!! As it is written, you would expect it to work on ALL device you purchase!!! 2. Voice command works as expected. Just remember to KEEP your finger pressed on the mike button when you are asking a question. If you release the button that will be the end of what Alexa hears. Also, as opposed to using the echo, you do not need to say &#34;alexa&#34; as there is not wake-up required when you press a mike button. So, just ask your question or give your command. One nice thing is if you already have an Alexa device that you use (Echo as an example), you can use this to interact with that. As an example, if you are watching a program and decide you want to place an ingredient in your shopping list, just press the mike button on the remote and tell it to add that ingredient to your shopping list. It will do it and confirm the addition and then you go back to what you were doing. 3. You should be aware that there is NO way to turn off this device! As such, it is NOT compliant with auto switching features if you are using a HDMI auto switch. The device maintains power to the HDMI interface all of the time so automatic switching does not work. Also, this device does go into a sort of sleep mode after a period of time. So, if you switch to the HDMI port on your TV or on your HDMI switch, you may not have any video. To bring back the signal, just push the home button on the control. That should be enough to wake it up. It works on my TVs and on my switch that way. 4. Amazon support is a real nightmare. Expect to spend lots of time finding only Q&A sections that are fine for 80% of the basic questions, but will not generally address a problem such as streaming music on more than one device. Expect silly questions like what CAT level cable you have for Internet when you do get ahold of someone. They are working a script and you are NOT going to get around it!!! 5. One last thing, expect the back of the remote to be a GIANT pain to get open! You can push as much as you want to try and get it to open and it will probably not work. I finally had to resort to using a pen knife blade point to gently fit in the end to get the case to open. Just so you know, I had four other people try opening it using the instructions and no one was able to do it. I have had this same issue on every remote of this type (I have four Amazon Echo devices with this remote and three fire TV devices).All in all, this is a GREAT product as a standalone device if you have NO other Amazon products that stream video or audio. It is REALLY shaky when you have any of the Echo products and you want to use the Fire TV to stream music. It is also frustrating if you want to stream video to more than two TVs. Within those limitations it works well.",3,100,neutral,0.5238469243049622,0.449045866727829,0.5238469243049622,0.02710725925862789,0.4219,2,4003,0,0
Good deal as long as there is fast internet service and you have a lot of batteries.,"This device needs a TV, electrical power, a wifi network with broadband internet connection to work. It takes a few minutes to set up in the home network but its MAC address is easily found on one screen and the screens to input passwords and to connect to Amazon are both less awkward to use than much of my experience with previous devices.Once either the Firefox browser or the proprietary Silk browser from Amazon is downloaded it becomes an internet device with better capability than a smart phone, plus that huge TV screen. Web searches trend to those slimmed down sites you can put on a smart phone, but you can input regular URLs too. I'm in the process of collecting data so I can listen to my European news and music stations; you'd be surprised how much Euro internet media is free, plus there is the bonus of not having news filtered through the US network goggles. I'm taken by the youtube app, which is basically just a browser bookmark.Amazon also has a lot of free things for Prime users, particularly movies and TV shows. It is the rough equivalent to basic cable, plus Prime gives you free book shipping, other bells and whistles. Damned site cheaper than basic satellite plus equipment rental. Apps like HBO et cetera are free to download, but the subscription fee the HBO pirates stick you with is no more than if you'd had cable or satellite. And most of the third party subscription packages have the same expensive added crap as on cable. (I mean really, I'm an Amazon customer. I can read. I don't have time to watch idiots banging their heads together pushing a ball around on fake grass and I surely don't have time to watch home shopping networks, porn or the other crap.)I especially like the fact that this device can play my Amazon music library, but there is a big glaring flaw in the system. It will only readily play the electronic music stored in my Amazon account, not the Amazon purchased CDs I've put into my iTunes library, nor other CDs for that matter. (There is an inconvenient way for the Fire Stick to play iTunes from my local computer, but not iCloud. This involves enabling local file sharing, setting up Apple airplay, fiddling with iTunes settings, buying a third party Fire Stick app, setting up the app.) Amazon and Apple apparently don't believe in getting along and allowing the user to easily and quickly merge their libraries. Shame on you both. That's why this review is four instead of five stars.Oh, yes the remote. If there is problem opening it, a baby can get into it in about a minute, but watch out that they don't eat the batteries. Speaking of eating batteries, the remote batteries don't last long at all. And for me Alexa is a waste since I never use it. There should be a way of hardware disabling it so it doesn't contribute to battery wastage.After several months I'm adding the comment that I've downgraded my review from 4 to 3 stars over a variation of the same issue, battery wastage. The remote tends to draw heavily on batteries so that every click weakens them. This is particularly annoying if you like to do media searches on the device rather than logging on to your computer to do them there. What happens is you are clicking, perhaps trying to pause a video or go back to home, basically any click. Suddenly everything freezes and the only way out is to open up the damned remote, remove one of the batteries and then replace it. Apparently the problem is a momentary voltage drop because you can replace it with the same battery. I don't know the specific reason but it is really annoying. You will notice the older the batteries get the more frequent are the stops. You begin to feel like the rat in the Skinner box, click x number of times and the remote will reward you.",3,101,neutral,0.5954642295837402,0.3683590292930603,0.5954642295837402,0.03617680445313454,0.3322,5,3756,0,0
I like it but it's not better than the Roku in some ways,"I'll start with the good and work my way to the bad1. Voice controls are far superior to the Roku and you can control it from the remote or another Alexa device2. Comes with a HDMI extension if it doesn't fit straight in the hdmi port (It also said this small cord will boost wifi)3. It has beautiful photos for a screensaver4. It has good image quality most of the time5. It has a way better way amazon prime interface than the roku6. It still has Viki Asian drama channel (which has been removed from the Roku for some reason)7. It has a web browser which i probably won't use except for youtube.8. I got it a lot cheaper than the Roku stick9. There's parental controls that can be set require a pin to buy videos/apps and/or open apps.10. it has games which may be nice for some people11. It felt like an easy setup to me and I didn't need to look at the instructions.12. The interface looks attractive (This does not mean I like the interface just it's looks)Now is time for the bad1. The interface is horrible! Nothing stays the same so you have to hunt for the app you need unless you always open all apps.2. There are a lot of ads throughout the experience (Roku's ads are not intrusive like these are)3. Random apps have popped up in my app's and channels section (I hate ESPN Amazon!)4. No google apps at all so if you or your kids like YouTube or YouTube kids this is a bad choice (you can use the browser app to view youtube but it is really slow and doesn't have the kids version)5. There are a lot less apps than Roku so I would see if the channels you want are available (They don't have my cable company's apps, Vudu, and a few others that I would miss if I didn't have a Roku in the front room. Although movies anywhere fixes some of the problem apps)6.The remote doesn't have a dedicated Netflix and hulu buttons... Or even better i should have four customizable buttons that I could choose which apps I could open.7. While the quality is nice and crisp most of the time I have had random slowdowns or quality drops every once in a while. Roku doesn't seem to have this problem and the fire is right next to the wifi. I also don't have internet that gets throttled so I don't know what would be causing it I may just get the optional Ethernet adapter if I notice it too much since the router is next to my TV.8. There is no TV controls on this remote! I didn't realize how nice the Roku remote was until I got this as I can't change my tv's volume or turn it off and on. Regretfully I will need two remotes to watch tv in my bedroom.9. It's a lot slower than the Roku (Apps just pop up quickly on Roku while these fade in and out)10. When you close a app it doesn't keep it in the memory that long so you can't always reopen an app and return to the movie you were watching if you accidentally press the home button11. The Plex app doesn't seem as polished as the Roku version.And I'm not sure if I like or hate the fire TV iOS app yet. It makes it a lot easier to find apps but it's really easy to scroll to fast. I Think the Roku app is better but that doesn't make this app bad. All in all it was good for the price I payed so it will get 3 stars for now. If they fixed their interface I wouldn't think twice about giving it a four star review.",3,102,positive,0.7721822261810303,0.7721822261810303,0.2120828926563263,0.01573486626148224,0.7564,5,3264,0,1
i literally cannot with this lag!!!,"Assuming everyone already knows what this is and what it does, the only real question left is &#34;why do I need this?&#34; Realistically, there's nothing special about the firestick. Sure it's small and cheap, but just about everyone over the age of 16 owns a device or 3 that can do everything the firestick can, and more. It could be convenient for those who travel, and stay at hotels often, but again, there's just no exclusive perks for it to hold a candle to, let alone replace a laptop, a tablet, or even today's cell phone. Sure it connects to your tv, but so can your MacBook, and with 1 cord instead of 2. It has a remote yes, but many pc's come standard with those as well, that don't lag terribly like the firestick remote does, and boy does it lag!!! Sometimes it's not responsive at all. Removing the batteries and reinserting them usually works. I threw out a bunch thinking they were drained due to this.but serisously tho, wireless remotes have been working seamlessly for decades now, I seriously don't understand how this is even an issue in 2017Also, opening up your cable channel apps is such a pain!!!! You'd think that setting it up initially means you're good to go right? Nope. And it's not like a one step process either. It would be nice if there was a single link to your cable provider app that would allow access to your cable package, but instead, you have to download channel apps individually, install, THEN choose provider, enter SN and PW, send a code, and input the code on your tv screen. And this process is repeated for every channel app you install. Icing on the cake, voice control is absolutely useless. It never understands, nor executes any commands that would actually make it even the slightest bit helpful. Can we at least get a talk-to-text input going on search bars? its functions are pretty much exclusive to amazon video, which also sucks btw. There are so few good titles to choose from, and navigation is just a mess. Netflix, however, does run nicely on this device.So why is this buggy and unnecessary device so popular? One reason. Kodi. Kodi changes everything, it's called a jailbreak, but its really just an app you manually install onto your firestick. It's pretty simple to do with step by step instructions online, even non techies can do it without breaking a sweat. kodi hosts a number of add ons you can install to watch just about anything you like for free. exodus is really the only add-on you need. With it, you get a really nice layout of video content to choose from, and categories lists that make browsing much easier. Also complete with thumbnail cover art, movie titles and content info/description. They have literally every show and movie you could ever want to watch. Some even still in theatres, but not always the greatest copies. Its like a painless version of a torrent search without the headache of popups and downloads. It does disappear sometimes but you can easily reinstall it from your repository in the settings menu.So in conclusion, the amazon firestick is definitely worth the purchase, but the credit really goes to kodi for making it at all relevant.",3,103,negative,0.6212140917778015,0.03733877092599869,0.341447114944458,0.6212140917778015,-0.5839,5,3147,1,0
"It works, but the Amazon specific UI is poor compared to other devices.","My views on this are mixed. I got it to replace a failing Roku stick. The Roku was annoying me as it kept losing the remote and requiring hard resets and re-entering account info for every service I use. The Amazon Stick I had hoped would be a fast experience with better features.My opinion on it is mixed. It has a nice startup. Setup is not as annoying as the Roku, but still annoying. The speed and performance of the device is exactly the same as the Roku, so much so that I suspect they use the exact same hardware. But not a bad thing, except that the Amazon costs $10 more...My biggest issue with the Amazon Fire stick is the Amazon App and Menu system. I am an Amazon Prime member, I also have quite an extensive Amazon Library of movies and television that I have bought. I frequently like to view from this library, first and foremost. Amazon however seems determined to make getting to my purchased library as difficult as possible. Instead force feeding me new shows that I might wish to purchase or watch on Amazon Prime instead. After 10 minutes of digging with each login I can finally reach the single narrow strip that contains my purchased content. I now have to punch the left right buttons several hundred times to scroll through it all to find what I wish. All while Amazon tries to entice me to buy other stuff over the remaining 90% of the Television screen. Manipulating your purchased video content using the Kindle Fire Stick is just awful. Hats off to Roku, they do it 1000x better, for Amazon. The Netflix app on the Fire Stick is similarly much m uch better presentation and UI than Amazon's own. As is the Hulu and the Funimation, and Crunchyroll (seeing a pattern?)My second negative comes from a more unique situation to myself and my household. The Voice Navigation. My voice was medically compromised via a surgical error many years ago. I can speak well enough for humans, but the truth is only one vocal cord functions. So voice recognition machines cannot handle me. They are nothing but frustration in every way possible.The Fire TV Stick With &#34;Alexa&#34; is an ok experience. So far it has not had the number of repeated problems I had with the Roku stick. But this is countered by the Fire Stick having its own negatives including performance, a horrible and slow Amazon interface, the idiotic Alexa Voice Services that are useless for many people. It does have a nice responsive remote. Gotta give them that.If you like shouting into your remote trying to explain that you want to watch Star Wars, and not something far far worse, over and over, like a bad comedy routine, this might be for you. If you have that perfectly pitched announcers voice, with every crisp cadence exactly where it should be, you might actually find what you are looking for. Everybody else seeming gets a random selection from the &#34;worst of the Saturday Afternnoon SyFy channel movie playlist. You know what movies I'm talking about. You really do.",3,104,negative,0.6309058666229248,0.06425926834344864,0.30483484268188477,0.6309058666229248,-0.5666,5,2975,1,0
Adequate but choose the Roku instead for a better interface and better choices.,"We have both the Roku and the Amazon Fire stick and have compared extensively over almost a year now. We think the Alexxa feature is great but the Amazon Fire Stick has so many limitations we prefer the Roku by a large margin.First - The interface. We find the homepage easily misleading because you are always tempted to use the arrow keys to the right but it starts at the topmost menu and you think it is starting lower down. You think this because the top menu tends to be in a smaller viewing field and the main thing on the screen are Amazon highlights. They should have the topmost menu bigger and also have a lot more size / contrast for the highlighted selection. When we pause things like Plex, the unit will return to the main menu if the screensaver kicks in and we have to drill down multiple levels just to return to what we were watching which is a really annoying. Both devices offer using your phone as an alternate remote which is handy and helps a lot when you either cannot find your remote or the batteries have died.Second - Apps. Apps like the CW only list about a third of the shows that show up on the Roku and there is no option to sign in on many of them like you can on the Roku. The more you limit the apps and try to push people to the Amazon the more the Roku will appeal to consumers. The choices amongst apps is much more limited compared to the Roku and seem driven by demand instead of supply since they might contend with Amazon content delivery and so it is this conflict which I see driving lots of decisions behind the creation and management of this device.Third - convenience. I would say this and the Roku are both highly comparable as easily portable. It is very easy to grab the stick, the cord and the remote and travel anywhere.Fourth - Playback. With regards to playback it does a good job but is not as good as our Roku which is six months older. The fire stick often complains that it is unable to playback at full resolution (1080) either due to connection or transcoding issues from Plex but the Roku never has that problem. I believe the Roku has a larger memory or a larger portion set aside as a buffer and that compensates as well as the other variables like processor speed, architecture, etc. Bottom line - the Roku plays without issue and the Amazon Fire Stick has issues with playback. Another issue with playback are the control options. Subtitles cannot be adjusted for timing and this is a very big issue since some apps download subs separately and need the ability to adjust the timing to match the flick. This is a major flaw or shortcoming for the Plex app within the Amazon Fire series.Overall, we have enjoyed this Amazon Fire Stick but the Roku is simply better on many fronts especially the number of applications, signing in to specific applications, playback, and the general interface.",3,105,positive,0.6984099745750427,0.6984099745750427,0.26854047179222107,0.033049531280994415,0.6654,5,2858,0,1
"annoyed, i did so","idk if this is the appropriate forum for this but idk where else to leave this grievance. about a week ago i turned on my tv/fire stick and got the &#34;what's new&#34; screen showing a picture of a tv with the fire tv homescreen on the right and listing what's new on the left side with a &#34;continue&#34; tab at the bottom. i had never see this screen before. coincidently the remote that came with the fire stick had decided to stop working so i had been using the remote app on my iPhone exclusively. problem was now the app couldn't connect to the fire stick. at the time, since i had never seen the &#34;what's new&#34; screen before, i assumed the fire stick had reverted to factory settings for some reason and as a result was now longer connected to my wifi. that being the reason the app couldn't connect to the fire stick. with the app not connected and the original remote not working i had no way to &#34;continue&#34;. after trying everything i could think of and read on the web i finally called amazon. they basically told me that there was no way i was gonna be able to continue using it if the remote wasn't working and the app wouldn't connect. they told me i would have to get a new one and gave me a $30 credit toward it. annoyed, i did so. i got the new fire stick and after connecting to my wifi i tried the app. i had to put in a 4 digit code that appeared on screen which i never had to do before but it connected and worked perfectly. i used the app for a couple of hours and then went out for a few hours. when i got home and went to use the fire stick i got that same &#34;what's new&#34; screen and again my app would not connect. the regular remote worked so i was able to &#34;continue&#34; but no matter what i tried the app wouldn't connect. it would find the fire stick when searching for devices but would then give the &#34;can not connect try again&#34; message. i tried rebooting both the app and fire stick several times. i tried downloading the app to my iPad in case it was an issue with my iPhone. i even tried resetting the fire stick to factory settings. nothing worked. it simply wouldn't connect. the app did however still work with my other none voice control fire stick without a problem so i knew it wasn't an issue with the app or my network. i finally called amazon and asked to exchange the fire stick thinking this one was just a lemon. i got the new one yesterday, set it up and the app was working flawlessly but when i went to use it today i got the same &#34;what's new&#34; screen and again the app won't connect!!!! it's clear now that there was some kind of update to the fire stick that is incompatible with the remote app. i hope that amazon addresses this issue soon as not being able to use the app/keyboard is very annoying and inconvenient. has anyone else had this problem?",3,106,negative,0.6325831413269043,0.012067592702805996,0.35534924268722534,0.6325831413269043,-0.6205,7,2842,1,0
"Adequate, but doesn't really do all you might think as well as you might think.","Bought a FireTV stick to replace my Roku, because I wanted something that would play nice with the Echo Dot I got for Christmas. And it's... adequate?The interface on the FireTV is not great. It's not as intuitive or as easy to find things. If I do a search using my Roku stick, it'll find the show I'm looking for on every service it's available on, and let me choose which one, right there on the main screen. FireTV finds the show, doesn't always tell me which service it's on (or even if it's on one that I have, or whether it's free), and gives you a &#34;watch other ways&#34; link to show you other services it might be available on.There are a LOT of apps available for the FireTV. The main issue is, a lot of them are substandard. The CW app, the Starz app, and several others, are all cookie-cuttered from the same base, which makes sense. Unfortunately, that base is kind of crappy. They tend to lock up, or menu options don't do what they're supposed to. You might click on the latest episode of iZombie and the system starts Riverdale instead. I would have chalked it up to a quirk of the CW app if I hadn't seen the exact same behavior on several others.The Netflix app is fine, it's pretty standard. The Amazon Prime functionality is actually better on the Roku for some reason.And as far as playing nice with the Echo Dot? If I say, &#34;Alexa, play Jessica Jones on FireTV,&#34; it's smart enough to know I want it to open Netflix and start Jessica Jones. But it won't let me be more specific... say, maybe resume the last episode I was watching. Nope, it starts up Netflix and starts at the beginning of the series, because Netflix shows that I've watched every episode already. I can't tell the FireTV to play Jessica Jones, Season 1, Episode 4, because it chokes on that command.Other things I want to watch through other apps, it won't just play on voice command to the Echo Dot. You have to have the remote in your hand, which kind of defeats the purpose of voice control. So if I say, &#34;Alexa, play The Flash on FireTV&#34;, it finds &#34;The Flash&#34; and shows me that I can watch it on the CW app. I then have to pick up the remote, select the &#34;Watch now&#34; option... and it starts a random episode of The Flash, not the latest episode.These little quirks are enough to bring the rating to a 3 at best, and to make the Roku a far better device. I wanted a system that would be able to work reliable on voice commands alone. This does not. Without the remote in hand, there's not a lot you can do other than watch a Netflix show without being able to pick the episode. And with the not-as-good visual interface on the FireTV, the Roku is by far the better device.",3,107,negative,0.7157304883003235,0.037749771028757095,0.2465197741985321,0.7157304883003235,-0.678,5,2698,1,0
Meh. Seriously consider all variables before buying.,"DISCLAIMER: The actual rating is a 3.5.The stick is severely overpriced and buggy. Within the first hour of the installing the Stick it randomly froze on the spotify app. I restart the device and spend 15 min trying to figure out why it won't connect to WIFI after WIFI previously working just 20 minutes ago WHILE the remote froze. So i quite literally couldn't do anything. This has happened a solid 5 times since then, the only difference is that the remote stopped freezing.The voice assistant is borderline useless. &#34;Open Spotify&#34;. &#34;This is what we found about &#34;spotify&#34; and presents two apps that are related to spotify, i have to click three things to actually get to the app. I could easily just press home, click Spotify and be there with 3 seconds to save. The voice assistant is more of a gimmick and some superfluous selling point than an actual decent feature that advances the product.The three lines on the remote next to the home button is literally the most useless feature of this entire setup. I haven't found one instance were it actually works. I was under the assumption it's suppose to pull up some periphery menu in whatever application i was currently running on the tv. Nope. Does nothing. So why include it?My BIGGEST peeve is the fact that no volume button exists, not a software button (great way to make use to the three line button) or a physical button which is a gigantic pain. I have to constantly adjust the volume from my speakers manually for Tv then back down again for Music. The whole point of this stick is convenience.Now for the good:Most applications are aesthetically beautiful. I don't know if Amazon created some of these apps or its the individual companies but i'm impressed. It has Plex, Spotify, Youtube and Netflix which are my big four. They have other services like sports through multiple vendors which is great. I don't much care about NFL or NBA but i love Soccer and having other vendors who have their own apps just for those needs is really nice.PRO:-Aesthetically beautiful app.-Diverse app ecosystemCons:-No volume button****-Useless buttons on the remote-Voice assistant is a gimmick-Extremely buggy-Expensive. This thing should cost 25-30 bucks max. It doesn't offer enough to seriously justify paying 10 bucks extra over a Chromecast or Roku.I'll evaluate its convenience and consider returning it. The volume problem is such a bummer. The first stick didn't have one either. It's actually baffling that the second iteration doesn't have this. Ridiculous.",3,108,negative,0.9136389493942261,0.006931318435817957,0.07942972332239151,0.9136389493942261,-0.9067,5,2540,1,0
Great Product But Could Use Improvement,"I rate this product 3/5 stars overall given as an average for the two most important features I use.Streaming While Directly in Front of Television: 5/5 stars... Excellent product to stream movies using Netflix, Amazon Prime Movies and Music, DirectvNOW, many other apps that are available on this device. While sitting in front of the television you can control the interface seamlessly and the user experience is wonderful. There is also an app that allows you to use your phone or tablet as a controller. You must be in front of your TV to see what you are doing is the only caveat.Casting to Device from a Different Location in the Home: 1/5 stars... The only way to cast to this device is by using device mirroring. This application on phones/tablets consumes the power on the mobile device at a substantially large rate. While there is a remote app that you can use on your phone, there is not an interface that allows you to see what is being displayed on the device nor a navigation feature to choose different media from. It is a simple controller that has the exact same functionality of the remote that comes with the Fire TV Stick.In conclusion, if you are wanting a device that is used while sitting in front of the TV, or streaming Amazon Prime Media features is the goal of the use of this product... this device is exactly what you need. If you want to be able to cast third party applications, such as Pandora, Netflix, DirectvNOW, PlutoTV, IHeartRadio, YouTube, etc. from a phone or a tablet, then this device is probably not the best purchase in my opinion. I have only two televisions in my home. I have both a Chromecast device connected to a TV and a Fire TV Stick connect to a different TV in the home. I have just recently made a purchase of another Chromecast device to put on the TV that has the Fire Stick TV. For what I do in my home, I need the type of casting that Chromecast allows. With that said, I will be keeping my Fire TV Stick due to the wonderful interface and overall experience with their device. I just simply need something additional that they do not offer on their device.I hope this review helps.ADDITIONAL &#34;IN VAIN&#34; NOTE: If you are a developer for Fire Stick TV or Chromecast... please put your pride aside and collaborate to develop a product that works together seamlessly on one HDMI slot. You have the intellectual ability to create this product. Just charge more for the device, double the price if it makes your pockets feel better. I'm sure I am not the only one that would pay $75 for a product that meets the demands I described above.",3,109,positive,0.9641278982162476,0.9641278982162476,0.03323446214199066,0.0026375981979072094,0.9615,5,2600,0,1
Problems with speed; solved in odd way,"UPDATED REVIEW: For anyone else that has the same problems described in the original review posted at the end of this update:I checked with customer service, and their suggestion was to restart the device. That did help a little bit, but it was still too slow to be useable. After additional searching I came across a thread saying that moving the Fire Stick further from your router will solve this problem. As counterintuitive as that seems, I tried it. The lag and buffering disappeared.Just to make sure it wasn't the reset that solved the problem I moved it back to the TV near my router. The lag and buffering returned. The solution I came to was to switch the Fire Stick to my secondary network, which is a little slower and generally has a slightly weaker signal. This has sped up the Stick considerably. The speed is acceptable now and I've decided to keep it. In all other aspects I'd give the Fire Stick 4 to 5 stars. It's easy to set up, easy to use, and the UI is quite intuitive. If it weren't for the problems solving the lag switching between apps, which took a lot of searching and not a little bit of luck (not in a million years would I have guessed that moving it further from the router would be the solution) I'd give the Fire Stick 4 to 5 stars.END UPDATED REVIEW.I'm going to check for solutions and/ or customer service, but if none are available I'll be returning it. The fire stick is so slow during UI navigation that it is unusable. It takes more than 5 minutes to switch between apps, and seems to forget apps I've downloaded previously, forcing me to download them again, which takes more than ten minutes. Bear in mind I've only had it a few days and have about 5 apps.I have the fastest internet I can get short of business internet, my router firmware is up to date, and none of my other devices, including my Roku, which is 40 feet further away from the router and on a different floor, have any similar problems.All that being said, I like the UI appearance, and once a stream is acquired it plays with no problems, so I am considering trying the fire tv instead of the stick.Since I found no other reviews complaining of this I'm forced to wonder if my fire stick is defective, although once I found the problem and searched for it I found numerous threads discussing it.Update to this review: my wife has corrected me. She says it started buffering during streams on day 2 and it's getting worse. We set it up 4 days ago. We put it on a secondary tv that we don't watch often, so it hasn't seen a tremendous amount of use in 4 days.",3,110,neutral,0.516533374786377,0.04174806922674179,0.516533374786377,0.44171860814094543,-0.4,7,2570,0,0
Great while it works correctly.,"I got this in October 2017 and up until last week I would have rated it 5 stars. That dropped to 4 stars when it started behaving oddly, skipping several menu selections at random. It made no difference what app you were in, or weather you were entering search information, one click on the remote could end you up anywhere. Jumping around with no reason. I changed the batteries in the remote, but it made no difference in operation. I next disconnected the power to the firestick, and then tried it again, same thing, jumping around. I then contacted Amazon to request a replacement remote control, since it's under warranty still. I sent an email. This is where it dropped to 3 stars. The reply suggested I try new batteries, power off and then on, all the stuff I mentioned that I had already tried in my email, requesting a replacement remote control. It went on to mention if these measures didn't solve the problem a call to a technician was in order. I just need a replacement remote, or perhaps the firestick itself is in need of replacement. I have never had problems with Amazon before. They have always replaced or refunded for damaged or faulty items. This one bears their name, and I'm getting a hassle about it. When it's working correctly it's great.Update 11/15/2018The last of the fire TV sticks I purchased in July of 2018. Out of the box, two of them would not work using voice. I have 4 of these now, so I can swap remote controls around. All of the controls would work the voice on my other 2 sticks, so I know that the problem is not the remote, but the fire TV sticks. Now one of the sticks that did work with voice, has stopped listening, voice no longer works on it. On another stick the back button no longer has an effect on it. Again I tried swapping remote controls and they worked perfectly on a different stick. I have returned defective sticks before and got replacements. I like the streaming that the sticks can do, but the quality needs to be so much better than it is. The stick gets quite warm, and everything is packed inside a small crowded package. Plan on replacing these twice a year if you use them a lot. Get the extended warranty. I hope that there will be a quality improvement in the future, but it looks as though Amazon would rather have you purchase a more expensive cube or the like. I am just not convinced to spend even more money on a product that might not last any longer than a fire TV stick.",3,111,negative,0.8312220573425293,0.013101529330015182,0.1556764841079712,0.8312220573425293,-0.8181,3,2450,1,0
Battery Drain - Key Is To Leave Remote In A Stationary Position - Not On The Bed - Unless Changing Channels,"7/20/2018 - Update - Back for more - Bought 2 Fire Sticks during Prime Day for TVs in kitchen and guest bedroom. The battery issue has been pretty much tamed by using Amazon batteries - who would have thought it - the batteries usually last 2-3 weeks now which is a terrific improvement. However, the only way I could get consistent connection is to leave the battery compartment open. Something about having the compartment clip in place didn't work for me. I'm not sure if other users have had this experience. My Amazon Fire Stick really gets a work out through Prime and Hulu as selections from their libraries require a lot of arrow button use and I'm wondering how long the Fire Stick will hold up to the abuse. Alexa is a help - if you know what you are looking for otherwise spelling in the Search option is very tedious. It still needs work on its design but it gets me where I want to go with a minimum of effort.2/03/2018 UpdateThanks to the information posted by others in the Amazon Community I have been able to reduce the &#34;stuttering&#34; and flat out &#34;freezing&#34; of my Hulu feed. It is so IMPORTANT to place the remote on a flat, non-moving surface and just let it be unless you need to change the channel. I had been placing the remote next to me on the bed and apparently every time I moved it woke the remote up and drained the batteries. It has now been 2 days on the same batteries and that is a record. Now only time will tell if the batteries still crash out too often. I have researched on YouTube the possibility of using a universal remote or a gaming keyboard instead of the Fire Stick Remote, but am still a bit foggy on how or if I will need to do so - I'll let you know. MicheleLike so many others, I am very disappointed in this Alexa Voice Remote. It is super sensitive and it goes through batteries EVERY OTHER DAY. That is completely unsatisfactory. Unfortunately, I am now hooked on Hulu as well as the Amazon Prime library. I switched from Dish for Hulu and had to purchase the Amazon Fire TV Stick to utilize the new service. What I would give to have a re-charging unit or even one that is tethered to an electrical source. I am going to research the availability of another type of remote, one that isn't a battery power drain costing a fortune in batteries. If anyone else has a suggestion, please let us all know - Amazon certainly won'twon't.",3,112,neutral,0.5214208960533142,0.43300533294677734,0.5214208960533142,0.04557373374700546,0.3874,7,2395,0,0
... my TV for almost 3 years now and I love it. HOWEVER,"I have been using a fire stick on my TV for almost 3 years now and I love it. HOWEVER... I decided to upgrade to the model with Alexa, especially since it was discounted to $25.00. Delivery was par with Amazons excellent service. I hooked it up and prepared to learn how to use Alexa. But I got no sound, none at all. Called Amazon customer service and a tech guided me through several options, all to no avail. I could see him scratching his head in puzzlement. Then he suggests switching HDMI ports. I have 3 on my TV. I got sound!! Problem solved. Out of curiosity I switched to the 3rd port and got a small boxed notice that said &#34;unsupported mode.&#34; I have no idea what that means but the Fire Stick would not work in it at all. The 1st port had no sound. The 2nd port I got sound. OK! Good! I can go on to enjoy my new Fire Stick.Next day I notice the Q on the Home screen is almost completely obscured by the edge of the screen. I go to settings to calibrate the display but I can't get the clibration markers to move. Now the arrows were partially buried in the edges of the screen which means the image is not fitting the screen. But the calibration feature doesn't work. Well I try switching ports again but the results are the same as the day before. There's still no sound on the first port but the arrows are right where they are supposed to be with the points just touching the edge of the screen. I call customer support and find out the the new generation of Fire Stick does not calibrate the display. It shows the arrows but they don't move. You have to change the settings on the TV. This is one of those fraking BRILLIANT ENGINEER moves of fixing something that wasn't broke. To calibrate the image on the new Fire Stick you have to change the settings on the TV, which only makes no sense at all. Because when you switch back to cable or regular TV, you have to reset the settings on the TV. Real Smart meaning really STUPID!!! Now it really is broke. I was given the option of replacing the Fire Stick and took it.. The replacement did exactly the same thing as the first one.I'm tempted to give them just one star because of the redesign, but I really do like the Fire Stick and will still use it.FYI My old Fire Stick works in all 3 ports with no change in the sound or the calibration between ports. I'm not throwing it away.",3,113,positive,0.9312925338745117,0.9312925338745117,0.05732043832540512,0.011387094855308533,0.9199,4,2356,0,1
It has its features but is limited in certain aspects...,"I am updating my review due to a issue I have with Amazon's part...This is the lower tier streaming stick. There is a fire TV. It has upgraded specs and such for just about everything from gaming to 4k I believe. It also is currently the only one able to be controlled by a Alexa powered echo dot like I bought to go along with my fire stick. Currently there seems no way to connect the two unless you buy another hub but thats such a downfall to a great product... -** for me. Other than that device works excellent with only slight hiccups on voice recognition on complicated words.------------This is a great option as far as pre-smart-tv streaming goes, but it has its issues. I wish you could set reminders with it, or even use the voice control fully. Yes the voice works for simple tasks but if you want to pickup on a certain episode of a show it may not bring you to the right place (easily fixed with manual control but sad all the same.)PROS:Packaging - god I have never seen such good packaging in my life! I have ordered hundreds of items and none have been so neatly packed in sections and presentation!! Brownie points amazonRemote - the older version of this product didn't have a voice control remote but this one does include such a handy feature.Ease of setup - the only issue I see happening is the usb on your tv may not have enough juice for this fire stick which you can fix by using the included wall outlet adapter.Sleek design - niceMenus are easy and self explanatoryAbility to link your accounts like Pandora, Spotify, YouTube, ect. :)))You can check weather, traffic, sports, among other things. ( I haven't found a way to track your orders with the Amazon app you can download so I assume you have to use some other device like an echo or dot to do that. )*OPTIONALYou can use your phone as a remote - a nice plusYou can shop with Amazon right on your tv?? Idk why you would want to but yeah I guess...CONS:Usb may be too short or long depending on your setup.Can only function as a streamer really, no setting reminders or alarms...If you are not a prime member then you are getting a bad deal... If you are prime your getting a great deal!",3,114,neutral,0.641396164894104,0.16092455387115479,0.641396164894104,0.19767925143241882,-0.0368,5,2171,0,0
"Amazon Bricked the Device with an Update, But They Helped","This is one of the odder devices I’ve used for streaming. I recommend you do your research rather than go directly for the cheapest item. Amazon pushed an automatic update to the Fire Stick. When the television was powered on, a message on the screen displayed that the update failed and the device reset. When the device reset, the Amazon logo displays on the center of the screen and that is where the device is frozen. After 45 minutes on the phone with technical support, their final offer was 15% off if we bought a new one over the phone. After declining the offer, Amazon upped the ante to a $10 account credit for our troubles. We also declined this offer. The device is out of warranty and we did not dispute this. I absolutely expect a streaming device lifecycle to surpass 9 months. Search this issue online and you’ll find an expansive array of users with the same problem.[Update] Amazon called back and they specifically mentioned this review (this is all in the same day, mind you). Another agent at a higher support tier suggested another troubleshooting technique. That method did not work either and the device is officially toast. At this time, they offered to combine the 15% off, plus the $10 credit, so we took that offer and ordered a new one. At the end of the phone call, I was asked if I had any recommendations for the development team. It is common practice and standard for devices to run a backup prior to updating as a failsafe, so that they can be rolled back and brought back online if an update fails. Sometimes this is not the case, but the original software/firmware is hard coded into the device and that’s roll back option. Neither of those occur on the Fire Stick. They took these notes over the call and said they work closely with the development team and will communicate the suggestion. I did feel this was genuine and not hot air.At the end of the day, Amazon is making a solid effort under their new customer-centric model. I do appreciate that and hope my suggestions make the product better.However, I still cannot bump up my review any further than my three stars (originally lower). Cheap, in this case, means potential short product lifecycle. Just be aware of that. If you get a crazy good deal, you might consider the two year warranty for $5.",3,115,negative,0.7479026913642883,0.016974054276943207,0.23512329161167145,0.7479026913642883,-0.7309,7,2295,1,0
Cool stuff with support & picture quality issues.,"I got this device as part of a promotion for DirecTV NOW.  My experience with streaming devices has always been Roku, so that's what I'm comparing it to.You get (almost) everything you need to get started out of the box. The remote comes with batteries included. There's a small HDMI extension cable, but it is REALLY short, so if you need a real extension, you'll have to buy a larger cable.I love the introduction to Alexa, though I don't use it that much. It is strange that I have to go to my computer to add &#34;skills&#34; and can't do it right on the device itself.I'd love to have some more customization of the menu. I do subscribe to Amazon Prime, but the focus on that content is a bit much for me. It got better in a recent update, but you really should have Amazon Prime to fully enjoy the Firestick, and I imagine any Fire TV device.My two biggest complaints, so far:1. SUPPORT - Amazon doesn't seem interested in supporting the device because they don't have a record of the sale. The site suggests going back to whomever sold it to me. Unfortunately, DirecTV NOW and AT&T are little help. I can return the device or get an exchange at the AT&T Store within 14 days, but after that I have no idea how to get support. Roku is GREAT with support even though I got the device through SlingTV.2. Picture Quality - you might wonder why I wanted support, well it was picture quality. The Firestick defaults to &#34;Auto&#34; for settings and it chose HD1080 as that's why my TV can handle. There were red &#34;snowy&#34; artifacts and some edging on items in the picture as well. The DirecTV NOW rep (without troubleshooting) determined that it was connectivity. Interestingly, I have fast uVerse Internet and that router is less than 20 feet from the Firestick, in the same location where the Roku regularly works well at 1080P with the same connection. I had to override the &#34;Auto&#34; setting and downgrade it to HD720 I'll keep the Firestick as it is has cool features with Alexa integration and it is more portable than Roku when I travel.  Roku will return to be the main device in my living room as soon as DirecTV NOW completes it's Roku app, which is supposed to happen here in Q1 of 2017.",3,116,positive,0.5112696886062622,0.5112696886062622,0.47276318073272705,0.01596713811159134,0.4953,5,2212,0,1
"Good hardware, software changes make it less family-friendly","Bought this to replace an old (slower) Firestick and to upgrade the remote to a voice-controlled model for the wife and toddler. The good news is that it runs smoother, transitions screens faster, loads content faster, and everything you would expect from a 2nd generation product. But I'm not sure if the bad doesn't outweigh the good. Once it updated it's firmware, we were given the new interface which, while providing a more &#34;cinematic&#34; experience, also has some major flaws.Firstly, the prominence of the currently promoted Amazon original... it's so easy to click on (and streams a trailer video automatically if not turned off), that I had to enable parental controls on content for my young one. The fact that Mature includes unrated content means that, if enabled, my young one can't stream Timmy Time or any other unrated children's content without help. By not separating MA, R, etc, from unrated and not marking content as safe (whether it's actually MPAA rated as G, PG, TV-Y), means that you either have to risk your child viewing extremely inappropriate material or miss half of their shows.Secondly, and again, this deals with use by children, is the new menu system. The design went from a image-based GUI that rarely relied on text to one where reading is a needed skill. Previously, if you clicked on a show, you'd get a screen-capped listing of each episode. To watch it, you could simply select it, but to watch from the beginning you'd have to read the text icon... no biggie. Now, you select the tv show, which then shows you the current episode. Another click will resume that episode, however, to get to any other episodes, you need to use a text menu. The second button reads &#34;Watch from the beginning&#34;, which is not a real change, however, the episode list is hidden under a 3rd text button entitled &#34;Seasons and Episodes&#34;. Also, the main screen has now been used mostly for promoted content, while the recent and favorites are hidden in a screen to the right. Overall, this has made the device less family-friendly. Considering a good bit of Amazon's original content is tailored towards children, you'd think they'd have put more thought into the new interface.",3,117,positive,0.5352228879928589,0.5352228879928589,0.38587650656700134,0.07890064269304276,0.4563,5,2215,0,1
"Awesome, with glaring problems","I'm a huge fan of Android and Android TV, so this is perhaps my 5th or 6th purchase related to Android tv. This is an awesome device, but it does have some glitches. That they were able to pack the functionality of a full Android box into a stick form-factor is very cool. The specifications are modest, at only 1g Ram and 8g storage, but I'm sure there are challenges to fitting all that into a stick.If you get a USB cable, many televisions produce enough power out their builtin USB slot to power the stick, so you can install the stick entirely into the back of a television without additional cords or boxes hanging off it! It's almost like adding hardware modules to your existing television, without the muss and fuss of having more visible A/V equipment cluttering up your house.Except for one big bit of clutter, the remote. The stick uses a Bluetooth remote, which unfortunately makes it difficult to replace with a Universal remote, since there are very few Bluetooth enabled universal remotes on the market. If you are lucky, the CEC function on your TV might make the right mote unnecessary. Otherwise, you'll have to drop another $30 for a good Bluetooth universal or use the Firestick remote.Unfortunately, the Firestick remote also leaves off one critical feature... Volume control. I don't know what marketing genius decided that building a product without volume control was a good idea, but that makes for even more juggling of remotes. Even the Firestick app doesn't have a volume control. Unbelievable.Another glaring issue is the lack of a microSD slot, because the way the Android OS is designed, microSd cards are treated like native device storage for more applications as well as data and photos. Leaving it off means the customer is left with a very low ceiling for the number of installed applications that the device can hold.Overall, I like the device, particularly the stick form-factor. I might even buy another one when it's on sale. However, some of the choices made in designing the product, such as leaving off a Microsd slot, remote incompatibility, and lack of a volume control make me question the sanity of the product designers.",3,118,positive,0.9574705362319946,0.9574705362319946,0.0361279658973217,0.006401455961167812,0.9511,5,2169,0,1
"Amazon Firestick Review vs Roku March 27, 2019","Please read, very informative. I purchased the fire stick a few months ago. I really like my Roku a lot better. The firestick physical remote is the same size about 4 inches long and 1 1/2 inch wide. There's a circle at the top that you click the center for ""ok or enter"" and the edge of this 50 cent size circle is used to navigate up, right, left, fast forward, backward and pageback which I have not figured out yet. The connector to the back of your TV Sticks out about 3 to 3 1/2 inches and has a cord about 6 foot long. If you loose your firestick remote you can download the app on your phone, but it's difficult to operate. When netflix asks if you are still watching it a real pain to stop what you're doing to click on the app, wait for it to find your firestick and click it a few times to get the movie playing again and you have to be connected to your home internet in order for it to work. (We lost the physical remote so I can't give you a picture of that, only the app screen). The phone app works like the mouse pad of a laptop. You have to tap, swipe up or down, tap, tap. The phone app for the remote also has the Alexa voice command. It works pretty cooI.. ""Alexa, play NCIS on Netflix"" and it will play without having to search for it through 5,000 movie titles. The firestick does have the basic a, b, c search option same as the Roku Th Roku has buttons for fast forward, ok, backward and page back, the Firestick is just harder for me to operate. I'm 50 years old and manage my own website by myself, so I'm not stupid or technology challenged. I give the Firestick 3 stars and give the Roku 5 stars compared. The Roku does not have a voice command option, but is much more user friendly and easier to operate. The connection to TV is 2 wires, and a small router about 3 inch by 3 inch and lies flat beside the TV like a super small version of a DVD player. The Roku has a few more connection problems than the fire stick, but both work perfectly if you connect directly to your internet router via an Ethernet line. I can say my 25 year old daughter prefers the Firestick to the Roku and says it doesn't crash as often and won't be obsolete when the new Roku comes out. To each his own.",3,119,positive,0.946010172367096,0.946010172367096,0.05058155208826065,0.003408274846151471,0.9426,6,2212,0,1
"Okay for low usage, terrible for anything more.","TL;DR: Anything without an ethernet port is going to suck no matter how close to wifi it is especially in older houses with a lot of crap in the walls that cause interference. That said, the wifi is sufficient for pandora, and perhaps 720 streams but will SUCK with anything higher. Avoid it if you're an enthusiast like I claim to be, or if you expect your usage to scale to those levels over time as you'll eventually have to replace it when it does.Full: I bought this for an older 1080p TV that while technically a smart tv was showing its age, and I think no longer updated as it was using older app versions. I'm not the primary user of this particular TV and the people using it use fire sticks on their other TVs. These people rarely use my plex and are content using netflix, pandora, hbo prime, etc. but more importantly they are familiar with this setup so I didn't want to go all out and buy an apple tv for it when this was a cheap quick fix (as they said themselves the smart TV sucked). I would get called down occasionally to &#34;fix&#34; problems (buffering, stalling, etc) that was often solved by simply restarting the app or device. I started to loath this device as in the past I was similarly called to fix issues with the other fire sticks they had and I gradually had them upgrade their TVs so the Ethernet runs I ran in the beginning would do their job.Ultimately these devices run fine most of the time, but no matter now close to a WiFi signal there will occasionally be issues caused by interference which a normal person wouldn't expect to cause them (vases, containers, metal, etc). I tried to love them as cheap solutions to non primary devices and that's really what they are intended for but as there is no Ethernet there are issues.The best example of this btw, is when I upgraded the 1080p tv with an apple tv and tried to re-purpose the fire stick on a tv closer to a wifi signal (2ft). In that scenario there was a relatively high ping (30-50 in test) and I just gave up on it for that reason. The UI itself is nice looking and relatively fast but there are bottlenecks. So pissed off was I that I actually wrote this review!",3,120,negative,0.788033127784729,0.020921221002936363,0.19104568660259247,0.788033127784729,-0.7671,4,2163,1,0
Doesn't support VPN.,"This product has a lot of issues that are not advertised. I've seen several questions answered for this product stating that it will work with VPN. My experience is that it MAY work with VPN. I was having connection issues claiming that I was out of the geographic area and couldn't watch certain videos. I am physically in the US, and my VPN makes me appear as though I am in the US, so there should be no geographic issues. I contacted Amazon tech support, explained the issues I was having, and that I was connecting through a VPN because I figured that was the problem.They found a disclaimer on the Amazon site stating it should NOT be used with VPN, so they didn't offer any more help than tell me to not use a VPN: https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html/ref=help_search_1-3?ie=UTF8&nodeId=201422810&qid=1505415910&sr=1-3Here's the quote from that: &#34;Note: Amazon Video streaming is not supported through Virtual Private Network (VPN) or proxy connections. To watch Amazon Video, you'll need to disable these services for your device or try switching to another available connection.&#34; My experience with using the VPN is that it will work for a month or two, then shut down. If I change to a different VPN server(still within the US), I can get it to work again for a little while. But this is a nuisance, and I shouldn't have to get rid of my VPN to use their service. I have also had issues with reset. There is no power button on it, and occasionally it has frozen. When this happens I have to crawl behind the TV to get to the power cord to unplug this. It really shouldn't cost that much more to put a switch there, or allow it to be switched on and off by the TV. When it works, it is mostly good. The streaming is fast. The interface still needs a little work, I don't think it is laid out that well. The voice search generally is the fix for this. But voice recognition doesn't always work(and sometimes a reset fixes this). The voice search seems to have more issues when the remote batteries get low too, although maybe that is just a coincidence.",3,121,negative,0.7049050331115723,0.01619160734117031,0.2789033055305481,0.7049050331115723,-0.6887,3,2084,1,0
I suffered a disappointing blow!,"I enjoy the ease of set up & use of Fire TV Stick. I also like Alexa voice command....it works well if you are very specific in what you look for. It will take a little time to figure that out though.Even though it has been a positive experience, there are 2 issues which must be addressed.1. As I was scrolling thru the long list of my music, the entire system froze completely. I had to turn off the TV/DTV box. The next day I simply unplugged everything & reset the DTV box & the router. This finally cleared up the problem, but it was a royal pain, & can only wish that thistechnology be as problem free as possible. I don't really understand what happened, or why this happened. This is one thing I don't have to dowith Direct TV......so I expect the same from Fire TV stick.2. The other issue is how I spent 1/2 a day putting tons of movies on my Watch List.....only to find out when my friend was anxious to watch some of these cool movies with me, I noticed a problem. Much to my surprise (& disappointment), most of what I selected I would have to pay for. My problem with this??? I'm trying to reduce my costs associated with TV/Internet & Phone which I currently have. I already pay $99 for Prime...but to add another station for a monthly fee will actually bump up the cost considerably. Then to have to pay for movies as well is insane!!!!!!!!! When is there ever going to be a company that blows the companies who monopolize these services completely out of the water, AND gives the customers reasonable prices AND freebies??????So, tell me....just how is Amazon going to keep my business considering these circumstances/issues???? My main goal is to get away from all the cable & satellite companies, so I truly thought Amazon was my answer. Now I'm not too sure. I've been an Amazon customer for many years & have always remained faithful to this company. Just how, I wonder, will Amazon provide me w/excellent customer satisfaction? Well, I'll find out soon enough & make my decision to stay with Amazon or continue w/Direct TV.",3,122,positive,0.7989616990089417,0.7989616990089417,0.17950449883937836,0.021533817052841187,0.7774,0,2045,0,1
"Fire TV Stick is good!!  (NO don't listen to me.  It turns you and your television into a ""TV Stick Zombie""","There are a few good things about the TV Stick, and some bad things:Good things:You won't have a problem with caching and buffering with legit applications (applications that pirate content are a whole different story).Your computer can be turned off when you use your Fire TV StickThe graphics layout is respectable, and app is very responsive. Changing programming, and starting shows is very fast. (but not with apps like terrarium or mobdro).Running the remote is not super-intuitive, but it's not really that bad either.Bad Things:1) Zombie Activity. My big flat screen has five HDMI inputs as well as coaxial (we use an antenna). When the TV Stick is plugged in it takes over your television's brain and makes it play ALL TV STICK, ALL THE TIME. So, if you're watching a DVD, or live television, the TV stick will change the input so that the TV stick is what you see. If you change it back to the DVD input, the TV Stick will change it right back again. I discovered this problem during a particularly exciting part of the Super Bowl when the TV Stick switched us from football to the TV Stick's home screen (I got vivid flashbacks to the &#34;Heidi&#34; Bowl. And yes if you remember that you are old). DON'T BECOME A TV STICK ZOMBIE. The only solution is to unplug the Fire TV Stick. I called Amazon tech support and they said THIS TV BRAIN STEALING ACTIVITY IS NORMAL.2) If you ain't paying for a service, Fire TV Stick will not show you their content. In other words, you won't get ESPN by merely downloading the Fire TV Stick ESPN APP.3) Access to UTube appears to be quite limited.4) Alexa is a corporate shill and only likes to answer questions pertaining to Amazon Prime programming.A word to folks who want to use Terrarium TV and Mobdro (I can't speak for Kodi). 95% of the links are unwatchable as they buffer literally every five seconds. Get yourself a notebook and make note of the 5% of the links that do work. It's a lot of work, but in the end it makes this apps worth using.",3,123,positive,0.5805577039718628,0.5805577039718628,0.3458511233329773,0.07359117269515991,0.507,4,1999,0,1
Great out of the box but apps need improvement,"I currently stream through Apple TV and have to use the AirPlay feature to watch Amazon Video on my TV. Since this is inconvenient due to the location of my computer, I decided to purchase a device to allow me to directly stream Amazon Video through my TV (and likely replace my Apple TV).Out of the box, the All-New Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote was quick & easy to set up and I was watching Amazon video on my TV in just a few minutes. The most difficult aspect of setup was getting the battery compartment on the remote to open (which I noticed numerous others have mentioned) - a serious flaw - I have good manual dexterity and it was actually quite difficult for me. I was impressed that someone thought to have the welcome/introduction video play automatically during the short wait for the system to be configured. The voice remote was fun to play with but I doubt it will get very much use in my home, as we mostly watch series and the results from the voice search don't take you to the correct episode in your queue. I imagine it would be more useful for finding movies, or shows that are not yet in your watch lists. Picture resolution is fantastic and color is vibrant (actually so vibrant and rich that I found I preferred a less-vibrant color setting on my TV). I was really excited at first, and expected that it might replace our Apple TV. This was not to last for long however, as I was disappointed that the only way to view your watch list for both Amazon and Netflix are by scrolling through a carousel (which is cumbersome at best - unless you only have a few titles saved - and I doubt very many people fit in this category). Although not directly the fault of Amazon Fire Stick (since they are apps), I thought I would mention it in case you are expecting your Netflix or Amazon Video watch list to look & perform the way it does on computer or Kindle Fire (or Apple TV for Netflix). If it were priced any higher I likely would have returned it - but since it does allow me to watch Amazon on my TV, I'll be keeping it.",3,124,neutral,0.6444852948188782,0.29990923404693604,0.6444852948188782,0.055605512112379074,0.2443,5,2050,0,0
"Good, could be better.(Starz is blocked)","I purchased this as a gift for my mother.She loves the Voice feature, however she complains that its hard to find shows directly. IE if you want the newest episodes of Supernatural that are on the CW you can't just say Supernatural. You have to say CW then navigate to the cw app then search for supernatural.Its a little better if the show is on prime or Netflix, however it is hard for her to figure out which service she would be watching it on. And some times there is a show on Netflix and on Amazon but not prime and she accidentally clicks the wrong one and gets frustrated.Another HUGE issue (to us) is that it will not allow you to download the starz/encoure app. when you try you get an error saying its not available on this device. Thus the only way for us to watch starz on the stick (even though we have a subscription though our cable company) is to purchase an additional subscription through amazon channels, which is ridiculous. I contacted amazon customer support about this, and the rep tried to convince me to subscribe to the amazon starz channel and claimed I wouldn't be charged. I then asked to talk to a supervisor and she put me a hold for a significant amount of time came back and seemed surprised I was still there and then told me that the supervisors were all busy and that I would have to have them call me back that I couldn't wait on the phone for them. I waited 3 days and contacted them again and they apparently had no intention of calling me back. Amazon usually has stellar customer support though in this instance they were horrible.(its been over a month now and still no contact)Please note. Normally I would never include My experience with Amazon in a review for an item I purchased on Amazon.com. I include the information about my experience with Amazon as it regards to this particular device as it is made by Amazon and the capacity in which I am reviewing them is in the Manufacture and Maintenance of their product. This has nothing to do with reviewing the seller/shipping experience.",3,125,positive,0.6153662204742432,0.6153662204742432,0.3369913399219513,0.047642484307289124,0.5677,2,2036,0,1
"For $16, it's alright.","I'll cover a few basic points that I feel are important in evaluating a streaming device:VIDEOOne major issue when streaming video - even when the stick is configured to stream video at 1080P/60hz via the Settings, it will stream 720p initally and then switch to 1080P after some time with Amazon Video/Netflix. I have a 7Mbps connection and on my Apple TV, which is placed at about the same distance from my Wi-Fi router as the Fire Stick, the stream kicks off at 1080p from the start. Well, kind of annoying but bearable.CONNECTIVITYI did not experience any of the Wi-Fi issues (stuttering/lag) other users have mentioned while streaming Amazon Prime Video/Netflix. Maybe the home network setup and the Fire Stick settings just happened to align.PERFORMANCEThe performance of this device is crap when it comes to doing basic tasks. For example, when I navigate the menu to switch between movies/apps/etc.., the UI sometimes freezes for a good 3-8 seconds before it can receive anymore commands from the remote. Also, when searching for content by &#34;typing&#34; with the remote, the UI will sometimes pause for 2-4 seconds as it fetches the results. This really kills the TV-only user experience for me and is the reason I took off a star.USER EXPERIENCEIt's not as slick as Apple TV's UI but it's not terrible either. Very similar to what you'd see for Windows 10's &#34;Metro&#34; look.REMOTEThis is basically a dumbed-down version of the standard TV remote (fewer buttons) but with an added microphone for Alexa Search. If you are a heavy smartphone (Android?) user, then the icons on the remote will be intuitive and you'll be able to figure your way around with ease.Honestly, I'd prefer the Apple TV remote with the touchpad surface (I know its made of glass, which can shatter) since it lets you scroll through content as opposed to repeatedly tapping on the arrow buttons.ALEXA SEARCHSeems to work about as well as Siri.",3,126,neutral,0.7364454865455627,0.0981677770614624,0.7364454865455627,0.16538670659065247,-0.0672,5,1932,0,0
"Not bad, I bought it to use exclusively with Playstation ...","Not bad, I bought it to use exclusively with Playstation Vue. PS Vue guide interface is very cumbersome on the Roku so I bought the fire stick just so I could use the grid view for channel schedules. My router is located 2 ft from my tv so I know the signal strength is good and I had no problem with the Roku. I have had the stick for 2 days. I have not had an uninterrupted tv session yet. I got a screen message when I first set up that said the USB power was insufficient, that might be a cause. It seems that they are aware of this issue because it gives you an option to continue. Also there is an adapter supplied for wall outlet use. I have not tried that yet. I have a name brand TV and have used other similar devices and never had that issue before. The Lexa works Good, I was very impressed with that.. I gave this 3 stars because I have used other streaming devices for over a year and the wireless technology is just not there yet. My other devices I have hard wired with ethernet and I have great reliability. Even my TV is wireless Smart TV but they recommend ethernet cable in the owners manual for streaming purposes. I wish they would figure this out for the sticks. I started with sticks and found their reliability is not as good as the box versions. But for $30 on sale I took the gamble.All in all I won't say either way to encourage or discourage purchase. I bought on sale and I am familiar with the Amazon Video format which is the same on the Stick and you incorporate apps into it. So it keeps everything in one place. I don't use the stick exclusively and I don't see myself making it my preferred device.I have not used the box version but I've heard is very good but I am cheap and the narrow use I had in mind I thought the stick was economical. I already have other box devices and they are great. The issue's are not with the brand per se but more with wireless technology. They are packing a lot of technology into a small space and something has to give.",3,127,neutral,0.5697290897369385,0.35603010654449463,0.5697290897369385,0.07424072176218033,0.2818,4,1990,0,0
Screen Saver doesn't always work on Amazon Music!  Screen damage warning!,"While the Amazon Fire TV Stick comes with a screen saver, it can't easily be made to work when you're connected to Amazon Music! If you select a 40 minute classical work, you can be sure that some graphics, a smaller version of the album cover, and some operational icons will be sitting there, always in the same position, at full brightness, burning into your TV screen! However, after some long unproductive chat with the Amazon crowd, I decided to do some more experimentation on my own. It turns out, that after you select your music and it's playing, if you go to the ""Browse"" menu on Amazon Music, and leave it there, the screensaver DOES operate. Nobody at Amazon, not even the supervisor, could figure that out! Your music will continue to play and you get the lovely photographs Amazon provides for a screensaver [or provide your own photos].Another problem I found with this product is its low HDMI signal level. Its HDMI output couldn't even drive a 3-foot HDMI cable! This device MUST be plugged directly into an HDMI input on a TV etc, or, into an active splitter. [Don't use those HDMI amplifiers that take their power from the HDMI cable, use a splitter with it's own power supply, even if you don't use any of the other outputs on the splitter.] I also have found that sometimes placing a splitter at the END of a long cable run, rather than at its beginning, will work the best! Experimentation is called for. Right now I have my Amazon Fire TV stick supplying its signal to three TV's, one of which is at about 75 feet away from the TV stick!If your TV input is hidden away, you may have trouble receiving your Wi-Fi signal with your TV stick hidden somewhere in the cable mess behind your TV. Best way to go is to purchase an HDMI splitter and use that to drive a length of cable plugged into your TV input. That way you can position your Fire TV Stick for best Wi-Fi performance. This is a good product once you figure out how to use it!!",3,128,neutral,0.514708936214447,0.07661514729261398,0.514708936214447,0.408675879240036,-0.3321,4,1959,0,0
Lacks processing power for streaming live TV,"Well, I think just like anything else, we want the &#34;end all be all&#34;. I sure did. I had Comcast service and with their rates going up and up, I wanted something to help me cut the cord finally. I'm very technical, so I didn't mind messing with the Fire Stick to get the extras going, but explaining the constant buffering/lag on the TV service portion is unsettling. Streaming via Netflix, Amazon, etc., is fine. No issues there. The only issue becomes when you try to view live TV. I've read all about the buffering fixes, tweaks, etc., but still very disappointed with the lagging. I have extremely fast internet so I know it's more of the processing power (or lack thereof) of the Fire Stick, as opposed to speed. In addition, since the &#34;native&#34; streaming works, clearly it's more of a processing issue from the IPTV servers that the Fire Stick just doesn't play nice with.I don't mind rebooting the stick, or just dealing with the lags/stuttering, etc., but everyone else in the household finds it annoying. There is definitely something soothing about a long day at work and coming home and turning on the TV and it just working. Nothing more frustrating than coming home and messing with settings., etc., just to watch TV (not movies).I bought the Fire Stick based on the reviews and surprised so many people are not reporting the same issue. The Fire TV (the &#34;box&#34; version) was out of stock for 1-2 months, so I got this instead. I think the Fire TV may be a better choice as it's got more processing power than the stick. If it still buffers and keeps driving the family crazy, I may just order the Fire TV, or a different box altogether, and try that instead.Conceptually, it's awesome. For regular streaming, it's just fine. For live TV, it's below average. I think it depends on what your intended purpose is, but if it's watching &#34;cable tv&#34;, you may want to get something more powerful.",3,129,neutral,0.4353524446487427,0.2252199798822403,0.4353524446487427,0.339427649974823,-0.1142,7,1929,0,0
"OK, but a bit sketchy. I returned the item and went back with cable.","First off, I have to say that it is very possible you will not encounter the same issues that I did depending on your wifi connections, etc. I have Up to 50 Mbps download via my internet provider and a pretty nice router. Though I have what I thought to be a pretty good config, we still had a lot of stutters and stops in programming to the point where it was annoying. If I were a person that was not used to the glamorous world of a cable provider and all the things that come with it, I think this would be perfect. Could I have lived with this, sure, but could my wife, nope. Reverting back from a great cable package to the stick is a bit difficult. This option was going to save me about $80/month, so trust me, I really wanted it to be a success. I also wanted to have the satisfaction of walking into my cable provider and putting all of that equipment on their counter and cancelling due to their excessive prices. When I got the stick, I also got Playstation Vue. Vue's program selection and pricing was pretty good, but one shortfall is that they did not have the History Channel. Yes, many would now view me as being lame, but I enjoy watching some of their programming and to keep this around, I would have had to add in Sling or some other web viewer. Vue's channel guide was also a challenge. They seem to update programming live, so when you surf timing (earlier/later), through the channel options, it's very slow to respond. I don't believe this to be an issue with the stick, but wanted you to be aware. One other complaint with the stick is that the remote is soooooo small. We continually lost it in the couch, etc. Also the inability to adjust channel/volume from a single remote is annoying. Anyway, like I said, many have not had a negative experience and I was hoping for a success, but I think I will wait another year or so to see how web programming advances and how this technology also improves, then give it another shot.",3,130,positive,0.43965625762939453,0.43965625762939453,0.43667304515838623,0.12367069721221924,0.316,0,1953,0,1
first one failed.. but see comparison to other popular streamers.listed,"We are very Overly saturated with streaming devices. Don't know why, it just happened.*Samsung Smart 8000 series 4k 3D TV..baked in*Samsung 3D Smart Blu Ray..baked in*Toshiba Smart Bluray..baked in*Shield TV with Remote and Game Controller..the best most versatile Streaming Device we have..Most Pricey as well.4k..best sound and picture..Good voice control and private headphone jacks.rechargeable remotes.Plex server built in...great gaming system..constant major updates from Nvidia..easy to add at least 8TB additional store.etc*3..Roku 3's needed for multiple TVs..very over priced with flimsy poor quality remotes..has headphone jack for private listenlng.terrible voice search..great interface*Roku Stick for travel..*Chrome Cast 2 needed for Google Home..in many ways more useful then Fire Stick..no remote . good buy for the $25 sale price*New Fire Stick..just to try..received defective one..ALEXA lacking for information compared to Google Home.good remote.. voice search better then Roku.cheapest price of any of the others***Comparing the Samsung TV to Fire stick..do you even need a Fire Stick.**advantages of Samsung over Fire Stick..1) It is included2) only one remote to deal with3) voice feature and mouse built in the pod style remote4) Web browser built in without complicated apk slide loading5) boots much faster6) plays from hard drives and Flash Drives for photos and videos**Fire Stick advantages over Samsung Smart TV1) no smart TV needed2) Alexa provides nice detraction for fun3) Voice control does different things4) better complete account access such as photos etc.5) orders from amazon if you know exactly what you want.pain if you don't..6) worth the $29.95 even if you have smart TV7) have not yet tried for travel but assume it will set up on hotel TVs",3,131,positive,0.6085577011108398,0.6085577011108398,0.32841360569000244,0.0630287304520607,0.5455,4,1787,0,1
Over the past year my cable bill has ballooned up every month to the point where I just felt like I was getting ripped off,"I'm writing an honest review of the fire stick. Over the past year my cable bill has ballooned up every month to the point where I just felt like I was getting ripped off. The reason was there aren't any other option in our area that offer the same internet speed and tv packages. So I started talking to some friends and alot of people told me about the fire stick and how they cut the cord on cable. I wanted to give it a try a and see how it goes. The fire stick is well built and easy to install, the interface is just like any other streaming service (netflix or hulu) out there. From a movie/tv show rerun perspective this thing was great, the disappointment for me came in a few areas. When your used to live tv you still want that type of service and the fire stick isn't that. Its not a flip through the channels type of device, more so its a I have a particular show I like to watch and lets find it type of one. You can download various apps that search for live tv streams but remember they might not necessarily be in your local demographic, so local stuff or even sporting events are hard to find. Than if you manage to find what you want you have to remember your really just watching a stream that someone else is broadcasting, the quality might be sup par and not 720-1080 quality, there are delays and skipping at times which might not even be related to your own network or isp but rather the streamer. One also has to have the proper hardware in place to support streaming. An internet connection that is capable, and the network hardware of supporting higher speed wireless streaming. Even though I have a 200mbps service from my isp, my router was only capable of 54mps which means to to take advantage of the fire stick and increase the speeds I needed to upgrade my router to a newer ac protocol. If your looking for a device that offers movies and tv shows this is up your alley but as a full on tv replacement it just isn't there yet.",3,132,negative,0.610056459903717,0.06182536855340004,0.3281181752681732,0.610056459903717,-0.5482,0,1960,1,0
AMAZON PLEASE UPGRADE Fire Stick to 21st Century technology.  Back Light LEDS; Rechargeable Battery / BASE...,"Amazon Prime TV / Movies / Music are MUCH BETTER than ALL THE COMPETITION. My ONLY Complaint is the FIRE STICK! It is OLD Technology. Redesign STICK using Rechargeable Batteries that sits on a base; Install LED Back Lighting in Stick and Base so I can FIND the Stick AND SEE the BUTTONS. Finally the Voice feature works so poorly, I do NOT waste time trying to use it anymore.Amazon Prime, IMHO, is Top of the LIST for Audio/Video companies and HD viewing and listening.Except for the The Fire Stick. It works OK, BUT IT REALLY NEEDS UPGRADES for the 21st Century!1. Voice activated microphone DOES NOT UNDERSTAND nor does it FIND anything. I can SPELL a Movie, or Program, and it will find the item. BUT IT STILL CAN'T BRING IT UP TO PLAY or start the selection.2. Fire Stick should be an LED &#34;back-lit&#34; device. The Fire Stick is impossible to SEE or FIND in darkness for night time viewing.3. BURNS THROUGH Batteries!!4. VERY LEAST, Please UPLOAD THE COMMANDS TO LOGITECH SO I CAN PROGRAM MY LOGITECH HARMONY WITH THE FIRSE STICK Commands AND USE JUST A SINGLE DEVICE TO START AUDIO RECEIVER; TV; AND FIRE STICK. Even with Competition, I was able to program all their REMOTES to my Logitech and USE ONLY ONE, 1, REMOTE for ALL MY Electronic DEVICES to operate ALL my Video and or Audio components for 10 years! Until now.I have a drawer full of very expensive remotes, AND use ONLY ONE to work ALL MY ELECTRONIC NEEDS. NOW I have to use the Fire Stick along with Logitech Harmony. At least I can ALWAYS find Logitech because it is lighted, has a rechargeable base, and is a ONE Button Remote. Come On Amazon, I'm impressed with Prime, AFTER YEARS of Other's services, I CANCELLED the Competition. My friends and neighbors who STILL pay for the Competition... are impressed too with how Prime's Menu works, Recents, Watch list etc, Impressed with EVERYTHING EXCEPT the Fire Stick Remote.",3,133,negative,0.3602202534675598,0.3461132049560547,0.2936665415763855,0.3602202534675598,-0.0141,5,1896,1,0
"It's okay, it works, a couple of flaws.","Issues with the remote prevent this from being a really good experience. Battery compartment is very difficult to get open as other have mentioned. Some apps seem to have problems with the remote. Remote works, but after watching a show, it seems to disconnect and the app crashes and restarts before the remote responds again. Speaking into the remote works quite well. Had no problems connecting to WiFi and it's pre-registered to my Amazon account, so setup took about 1-2 minutes. As some have noted, it does seem to 'broadcast' a WiFi SSID, which I have read the remote uses. This may be part of the problem I have with the remote disconnecting during periods of non-use while watching shows. Not certain how to fix this, or if it's a power saving feature. It's definitely a problem and I really don't understand why Amazon decided to use this kind of setup. It operates in the 5Ghz spectrum and does not seem to be interfering with my access points' operation, nor being interfered with by other transmitters.Picture quality is what I expected, menu systems are FAR superior to Apple's Gen 4 Apple TV, especially manual input of letters and numbers with the remote. Onscreen alphabet is in a rectangle 5x6 characters versus Apple's ridiculous A-Z line that goes from one side of the screen to the other. While still tedious compared to a keyboard, it's far easier than using Apple's. The instructions that come with it are sparse. Granted, it's fairly straight forward, and a no brainer for anyone familiar with A/V and WiFi, but for non-technically inclined people with no network or A/V experience, this might be problematic.Also had trouble getting it to fit directly into HDMI port on my TV, as well as the adapter/extension that came with it. Seems to be bigger or 'oversized'. Had to really fight to get it to slide in.Too many silly problems to give it better than a 3/5.",3,134,negative,0.7091735005378723,0.02661643549799919,0.2642100751399994,0.7091735005378723,-0.6826,4,1884,1,0
Where's the Spectrum App?,"Edit (10/28/2018):There appears to be a Spectrum app for Fire platforms now. At least there was one that came out many months ago for Fire HD tablet. Unfortunately I do not have the means to test its usability and quality on this particular device (Fire TV Stick) without purchasing another. Since I have no reason to do so, I've upgraded the rating to 3 stars (average) simply since I cannot discredit them without being able to test it. I should also point out that this is probably more Spectrum's fault than Amazon's, since most likely the software would have been written by Spectrum or some company on Spectrum's behalf to make it for Fire platforms. Either way, the original review was based on the fact it didn't support the one reason it was purchased. Now that it apparently does, I cannot let a 1 star remain.Original review---------------------Bought this for a friend, and *was* going to buy the Fire TV (4K HD version) for myself until I helped my friend set up their Fire TV Stick. We both have Spectrum for a cable provider. I have 2 Fire HD 8's and Amazon App Store has the Spectrum app on it which works fine on the Fire HD tablet, but the Fire TV Stick can't find that app in Amazon's app store. So apparently, the Spectrum App is compatible with the Fire HD 8, but not the Fire TV Stick. That or someone at Amazon made it not &#34;findable&#34; via the Fire TV Stick. AT&T Uverse app, Direct TV app, others there, just not Spectrum.If the Fire TV is in the same situation, I'm certainly not buying that. And, we'll probably have to return this Stick as well, since she wanted it to provide regular TV channels from Spectrum in the bedroom of their rental unit for renters. If someone from Amazon can point out a way to get the Spectrum app on the Fire TV stick, I can avoid the trouble I suppose. &#60;knock&#62; &#60;knock&#62;... Amazon? You listening?",3,135,neutral,0.5448768138885498,0.04397190734744072,0.5448768138885498,0.41115128993988037,-0.3672,7,1874,0,0
Pros and Cons of Fire TV Stick,"Pro: This is the slickest little device I have ever bought. Tons of apps either already installed or available to install. Remote is utilitarian, but has all of the controls necessary. Installation was a snap. And it's WiFi rather than IR or Bluetooth, which I thought was perfect for my setup.Con: The left, right, up, down buttons wouldn't stop scrolling. Click - moves one place. Click - moves one place. Click - moves 12 places. Navigating to the correct selection becomes a test of patience. Google solutions include fresh batteries, moving location, using supplied dongle, resetting, calling Amazon for a replacement, etc. I got a refurbished replacement from Amazon, same problem. My equipment, other than the TV, is in a wiring closet probably 30 feet from my couch, with a couple of walls in between. So the Fire Stick is in the wiring closet, remote is on the couch. Signal is strong in the wiring closet. I removed Fire Stick and plugged it into back of TV. Works like a charm. (Good-bye surround sound.) My next experiment will be to get a 3 ft. HDMI male-female cable and see if i can re-orient the Fire Stick in the wiring closet to improve communication. If that doesn't work, a 40 ft. HDMI cable from wiring closet to TV (or somewhere closer, maybe just overhead in attic, but has to be where I can plug the Fire Stick into power) is the next attempted solution.The other issue I had with the remote, is that Alexa either wouldn't come up (get the blue bar and wait for the tone), or couldn't understand what I said. That said, it is working better plugged into the back of the TV, so it is probably a part of the distance problem.All of the above being said, I still think it is a super product, and I'm going to continue trying to get it to work the way I want it to. If any of the above solutions improve my situation, I will update this review.",3,136,positive,0.8987553715705872,0.8987553715705872,0.08508692681789398,0.016157666221261024,0.8826,7,1864,0,1
FireTV vs. Roku Streaming Stick,"I bought a Roku Streaming Stick and a FireTV stick at my local Target store. Both of them were priced at $39.99. I ended up staying with the FireTV stick and returned the Roku. I've found that Roku makes great software but their hardware quality control is very poor.Hardware- FireTV offers much better hardware (faster CPU, more ram)- Roku is very thoughtful to their remote control. You can turn on/off the TV and control the volume, so that you don't need to carry two remotes at the same time.- Fire TV supports 802.11ac, which runs on 5.6GHz wifi network. Roku only supports 2.4GHz one. This is very important to us because our living room is very close to our kitchen. When the microwave oven is on, it will mess up the 2.4GHz wifi network.- Fire TV supports fast Ethernet (not gigabit) via optional add on, although the speed is slower than wireless.- My Roku won't turn on after 2 days of uses. Exchanged it and the second one was dead after three days.User Interface- FireTV: The user interface is messy and hard to find the items you want. A lot of time I am unable to find the content I want.- Roku: Very easy and intuitiveVoice Search- I like the Roku one better.Content:I am not a subscriber of cable TV nor streaming service (e.g., Netflix, prime etc). I rely on the free content.- Roku offers a lot more FREE contents, such as national geographic channels etc.- FireTV offers the free contents too, but you will need to dig them out. By default, Amazon will display the prime video first because they want you to be a prime member. For example, my kid likes Arthur, which is free in the PBS kid app.The only reason I stick with Amazon Fire TV because of its hardware. I really like the software from Roku. Unfortunately, their hardware is not very good.",3,137,neutral,0.586863100528717,0.22334086894989014,0.586863100528717,0.18979600071907043,0.0335,6,1768,0,0
Roku or Fire TV Stick? First Impressions,"I have been using Roku for quite some time, but lately my Roku has been acting up. I decided to give the Fire TV Stick a try. The first problem? Getting the remote open to put the batteries in was almost impossible. It was as if it were glued shut. I went online to see if there were some trick to it, and found that there were lots of people with the same problem. After wrestling with it for a while, I finally managed to get it open. Set up was fairly easy, just as it is for Roku. Next I thought I would take a look at the series I've been watching on Amazon Prime with Roku, and was surprised to see that Fire TV letterboxes the picture. How is it that Roku plays Amazon Prime shows full sized, and Amazon's own Fire TV Stick letterboxes them?! I switched over to a show on Netflix, and the picture was back to full size. I'm also finding navigation to be a bit trickier than it was with Roku, a bit less intuitive. It makes an annoying click with every move using the remote. The remote on the Roku helpfully had buttons for Amazon and Netflix, as well as a couple of others. Fire TV Stick doesn't have any of those, so it takes more clicks to get to where you want to go. The jury is still out, but so far I'm leaning towards Roku. The one thing that Fire TV Stick does have is the voice remote. It seems to be helpful to open apps...&#34;Open YouTube, Amazon, Netflix, etc.&#34; But I haven't found it very successful in looking for FREE Amazon Prime (or other) content. When you just do a search, for example &#34;search for comedies,&#34; it will bring up a bunch of comedies that you have to pay for. If I do a search on Roku, I can apply a filter that has only Amazon Prime results. If I want to click through everything, I see plenty of categories of Prime, but then, that makes Fire TV's voice remote just a handy substitute for the amazon or netflix button on the Roku.",3,138,negative,0.6210071444511414,0.04455060139298439,0.33444222807884216,0.6210071444511414,-0.5765,5,1884,1,0
Nice for a spare room,"Let me start off saying that I have owned Roku products for the last 7 years, and currently have two Roku 3's for my two main TV's in my house.That being said, I have been spoiled by the vast channel/app library Roku has (including Amazon video) and the ease of the Roku user interface.The Fire TV interface isn't terrible, and I'm sure I'll grow more comfortable with it, but out of the box, it seems very disorganized. The main home screen lists a bunch of shows you can watch free with your Prime subscription, app and game recommendations, and your recently watched. Compared to the Roku, which lists all of your channels/apps very simply in a grid layout and separate menus to browse available apps (which granted the Fire TV has too), the Fire's home screen is more like a new girlfriend trying to get you try new things you aren't interested in.As for search: the Roku still has the best multi channel/ app search which now includes voice search when you buy the upgraded remote or use the mobile app, but the Fire TV has Alexa. And that makes it far easier and natural than the Roku for not only searching, but for general Siri/ Google Assistant type inquiries like &#34;When is the 2017 Super Bowl?&#34;Lastly, most of the Roku lineup now has wireless listening to whatever you are watching on your device by pluggining in a pair of headphones into the remote. In the past when I lived with noisy roommates, this feature was a lifesaver. Even today when I want to watch a movie while the Fam is asleep, I have that option for personal audio. This is one of the nicest features found in any media player in my opinion, and why I will continue to use the Roku as my main device.All in all, it's a decent device, especially for use in a spare room (which is where I'm using it). But my personal preference is Roku.",3,139,neutral,0.6052022576332092,0.2861931622028351,0.6052022576332092,0.10860457271337509,0.1776,5,1820,0,0
"Works OK, but No Cigar","I've had the firestick since March 2018. I have small hands for a man, and the remote is too small. I think it needs to be 2 times larger (and I hate most large remotes, but this remote is tiny). The buttons need to be larger too. Most importantly, it needs a volume up/down, channel up/down, mute, source, power button and it needs to be backlit. I'd like to be able to change from FireTV to Antenna without using a separate remote. I just viewed the newest Firestick remote which includes volume and mute buttons, but that's still not enough.OTHER CONS:1. It cuts out and buffers often and I have a fast 144 M/bit connection2. Battery gets too hot and I have to unplug and let it cool before it works again3. Goes back to Home screen on its own sometimes4. Resume works sometimes, but on hitting back button, it often goes all the way back to Home, making it cumbersome to go back to where you were in a movie.5. Starts playing sometimes when I have it paused6. Alexa isn't great. When I request a movie, she often brings ups a wikipedia page or a definition. Otherwise, it just puts an error on the screen or Alexa says she doesn't understand. I wish it had Google Assistant which is the #1 voice assistant. Alexa is #2.7. Remote battery doesn't last long. They lasted a long time until I replaced the batteries the first time.8. I thought I'd try to tell Alexa to turn off the firestick so I said &#34;Alexa, turn off firestick.&#34; She replied, &#34;Sorry, I didn't find a device named firestick.&#34; Unbelievable!9. WAY TOO MANY AMAZON ADS taking up too much real estate on my TV screen. STOP IT, AMAZON!and I thought Microsoft Windows was buggy.UPDATE: Just ordered the 4K Firestick a few days ago and have not received it yet. I'm glad the 4K Firestick remote is bigger.",3,140,negative,0.5425807237625122,0.06758315861225128,0.3898361921310425,0.5425807237625122,-0.475,5,1780,1,0
Not as pleased as I expected to be,"I purchased this before Christmas to replace the fire tv unit I have had for a couple of years. I bought the fire tv stick because it is portable. I have never been displeased with the Amazon Prime streaming service. With that being said the fire stick is not living up to my expectations. As long as I am streaming Amazon Prime video there is no difficulty with connectivity, but oddly enough, if I am streaming a television show or movie from any other app, such as, Hulu, Netflix, NBC, Playstation Vue or PBS, I receive an error message about a connection issue. I know I have internet because I simply look at my computer to check the internet connection. I scanned other reviews before posting my review and the problem seems to be causing dissatisfaction with more than a few other customers. I hope that Amazon comes up with a solution to this annoyance. I am seriously considering going back to my original unit and using the stick as a back-up if and when I need one. I would return it but I have disposed of the original packaging. I was so pleased with my original unit that I never considered there would be an issue with the fire stick. Naive, on my part, I admit. I gave the fire stick three stars because it is easy to use and set up; Alexa voice commands work pretty well (when I remember to use the voice command option); and the picture quality is very nice. As I stated at the beginning of this review I have always been pleased with the Amazon Prime streaming service and my fire tv unit. The annoyance and frustration I am encountering with the connection error message is the reason I have decided to write a tepid review. Please understand this has been happening often. I stream movies and television only. I do not watch live television. It has taken many, many connection issues before I decided to write a review.",3,141,neutral,0.5023588538169861,0.23125147819519043,0.5023588538169861,0.2663896381855011,-0.0351,7,1840,0,0
Medium Expections,"I think I had some types of expectations for this device. Before getting it, I was accessing Amazon Prime from my Blu-ray player, my Vizio TV, my tablet PCs, and my cell phones. I was expecting to get or see some type of difference with the new device. To my first surprise, the screen design between, on one hand the Blu-ray player, my TV set, the tablet PCs, and the cell phones, and on the other hand the Amazon Fire TV was the same (same design and same options). So, on the screen design and the ability to play Amazon Prime movies and TV shows, the Fire TV offered the same thing my Blu-ray player already had.If the screen design and the player were the same, I was expecting some extra things from the Fire TV. OK, the Fire TV presents some apps you expect from a TV device, including YouTube and Netflix. The Fire TV also presents apps that are not available on the Blu-ray player, my TV set, and other devices. I started checking the icons of TV channels on the Fire TV screen and other that had to be installed: NBC Sports, ESPN, other TV channels (Hallmark, TBS, etc). On every one of them, I was asked to select my Cable TV provider, then to put a username and a password. I was already familiar with this process because this is the same if I try watching a game on ESPN or NBC Sports from my tablet PC or cell phone while in the park or commuting. So once again, the Fire TV was not offering me any thing unfamiliar.My conclusion is that, while I admit that I am probably not familiar with Amazon Fire TV or I didn't dig in it deep enough, I didn't see anything that my Blu-ray player or my tablet PC was not offering. So if I already have a good Blu-ray player or multimedia TV, I don't see any need for the Fire TV (if you don't have a Blu-ray player or modern TV set, then the Amazon Fire TV may be fine).",3,142,neutral,0.6617212891578674,0.31570005416870117,0.6617212891578674,0.02257867157459259,0.2931,4,1823,0,0
It’s OK but seriously lacking in key respects,"I’ve had the Fire TV stick almost since it was introduced. In fact, I have two of them. They perform on a very average level. I can’t believe how sluggish they are to respond to input from the remote. I mean, you will wait...and wait...and wait for the cursor to shift up, down or side-to-side. You will wait so long you will think the stick part is not responding, and this will cause you to frequently overshoot the program you were aiming for and instead activate some damn trailer you have no interest in. (Prepare for that to play for 5-10 more seconds before the stick responds to switch it off.) And if you push the microphone to summon Alexa, well, be prepared to wait some more. You will push and hold the microphone button, then release it thinking it’s not working only for it to respond...but, too late! Now you’ll have to push the button again. Also, be aware the stick part of the Fire stick becomes insanely hot. My first one gave up the ghost after a year, and I’m convinced it’s because it simply burned itself up. Also, if you plug the stick directly into your TV’s port, you can expect to hear a horrible, loud clicking sound periodically. This happened to me with both a Vizio and a Samsung, so clearly not brand-specific. According to Amazon support this is a known problem, and you should use a cable to connect the stick, which seems like a massive design fail to me, but whatevs. It also would be great if the software interface actually remembered what you were watching previously and populated the “recently watched” section with those titles, but don’t count on it - especially for titles you were watching through Netflix or BritBox or some other app. Be prepared to go searching every. Single. Blessed. Time. for those titles. Still, all things considered, I suppose I get my money’s worth.",3,143,negative,0.7600357532501221,0.059541989117860794,0.18042230606079102,0.7600357532501221,-0.7005,6,1820,1,0
Using it more than Chromecast,"Edit: Docked another star for the fact that Amazon doesn't know how to stop pestering me with ads through emails with the subject &#34;Get to know Amazon Fire TV&#34; as if, to someone who owns one already, they're trying to help people learn more about features they may not know it has.Works really nicely, I love being able to skip intros in the netflix app. This actually has me using it more than my chromecast which is nice because it's saving me a little on my phone's battery(even though the phone doesn't stream the video to chromecast, there's still communication going on for play, pause, skip, etc.). The Alexa voice stuff is far from perfect, but it's nice that it does ask for clarification at times. It would also be nice if they had the little Prime logo for any videos free for prime members like they do on the webpage version. The screensaver feature is great too, especially since on my TV I can tell when it goes black it even cuts out the backlight, so it's keeping me from burning out the TV too.I have had to reboot it a couple times(hold center button and play/pause), but I think each time it had been on most of the day sitting around. It seems that since my TV's usb doesn't have enough juice, and that using the wall plug adapter causes the device to be on all the time. This isn't a huge problem, but I think this coupled with the fact that it doesn't seem to ever close apps running in the background might be the cause of some app related issues(Netflix crashing upon opening).Overall it's a pretty solid product, and you couldn't beat that deal they just had for Prime members, especially since it's one of the few TV streaming stick platforms for watching your Prime videos...and offers a fair number of other options for streaming video.",3,144,neutral,0.45490992069244385,0.2865515947341919,0.45490992069244385,0.25853848457336426,0.028,5,1772,0,0
"Fire stick,Roku,chromecast","I purchased 5 fire tv sticks on prime day 2018. I have been fortunate to also have purchased Roku device as well as chromecast device. I Was able to compare them all and here is what I found1. Roku is the best. It always works well and it was easy to setup. It was the only one with an infinity app that loaded easily. It also worked the best with infinity/Comcast, although it was a beta app. I have it on 2 TVs and it is reliable and have no ne.twork connection issues.2. Fire stick was my second choice. It would be the best is it had a better functioning infinity/Comcast app. This app was the most cumbersome to load and require you to complete various steps I feel some people will have difficulty. It is also a beta app and really doesn’t support all features offered by Comcast. I have one fire stick that continually has problems connecting to my network making the Comcast app impossible to function. It could be a weak WiFi link. I tried to connect to my extender but the fire stick would not connect. Strangely, I have a tv a bit further and it works better. It could be a bad fire stick. The fire stick works great on all other apps and it could potential reach free tv state. It works even better with prime tv. What could really be great if you could device a way to save login setting, so I would not have to put in my Comcast tv sign on to gain access to apps like abc, fox, nbc.3. Chromecast deserves an honorable mention as this was my first streaming device, but it doesn’t work with Comcast at all. It work well and I never have any issues streaming YouTube, even on the tv that use the fire stick. It maybe better to except a small delay with stream so the the device could buffer the programming and avoid the fire stick pause during viewing.",3,145,positive,0.9487519860267639,0.9487519860267639,0.04846577346324921,0.0027822242118418217,0.946,5,1765,0,1
"Great Content and Features, Faulty Device","I've had this device for about a week. After installing it, which was a matter of plugging it into a vacant HDMI slot, then plugging the power source in and selecting that HDMI channel on the receiver, I was very impressed with the abundance of content available. But of course that's Amazon, not the firestick itself. After using it for several days the unit simply stopped in the middle of a series I was watching. I tried other content but kept receiving an error message that the unit could not connect to the internet. A check of other devices showed that there was no problem with my internet connection. I reset the Firestick and that resolved the problem, but only for an hour, after which I had to repeat the reset procedure ... and again an hour later.I contacted Amazon Support about this, and of course I found myself speaking to someone in Bangladesh or somewhere in that part of the world. This is fine except everything has to be repeated once or twice due to the language/dialect difference. The representative took me through a hard reset, which is simply a power disconnect for two minutes. After this I restarted the unit and successfully resumed watching my series and the rep said she would contact me in 24 hours to check on the problem, which was confirmed by an email.Then I got to experience the whole thing again twenty minutes later, having to reset my Firestick once again in order to watch. And guess what ... the support rep never did contact me again, either by phone or internet.The bottom line is that I'm very impressed with the amount of programming available from Amazon Prime, including recently released top-rated movies I watch with no additional charge, but I'm pretty annoyed with the constant failure of the actual device.",3,146,positive,0.8400346636772156,0.8400346636772156,0.14748801290988922,0.012477310374379158,0.8276,7,1764,0,1
Don't buy this. Buy the regular Fire TV,"If you are deciding between the fire tv stick and the fire tv. Stop. Buy the Fire TV. My wife and I for the last year have had 3 fire tv sticks, one on every TV. We've used them almost exclusively for content (minus a couple shows and games on broadcast networks) and they have been solid- haven't had any issues except for two things.#1 Sling worked TERRIBLY. Half the time we would just restart the fire tv stick before going to sling because otherwise it would sit and spin forever and once in the app never start streaming. In fact we unsubscribed to Sling for 7 months because it was basically unusable and just re-subscribed the last two months to get some college football games that stuttered and were annoying but was our only option.#2 General slowness. Our other mainly used apps are Netflix, Hulu, and Plex. They very rarely had issues but things like menu loads and starting streams took just a littttlllle longer than we wanted to and would often be in standard definition for the first 30 seconds or more while buffering. (this is with 100mb cable and fantastic signal strength)5 minutes after setting up the Fire TV box we decided to replace our other sticks IMMEDIATELY and also bought one to replace my in-laws stick-they deserve better. Sling works perfectly. fast fast fast. menus are fast. switching apps is fast. starting streams is fast. streams always start in HD. its amazing and I can't believe what I put up with for the last year. The sticks are.. fine i guess-whatever. They work. mostly. But for something we use every day to access services that we pay $45/m for, saving the $60 bucks seems like a crazy thing I did long ago and will never do again.We love our box and we aint going back!",3,147,neutral,0.5373480319976807,0.36407169699668884,0.5373480319976807,0.0985802486538887,0.2655,0,1719,0,0
Amazing product but faulty with some apps,"This product is amazing for what it is designed to do. My gripes come with some annoying experiences with the YouTube and WWE apps.- Whenever I watch a YouTube video with ads, the ad will play as it should, but then when the video continues, the volume lowers to the point that I have to raise the TV volume by about 10-15 notches but when another ad comes in, it'll play at adjusted higher volume as if the volume was never affected in the first place which really startles me and whoever else is nearby because it is unnecessarily loud amd then when the video continues after the second ad, I have to adjust the volume once again. Very annoying. This does not happen when I run YouTube on any other device.- When I watch a WWE PPV on the Network, it will sometimes freeze for 10 seconds to sometimes even a minute (or NOT even continue at all which results in having to either restart the app or spend extra time using a different device) and that completely takes away from the experience. When I watch a live PPV on the WWE Network on any other device (tablet, phone, PS4) I never experience any freezes but some slight hiccups that get resolved within literal seconds.I have the stick literally inches away from my modem so I don't believe it's a connection issue but I believe there is something faulty with the apps when run by the Fire Stick.Once again, great product for what it is designed to do but the setbacks I mentioned make me tempted to see if I can potentially return this for a full refund even if I have owned this for a few weeks. If not, I may try a different device and if I like it better than the Fire Stick, I may just give this away as a gift as I'd rather not see my $40 collect dust.",3,148,positive,0.44494304060935974,0.44494304060935974,0.31537383794784546,0.2396831214427948,0.2053,5,1712,0,1
Not Happy,"I bought these (four, I believe) for my family members, including my fur babies who's favorite program is The Pet Collective! I have tried with 2 different devices, as they (my girls) are not always with me or in the recreation room (the only one that DOES connect). At first it showed a cloud and said, download it, you own it! So, I started the process and after a while a sign came up that said I had too many apps or some other something was causing the issue. Mind you, one of the TV's was a brand new Samsung Smart TV with TV Plus! So, I removed about 5 apps, still the same thing! Then I stripped the baby down to almost bare bones and still no Pet Collective! The only way I could get it was to go through YouTube, subscribe and then line up with a boat load of selections! But why should I have to do this after all the money I've dropped buying Amazon products!! Of course, when living your life, getting several items at once (around a holiday or birthday) one usually can never find time to set everything up in the 30 days or so to return them. Even trying to get customer service requires an act of God with an attached essay on why you want them to call you! So, I'm stuck with them and I won't be upgrading!. The other features are alright, the selection of programs must be for watchers who fall into a different category than I do, but I don't enjoy most of the vamps, gore and GOT type programs that seem the current trend! But, my fur babies are greatly disappointed and since they ( all three of them) have Mommy buy many goods for their room/care/entertainment through Amazon, well Amazon will have to contact them to see if they will let Mommy buy anything else from them! I wouldn't hold my breath, they're a bit spoiled and affronted!",3,149,positive,0.5316291451454163,0.5316291451454163,0.4502795934677124,0.01809130236506462,0.5135,7,1759,0,1
Quite versatile and capable - but can be glitchy at times,"Got the Fire TV stick today and have tried out its various capabilities only for a short time so far. So, this is more of a first impressions review that may need to be modified later as time passes.The product came on time and well packaged. The package contains the TV stick, an HDMI extender, a power cable with a wall-wart, a remote control with batteries, and a quick-start guide. Getting behind the TV to physically install the stick was the toughest thing about installation. Once that was done, the on-screen prompts walk you through the initial set-up, such as connecting to your wi-fi, etc.You have a large choice of apps to provide various streaming services, and you can choose to install as many or as few as you need. I installed Netflix, Youtube, and Hulu first. When I tried installing Amazon Prime videos after this, I ran into a problem. It kept telling me that there was an error and I had to contact customer service to resolve it if it persisted.So, I called customer service. The nice lady on the phone got me to go to the prime video app and delete its associated data and cache. She then had me install a system update for the fire tv stick itself. She even had me pull the plug on the TV Stick for 30 seconds and replug it in to see if that will hard-reboot it. She was also able to take control of my TV Stick and could operate it remotely while being able to see what was on my TV screen - with my permission, but the technology was still quite impressive. But all this took about 45 minutes, and did not help the problem one bit. Same error when I tried installing the prime video app. The customer service agent gave me 2 options: she could escalate the issue and have someone call me in a day or two, or I could return this unit as defective and order a new one. And there was no guarantee that the new unit would not malfunction either.I got off the phone and decided to try one last thing: I did a factory reset on the stick. This took about 15 minutes before it booted back up. I had to go through the initial set up steps again. At the end of that, instead of installing Netflix, hulu or youtube, I decided to install Amazon Prime Video first. And lo and behold, the installation succeeded without any glitches. After that, I went back and installed Netflix, Youtube and Hulu, and now everything I need works. Moral of the story is that this is a somewhat glitchy piece of hardware, and if something does not work for whatever reason, try doing things in a different order, and it just might work!Streaming speeds on all the platforms (Netflix, youtube, hulu, amazon prime were the ones I tried) are more than adequate. The device is quite responsive and quick (except if you update the system or do a factory reset. Any such operation makes the device go through a long process of ""optimizing storage"" that takes literally several minutes). The tactile feel of the remote is good, and because of the simplicity of the remote (which I talk about next), it is easy to operate it even in complete darkness. One of the apps you install is a web browser (Firefox or Silk are the two options), and once you do that, you can visit any streaming site and probably stream content from there through your TV Stick onto your TV.The remote itself is very simple. It only has 6 buttons apart from a set of directional controls with a round ""Enter"" button at their center, and a button at the top that you hold down to activate voice controls. There are forward, rewind and play/pause buttons for the video you are streaming, then a home button, a back button and a menu button (which doubles as a Subtitle button when you are streaming something) to control the Fire TV Stick itself. If you don't want to use one more remote and hate remote clutter, you can download a Fire TV Remote app on the play store or apple's app store that will give you the same controls as the remote on your phone. You have to pair the app with your device by entering a code on your phone so, your phone controls your device, not the Fire TV stick in a friend's house, for example.The TV Stick's settings menu is quite extensive and has various options including parental controls, data gathering, data usage, etc. Most of the stuff is quite self-explanatory. One of the interesting settings is under ""Display and Sounds"", where you can set up the Fire TV Stick to mirror your hand-held device's display. This can be a phone or tablet screen, so you can set it up so that you can watch your small phone screen on your large TV display. On my android phone, I had to go under ""Connected Devices"" under settings to ""cast"" my screen onto my TV through the Fire TV Stick. This is very useful because you can then watch anything on your TV that you can watch on your phone or tablet screen, including games or other video streaming apps you may not be able to install on the Fire TV Stick directly.So, first impressions: the technology is quite impressive, though a little glitchy and touchy. The device is zippy and responsive, and the user interface is easy to understand and navigate. The range of streaming apps available is very extensive (includes Showtime, HBO, ESPN, etc., etc.), and because a web browser is included, you may be able to stream content even if there is no Fire TV-compatible app for a particular streaming platform. Worse comes to worst, if you can stream or show content of any kind on your phone, you can mirror it on your TV through your TV Stick, so you are covered for all eventualities. And price is right, with most other equivalent solutions (such as Chromecast, Roku TV, etc.) costing more than this device. So far, so good. I penalized it one star for wasting an hour of my time by forcing me to call customer service, do a factory reset, etc., just to solve a problem which should not even have occurred in the first place. If I find more problems, I will update the review and the star-rating appropriately.",4,150,positive,0.6178421378135681,0.6178421378135681,0.37371909618377686,0.008438756689429283,0.6094,5,5940,0,1
Good for what it does but do your research,"I've had my Fire Stick since Christmas and I've discovered quite a bit I like and some things I really hate. We switched from satellite to streaming TV in December so having a streaming device was a must. I have had Amazon Prime for years so a Fire Stick was a natural choice. We added Netflix and DirecTV NOW. Overall, it works great. It is easy to set up and find apps to download such as Netflix, DirecTV NOW, and various channel apps like NBC, FoxNOW etc.Some apps work better than others but I will refrain from talking much about that since I'm not sure if it has anything to do with the Fire Stick interface or not. For example DirecTV NOW buffers quite a bit at times and Netflix occasionally gives an Error Message when you first open it but if you open it a second time it works fine. Again, not sure if this is due to a problem with the app or the app's interface with the Fire Stick.As far as the voice controls, it isn't all it's cracked up to be. It works fine if you are watching something on Amazon such as Goliath, it will start the video, pause, resume etc. However, since you have to press the microphone button on the remote, wait for the beep and the blue bar on the screen to appear to let you know it is listening, then speak, it is actually more difficult to operate than to just push the play/pause button for these functions. It also doesn't interface with Netflix, DirecTV NOW, or most of the other channel apps I use. I mostly use it to search for a specific show I want to watch but even this is hit or miss. Half the time, it misunderstands me. For example, I say &#34;Play Hailey Dean Mysteries&#34; and it hears &#34;Dean&#34;. I asked it to play &#34;Partners in Crime&#34; which is a series available on Amazon Prime, instead it played the song. It will sometimes find shows and let you know which app it is available such as Netflix, Brit Box, etc. but this doesn't always work either. Ask it to play &#34;The Staircase&#34; which is available on Netflix and I get &#34;An American Murder Mystery: The Staircase&#34; which is available on Investigation Discovery Go for which I don't have a subscription. It's mostly just frustrating.As far as the Home Screen and other functions, it can be a little irritating. The Home Screen has 5-6 preview videos of new content will play once you arrow down off the word Home at the top. Nice if you are looking for something new to watch. The next row is labelled &#34;Recent&#34; which has the last 28 items you watched, in the order you watched them, whether it be a show like Goliath, an app like Netflix, or a movie like Thor. They don't go away and as far as I can tell you can't remove them. It's great that your most commonly used apps are usually right there or I can pick right up watching Goliath where I left off without having to search for it. On the other hand, why would I want to watch Thor again today when I watched the whole thing yesterday. Also, I found a show I thought would be interesting only to discover it is a Russian language TV show with English subtitles. Not my cup of tea since I'm usually doing other things while watching TV such as knitting. However, this is still on my Recent list.The next row is &#34;Your Apps and Channels&#34; but it really isn't. Sure the first couple are Netflix, Prime Video, Photos, but then there are several apps I don't use and haven't downloaded such as Hulu and Sling. Animal Plant Go, which I do watch, is 12th on the list, after 8 apps I haven't even downloaded. It would be nice to have a row that is just my downloaded apps, in an order I choose, so they are easier to find. The rest of the 20 or so rows are Recommendations, Featured shows and apps, etc. It is all so random, it's like navigating a grocery store you've never been to before. You might find something you want to try and didn't know was there but good luck finding something specific on your shopping list. The other screens, such as &#34;Your Videos&#34;, &#34;Movies&#34; etc. are arranged in a similar fashion.My other complaint is my personal video library. First, there are a couple of ways to access your Personal Video Library, but the Home Screen isn't one of them. You can go to the &#34;Your Videos&#34; screen, &#34;Your Video Library&#34; will be the 5th row or you can open the Prime Video app &#34;Your Video :ibrary&#34; will be the 3rd row. They are in the ordered you purchased them. I changed the order on my Kindle to alphabetical but this had no effect on the list on the Fire Stick. I have been collecting digital copies of movies for several years now by buying the Blu-Rays with Digital Copy (my husband likes to have a physical copy). I use UltraViolet to redeem the digital codes which, I thought, automatically made them accessible in my Amazon Video Library because I linked my Amazon Video Library to UltraViolet via Movies Anywhere. However, I recently discovered that this is not the case. I just redeemed codes for the more recent Star Trek Trilogy from Paramount Pictures. Although you still redeem Ultraviolet codes, Paramount doesn't have an agreement with Movies Anywhere but it does with VUDU. So I can watch Star Trek on VUDU but not Movies Anywhere. Since VUDU doesn't have an agreement with Amazon, not only can I not link my VUDU account with Amazon Video, I can't get the VUDU app on my Fire Stick. So I don't have a complete digital video library that includes all the movies I own anywhere. And, to watch Star Trek, I have to use a different device that supports VUDU.Overall, I recommend you do your research. The Fire Stick works good for what it does although the voice remote could be much more user friendly and the content could be much better organized especially the way downloaded or most commonly used apps are accessible. Depending on whether you have a Prime subscription, the apps you use, and how you purchase digital content, the Fire Stick may or may not be for you.",4,151,positive,0.8383814692497253,0.8383814692497253,0.1413266360759735,0.020291849970817566,0.8181,5,5937,0,1
Short (micro-USB) power cord and extended warranty information,"(Preface: Everything I've written below is correct and current as of right this moment, 2018-Sept-8th. Anything after today could potentially be different based on Amazon or SquareTrade changing designs, policies, etc.)So technically, I haven't purchased THIS particular Fire TV. I have the 2015 model. However, the power cord situation is the same. The issue arises with such a short power cord and the way it's integrated into the Fire TV.If your TV is mounted on the wall, which most TVs are, then the included power cable (USB cord and power plug) are going to hang off the Fire TV and not likely reach the wall outlet, unless you have a power outlet higher up on the wall specifically for this type of device/appliance. MOST power outlets are still down closer to the floor. This is a problem for one or two reasons. The power cord- and resulting extension cord you're going to need- is going to put stress on the micro-USB port of the Fire TV and/or the HDMI port of your TV.For this reason, I HIGHLY recommend that you utilize the included HDMI Extender cable that comes with this unit. Regardless of the orientation of the Fire TV and your TV's HDMI port, this is going to relieve 'some' stress on the TV 's HDMI port.With regards to powering the Fire TV itself, if you are fortunate enough to have a newer TV that also has a 'powered' USB port, then you can probably buy a standard, 6"" USB to micro-USB cable. (You can find these cables on Amazon.) If your TV does NOT have a powered USB port, then rather than using a heavier electric extension cord, I would look for a 6ft USB to Micro-USB cable to replace the one that ships with this unit. That should cover the distance from the wall power outlet up to the Fire TV hanging off the supplied HDMI Extender.ALL THAT BEING SAID... this brings me to the Extended Warranty part of this 'review'.I looked at the extended warranty noted as an ""Additional Item"" in the right-side pane of Fire TV product page. There is both a 2yr and 3yr warranty offered by SquareTrade. I just had my questions confirmed by Amazon Support so that's the other reason for this 'review' even though I haven't formally hit the ""Order"" button yet.1) The warranty page says that it covers the ""2016 Release"" of the Fire TV. Well, I'm writing this review in Sept 2018.The warranty WILL cover this device, as confirmed by a (saved) chat session with an Amazon rep. While the Amazon rep was initially confirming the coverage, I also noticed that on the main product info page for this Fire TV, if you scroll WAAAAAY down past all the sales pitch stuff and get to the Product Description table (conveniently right above the ""Customer Question & Answer"" section), you'll see in the bottom-right corner... ""Generation: Fire TV Stick 2nd Generation - 2016 release"".2) I have been using SquareTrade warranties for years now and I've never had a problem engaging them. What people need to keep in mind, and what's stated in the information page for the 2- and 3-yr warranty, is that it STARTS from the time of purchase, NOT after the manufacturers warranty expires. This Fire TV only has a 90-day warranty (""Ouch!""). If any part(s) of the delivered product fail within the first 90 days, contact Amazon, NOT SquareTrade. This will be the easiest route for replacement. Once the 90 days (~3 months) has elapsed, for the remaining 21 or 33 months, you'll want to contact SquareTrade.Because stress points are factored into the design, if you have a unit that fails due to these natural stress points, you SHOULD be able to get it covered under warranty. Your mileage may vary based on the time of day, the alignment of the stars, the rep you talk to, etc. There are reports of people getting the runaround. I can only speak from the experience of talking directly with an Amazon rep when they took care of a similar failure during a previous warranty claim with one of my Fire TVs.What WON'T be covered is if it breaks the HDMI port on your TV. You'll need to take that up with the manufacturer of your TV or the place you purchased it. But don't go in expecting them to honor a warranty from a 3rd party device (the Fire TV) that caused the HDMI port on the TV to fail. Again, as stated above, utilizing the supplied HDMI Extender will alleviate a LOT of the stress on the TVs HDMI port, so a failure on your TV should be a very rare occurrence for most consumers.Hope this helps clear up any questions you may have had. I figure that if a tech-savvy consumer such as myself has these questions or situations arise, others may also.",4,152,neutral,0.8799219131469727,0.06636807322502136,0.8799219131469727,0.05371001735329628,0.0127,3,4555,0,0
Not the best for international use (I live in Mexico),"I bought this because I wanted to try it out. The device works as it should, no isses regarding its operation, it took about 15 minutes updating its software once it got online, and when it finished it was ready to go, no issues whatsoever.The problem here in Mexico, at least in the city I live is that a lot of channels and services are not available here which is a shame because it reduces its functionality dramatically. Not even some basic app downloads work, (such as Downloader!!) which made it difficult to do a simple task like installing Kodi. Apps like HBO GO, HISTORY, DISCOVERY, THE CW, are off the tableI did manage to get Kodi installed, but non of the popular tutorials that rely on using Downloader helped me.I'll give you the exact instructions on how to do it if you are not in the US and are unable to download basic apps.You'll need an Android phone or tablet that uses a 32bit processor, otherwise it won't work. I first tried with my 64bit Android phone and I always got errors, until I figured out that the version of Kodi I was sending to the Firestick wasn't compatible because of this little detail. So then I tried my old Android tablet and it worked like a charm. Whatever device you use must be connected to the same network your FireTV is connected to.If you don't know if your device has a 32 or 64 bit processor, the easiest way it to download an app from the play store called AIDA64, that app will show you all the thecnical information about your phone, and under CPU you'll see if your device has a 32 or 64 bit processor.So here is the process for installing Kodi without using the Downloader app:1.- On your FireTV Go to Configuration &#62; Device &#62; Developer options &#62; Enable both settings there2.- On your 32bit Android phone or Tablet, make sure you already have Kodi installed, if not, do it now, you'll find it on the Play Store3.- On Google Play Store search for and install the app named Apps2Fire4.- On Apps2Fire settings search for your FireTV device, if you can't find it automatically you'll need to input the FireTVs IP address, which you can find here: On your FireTV go to Configuration &#62; Device &#62; About &#62; Network, The IP will be shown on the right of the screen5.- On your phone, go back to the apps list in Apps2Fire and select Kodi and then Install.If you get an error message saying something about Apps2Fire not being able to locate the FireTV device, reboot both devices and try again6.- You'll see a progress bar and once it's done, you'll have Kodi installed on your FireTV, which brings a whole other level of entertainment.7.- Repeat Step 1 and disable both settingsEnjoy!Do I recommend this device? Yes I do. My last device was a WD TV Live. It still works but you can feel the years on it. It feels old and sluggish and this FireTV device is like a breath of fresh air. Its fast, good quality, and the setup couldn't be easier (aside from installing Kodi). I tried to install HBO GO the same way I did Kodi, but the app doesnt work on the FireTV.Spotify, Netflix, TuneIn Radio, work great. YouTube funnily works through a web browser of your choice and works good, I just wish there was a dedicated app, and not a web browser to use it. Since it has the Fire ecosystem on top of Android, it works pretty well and is compatible with most android apps. However those Android Apps that Require Google Play Services won't work on it, like Google Play Movies.Being able to install Kodi takes this device to a whole new level, so even if I can't enjoy the channels I wanted to, there are always options within kodi to get that sorted out, but I won't talk about them on this review.Alexa is awesome, however it doesn't understand spanish at all, and most recommendations it gives me, don't work here, so I'm like in the middle of the WD TV Live and a device built back in 2014. It has great functionality but I can't take advantage of it due to where I live and nothing else.I hope this review helps international customers. Feel free to ask your questions, I'll do my best to ander them.",4,153,positive,0.6935650110244751,0.6935650110244751,0.25926902890205383,0.047165971249341965,0.6464,5,4068,0,1
"Now that I am fully set up, it's seems to be working fine (UPDATED)","UPDATED 13 Sep 2019: No change in my rating; I just wanted to add a comment on the Voice Remote. It works fine; however, the batteries last only about 25% to 50% as long as they do with the old generation #1 Fire TV Stick. About six months ago, after changing batteries an average of every 6-8 weeks, I broke out my old remote and paired it with the new Fire TV Stick. I reserve the Voice Remote for when I use Alexa, and use the 1st gen remote the rest of the time. I just replaced my 1st gen remote batteries for the first time, and my Voice Remote batteries are still registering in the ""Good "" range on my battery tester. I don't know if the voice command portion of the Voice Remote eats up all the power or whether it simply uses much more power for all functions. It's also possible my particular Voice Remote has a defect. In any case, be forewarned if you are upgrading from a 1st Gen Fire TV Stick that you may find yourself replacing batteries much more frequently with the new Voice Remote.ORIGINAL REVIEW: I upgraded from the original Fire TV Stick and I have generally been pleased—so far. I had the original for about three years and worked my way through three remotes and, in its final days, my original Fire TV Stick's reliability was questionable. Basic installation should have been simple, and I suspect for many people it is. I thought I could just connect the new units to the old cables, but it was not to be. Instead, the cables for the two models were unique to those models. For many people, this may be no issue at all; however, my patched-together entertainment system that includes several generations of components and has dozens of connections and cables to make it all work. As a result, disconnecting the old cables and installing the new ones was not a trivial process. But once I finished, then I went to complete the software set up.I believe I missed a how-to video on the upgrade process—at least I hope I did. None of my apps appeared on the new Fire TV Stick, which was not a surprise. However, I saw no way to transfer app data available whenever I used them on my old Fire TV Stick. Whether I just missed the procedure or whether there is no such procedure, I wound up having to download all my Fire TV apps from my account and reinstalling them. This was not a trivial process, taking hours. If Amazon has a procedure for updating apps from the old to new Fire TV Stick, it should have been made more prominent. I suggest a one-time screen asking the user whether they are upgrading, and if so, providing step-by-step instructions or a link to a how-two video on the Fire TV Stick or a web site. Instructions for upgrading or a link to them should also be included with the product. Those procedures should address the concerns of just about an upgrader. [Of course, upgrades have to be treated like a new installation, letting purchasers know that as well would be nice....]OK, now I have the new Fire TV Stick. How does it improve on the old one? First, apps load faster and—so far—have almost never crashed, which was starting to become a problem with the old one. The remote includes an Alexa-enabled microphone. Frankly, I'm not finding substantial value in it yet, although that may be a learning curve issue and the fact that the apartment I rent was built well before the term &#34;smart technology&#34; came into the vocabulary and is unlikely to be upgraded by the current owner.In short, my upgrade to the new Fire TV Stick seems to have ended an increasing number of reliability issues I was having, presumably because it has more memory and a faster processor than the original model. I wish I had been aware of procedures for upgrading my apps from the original model—whether because I just missed them or because there actually are none. But now that it's set up, my apps are generally running much more smoothly than they had been toward the end of the life of my old device. I am looking forward to figuring out how to get more value from Alexa.",4,154,neutral,0.5240718126296997,0.45114991068840027,0.5240718126296997,0.02477826364338398,0.4264,7,4006,0,0
"Cool, but frustrating","Updated:Originally I rated this as a 2 star item.I'm still finding it a bit difficult to find programming and channels. However, I am finding more and more channels, sometimes thru Hulu, sometimes as apps. Some channels will cost, some require cable or satellite subscriptions and will be free, some are free.Finding more things to watch, I'm finding it a better value, thus an increase to 4 stars.I still have not gotten the Alexa to work properly. Therefore, it cannot be a 5 star rating.Original review:It's actually relatively cool. It's meant to work with Amazon Prime. But offers a bunch of additional apps as well: Netflix, Hulu, YouTube, and a ton of cable/satellite apps. This year's model also comes with some form of Alexa, This year's model has extra memory and a faster processor over previous generations; this is, of course a huge plus.Being portable is pretty cool, too. Once set up (not too difficult. Plug the device into an open HDMI port, plug in to a socket, enter email address and password, and you're good to go. Want to take it with? It truly is plug and play. You'll simply need to know the router ID at your friend's house, hotel, etc.)Being a Prime member, I get some of the features already. Being a Netflix member, I get some extra features. And, that's about all the good I am experiencing after several weeks of use.For those &#34;cutting the cable&#34;, think twice. Pissed at your cable or satellite co. because they just keep skyrocketing in price and play the same 3-4 shows every day all day? Yeah; me too. But, finding free TV apps is very cumbersome, and the couple I did find were lame. Seriously.Amazon lists a bunch of TV apps as free, UP, Cooking Channel, even a channel dedicated to Comic Con are all called &#34;Free&#34;. Yep it's true, the app may be free, but, don't expect any of the content free. Well, there is a free 7 day trial; but, I don't call that free. Do you?Again, there may be actually free TV apps, but, I haven't found too many. Which makes this a $40 purchase tp watch Netflix, Hulu, and the usual HBO Go, Showtime, etc., etc., etc. to watch on a big screen.So, when using a streaming stick, realize that there are (in comparison) very few &#34;freebies&#34;. So back to cutting the cable. How much are you really saving? If you're cool with just two or three paid apps, to watch on bigger screen, this could be really cool. Otherwise, you may find yourself paying way more than subscription TV, and getting less.Alexa Voice. A nice addition to this year's model. It's added in at no additional cost, making this the &#34;obvious&#34; choice. Personally, I have not it to be as cool as it should be. It seems all the commands are geared to work solely with Amazon. If it works. Example, I say &#34;Music&#34;, &#34;Play music&#34;, and it looks for movies with Music in the title. Needless to say, I am personally annoyed by the lack of proper functionality. I will say, it could be me.I'm a bit disappointed in the lack of actually free TV channel apps, and the (so far) lack of proper functionality of Alexa. Oh, and btw, just for kicks and giggles, I tried to order a pizza, NOT that I planned on ordering from Domino's just that I wanted to see what happened, and it took me to a Pizza kit being sold on Amazon. Ewwww. That is worse than Domino's.Ok, so, that has been my experience over the past couple weeks. Cool, but, can be pretty frustrating.",4,155,neutral,0.608432948589325,0.12889373302459717,0.608432948589325,0.26267334818840027,-0.1338,0,3417,0,0
"Perhaps the best streaming device out. And Yes, you can STILL use Kodi on this device!","[[VIDEOID:36aa8d56414fef112d1ed3940cba62a6]]I know why most of you are here. So before I get started, YES. The All-New Amazon Fire TV Stick DOES work with KODI. I repeat, you will STILL be able to sideload Kodi onto this device!Now that we have that incredibly important piece of information out of the way, I will start off by saying the All-New Amazon Fire TV Stick picks off where its ever so popular predecessor left off, offering you one of the most inexpensive ways to stream HOURS of content to your TV.The package itself includes:- The Fire TV Stick- The Remote control WITH Alexa voice control- A Power adapter- 2 AAA batteries (by Amazon basics)- an HDMI extender if the Fire TV Stick does not fit into your TV’s HDMI port.The device itself couldn’t be easier to use. Simply plug it into your TV, and you’re good to go! With this device, you’ll be able to use apps such as Netflix, Pandora, HBO, and even Amazon prime (provided you’re a prime member). You will of course need accounts for all of the previously mentioned apps, but if you do not, you can also use YouTube through this device, which has hours of content on it by itself! If you’re an Amazo Prime member, you will already have access to thousands of TV shows and Movies… just in case you didn’t know!The All New Amazon Fire TV Stick features some changes that are worth mentioning, but if you’re not too tech-savy, just know that this stick performs faster than the older model. This is due to a stronger processor, a 1.3ghz quad core processor vs a 1ghz dual core processor from older models. I WAS a bit disappointed to see that the All-New Fire TV Stick did not upgrade to 2gb of Ram. While 1gb is plenty for streaming in most cases, users may find occasional lag on the home screen, especially when first booting the device up. I’ve found that if I turn on my firestick, and go do something else for a few minutes, or just allow the device some time to boot up, I do not run into this issue. While there has not been an update in ram, I have noticed that navigating the fire stick is MUCH quicker than previous models, which will make anybody happy.Perhaps the biggest change from the previous Fire TV Stick is the remote control. While all of the buttons are the same, you now have a “Voice Control” button on top of the remote control. By pressing this button, you are allowed access to wide range of commands that take all of the grunt work out of browsing your streaming device. For instance, you can ask Alexa to “Find horror movies”, “play music from pandora”, “fast forward 5 minutes”, etc. This feature is ESPECIALLY useful given the difficulties surrounding the use of streaming devices with a remote control that doesn’t have a keyboard or mouse. It is also worth mentioning that the buttons are now made of a soft rubber material, and are easier to use.To conclude, If you’re looking for a portable, depdnable, and easy to use streaming device, this is it. At just under $40.00, It’s hard to say no to perhaps the least expensive streaming device on the market. While I do wish that this model featured 2gb of ram for quicker browsing, 1gb is plenty for what most people will be using this device for; streaming. All in all, I would very much recommend this device!IF you have any questions about this device, please feel free to comment. As somebody who uses Amazon almost daily, I’ll get back to you very shortly.",4,156,positive,0.8345333933830261,0.8345333933830261,0.16105905175209045,0.0044075800105929375,0.8301,4,3404,0,1
Cannot believe the value. Almost perfect!,"Promise to update this as we use it more. I can say that it's the best streaming device we have used. It's not perfect, but honestly better than what we have.Comparisons:vs. chromecast - Chromecast works fine, but it requires the use of another device to stream. This means that I'm draining the battery on my phone or tablet just to stream tv. I want something entirely separate from my other smart devices.vs. apple tv. Apple tv is good, and beautiful, but for the price doesn't really give me any benefits. Also, the new Apple tv remote is incredibly difficult to use with it's sensitive swiping requirements. Give me buttons any day. I also think Alexa is better at doing things than Siri.vs. Xbox. No comparison. Seriously. Clearly we were in the dark ages by continuing to rely upon the xbox for streaming.First, the good: - This thing is fast, and brings clear streaming. We used to use the Xbox as a platform for all our streaming needs and it was simply awful, likely due to the fact that streaming channels weren't really putting much effort into supporting the platform. NOT SO with the fire tv. We don't have lightning speed internet in our area (Minneapolis suburbs), but it's no problem with the fire tv. Nothing has slowed down, nothing has been poor quality. This little guy is great. For the price, I'd say definitely purchase.- size - I can't believe something this tiny works so well. - compatibility - it works great with our 5-year old Samsung HDTV - apps: there are a large number of streaming apps well-supported on the platform. Clearly the market has realized that the fire tv is important and continues to ensure the functionality is great.Cons: - using the voice remote: We've found that the voice remote works pretty well with certain apps, but not with others (for example, spotify has problems and so does CBS). It would be great to have some more support or common commands with every app. I understand that's not likely a realistic expectation, but it would certainly go a long way. Hopefully when I update this review I'll have mastered the system and be able to give it 5 stars. - no YouTube App. And I get why, and I get that it's probably not Amazon's fault. Google wants you to chromecast. Fine. At least Amazon has found a browser method to get around the issue. While not completely seamless, it will still get me the Fitness Marshall dance videos :) - Alexa integration without an amazon device: We've been using this with a Eufy Genie, and are having some trouble figuring out the correct commands to get the fire tv working and finding content. This may be an issue with the Eufy system, or possibly with the fire tv. I'm obtaining an echo dot this week, so I will be able to update soon.Pro Tip: Do you need the 4k version? IMO, not yet, unless you're really into being ahead of the curve. We think we'll purchase a 4k tv in the next couple years, and thought about going with the 4k version just to be ready for it, but by that time Amazon will likely have come out with something better in the next generation.Pro Tip: If you're going with the amazon ecosystem, which we are, then you just need this on your tv. I would suggest getting a compatible universal remote. We're waiting for a sale, and then intend to grab a good one that interacts with echo devices.",4,157,positive,0.8930667638778687,0.8930667638778687,0.08669858425855637,0.020234622061252594,0.8728,5,3306,0,1
Great when it works.,"UPDATE 2:Well, it has become rather comical, but somewhate manageable. I'm working on a whopping 20 mb Excel file. When I click &#34;save&#34;, it saves to my hard drive and uploads to OneDrive (which I want it to do, thank god for the cloud). However, when that happens, it apparently strains the wifi enough to make the Fire TV freeze for a few seconds, then come back a bit blurry, then it will sharpen again when the file has been uploaded to OneDrive.I don't see this lag/freezing behavior on my wifi generally or other devices. I can only imagine it is due to the specs of the Fire TV stick. At least it's manageable and predictable.UPDATE 1:Through no help from Amazon or anything on the interwebs, i figured out the issue below. MS OneDrive was working on backing up some very large files and it was apparently stressing my wifi. Though the Fire Stick was the most glaring non-beneficiary of that stress; other things had only minor effects. Amazon's help page for these types of issues is incredibly thin. Basically, reboot, delete re-install, etc. Ridiculous. Having your wifi stressed by some other application should easily be one of the many more things Amazon should include on its help page. To its credit, Amazon did call when they saw this review, to try to help, but by then I had solved it myself. I revised my rating to 4 stars because, other than the issue below, it's performed pretty well.PRIOR REVIEW:I strongly prefer the standard Fire TV from a few years ago. (For some reason, Amazon sometimes downgrades products as it updates them; did the same with the Fire Tablet, whose most powerful version was circa 2013 or so). I've had a couple of Fire Sticks and the performance was lacking. However, I figured with the quad-core processer in this new one and a $19 Prime Day deal, I'd give it a try to replace the frustrating Fire Stick I bought several years ago.It was great, for about 3 weeks. Clear picture, reasonably fast response, not frequent lagging.But yesterday, it all changed. Freezing, lagging, blurry picture on both of the 2 apps (MLB TV and Netflix) that I use it on.I did everything. Cleared cache and data from all apps. Unplugged and replugged. Rebooted multiple times. Finally did a full factory reset. Wifi connection was strong at all times. Nothing helped.Then I noticed a slight delay with the interweb on my PC. I thought maybe wifi was running a little slow so I rebooted all three AT&T devices (modem, router, gatweay). And voila!!!! That solved the problem...for about 10 minutes. Then it returned to form.I think the wifi IS running just a tad slow today, and I think it affects this Fire TV stick because it has less power than a regular Fire TV. The choppiness/freezing/blurry picture is an extreme reaction given there is only a very slight occasional hiccup on my PC, and my Fire TV doesn't seem to be having any issues. So I can only conclude, after doing everything possible, that this Fire TV stick only runs smoothly when wifi is absolutely perfect.Gonna give it another day or two and then will return. No reason to think the problem will fix itself, but might as well give it a chance. Then I guess I'll look for a several generations-ago Fire TV. Sigh.",4,158,negative,0.46136075258255005,0.08649883419275284,0.45214033126831055,0.46136075258255005,-0.3749,7,3215,1,0
Rev 2 is Superior to Rev 1 Stick,"Update for 2nd Rev stick.After years of cursing Amazon - customer service finally agreed the rev 1 was garbage - I was sent a gratis Rev 2 stick. What a difference! No more errors --- finally! The stick responds to commands the way it is supposed to. Opening PlayStation Vue is no longer a 20 minute adventure in madness. The lone complaint is the Fire App on my iPhone SE occasionally loses contact with the stick forcing me to reboot the stick (pulling the power supply to the stick for a few seconds).4 Stars for Rev 2Fire Stick Rev 1 Review:I have owned this Fire Stick with Voice Remote (Best Buy purchase) for almost 3 years and bought it primarily because I already own an Echo device and was pretty amazed at that one. I want to address issues I found after years of use.The Bad, The Ugly, and the Good1) S-L-O-W Response to commands. And I mean slow...Recently found out that this generation of Fire Stick (and I don't know which one it is) is not compatible with the 5GHz modems.My wireless internet stream is roughly 200 MBS. It's fast. And my Fire Stick is roughly 15 feet from the modem. But, pushing a command on the Amazon controller can take anywhere from an almost instant response to no response whatsoever. It is insane. You never know.2) There are occasional times I click on one show and get a different show that I previously backed out from. Very odd. This happens intermittently even if the app has been &#34;refreshed&#34; by following the Amazon protocol.3) Audio burps. You read that right. On occasion the audio will literally burp. There is a buzz sound that last anywhere from a second to 5-6-7 seconds. I have no idea why. These audio burps occur whether I have a directly plugged speakers into the TV or bluetooth headset. There is no rhyme nor reason why or when.The Good - Really Good1) This is the best one - because Fire Stick is an android device you can download other apps not pre-installed with your Fire Stick. Yes you can. And it's easy. Without getting into the how-to (which you can easily find on YouTube) let's just say there are legal apps out there that will allow you to watch just about every TV show ever made - and every episode - all free with no sign-ups and no credit card. Some of these apps may not be intuitive but they work. Some don't work well and some require a mouse app.2) Simple installation of the device and iPhone app that works. It's plug and play and starts right up. The iPhone apps works nicely too and comes with a keyboard function.3) I'm not sure you can do this with Roku. Roku is an android device too but my son says he was not able to add apps.The Ugly:Comparison to Roku:My son and daughter both own Roku (one with a Roku 3 auxiliary device and the other a Roku TV) and they both operate in my house so the same Xfinity modem is common to all. Neither are as slow as Fire stick and neither have any of the above issues.Performance:1) Roku is faster without errors.2) Roku has no audio burps.3) You never need to reboot Roku as you sometimes have to do with Fire Stick.4) Roku's controller is better designed.",4,159,positive,0.5830395221710205,0.5830395221710205,0.2867068946361542,0.1302535980939865,0.4528,5,3088,0,1
Pretty well done....  but there's always a but....,"Just got it. Used it for 2 days now and have some points to make.First - the interface has been responsive with very little lag. The menus are very HD - clear and easy to understand.The app interface is a little quirky as you have to tell it which apps you want to use and then later will have a hard time finding them in the menus, but with a little learning curve you'll figure it out.Next is the Alexa feature. Very responsive and very smart. Always finds the things you are looking for quickly. I am impressed on how well Amazon is doing with this voice capability on all their stuff. And it seems to keep getting better.Here are the flaws:Video Quality is definitely an issue. I am not a novice to internet TV and I still believe a Broadcast TV Antenna connection is the best picture people can get (especially for the price). Heck it even seems that broadcast is equal to blu-ray in quality. But I digress... the Internet has all different methods of streaming compression and extraction. Anyone who has used Netflix for a long time has noticed the different buffering times and quality picture and how Netflix has improved this over the years (have you ever gone to your buddy's house and seen how is Netflix app works differently).. and so some of this depends on TV brand, Year of TV, Year of Smart Feature, etc... But still, many of us standard internet connection users (I'm at 24mbs) will watch the first minute of many shows in grainy detail. I've always wished I could push a button that says &#34;go ahead and buffer and don't start show until its perfect quality&#34;. On some devices (or streaming mediums) pause seems to allow that a little (IOW: the video will continue to download while you are in pause). The Firestick appears to have optomized but not perfected this capability. Perfect is in the eye of the beholder of course - some people don't mind grainyness as much as others and many probably agree it depends on what your watching. So that end, I think the Firestick is struggling. I watch Deadwood through my Laptop, Vizio TV Amazon App, and Firestick and let me tell you - Firestick is lagging. Same goes for Walking Dead.... shoot I'm not sure what the issue is , but watching Walking Dead through the AMC app on Firestick - it never gets focused.Next issue is what the heck is with Prime. I watch videos on prime on my smart TV and on my computer and phones and tablets, but the minute I fire-up the Firestick - it tells me I have to pay to watch the same shows that I have been watching for free on all my other devices. This is where the state of the art is with Internet TV. I can watch NBC &#34;This Is Us&#34; free on my phone no problem, but try on my TV or Firestick - you need special permission or money or something. Those bugs will all have to be worked out. Maybe Roku does it, maybe not, but either way - if the content is our there for free, these TV adapters should just figure out how to show it.UPDATE on this review:Been using the 'stick for a week or so now. The video quality is much improved. Actually - it is now excellent. Best of what can be possible on my 1080p HDTV. Also - user friendliness has improved. We are basically using it full time now. Starting to love it.",4,160,positive,0.864639937877655,0.864639937877655,0.12474566698074341,0.010614358820021152,0.854,0,3226,0,1
I will gladly buy another!,"The Amazon fire stick is a great device to buy if you are trying to save money from paying high bills from other television services and movies. However, this device only works through having internet (Wi-Fi). The fire stick works through apps, which is provided through the device, only if you have an Amazon account. Personally, this device is the best thing I have ever ordered off of Amazon. The price, qualities, and features of this device are outstanding.The Fire stick was well-known when I ordered it. I heard that it was the best thing to have for streaming shows and movies than having to pay an excessive amount of money on any cable companies or going to the movie theater. It can be ordered off of Amazon.com it costs $39.99, plus tax, which is better than paying almost $250 worth of cable and $30 at the theaters. The fire stick is more affordable and is economical for anyone and everyone. The fire stick is the lowest price of some of its competitors which makes it the best option to go to. Such as the Apple box which is about $200 dollars and that is a lot even though it does not have the same features and qualities the fires stick has.One of the qualities of the fire stick would be the fire stick remote; it makes it easy to navigate through the different apps and menus. The remote has a new voice feature so you will not have to waste your time clicking through apps. Also, the remote is bigger than the last version’s remote which makes it easier to press the buttons. Another quality is that this upgraded version of the fire stick can download more apps that it is compatible with. One last quality is that it is easy to hook up to your TV. It only consists of one power cord and the fire stick can just be stuck into the HDMI port of your TV.The features of the Fire stick are better than any other devices that it is competing against. The new voice feature, named Alexa makes scrolling through menus and apps easy and fast to do. All you would have to do is press the microphone button at the top of the remote and say any task you want it to do, such as “Open Netflix” or “Find my favorite song.” The fire stick streams movies and shows faster and play in high-definition. Usually when I watch my favorite movies and shows, they never skip or have to load or glitch. The fire stick also has Bluetooth which you can sync your android phone to and a pair of Bluetooth headphones.I have read some reviews on the fire stick, and some customers began to have a problem with the fire stick remotes, that caused them to by a whole new one. The only problem I have had personally is that the remote is way smaller than a regular cable box remote, and it may be hard to keep up with it. Even though the remote has been upgraded by size and it is not difficult to use, it is still a little tricky to press the buttons. Another downfall of having a fire stick is that if your Wi-Fi goes out you or you do not have Wi-Fi, you will not be able to use it. Also, when the device updates it could take up to 24 hours to do so.In conclusion, if you are looking to save money on movies and shows, I highly recommend buying the Amazon fire stick.",4,161,positive,0.9583041071891785,0.9583041071891785,0.03824153542518616,0.0034544013906270266,0.9548,4,3161,0,1
Reliable with great video/sound,"Please hit the HELPFUL button if this provided you with information that helped your buying decision.Cliff’s Notes: If you watch/listen mostly to Prime content, you will love this. And you can pay for some subscription-based services to customize what you want to watch. Reliable with great video/sound.I wanted to cut the cord from my TV provider and decided to go with Amazon’s Fire products. The Amazon 4K Fire TV is an upgrade to the Fire TV Stick. I have a newer Firestick and bought the 4K Fire TV after that because I wanted to be able to add apps outside the Amazon store. Going into developer mode and turning on those permissions allowed me to add some apps I wanted that were not in Amazon’s store easily and with no installation issues.To ensure you get the best picture for your TV resolution, you should go into the settings and ensure that the Auto-detect setting is set. This way you can be sure it is providing 1080, 2k or 4k, depending on your TV specs.I have 200 mbps FIOS internet through an AC band router using the 5 Ghz band and it streams effortlessly with no slowdown, glitches, or delays. The interface is well designed, but be aware that you might need to scroll down on some screens to get something you want outside of the Prime offerings, as they list things with Amazon services first.Amazon sends this to you with your account already set-up…great customer experience. You can also set up a password for purchases, in case you have children or others that might inadvertently buy new content. Of course, Prime services are preloaded, but you might need to add some items like Netflix, which is very easy using their setup mode.The Alexa integration on the voice activated remote is great. You can ask Alexa to show you action movies, the weather, etc. I found the response to be fast and pretty accurate, although it might take a little learning how to best ask Alexa for things to get the best responses.Another probably not used as much item is the Bluetooth…with that, I have connected a Bluetooth keyboard that REALLY is a time saver when you have to put in passwords, or put in a URL address if you are adding something outside the Amazon store. Bluetooth can be used for headphones also, if you want to watch/listen while not disturbing others.Negatives (not deal breakers):Amazon should allow more competitor apps…after all, if this is for entertainment and people use different apps/services, they should have it available. You can add them yourself, but that should not be necessary. This is putting Amazon OVER the customer needs.Also, not having an ethernet port might not be criminal, but it is again because Amazon wants you to BUY another device, rather than provide what should be in the box. Greed like that is inexcusable.The HDMI cable should be longer…I had to attach an extender to mine to get it where I wanted since my audio and video components are on wall shelving.There are not as many free apps as you might expect, so it would be nice to have a filter for just free apps.",4,162,positive,0.9523179531097412,0.9523179531097412,0.04524952918291092,0.0024325097911059856,0.9499,5,3030,0,1
Awesome! 4 stars for Lack of VUDU.,"Amazon Fire TV stick is almost essential to any TV buying experience. Whether you want to buy a non-smart TV and use this to gain access to awesome smart features, or upgrade an existing smart TV that has started to lose its speed and effectiveness.I got two of these to upgrade my Samsung F8500 plasma's from 2013. The smart features were very robust 4 years ago, and had an amazing speed with a first of its kind quad core processor on the board. Sadly, after the years gone by, Ive noticed a major lack in updates, and loss of speed in the TV's features. This is where the firestick comes into play.The cool thing with this fire stick is it is being used to eliminate two massively irritating habits the Samsung smart interface poses, pre-Tizen OS, that have gotten insensibly irritating. One, you can't exit any apps with out telling the app its okay to exit, (think of Windows Vista style &#34;Are you sure&#34; questioning constantly.) And then it has this &#34;Please wait while smart hub is being updated&#34; every single time you start the TV, and since I have a Harmony Ultimate and start the TV with &#34;watch smart TV&#34; or &#34;Watch Netflix&#34; it repeatedly pops up, everytime, I start the activity. No updates are available, and apparently this is an issue with older model Samsung Smarts. The new Tizen OS is wonderful, and with my two 40&#34; K6300 4ks, its a blast to use, which made my hatred for my older smarts grow.This is where the Firestick comes in. Bought two of of these for my parents for Christmas to help them drop their snowballing DirecTV bill, and absolutely fell in love with the voice control features. Quickly and simple access whatever you want at the use of your voice. Amazon's brilliant GUI design team have nailed this on the head. If you really want it to tickle your happiness, ask it to play Bob's Burgers, and it'll bring up your most recently viewed episode, with a simple resume, which resumes where you left off, beings it from Netflix, or Hulu, or Prime, or whatever else you were watching it on. And if that isn't cool enough, if you click on &#34;Seasons & Episodes&#34; it will show you all the current seasons for the TV Show. This is where my example of Bob's Burgers comes into play, I know for a fact that the latest season, season 7, is ONLY on HULU, but Amazon's search reveals 7 select-able seasons. If you choose seasons 7, it asks if you want to watch on HULU, if you click 5, it asks if you want to watch on Netflix. This is by far the best smart interface feature I've ever come across. No need to load an app, search through it, just to find out it isn't there, and you now have to go on to back out and load a different app.Only thing that needs to be addressed is the lack of VUDU! and I really wish they would add support for this, beings as all of my movies and TV shows that I've bought, I get the Digital Copy and put the digital copy onto VUDU. Have for ever now, and I really miss having this feature.I will update rating once VUDU is placed on the App store. :)",4,163,positive,0.8741065263748169,0.8741065263748169,0.11805708706378937,0.007836396805942059,0.8663,5,3040,0,1
Great for on Viewing at Home or on the go!!!,"Great for those of who haven't invested in super smart TVs or like to travel. Bought a few for the family and some others as gifts. The in-laws have an older model TV, but thankfully have hdmi hook up. Super happy they can mooch off of our Netflix now. Brought those folks into 2010s. So... Good for them. We have one set up and password protected and only the apps of our choosing are on that one for the kiddos. So I feel pretty good about that so far. They aren't able to do as they please. Another great thing is you can take this anywhere you have a TV. Which is everywhere. Went on a trip a while back and we slapped this thing right into the hotel TV. They had enough bandwidth to support streaming movies and games so that's great.Now the downside is it's a bit clunky and it's got a ways before it's superior to other streaming sites and systems. For the price point the set up, I understand. So no big deal there. The black ring of multipurpose-ism is not user friendly. The kids seem to have adapted but the spouse and in-laws, not so much. Yes I know their are remotes and whatnots out there to make this easier. But again price point was great so a non issue.Pro tip: For the people who live like real people and don't go for that streamline look with no wires wall mounted television business... If you live like me, you could care less about wires. Besides electrical tape does wonders. The power cord that comes with it is about 3 or so feet long. You don't have to take up another socket in one of your many power strips behind the TV. Usually around/above the hdmi is a USB port. Plug that bad boy in there instead. It's gonna promot you a few times about not enough power. Your TV has the power to handle that tiny black brick or wonderment. Eventually it will stop prompting you, cause it's fine. Everything is fine! Also it's silly to buy the 6 inch 10 dollar adapter just to have less cords. Cords are what makes you feel like you've accomplished somthing. It's a sh¡t show behind the TV but you marvel at how all your doodads are up and running with no issue. You did good. I'm proud of you.Also I read about folks crying and moaning on how Alexia listens to your canned conversations in your home for hot button words to push ads and on you when accessing your Amazon sites and items. Such as... ""I need to do laundry."" Before you know it they are pushing some sort of laundry detergent ad or subscription on you. Or so I've read or heard... I'm guessing that's why you got that long cord. Keeps that brick juiced so it can listen to all your needs and force your dreams to come true by presenting you an opportunity to pay for it. But if plugged into the telly... Once you turn the telly off, the brick turns off as well. So you can rest your pretty little heads at night. Unless your TV junkies... Your problem, not mine.Again cost and efficiency is what this is really all about. Personally, I can't complain. This was a great buy.",4,164,positive,0.9057169556617737,0.9057169556617737,0.08014222234487534,0.014140886254608631,0.8916,4,2958,0,1
Great for simple viewing,"Got this device only to play Amazon videos available on prime, and Hulu and Netflix for which I have subscriptions. Later I bought an Apple TV4K because I was interested in mirroring content from my phone to my TV.The inducement for buying the Fire TV stick was to streamline finding content from Netflix, Hulu and Amazon Instant Video services, and it works well. For example, as soon as the TV is on, speak into the mike ‘Jessica Jones’; and that series is immediately selected with no other steps. Likewise, say ‘Transparent’; and that series shows up. Likewise, ‘Transparent Season Three’; produces that season.Alexa doesn't always get a request the first time and you may have to reword it. An example is asking for the Netflix series ‘Anne with an E’; which I could not get Alexa to understand.The Firestick works well with Amazon Video as well as Hulu, Netflix, PBS, and FilmStruck. There are many other apps available that I have not tried. U-Tube is available via the Firefox web browser. (Search inside U-Tube works easily with Alexa, for example, once inside U-Tube, the request to Alexa: “Bach, Well-Tempered Clavier” turns up versions available on U-Tube).Alexa also will order stuff for you: for example ‘Order Kindle Voyage’ will produce a description and the inquiry ‘Would you like to buy it now?’ Similarly for book titles. However, you cannot browse a sample or look at reviews.Clicking Home button (the Up-Arrow just below the top Select button) on the Stick automatically turns on my Sony TV and selects correct HDMI input. Some reviewers are unaware that the device can be turned off by holding down this button to produce a menu with the “sleep” option. It is not necessary to unplug the device, as some users suggest.A few customers had trouble putting batteries in the remote. The frustration arises because it appears that, like most such remotes, the battery compartment is opened by sliding up its door. But in this case, the door only slides up a little, and stops. What's wrong? The answer is that when it stops you have to twist the exposed end of the lid lightly to flip the door open. That is a discovery not explained.Another minor frustration is pairing the device. The pairing process asks you to enter a four digit code ‘found on the back of the fire stick’. Nope. If you are lucky, the correct code is shown on the TV screen. If not, you'll have to unplug the fire stick and plug it in again to reveal the code. Give it half a minute to fire up.Other than these unchallenging issues, everything works smoothly.Of course, apps are not necessarily free. And available episodes are not always very current unless they are Amazon or Hulu or Netflix originals.Although I have an Apple TV 4K, which does access U-Tube directly instead of through a browser, I very rarely use it except for AirPlay.",4,165,neutral,0.5325151681900024,0.45723405480384827,0.5325151681900024,0.01025073416531086,0.447,5,2829,0,0
Problems with Echo TV Control on non-FireTVs...wait until next software update to buy.,"UPDATE: So, I tried the interface again last night and it seems to be working fine now. Perhaps there was an Echo firmware update, because the software version on the Fire Stick did not change. Still, there are a few issues that need to be worked out. The voice interface does all the technical basics like turn on and off, raise/lower volume, change channels, select the correct inputs, and even allows you to find a specific show or category of shows. Unfortunately, the functionality stops there. If the show is specific and unique with no possibility of name confusion (e.g. &#34;Find Bloodline&#34; and &#34;Find Fawlty Towers&#34; are great examples), the voice command can go one step further and actually start playing your selection. But if your search results are not unique (such as &#34;Find Star Trek&#34;), you cannot further specify or play any selection without going to the remote. Simple &#34;Left, Right, Up, Down&#34; commands could easily solve this, as could a &#34;Select&#34; command. Additionally, even for unique shows, the command to &#34;play&#34; will always start you on the very first episode. There is no way to select different seasons or episodes without picking up the remote. &#34;Next episode&#34; also will not work if you're watching a series. But, for the most part, it understands. Enough that it's worth it for me to keep. I hope the next software update adds these features.OLD REVIEW:I bought this stick due to the online notifications and articles I read a week ago that it is now possible to control your TV directly through Echo. And this stick works quite well in every capacity...EXCEPT that one. We tried connecting with two different systems at opposite ends of the house and ran into the same issues. Echo Dot sees the fire stick just fine but when actually trying to execute a command (e.g. &#34;start Netflix&#34;, &#34;Find comedies on Fire TV&#34;), we always get the same message, &#34;OK, finding comedies on Fire TV&#34;...and then, &#34;I'm having trouble communicating, please check your connections.&#34;When I called Amazon support about the issue, the first-tier customer support representative wasn't even aware of the new supposed compatibility.The second-tier representative was aware, vaguely, but needed to do more research and call me back.He did as promised, and let me know that Amazon is aware of the compatibility issues and likely released the compatibility software update too soon before thorough testing.I'll be holding on to the device until the next software update release.In the meantime, I advise others who want to buy this for the purpose of Echo-direct-control capability to wait until the next announcement of the new software update.I'll be updating this review when I see the new announcement.",4,166,neutral,0.6846643686294556,0.2297944724559784,0.6846643686294556,0.08554118126630783,0.1443,7,2782,0,0
A decent basic device for those new to streaming.,"First... I received this device free with a subscription to a live TV service. I cut the cable a long time ago and have been using an android tv box for over a year. That said, I'm probably spoiled by the extended functionalities and customizations the android box offers. I did give it a full 2 weeks plus before giving up on the FireStick and going back to my old android box.Out of the box, the FireStick was easy to install and get set up. In under 15 minutes I was able to watch live tv. Navigation was simple, but customization is almost non existent. You get the layout they give you and either love it or hate it.If you've never used anything else, you'll probably think &#34;Wow! This is great&#34;. Menus are fast, apps start quickly and streaming is great with a good wifi connection. But you won't be so impressed if you have other devices to compare it to. A couple big things that really bugged me:My initial thought during my first use was &#34;Really?? Do I have to look at these ads for Amazon content every time I use this? I need to turn that off!&#34; I've explored every menu option - you can't get rid of the advertising. It dominates half of the screen as soon as you turn on the device. Yeah it goes away when you start an app, but you have to navigate past it to get to your apps.Next big issue for me: When I first fired up my live TV app, the volume was way too loud. WHERE IS THE VOLUME BUTTON ON THE REMOTE!?!? It doesn't have one! I had to find my TV remote to adjust the volume. How does a company like Amazon make a video playback device and forget to include a volume control button? Different streaming choices can have very different base volume levels. So make sure you have your tv remote nearby to adjust the volume.As for the Alexa voice control, I've yet to be able to make it do anything useful. I suppose if you want to search Amazon content for a particular movie or song it might be handy, since typing in a search box is very cumbersome with the remote, but voice search doesn't work with other apps such as YouTube.If you are new to streaming content, this is a decent basic device and you won't get lost trying to set up. It works, but has some annoying quirks you don't find with other devices in the same price range. (NOTE: Most quality content on ANY streaming device requires a subscription fee and the appropriate app. The free stuff is usually garbage no one would ever pay for, delivered by poorly created apps that hardly work. A point that a lot of people seem to miss and blame it on the FireStick.)For me, my $40 android tv box blows this device away. However, it did take a bit of tweaking and experimenting to make the android box work the way I wanted it to - something not everyone is interested in doing.",4,167,neutral,0.49417123198509216,0.44655507802963257,0.49417123198509216,0.05927372723817825,0.3873,5,2768,0,0
Software issues resolved!,"Early versions of the firmware had problems with wifi dropping out, but this seems to be fixed around May 2017, which makes this a solid product.I measured power consumption with a multimeter. You can expect the power draw to top out at 0.9 amps. With standby at 0.15 and idle at 0.3. Decoding 1080p x264 video draws about 0.6-0.7 amps. Note that the included power supply is 1 amp, and most tv USB ports are only 0.5 amps, so do not try to use those.Apps are required for most functionality, but the homescreen only allows a limited number of apps to be placed, and they are all in one row under one specific part of the menu. The home screen has sponsored content and advertisements. It is a little annoying, but you can disable the auto play video and sound from them in the system settings. Even though this is android, you can't replace the system launcher. The amazon app store is very limited. You can not access the play store (no play services). Apps can be sideloaded however, so that is a major plus.Voice search feature is nearly useless. It only works for finding paid/promoted content. You can not use it as an input method in any apps to do searches or speech to text (like you can on android phone). It does not integrate into youtube search or various apps.Resolution is locked at 1080p, and always renders this. If you set 720p output, it will downscale the 1080 image.Volume control and mute does not function on the android OS, so rf remotes can not adjust volume. You must change volume directly on your tv (ir remote).HDMI CEC support has been fixed as of May 2017. Pressing a key on the amazon remote will switch inputs to the fire tv, and will power on the television. Using an IR CEC remote works fairly well, though some button presses are missed, especially rapid ones.The on screen keyboard is simply horrid. You can replace this by sideloading a IME (keyboard app) and then activating the IME over ADB. I suggest LeanKey, its free and designed for TV.USB works, you just need an Otg cable. Then you can use hubs, storage, keyboards/mice, rf air remotes, etc. Just a note though, if you have ADB enabled, it will temporarily disable USB devices.The homescreen does not draw the mouse cursor, but registers mouse clicks, which is annoying. The right click button does not do the android back impulse, and you can not edit the keymaps to fix this. If you have an air mouse, it is likely the back button is right click, and wont work right. You can set up right mouse behavior in some apps (like kodi/xmbc) to overcome this.Gamepad right and left trigger support does not exist. Most sideloaded games will not work. Amazon has used special keys, break and gas, and remaps controllers to use break and gas.",4,168,neutral,0.5282226800918579,0.4266378581523895,0.5282226800918579,0.04513949900865555,0.3815,5,2730,0,0
Dont kick your self for waitng TOO long to get one!,"I FINALLY got this Fire Stick and very glad that I did.PRESENT DAY: Very easy to set up. Picture is wonderful, Its great to have all of your AMAZON features on a big TV Screen you can access from bed!I don't tend to use the Alexa feature much- but so far so good with this purchase. Many Apps in the App Store and I've been quite happy with the format of viewing on the screen.PREVIOUSLY:I had bought a &#34;TCL&#34; SMART TV recently in my quest to &#34;Cut the Chord&#34; and get away from the Cable companies.This TV model has ROKU embedded in the TV System.I signed up with a Streaming TV/Movie service ( that used to have satellite dishes but now come to you by streaming) and downloaded the Streaming Services App and I've had problems with excessive buffering, shows shutting down constantly, getting knocked out of the whole system and having to sign in...it was a nightmare.I realized that my other streaming services ( Amazon Prime, Netflix) weren't having ANY of those problems so I deducted that the problem was with the app for the TV/Movie streaming service, not anything else ( my wifi level, router, connection etc etc )Finally contacted the company itself to find out that that service does NOT support the TCL models of Televisions ( at least most models) and they could not give me any time frame as to when they would become compatible and or if there was a fix for it.Prime Day came up and I figured, may as well try the Fire Stick on the TV. I was worried that the Roku device and the Fire Stick would have issues. So I deleted the majority of the TV/Movie Streaming services app - then installed the FIre Stick w Alexa and downloaded the TV/Movie streaming company's app onto the Fire Stick ( Easy Peazy).I've had little to no problems since. The voice tracking will go off sometimes... but easy fix means just changing the channel for a moment and going back to the original channel to get the tracking back on line.When turning on the TV, my TCL has me go to the home page, then find the input ( in my case an HDMI Streaming portal) - I am finding I have to do that last step twice for it to work.. but the TV goes right to the last channel I was watching- great sound, great picture.(The TV/Movie service that I had purchased had no such &#34;memory&#34; so when you got knocked off air, you'd have to find the guide then scroll through to find your channel again one station at a time!)I'm glad that I caught the sale, but these baby's are worth it at their full price too. So many channels to have access to, the ability to view my prime photo's , the internet, Audible, Books and all on my Amazon profile ! I even bought one for a friend for Christmas...she is going to LOVE IT!",4,169,positive,0.980144739151001,0.980144739151001,0.01576627790927887,0.0040890006348490715,0.9761,4,2707,0,1
NOT for YouTube TV services... blocked!  Superior in every other way.,"When I first bought this dongle in December 2017, it was in addition to my Chromecast because I had a subscription to YouTube TV, which I was very happy with.The more I used the Firestick in the bedroom, the more I liked it and the LESS I liked Chromecast! The fact that I had to not only have 3 remotes (TV remote, Sound Bar remote, Firestick remote), if I wanted to watch my YouTube TV subscription, I had to also have my cellphone there with all of the remotes. After using Firestick to control the TV for a while, the phone became more and more of a pain since it displayed only a small portion of the content and if I was just browsing the previous day's shows or all of the live programming it took a long time to tap tap tap along to scan all of the thumbnails.One big surprise was finding out that at any time I could pause a video or music and ask Alexa a question... even about status of an Amazon order... or find something I'd forgotten to order and add it to my shopping cart before I forget it again (don't want to quit my movie and go order it on my desktop right then, but forget about it before the movie ends).FIRESTICK DISPLAYS THE FULL SCREEN ON THE TV AND YOU MAKE SELECTIONS FROM YOUR TV SCREEN EVEN MORE EASILY THAN ON A SATELLITE OR CABLE BOX! To see what is available on YouTube using your Smartphone, you have to search using a lot of tapping and scanning and swiping to bring the little thumbnail pictures into the screen. With the Firestick, you just tell Alexa what you want and there (all but YouTubeTV) it is! No, Alexa might not be able to find every show available, but it can get you into the exact area you need to be and you can just click the big ring on the remote to walk along the LARGE thumbnail pictures and select the one you want... wow! You wouldn't think it would be that much easier until you'd tried it!Typing a search into the Firestick is not as easy as doing that on the cellphone of course... but in “most” cases you can search just by telling Alexa to find it...Easy to see that I'm going to have to find a different TV provider, even though I do love YouTube TV. That's a difficult thing for me to do because YTTV provides exactly the shows I like most. Others seem to be missing one or more of my favorites, especially CBS... YTTV includes full access to all of CBS and still costs less than the streamers that do not include it. But that's a different discussion.Using Kodi seems like a solution as well... I have it, but there are kinks in that as well, including labored typing that Alexa can't help with.I love Amazon's Alexa Fire Stick and I love Google's YouTube TV... dilemma. Still looking for a new streaming provider that compares.",4,170,positive,0.8823583126068115,0.8823583126068115,0.11089162528514862,0.0067500341683626175,0.8756,5,2696,0,1
"Great, compact, but way too many ads during YouTube videos","TL;DR: Overall, for the price paid, it's a great, compact way to get video/audio streaming on a TV. Initial technical issues, but overcame them with some crafty internet searching. And just having the Amazon Prime Video, Prime Music, YouTube, and Netflix apps, is more than enough content for my household to enjoy. We just have to tolerate the constant barrage of ads on the YouTube app and the scrolling/navigation lag. Remote is simple and doesn't drain batteries quickly.It's been about 3 years now since my initial review and it's been mostly good. I used it directly plugged into a TV for a few months, but now have it plugged into an audio/video receiver. It's been a mostly good experience in either cases. It isn't blazing fast, but for the price I've learned to deal with the lag and buffer. That same lag and buffer is more noticeable on the Amazon Music and Disney+ apps. Navigation speed is tolerable throughout the entire main menu and home page. The way it processes data reminds me of a late 1990s Pentium or early 2000s Celeron-based computer running on minimum RAM. While trying to searching around to watch a movie, either on the home page or in the Amazon Prime Video and Music apps, the thumbnails show up quite slowly, which is a bit of an annoyance.*The search page has a layout that's easy to read and easy to select text. It populates what you're searching for very well.*The Amazon Prime Video app works, but it takes a long time for it to get to HD picture quality on most selections.*Netflix app works good. The picture quality is a lot quicker to get to HD levels on most selections, especially on content you're trying to resume watching. There is still a bit of scrolling/navigation lag that I've learned to tolerate.*Disney+ app feels like it's in beta mode. Not as stable or content-filled as Netflix.*What I don't like about the Fire TV Stick is that every so often the long-press home button, or even the single-press home button, doesn't work so I have to manually unplug it to restart or turn the thing off.*I discovered that clearing the memory cache in the Settings page every once in a while is one way to get rid of some of the scrolling/navigation lag.*I also don't like that there is no manual or software enabled on/off switch. It's constantly on and connected to my WiFi if I don't unplug or switch my router off or go into the Setting page.*My main dislike is the YouTube app having way too many ads DURING a video, but that's not Amazon's fault I think. It's YouTube and sometimes the content creator's fault for allowing the ads to occur. I don't mind ads before or after a video, but during a video is extremely frustrating.",4,171,positive,0.907372772693634,0.907372772693634,0.08223046362400055,0.010396761819720268,0.897,6,2673,0,1
A device to let you cut the cord is rendered useless when you do,"Edit: After 4 months I've increased my rating to 4 stars from 2. It's probably more like 3.5 but since I had it at 2 for so long I figured since I couldn't give it 3.5 a 4 was fair. Reasons for my improvement.1. Channels seem to be doing a better job of offering their content on Fire. I can now watch Shield a week later and shows on CW.2. Using this more, Chromecast less. Compared to the similarly priced Chromecast there is no comparison.3. There was an update awhile back and the lag is almost all gone, I never really haev a problem unles I have 12 apps running in the background. And I do appreciate hitting the big button on the remote turns on both my sound system and my TV so I'm ready to go.End edit. Original review follows, I'm leaving it as a warning, it's still not a simple device to replace cable tv.Bought an Amazon Fire TV stick that Amazon promotes as a way to cut the cord. And here's how that went for the 4 shows I wanted to watch.AMC app - doesn't have Preacher off-seasonBBC America app - has most shows, except Dr. Who, the 1 I watchUSA app - requires a cable subscription, which I still have, but not their channel, so no Mr. RobotABC app - which is free over the air with any cheap antenna requires a cable subscription, so no Agents of Shield that waySo that's not the devices fault, it's the apps fault, but my review is based on how functional the device is as marketed, so I don't care who's fault it is, just the end user experience.And speaking of experience, this thing lags all the time. Not the shows, those stream fine, but moving from 1 app to the next or 1 show to the next within any app. Sometimes it just works fine, but others it's wait 5 or 6 seconds for the cursor to move, or sometimes you need to hit the button again. It isn't smooth, not by a long shot. And the Amazon Prime app is much better on my PS3. It's nice to have an app dedicated to shows only on Prime but using it is a chore. I only add shows to my Watchlist on on PC on the website, it's too hard to search and navigate on the device.But I did keep it. It cost me $25 and I received a $7 Amazon video credit, 1 month of CBS All Access and a month of Showtime, so I basically got it for close to free. And since I'm paying for Prime anyway might as well watch some shows. I do like the remote, I got a Chromecast as a gift a week or so later and that doesn't have a remote, I have to use my phone, so I almost never use it.So know what you are getting, if you get this to cut the cord, well your shows may be cut as well. And there are many other devices if you only want Netflix. But this one is cheap, and comes with a remote, so it gets 2 stars.",4,172,positive,0.8247938752174377,0.8247938752174377,0.16355885565280914,0.01164728682488203,0.8131,0,2661,0,1
Welcome to Streaming TV!,"This has been my first experience with streaming TV, and it's been pretty good so far. I like how this little gadget makes a dumb TV smart and a smart TV even smarter. You get hundreds of &#34;channels&#34;, which are actually apps in Fire TV parlance. Some of those apps provide live TV feeds, but most of what you watch with Fire TV is what cable companies call Video On Demand (VOD). That takes some getting used to, because it pretty much means that with Fire TV, you don't just mindlessly channel-surf. On the other hand, you get mostly HD content without having to deal with two versions of channels, as you often do on cable TV systems.Fire TV's processor speed is respectable, and that comes into play because while streaming, the Fire TV has to download content, buffer it and render it into video, which it then outputs to the TV via the HDTV connection. A faster processor, combined with a solid, speedy Internet connection, provides smooth, uninterrupted video while minimizing the graininess and low resolution that lesser streaming systems often give you when a video first starts to play, before the player has a chance to amass a buffer full of rendered video.The Amazon Fire TV Stick with Alexa only does 1080p HDTV. If you want 4K HDTV, you need the more expensive, full-size Amazon Fire TV unit.I do have a few minor complaints, which is why I docked the Fire TV Stick one star:1. The Fire TV global search, whether you use Alexa or not, seems to favor paid video content. I've learned to repeat searches within my favorite apps, in which I often find the same program or movie free (or simply within an app in which I've already paid for such programs and movies).2. Alexa only works in the Fire TV global search. To search within specific apps, you must run the app and then use its built-in search, via its own on-screen keyboard.3. The only thing more curious than the selection of included apps is the ones that are missing. For example, VUDU is not available. (It is available with Roku.) Fortunately, I use my Fire TV Stick on a television to which I also have a smart Blu-Ray player, which does include VUDU.4. Finding &#34;included with Prime&#34; content within Amazon using the Fire TV Stick is a bit of a frustrating experience. Part of the problem is that Fire TV has its own way of categorizing Amazon video content, and it's not the same as when you look up content on amazon.com via a computer with a web browser. And part of it is that, as mentioned earlier, the search engine favors video content that costs extra.",4,173,positive,0.9521465301513672,0.9521465301513672,0.04359063133597374,0.0042628333903849125,0.9479,5,2551,0,1
"Great Device, but the $90 box is near perfect, get that instead, and get Prime. Me and my girlfriend love it.","This is the second purchase of the Fire TV series I have made. I bought the Fire TV box first off (with the 4k capability). Girlfriend and i loved the fire tv. It works near flawlessly, and being an Prime member makes the fire TV totally worth it. I would recommend signing up for prime if you get Fire TV (stick or drive). For christmas i decided to see how Apple TV compared. Cool setup and it looks like it may have had more mainstream media options. Unfortunately, you have to pay for all those options. I said sorry babe we're getting another amazon one, we both agreed we didn't want to pay for all those shows or movies. With a prime membership on amazon, many of them are free (it tells you what is and isn't if you don't know, and you soon will if you are new to prime.) So i decided after Apple TV to try the stick as it is half the price. Although it works and is easy and mobile, i gave this review a 4 star because the device buffers often, which is annoying. Who wants to play with their settings and wifi for days to get this to stop? not I. If it keeps up i might buy another Fire TV-drive-style ($90). That device i would give 5 stars. The description for the Fire TV box even notes a critical difference. &#34;Now with 75% more processing power, a dedicated graphics engine, better Wi-Fi support, 2 GB of memory, 8 GB of storage and expandable storage of up to 200 GB&#34; vs the stick. It makes sense, how could you cram perfection into that tiny USB style device? Anyway, to anyone reading this my recommendations. 1. if you are going to get fire TV, get the box spend twice the money for enjoyable relaxing flawless performance. 2. Get prime. this device wouldn't be the same without my prime membership. Plus, the prime subscription has more than paid for itself every year I've had it, just in shipping savings alone. 3. If you can't scratch up enough cash for the box vs the stick, the stick is still a great device. Definitely worth $40, only downfall is buffering issue. (my belief is this device may be more susceptible to interference from other devices, but I have no proof at this point.) To Apple lovers: I LOVE APPLE PRODUCTS. I hate android and PCs, and will never have any phone other than an iPhone, i am even typing this review on my 8-9 year old intel core 2 duo Macbook. Was Apple TV better than amazon fire TV? NO (but this is personally just because I use Prime membership for the TV and shipping/purchases). To someone who does not buy 200 items a year on Amazon, and would rather spend 20 bucks a pop on every show or movie on Apple TV, then maybe that device is for you.",4,174,positive,0.9567545056343079,0.9567545056343079,0.03919452428817749,0.004051023628562689,0.9527,4,2613,0,1
"Great Product for the Price, Some Issues to Work Out","Got the Fire TV Stick on sale for $25 on Black Friday, primarily because I didn't have access to Prime video on our Apple TV. For the price I can't complain, but I couldn't help but laugh when Prime video showed up on my Apple TV a week later.Anyway, this is a great product. The interface is snappy, the remote feels good, the apps are visually appealing, voice search works well, and the ability to customize which apps you want is great. My main critique is that picture quality is good, but not great. I'd say it's totally satisfactory for a smaller 720p -- 1080p TV, but you will notice a difference compared to an Apple TV (even older generations) or a higher end Roku product. I don't have a 4K TV, but from my use on multiple sets in the house, my overall impression was that the better the TV, the more you notice the difference in video quality for the stick versus other streamers.Obviously, this is cheaper than most of those products, but the issue doesn't seem to be that this lacks the computing power to put out a high res, high frequency picture, but that it prioritizes fast delivery of video over giving the highest quality picture. Perhaps it's lacking in internal memory, but I'd much rather spend an extra 10-20 seconds at the start of a movie to let a buffer load than get it started quicker in lower quality. Frame rate also seemed a bit down on this compared to watching the same videos sent from an Apple TV.One specific issue for a minority of users is the Plex app on the Fire Stick. Shows from certain channels recorded on my Plex server showed up with lots of artifacts and were almost unwatchable on the stick, but other channels looked ok. All shows looked like original quality when playing on the Plex app on Apple TV - so the issue is not the original recording. My guess is that this is something caused by having to transcode to get on the Fire TV Stick, but take it for what it is -- this may not (at least until a firmware update adding more codecs) be the best Plex client out there.Another issue I've had is that the Fire TV Stick would not power on when connected to the USB port of my 48&#34; Samsung. It kept power cycling and trying to start. I just attached it to wall power, which worked fine, but just adds to the mess of cords. I don't know whether to hold this against the Stick or the TV. Chromecast worked fine with the same TV, but the Stick has also worked flawlessly with the USB on a smaller Insignia (cheap Best Buy brand) bedroom TV. Your experience may vary.",4,175,positive,0.8731980919837952,0.8731980919837952,0.10738108307123184,0.019420849159359932,0.8538,4,2517,0,1
Fire TV Stick 2: Just amazing and it works!,"We got Amazon Prime, too. The stick arrived fine, VG shipping carton, no damage. But though the tracker said it had been &#34;delivered&#34;, it was nowhere to be seen until I drove down the hill to our mailbox and found it squeezed between two mail boxes right next to the street. YIKES! Totally exposed, a fine opportunity for anybody driving by. So 3.5 stars for the transaction rounds up to 4, should've been a solid 5.The retail boxology for stick + components is very clever, no wasted space at all. The stick came up on our Samsung LN52B TV w/ no problems. Nice touch: when using USB power, the stick evaluates the incoming juice and if it's too low you're advised to use the included AC to DC wall plug and long cable. Jaw dropping video quality, sound is excellent even with TV speakers, TV audio and video stay synchronized. With our fast home network and 50Mb bandwidth from cable co., so far the streaming performance is flawless over the 5Ghz channel, haven't tried 2.4Ghz. (Will buy another stick and test concurrent streaming.) Moved the stick to lower end Samsung UH40, no problem, it resumed with same state as the previous TV.Alexa's speech recognition/synthesis is accurate, even with different voices. The UI is sort of simple, once you understand the paradigms, such as apps stuff versus normal stuff, but the content choices are vast and mind boggling to navigate. Before it becomes muscle memory, gotta really concentrate. The stick comes with a skimpy how-to-connect pamphlet, that's it. Maybe there's usable detail stored in the stick, but so far I haven't found it, maybe Alexa knows where it is. I did find on the web a fer real How To Really USE pdf file, big relief.Note to owners of home theater surround sound gear: The stick is said to output encoded Dolby Digital Enhanced surround (5.1 maybe 6.1 or 7.1), along with the encoded HD video. Unless your system has HDMI input and a built in decoder, getting the stick's elegant audio into and through your system will be problematic. There are alleged solutions out there (converter boxes), but read the specs carefully for proper tech compatibility with your system and read as many reviews as you can find. Cheap price means cheap parts and, probably, low end circuit design with incorrect frequency splitting. You probably will have to live with the TV's two-channel analog RCA outputs, i.e. no surround FOR YOU! Even then, pray that the sound and video stay in sync. My McIntosh C-39 pre-amp is in the shop so I haven't tried it yet.",4,176,neutral,0.4973447322845459,0.20945076644420624,0.4973447322845459,0.2932044565677643,-0.0838,4,2517,0,0
Great purchase for a mostly all-in-one streaming device.,"Overall, this is a wonderful choice for a streaming device and I'm really pleased that it's so affordable.For context, we were given a really nice but slightly older model of gigantic TV that isn't a smart TV. We already owned a Google Chromecast for the super simple casting feature. We hoped it would be enough to be able to stream from the common apps, but the long-term problem with Chromecast is that there isn't an external user interface, so the once convenient feature of being able to cast anything from your phone becomes a bit tiresome and draining on your battery when you watch as much TV as we do. As Android phone, tablet, and computer users, the Chromecast is still necessary for us even with it's weaknesses because we purchase and rent SO much media from the Play store, and currently Amazon still refuses to play nice with Google.The exact reverse is why we are happy to have added the Fire Stick. We also have lots of content on this Prime account that we weren't able to cast to the Chromecast because Amazon refuses to allow their Prime content to participate on Google platforms.Frustrating that we can't quite find one solution to all of our first world problems in ONE device, but everything else about the experience is really, really positive.Pros:-Affordable.-Really attractive user interface.-Quick set-up, didn't even need to look at the instructions.-Tons of apps available.-Remote is easy to handle and looks clean.-Everything loads SO much faster than on the Roku my in-laws use. Images, apps, media, controls within streaming apps.Cons:-Alexa's voice feature baffles me. I'm young and comfortable with tech and still can't figure out whatever magic words I need to get Alexa to be actually helpful. This miiiiight be a cool feature for some, but Alexa and I just aren't on the same page.-Lots more buffering on certain apps than when we use Chromecast. HBO GO in particular. Unlikely that our WiFi connection is the issue as it's an incredibly fast private network with very few (if any) additional devices accessing the connection and a really nice router just a few feet away. You can't hard wire this device so that may just be an unavoidable irritation.-Cute remote is also easy to lose.-Prime doesn't cooperate with Google media so we still need to keep our Chromecast to access our media from the Play store.Would be 5 stars if it cooperated with Google media.",4,177,positive,0.9502020478248596,0.9502020478248596,0.04202675819396973,0.007771233096718788,0.9424,5,2400,0,1
Not as Advertised*REVISED*,"We have 3 tvs. We bought one firestick to try it out to determine if we like it before ordering for the other 2. Right now, I'm not convinced. This is more complicated than advertised. You do not pug in and go. You have to find an app for the channel you want. Many apps for the channels we would like require a cable subscription which is what we are trying to avoid. Kodi is cumbersome and suited for people in the EU, not USA. The &#34;Pluto App&#34; that comes with the Firestick and touts &#34;Free TV&#34; is ridiculous. Pluto's channels are not anything you have ever heard of before. We cannot locate local stations. So, basically, if you want a channel on firestick, you need to download that channel's app. THEN, within that app, you either need a cable subscription to activate it or pay a monthly subscription fee for a package that allows you to &#34;add on&#34; other channels that also cost you more money. So, if you think you are going to cut the cable and plug in a firestick, think again. Also, Alexa is not as responsive as I'd hoped. There is no changing &#34;channels&#34;, i.e., apps, via voice command. There is no &#34;resume&#34; feature if you leave an app. I'm hoping in the long run we will save some money and get the few channels we would like as we figure this out. It simply is not as easy as the Amazon people would have you believe. Be prepared to spend a great deal of time and set yourself a budget. Be patient, unlike me right now! HA!UPDATE 9/13/2017to be fair, I needed to come back and update my review. After considerable time researching and getting this firestick figured out, we actually are enjoying it immensely. It would be helpful if the firesticks could be linked so we didn't have to set each one individually; but overall, it has been worth the effort. We cut our cable bill in half. We have not missed anything we have wanted to see. We actually have seen more Cleveland Indians baseball here in NC than ever with the MLB at bat app that came on the firestick! Yes, many of the apps involve a monthly fee but when you know that and you know your budget, you can be in control! We each have our own youtube accounts so we have set those up on the firestick. We are prime members so getting movies is a breeze and if it's not on prime, we have many other choices to find it! Get the Firestick. Be prepared to put time into it and then get the joy of cutting cable and your monthly bill in half!",4,178,negative,0.5108782052993774,0.048423364758491516,0.44069844484329224,0.5108782052993774,-0.4625,0,2445,1,0
Too much content resticted!,"First off I want to say that I currently own two of these and have quite enjoyed them especially since I've been able to watch YouTube on the tv and have instant access to my prime account. However giving the fact that Amazon and Google seem to be in some school girl drama over devices being sold and allowing content to be available to the other, I will be losing YouTube very soon! Since I don't do cable or satellite service anymore it is important to me to have every viewing options available. Between this and the whole liberal leaning answers that Alexa gives calling Jesus Christ a fictional character (although they quickly &#34;corrected&#34; shortly before black friday!) I believe it is time to change devices. My wife will be returning the one that she bought me for Christmas (which is still in the box wrapped under the tree) to use our bedroom, and I'll be switching to roku sticks.Side note I do like Amazon service and the liberal leaning Alexa is only mildly annoying Especially since I don't use it ever! I dont care how you vote or what you believe in i just want it to quit bleeding over into my entertainment because this is my escape from the real world problems. (P.S. whether or not you believe in god or in Christianity, if you put all the spiritual stuff aside, Jesus Christ was a real figure who was well documented the Romans.) I also know that most people don't buy these just for the stock services and tend to &#34;upgrade ;-)&#34; with kodi. I personally don't mess with it anymore given the current legal issues in the UK which is where most of the add ons stream from and are kind of unreliable. So Netflix DVD and the occasional date night at the movies solves a lot of that! I just wish that these two companies can get their crap in order and do what they do best which is sell stuff and create easy to use content! For this reason I give two stars, one for ease of use and one for Amazon service in general but it loses three stars for restricting content available and easily accessed on every other device.Update! Changed my review to a four star from a two stars. Although my opinion has not changed about the two companies I have to hand it amazon for keeping the operating system open and to the people out there finding ways to open new doors when others close so I gave one more star to Amazon for the developer option and another star to the developers!",4,179,positive,0.8265167474746704,0.8265167474746704,0.13933369517326355,0.03414948657155037,0.7924,5,2402,0,1
"so good --- but trying to find a ""work-around"" for the ...","So far, so good --- but trying to find a &#34;work-around&#34; for the &#34;Alexa&#34; enabled software issues. Got this for a Christmas gift, with the &#34;cord cutting&#34; idea in mind. I have not elimanted my cable tv company yet. Set up the Fire Stick with no issues. Have downloaded a handful of network channels such as Syfy, Smithsonian, NASA, ESPN, etc. Decided to try a trial of the Hulu LIVE TV. Set that up also. Seems to work ok. With both Fire Stick and Hulu LIVE, there is always a brief delay, whenever you are switching things/programs. It's not instant like cable tv is. But you also PAY for that luxury, when it comes to cable tv.What I've noticed is that regular tv shows and movies seem to have a pretty good picture quality. But when it comes to watching sports, and anything that has a lot of fast motion (think Hockey, for example), the picture is blurring all the time. Makes it hard to watch sports. In researching this issue, quite a bit, I've learned that it seems like the Fire Stick with Alexa has it's software throttled a bit, in order for it to be able to NOW work with the newer Alexa feature. If you read a lot of the forums, it's a lot of the folks who NOW have the Fire Stick with Alexa, who are experiencing this same blurring effect (it also has to do with the &#34;frames per second&#34; rate that is being broadcasted also. More on that in a minute). But folks who own the older Fire Sticks that DON'T HAVE Alexa, are not having that problem.** So I am looking for a way to possibly (?) side-load an older version of the Fire Stick software, that DOESN'T HAVE Alexa. If anyone knows how, get in touch with me. I don't care about not having the Alexa feature. And I'm not returning this Fire Stick, as some folks might suggest.I also know that Hulu is still broadcasting at the lower 30 FPS (frames per second) rate, as many of the new tv streaming services are. A lot of the jittery motion during sports, comes from using that frame rate, but I have learned that plenty of non-Alexa Fire Stick users are NOT having as much of an issue. I'm not interested in debating that issue, as I've read plenty on it. I'm just looking for a &#34;work-around&#34;, while we are all waiting for these LIVE TV streaming companies to increase their FPS broadcast rates. So if you KNOW what I can do, please chime in. Thanks.",4,180,positive,0.5310348272323608,0.5310348272323608,0.4166232645511627,0.05234190821647644,0.4787,4,2349,0,1
Serves our simple streaming needs.,"Up until recently, I have been streaming my Netflix through an original circa 2006 Nintendo Wii (believe it or not) without a problem. Well, all great things eventually must come to an end and recently I was notified that I wouldn't be able to use my Wii to stream my Netflix as of January 2019. So, I went hunting for a simplistic streaming media player that was basic and affordable. That led me to the Fire Stick...Straight out of the box, the setup was a breeze. Simply plug in the power adapter, then attach the HDMI cable to tv (I had to use the little extender adapter for my setup [included]). That's it. You're done. Follow the on-screen instructions step by step to connect to your home wifi, then download the apps on-screen that you wish to use the device for. Done. In my case, I'm pretty much using it mostly for Netflix. Let me tell you, the picture clarity is a huge upgrade in comparison to the Wii that I was streaming it through previously! As for the remote...it's tiny, yet practical and basic. I'm not much of a vocalist when it comes to voice commands that prompt actions being taken (i.e. Alexa), however, it's nice to know that it exists if need be. All in all, this was a fine choice for me and it works great for my practical purposes and didn't break the bank. Win win!Con: My only real grumble is that the remote control's buttons are these tactile type of switches that are quite noisy with each ""click, click"" as you navigate. This isn't exactly fun when I slip my headphones on to watch some tv when coming home from the night shift at 2:00 a.m. and my sleeping wife is next to me (who wakes up at 6:00 a.m. for work). The loud ""clicks"" of the remote are far from superior in execution. I'm honestly surprised that I don't hear more people complaining of this, since watching tv at night (next to a sleeping spouse/partner) isn't anything uncommon or unheard of. These remotes should absolutely be quiet buttons, not a ""clicky"" loud plastic noise with each and every thumb command. I took a star off of my rating for this issue, but for the price point, I do understand that it's all in getting what you pay for, so the ""clicky"" tactile switches were surely used to keep costs down.There's also no on/off power button (Huh?? What??)! Yes, so this thing stays on all the time unless you unplug it. Odd!Overall, still a happy purchase.",4,181,positive,0.48660314083099365,0.48660314083099365,0.4111327826976776,0.1022641584277153,0.3843,4,2365,0,1
Firestick vs Apple TV,"My husband bought this for us and we turned off our cable and switched to streaming services instead. Month two-three & im very satisfied. My dad has apple instead and I played with his Apple TV the other day. Truly there’s little difference. I like the apple remote better but don’t dislike the fire stick remote at all. The touch pad is just a nice feature on the Apple TV remote. The price difference definitely makes up for that small preference and I’ve been an Apple product consumer since the first iPod came out. This feels a bit more like android type software and it reminds me of a more Netflix/Hulu application rather than a cable layout like Apple TV has. You can tell what they were designed for (directv now type for Apple and Hulu/Netflix for firestick) another difference is the games which frankly we’ll never ever use. Apple had a better selection but this isn’t something that would sway me. Additionally, I have kids and thankfully amazon has been a godsend in the past where they’ve ordered stuff on my smart tv and phones without my knowledge (amazon quickly reversed the charges without hassle and in a very friendly manner) - the fire stick keeps your credit card info on file for purchases which we love being able to buy amazon digital movies that are stored on our amazon accounts since we can’t lose them- kids can’t mess them up -etc. BUT there’s a purchase pin which I’m thankful for. Another point -My husband travels for work so he can take the firestick with him and plug it in and watch his football and shows on recording which is a huge plus! All in all—␀ this is the better purchase. It’s not necessarily better than Apple TV as i think they are pretty close to equal but when you account for the $100+ savings it’s well with getting the fire stick over the Apple TV. I’ve now convinced 2-3 family members to buy these instead and we’re all pretty much cutting the cords to save money without losing any of the luxuries of cable. Actually I prefer to use Alexa instead of having to scroll to find shows with a regular remote. It’s spoiling me already. My kids will probably act like someone lives in the stone age if they have to actually use cable remotes at someone else’s house. Saves times and answers questions, gives info IMDb style, and typical Alexa capabilities like weather, random facts etc..",4,182,positive,0.9019671082496643,0.9019671082496643,0.09040602296590805,0.007626840844750404,0.8943,5,2341,0,1
Great Streaming Stick.,"Love the Fire Stick. I have been using Roku box for a while now and wanted to see the difference for myself. But, I don't really know if it's a fair comparison, Roku Express is what I was currently using, which is the least expensive box they offer. But when Amazon offered the Fire Stick for $25 bucks, had to get one, and glad I did. The Home screen is a 100% improvement over Roku. There is no lag clicking between apps, settings, or wherever you go. And overall performance is much better. I'm sure the processor in Fire Stick is much more than what is in Roku Express, but both can be found at about the same price when Amazon is offering a sale on these (which seems to be quite a bit lately). The only reason I didn't give 5 stars is because I thought that it should have an ethernet port built in. Also, irecently received a Fire TV (free with one month prepaid Directv Now @ $35), and $35 bucks for a Fire TV box seemed like a good deal to me. The Fire TV is actually a bit faster than the Fire Stick, but I'm sure most people won't be able to tell the difference. I've read a lot complaints about the new Fire TV, compared to the previous model, but I never owned one before and only know what I see now. Although I totally agree that the upper end Fire TV should have an ethernet port built into it as well, and not offered as an accessory for $15 (which adopts to both the Fire Stick & Fire TV). I have relied on Roku for almost 2 years now since ditching cable, and it has always worked well for me. But, I never felt the urge to go spend upwards of $80 for an upper end model, figuring that within a year, someone would come out with a streaming box at a more affordable price with faster processors, and Amazon Fire stick was it. It's a great streamer (even at regular retail price), Android apps can be downloaded by APK or side loaded, and Kodi works like a charm on either (Kodi is possible with Roku, but it's a major hassle). Probably won't be going back to Roku streaming boxes for now, although I now own 2 TCL Roku TV's, and both TV's work just fine with either Amazon Fire TV or stick, and that pretty much covers all the bases for me as far as being extremely happy with streaming TV, and finally being totally happy with absolutely no TV cable or satellite bills any more.",4,183,positive,0.867743194103241,0.867743194103241,0.11002903431653976,0.022227732464671135,0.8455,4,2298,0,1
Not so bad if...,"First I will say that it was very easy to set up and get it working. It was very much plug and play. I couldn't ask for more in that department. Second of all, I like the voice search option and the remote. I used to watch Hulu & Netflix on my TV connected to my laptop, but I had to get up every time I wanted to pause something or watch something else.Next I will tell you that I did NOT like this product AT ALL in the very beginning. First of all, the menus and navigation are not user friendly. You can customize them a little bit, but not nearly enough. There's just a lot of unnecessary clutter all over the place. You can very easily get lost in menus and have NO idea how to get back to where you were. I finally realized that if you press the ''home'' button for a few seconds it will take you to a screen with JUST the apps you have installed...so you can by-pass all of the bs that Amazon thinks you want to see, but that you really don't. Second, out of the box, this is NOT a substitute for cable. None of the apps that Amazon has pre-installed or recommends give you any kind of free viewing options. If you subscribe to Prime, Netflix or Hulu you can set those up to watch whatever you want, but only if you have subscriptions. Not a huge surprise, but it's the same thing for apps like CBS, NBC, ABC, FOX, etc. Although those are FREE over-the-air broadcast channels, you can't watch hardly anything using those apps unless you have a cable subscription. What is the point of that then?!? Greedy much??? Yes, there are apps you can download with free TV and movies, but they are not new programs...they are 10+ years old. Another thing that's really annoying, is that you can't tell whether an app has free content until you've already downloaded it. I can't tell you how many apps I've downloaded only to have to uninstall right away because they require a subscription. Here's a hint, it's nearly ALL of them. In future versions the Fire would benefit from a filter that allowed you to just see the free vs. pay apps available.Anyway, all that being said, there are ways that you can get better TV and movies through the Fire stick. Just do a little online research... or ask the 15 year old next door to show you.",4,184,positive,0.9051085114479065,0.9051085114479065,0.07370931655168533,0.02118215523660183,0.8839,0,2233,0,1
Fire Stick wins over Roku Express and Apple TV,"I find this little device much better than buying a Roku Express stick or Apple TV and I own both. Here is a list of reason why the Fire TV stick is my preferred choice.1. This comes with Alexa Voice Remote. You can use this AI to search for movies or turn on and off your lights. The potential is endless with home automation. The Roku platform does not have access to voice assistant, unless you side load it, and Apple uses the selective AI SIRI. There are definitely more things compatible with Alexa than the Apple ecosystem.2. The Fire Stick lets you load a large number of apps and games, and runs them smoothly. It allows you to have Kodi and many other entertainment platform. Apple TV has less apps and games available, and you cannot load Kodi on it. Roku does allow you to install a large number of apps, but I find it is a bit laggy when playing games. The Fire Stick definitely is smoother than the Roku Express Stick.3. The Fire Stick comes with bluetooth. I like how the remote is bluetooth so you don't have to point it at the device when you use it. You can pair wireless headphone, bluetooth speaker, and even gaming controller to the Fire TV Stick. The Apple TV 4th gen has bluetooth, but Roku Express Stick does not.Final Verdict. Why 4 stars instead of 5? I wish they would add volume control on the remote or on the user interface. Something simple like that drives me nuts when i have to use a separate remote to adjust the volume. Some wireless bluetooth speakers don't even have remote, so I know there are many frustrated people out there over this volume control thing. You get more for your money, a lot more, when you go with the Fire TV Stick. This is an awesome device.Update: 04/25/2018After owning this device for quite some time, I still find it incredibly useful. Easy access and constant updates keeps this device competitive to similar devices in the market. However, as I download more apps and games to this device, it has gotten a bit slower. Youtube is no longer supported on this device, however you can get around that using silk browser or firefox. I do hope Amazon will update this device with a maintenance option to keep it running smoothly.",4,185,positive,0.9517673254013062,0.9517673254013062,0.044465117156505585,0.0037675865460187197,0.948,5,2189,0,1
Great except for lack of screen size calibration,"I own the 2015 version, 2016 (this version), and just purchased the 2017 4K version. This review is of the 2016 version.Background: I used my 2015 FireTV stick a great deal while travelling in 2016 for business and vacations. I used it in hotels in Kentucky and San Diego. (Couldn't quite get it to work in Japan as I recall, and don't recall if I used in Mexico.) However on one trip to Germany in late 2016 it wouldn't pick up the hotel wifi. My Surface tablet picked it up fine. (It must be said, however, that hotel & public wifi in Germany generally sucks, as I learned on later trips this year.)Having read that the newer 2016 version had better wifi antennae, I bought it on Black Friday 2016 (last year). This I can generally attest to...except again in Germany where the wifi sucks anyway. I think I did manage to use it in one hotel on one of my four trips there over the summer. Worked great in Mexico (except for geographic restrictions), and even in Kentucky. :-DI re-paired the older smaller non-voice remote with the newer Stick so it would be easier to pack and carry in a smaller case. And was able to do vice-versa with the newer remote and older Stick which I left at home.My only major complaint is that this version versus the old 2015 FireTV stick doesn't allow screen size calibration It basically just shows the arrows at the edges of the screen and says, &#34;Good luck, you're on your own with your TV.&#34; That absolutely sucks on older TV's which are still HD-capable but don't have all of the fine adjustment needed. It sucks even more for my intended purpose, use in hotels while traveling, as the TV's in hotels come in a wide variety, and many don't include the original remote.I just got the new 4k/UHD FireTV stick (square-shaped dongle) a month ago and they brought back the screen size calibration feature. I should think a simple firmware upgrade to the 2016 model would allow this feature to be reinstated. (From reading newer reviews it sounds like they haven't bothered to fix this.) Nevertheless I shall continue to travel with it and muddle through with my First World Problem.Other than that it's great. Makes me forget about my four-or-so Roku's.",4,186,neutral,0.7877795696258545,0.19022232294082642,0.7877795696258545,0.021998098120093346,0.1682,4,2191,0,0
Good but caution for customers with older TV's,"Update:Worked with Amazon Technical support on the issues I had. The Stick works on some of the TV systems and after working thru different scenarios we found my TV was the issue. I have a 10 year old Samsung 46 in. and it has been working fine. When using the stick it would freeze and sound stopped. Tried this on a Visio and another and did not have any issues. I was able to watch Prime movies, Dish Anywhere and no issues. Went to the Samsung site to try to get a firmware update on the TV that was not working (it supports it and shows you how in the manual) however Samsung did not have any upates available and never had. I am more disappointed on the Samsung than that of the fire stick. In conclusion you may want to try to confirm your old tv will work with the later technology or has updates available on the TV to avoid the issues I have had. Kudo's to Amazon tech support for all the help they gave me and the follow through. I've changed the rating since this will work on other systems but I have not been able to try on more than mentioned.(previously)Very disappointed on the TV stick freezing. I was waiting for Dish Anywhere to be availble as advertised (which it is now) but when we were watching anything that took more than 30 minutes it would freeze. Either the sound went dead or the TV froze. Only way to correct is to power off your TV, wait a minute, then power back on. When you are watching a movie or consumed in a show and it &#34;stops&#34; abruptly it is very frustrating. Other users think it is over heating and stopping (it does seem like that). Many were frustrated as was I.I was counting on this to use when on vacation and traveling however I think Amazon needs to look at this technology and the problems. It works but only for a short time. With Dish not available on the TV stick (which was advertised) and freezing, dropping sound I can't give this a good review. Amazon has been great at addressing any issues I have had and fixing them. I hope they either download a &#34;fix&#34; to fix the freezing or send me a new Fire TV Stick replacement when it performs as advertised and does not &#34;stop&#34; or freeze. I'm disappointed in amazon on this purchase.",4,187,neutral,0.7169162034988403,0.1969253569841385,0.7169162034988403,0.08615841716527939,0.1108,7,2206,0,0
Really love but a few problems...,"I purchased two for Christmas. One for me and one for my Mom.As far as the good things. You pretty much know them. It turns your old TV into a smart one. It is amazing all the little things Alexa can do. Coupled with a prime account you have a ton of entertainment from music to movies that can keep you busy for hours. I haven't turned my cable box back on yet lol.It's also super cool that I can take the stick and plug it in other TVs taking all of the devices content and my prime account with me.I am also interested in it's smart home capabilities and I'm going to invest in a few products to get started.Of course, there are issues. One major problem is that the sound can be inconsistent even across the same app such as the Prime Movies. This may be due to my older TV. Alexa also can't control the sound on my TV or my Mom's. Even worse for my Mom is that her other volume remote stopped working completely.Another major problem is the keyboard. I assumed, stupidly, that the microphone would also do speech to text in all search bars or inputs. Nope. And for a smart device to remind me of when I was a kid using the arrows to type my name into my black and white Gameboy… come on. That makes no sense. Luckily, it has an app for your phone where you can use the phones keyboard. Unluckily, I can't just use the remote that came with the device. Just really don't understand the lack of speech to text.My biggest issue though is it's zoom in vision assist which is incredibly clunky. My Mother doesn't have the best eyesight and the text is hard for her to read. It involves holding down the menu button zooming in and out with the fast forward and rewind and using the round buttons to pan the screen… all while continuing to hold down the menu button. Sometimes it's even hard for me to read small text. I wish you could just increase the text size.However, I still recommend it. Just wasn't as good for my Mother as I had hoped it would be. If the last two issues didn't exist I would have given it 5*. It's a great little device that continues to put a smile on both of our faces.",4,188,positive,0.9677296876907349,0.9677296876907349,0.02871246449649334,0.003557882271707058,0.9642,5,2095,0,1
Portable. Convenient. Reliable.  Can't ask for more.,"The Fire Stick was purchased because we wanted streaming media on the big TV in the family room - the Hulu app on the Smart TV crashes periodically, and nothing can be done to fix that. The Stick works perfectly - and we use the ethernet adapter for a faster, wired connection to the home network. The only issue I have with this is it doesn't update the watch lists with our media accounts. What that means is, we have to manually add the shows/movies we watch on services like Hulu because Hulu's watch list on the Fire Stick is empty, despite having many shows/movie on our watch list available on all our other internet-connected devices with the Hulu app. It's an odd thing that I've found no solution for. Shows we watch are updated on the Fire Stick. Go figure.I know some have reported problems with the ethernet adapter for this device and the best advice I can give is to set up the adapter with a static IP address so it doesn't change. Also be sure you use a good cat 6 cable as not all cables are created equal and cheap cables won't give you the performance of good cables.The Fire Stick is also great for travel. We take it along and connect it to the local internet service where ever we are and we have all our entertainment with us. It's far more convenient that way than trying to figure out local TV. We do have a battery pack that we sometimes have to use, depending on the TV we have where we stay, but that's not much of an issue. The battery pack will power this thing for a month. Beware of traveling internationally, because the services will change or may not work at all, depending on what country you're in. Sometimes a VPN can help, but streaming services are pretty good at detecting VPN networks.The user interface is easy to navigate and overall it's easy to use. The unit doesn't crash, freeze or give us any other problems, so that's a big plus. I hate an operating system that isn't stable (and I use Windows!).Overall, I like the portability, the convenience and the reliability of the Fire Stick.",4,189,neutral,0.4327038824558258,0.1353088766336441,0.4327038824558258,0.4319872260093689,-0.2967,4,2034,0,0
"It's good overall, but the performance should be better","Pros:-More affordable than it's counterpart (60 bucks cheaper)-The Alexa integration is useful, especially for finding and playing content-For everyone who has Prime, Prime Video is integrated into the UI, making it easy to get to that content as going to the Movies tab or the TV Shows tab-The content from the streaming apps is also integrated into the UI, thanks to the More Ways To Watch button when you look at content through the Movies tab or the TV Shows tab-It's so small that you can put it in your pocket, along with the power cord and plugging it up in a hotel or dorm is as simple as plugging the stick into a TV, plugging the power cord in the socket, and connecting to the Wi-Fi when it turns on-Remote is easy to use and controls are easy to pick up, as the remote has only 7 buttons with common controls that aren't different from other many other streaming media players and remotes-It supports HDMI CEC, which means that when connected to a compatible TV, you can turn on the TV or switch the TV input to the Fire TV Stick just by pressing a button on it's remote and control it with your TV's remote-It allows you to get casual games, such as Crossy Road and Pac-Man, and more high-end games such as Asphalt 8: Airborne-Nice and intuitive UI overallCons:-Slow, lags in certain tasks such as scrolling around for content-This might not be a common problem, but unfortunately, my remote only works with the batteries that came with it (AmazonBasics)-Drops frames, mainly when scrolling through AutoPlay content and TV guides (DIRECTV Now)-The port to plug in the power cord on the stick is in the middle (Roku Streaming Sticks have it on the end, which is a better place to put itBottom Line: The Amazon Fire TV Stick is a great device, considering it has the same useful features as it's larger, more expensive counterpart, such as Alexa integration and a beautifully simple UI, in such a small and cheap package. The only thing it could use is a boost in performance.",4,190,positive,0.892365038394928,0.892365038394928,0.10287056118249893,0.004764375276863575,0.8876,4,1987,0,1
Some Problems,"***UPDATE***Ok, so after a couple months... started to have some issues with the stick not turning on and changing channels or apps. Then the Fire Stick would not recognize our wi-fi for several days even though nothing had changed and the wi-fi was working and connecting to other devices. Called Amazon support and they only recommended resetting and powering down the device which I had already done multiple time including completely disconnecting it from power source over night. Even did a complete factory reset, whiched helped temporarily but after spending at least an hour reinstalling all the channels I had already downloaded and logging into each and every one of them, it started to act up again. Nothing helped! It would occasionally connect at random but then video was very choppy and would seem very slow. If you tried to scroll through the different apps, it was soooo slow that it would not scroll until about 30seconds to a minute later and speed through the buttons you pressed the minute before trying to catch up. Again called Amazon and they told me to reset and power down, maybe I have too many devices hooked up t the wifi which was only my two cell phone and nothing else so that wasn't the problem.So, I stopped using it for a couple weeks and thought I'd try it again. I did nothing different this time except turn it on and guess what?! It works!!! I have no idea what happened but I'm glad it's working. It sometimes is very slow just searching for apps but it does the job well.For this reason I give it a 4Absolutely love the Amazing Amazon Fire stick! This was the best investment ever!!! Kodie works perfect with this too! Steaming never was this easy before. I have now convinced at least 6 of m friends to get it and they have recruited at least 3 friends and family members too get one or two. I'm definitely getting two more; one for the bed room, and the other for the bonus room. This might actually replace our cable because you have all the channels and shows available at your fingertips!",4,191,negative,0.7601227164268494,0.013230226002633572,0.22664706408977509,0.7601227164268494,-0.7469,7,2034,1,0
May be older model.,"This Fire Stick was a gift from my sister from two years ago. I didn't know how to use it or really have a need for it at the time. I recently cut the cord on satellite TV and needed a streaming device to use, so I hooked it up. That part was VERY simple and it came right on and controlled and streamed my 4 tuner DVR pretty well. I do have quite a bit of buffering at times and don't know for sure whether that's an internet speed issue or whether perhaps a new Fire Stick might work better. After only using the remote for about a month, the batteries were getting sluggish. That surprised me. But they were also the two-year-old batteries that came with it. My main issue is the other programs and apps you're supposed to be able to use with it, It encourages you to browse a new app, like ESPN. So I do and immediately it asks me to sign up so that it can start billing me when my two weeks free trial is over. So I wasn't going to use it at all. I finally did click on the Australian Open once to try to watch it, but it didn't come on. Since then I tried once to watch a Pacers game and up popped a list of service providers asking me which one I was using. I was only using Fire Stick and that wasn't listed. So I gave up again. That's my main frustration. There is absolutely NO explanation of how these services work billing-wise. For example, can I use sling and buy only access to all Pacers games for $18 or do I have to buy the NBA League Pass for about $55 and hope I get some Pacers or add the $18 to the $55 or so to see my Pacers. If so, I may as well go back to satellite except the company I was using took my Pacers away from me. That's why I cut the cord. So yes, I'm totally frustrated about not knowing what MIGHT be available to me and being asked questions that I don't understand when I DO try to use ANY of them. So far I have not actually used ANY of these but it shows that I purchased 4 or 5 of them. SO I expect one day I'm going to get this HUGE bill for all this stuff I haven't even been able to use.",4,192,neutral,0.5548820495605469,0.34808146953582764,0.5548820495605469,0.09703654795885086,0.251,0,2035,0,0
Renewed Opinion of Fire Stick with Alexa,"Earlier I wrote a review with a rati n of (2) stars . I since have taken the time to explore the Fire Stick with Alexa Voice to a greater degree than earlier . I still believe it is similar to other formats , such as the Sony AppleTV unit , with exceptions . One exception is that I find it to be more user friendly , another is that what you do chose to purchase can be paid through your Amazon Prime Account , another being with the Prime Acc. membership you have axcess to all the free video offered through Prime with no extra membership fees .I do however still feel all these formats offer the similar programing in their free listings , things you can find most anywhere or the many offerings of little to no value to most viewers . Anything new or of mass desire will most always cost you additional charges to view . I feel this is the smoke and mirror aspect used by all the formats available to get that additional fee from the viewers . I can't help but be skeptical and disapointed with this practice .I however have now tried the Alexa feature of the Fire Stick with Alexa and find it to offer a less involved action related to finding things of interest or particular programs you may be searching for . It also will offer info. regarding what options are required to view the program either through a pay to use format or the fee necessary to view through Fire Stick . Regardless I now feel the Fire Stick offers a more user friendly format than most making available programing easier to find and how to be obtained if desired .As of this time I have found no major failings in the operation of Fire Stick or the Alexa option if used . None of the available gave been found to be without some glitch or fault , but with the Prime Acc. and addition of the Fire Stick I feel it may be a format to consider if looking for a way to break away from the way to expensive offerings of cable and satalite viewing . I wiuld recomend to simeone seeking that option .",4,193,positive,0.7382987141609192,0.7382987141609192,0.2572038173675537,0.0044975001364946365,0.7338,6,1973,0,1
Good for what it does,"So, I had heard so much about the Amazon Fire TV Stick. All of my friends and colleagues are always talking about using one with Kodi to watch sports and to not pay cable. I bought one back on the Christmas sales just to see what all the fuss was about. First problem, I have cable. I also have a Xbox One and a PS4. The television I watch the most is a Samsung smart television (2017 edition) and it has the good smart software on it unlike my other LG television. I can get my cable company's app on my Samsung and it does everything the Fire TV does. I really don't watch much television and what I do watch is easily found online like The Walking Dead on the AMC website. But I wasn't giving up on the Fire TV.I hooked it up to my mom's television. Her television is a LG smart but the smart software is useless on it. The Fire TV turned it into a very good smart television and she can finally use Amazon Video in her room. She also likes the voice remote. That's pretty good but I just don't see the huge advantage of having it. The first thing mom ran into was she couldn't use it with her DVR and I would say 90% of what she watches is through the DVR. I do think if you use Kodi and whatever other streaming services there are, it would be better and make it a great value. I personally think it works better than the Roku but I'm sure there's something the Roku does better. I just don't know what it is. It also works better than the PS4 and XB1. The question for me is if you have a video game system, I think the Xbox 360 even does it, would it be worth adding another steaming device? I think it is good for the situation like with my mom's television but unless you're using Kodi, I don't know that it adds that much unless you have no other streaming devices. I was going to rate it a 3 but the voice remote, for older people, for anyone who watches television in the dark, is a nice feature at this price so I bumped it up to a 4.",4,194,neutral,0.5685988068580627,0.3475489914417267,0.5685988068580627,0.08385219424962997,0.2637,0,1947,0,0
"Better Than Most Device, Except for One Part","First, let me say I was skeptical when I got my Fire Stick. I have a smart TV, two consoles, a laptop and a smart Blu-Ray. What could a Fire Stick do that those devices could not? Answer: Stream better. The quality is amazing, usually when I paused on the other devices there was a 5 to 30 second period a buffering after I hit play. Not so on the Fire Stick. This thing runs great. It has the option for phone games that is fun and TV apps I have on my phone that are easier to use.When I got it I told the person who bought it for me I didn't want to jailbreak it. I, unlike many others, know this is illegal and will void my warranty with Amazon. Many people are putting Kodi on this device to get stuff without having to pay for it. To me this is stealing. To acquire property without paying for it. It turns out the copyright board agrees. If you are caught with copyright infringement you are not just punished for the movie, but each piece of music in the movie. The penalty for copyright infringement is between 5 years in prison and $250,000 to 10 years in prison and $2,000,000 per offense. So, if a movie has 10 songs in it that is 11 offenses. Makes the $8 a month seem more palette-able.The only reason I didn't give it five stars is because it doesn't work with my Echo. I would love to tell Alexa to pause movie or play a certain movie on my Fire Stick without activating the remote. I don't understand how they could put the Alexa app in the remote and not tie it to the Echo. Google Chromecast and the Home/mini allow you to do this. If you own a Vizio with Chromecast built it you can control the TV with the Google Smart home devices. Apple's new device lets you activate apps on your Apple devices from their Smart home device. It makes sense that Amazon, who introduced the first mass market Smart home device, to have this as an available feature. Maybe in a patch or new design.",4,195,positive,0.7176546454429626,0.7176546454429626,0.24188180267810822,0.04046352580189705,0.6772,4,1901,0,1
Very good......but not quite 5 stars..........,"I bought this because my 5 year old smart TV stopped working with You Tube. I got a message on my screen saying they were not going to support my TV after June 30, 2017. The fire stick solved that problem. Installation and making it operational were relatively easy. The performance of the fire stick was a big improvement over my smart TV. There is very little buffering of any video and the motion is smooth. HD picture quality is very good.I don't like that voice commands from the remote do not work to navigate within non-Amazon apps, at least not in You Tube. Also, I tried and failed to re-order one of my previous Amazon orders using Alexa, (there was a 10 dollar credit for doing this on, &#34;prime day&#34;). The item placed in my cart was almost twice as expensive as the same item previously ordered, and I was told by Alexa the order could not be completed because of a shipping address problem. I never had a problem ordering with the same information from the Amazon website. I tried to get help from Amazon on-line but I could not find the quick call-back option I had used in the past. I think I will skip the &#34;convenience&#34; of voice re-ordering with Alexa and carefully check-out what I am re-ordering and the cost from within my Amazon account. To much chance of ordering the wrong thing or paying to much.Also, I asked Alexa for a &#34;pet joke&#34; and she said &#34;What is black and white and red all over&#34;........her answer was, &#34;an educated penguin&#34;. I'm pretty sure the correct answer is, &#34;an embarrassed penguin&#34;. LOLI give it 4 stars because it is very good for You Tube and I really enjoy watching and listening to the many music videos and concerts available. I also watched a free prime movie and it worked great for that. Otherwise, there are a few glitches which prevent a 5 star rating. Maybe some of that is my fault.",4,196,negative,0.44694265723228455,0.1428470015525818,0.41021037101745605,0.44694265723228455,-0.3041,2,1880,1,0
SERIOUS Flaw for use on older TV's! Please read!,"I really love the Amazon Firestick but they made a *serious* error when they disabled the TV calibration within the display settings. Older generation firesticks allow you to adjust your TV to fix overscan issues.If you go to TV Calibration now, the Firestick simply tells you to fix this issue with your TV's own settings.So this means that the sides of your picture will be cropped off unless you are able to adjust this.The problem is many perfectly capable OLDER TVs do not have any overscan adjustment setting.... There is no way to disable default overscan on my Sony 2007 46“ set. I also have another smaller 37“ Sharp TV from around that time that also has no capability to do this.All that needs to be done to fix this issue is a simple software update. The older LESS technically advanced sticks can obviously do this, so why can't the new ones? Amazon doesn't seem to listen to anyone about this. It's like they purposely crippled an important feature.Someone will say ""get a new TV' but why would I want to do that? The whole point of the Fire Stick is to add a cheap streaming capability to older TV sets!HOWEVERIf you have this problem, there's indeed a hackish workaround but you need to be able to issue ADB commands to your device.The instructions are here.https://tech.zsoldier.com/2017/09/misc-fire-tv-stick-2-screen-cut-off-no.html?m=1It's best to enter the TV Calibration area where you can instantly see the adjustments because it's trial and error.The settings that worked for me on a 2007 Sony were ` wm overscan 45,25,45,25 `This doesn't work with every app (nor the Main Menu) but with Kodi ...the app itself has internal adjustments.To test it in *Netflix*, search for ""Test Patterns"" and look at the bottom circles.",4,197,negative,0.5887426733970642,0.10607293993234634,0.30518433451652527,0.5887426733970642,-0.4827,4,1743,1,0
"A great product, unlike Amazon's delivery service","I have been trying to stream content from my Blu-ray device and not enjoying the experience. I finally ordered the Fire TV Stick and all of my streaming issues are gone. Its compact, easy to set up, and the voice command will be a big improvement on my old device. I will have a little bit of a learning curve in searching for content. The price was great too.All that being said, I have been having a terrible time getting my package. I place my order and on the promised delivery day I followed delivery tracking.Amazon said that the package was delivered to a ""resident"" at my home. When I arrived home, no package. My roommate who had been home all day said that nothing was delivered.I called customer service to complain and was promised that another unit would be shipped the next day. They apologized but had no explanation. On the promised day, exactly the same thing happened. Amazon had said they delivered, and they had not.Another call to customer service, and by this time I was really not happy. I was forwarded to an Amazon Logistics rep, so I was able to repeat my experience a third time. This was a frustrating experience since the logistics rep was saying that according to their system, the package had been delivered to the correct address on both occasions. Of course, this was not true. At that point, the logistics rep told me that they would not send a third unit until some sort of investigation was done.I admit, I lost it at that point.At any rate, one of my neighbors who actually received the package brought it to me.The only reason I've put in the time to write this because its not an isolated experience for me. As a Prime member, I want to have my package delivered as promised, and all to often it isn't. Has anyone else experienced delivery issues?",4,198,negative,0.3509829640388489,0.31689757108688354,0.33211949467658997,0.3509829640388489,-0.0341,2,1786,1,0
There's negatives but the positives far outweigh,"I decided to try the fire stick since Spectrum has encrypted all its cables and now we have to have a box for every TV that will eventually cost $7 a month. I'm not doing that. I will tell you this about the fire stick, when it works well, it works really well. However depending on your internet connection it will test your patience. There's one huge downfall to the fire stick that has made me order a Roku, you cannot get the Spectrum TV app on it. Back to the fire stick, channel surfing is really a thing of the past. You cannot just flip from channel to channel. You have to navigate through several menus to get to any channel. Then you have to wait for each channel that you choose to load. Sometimes the channels load quickly and sometimes it takes them a very long time and sometimes you actually have to restart through the menu system to get a channel to load. Also, this system works best if you already have a cable TV provider because your fire stick and access to all these channels will link to your provider. I'm not sure you would be able to get any live TV whatsoever without a provider to link to. I'm not even sure you would be able to link to your provider if you don't have a smartphone or a computer. Now with all that gloom-and-doom said, there are some big pluses to having the fire stick. There is a lot of stuff to watch. A lot! I doubt anyone would even get through it all in their lifetime. Tons of free movies, TV shows, internet shows, etc, etc. And when your fire stick is working properly, the picture is definitely high-definition even on the lower end Fire Sticks. I especially enjoy watching episodes of shows on the Food Network that they do not air anymore. And the best part about the whole thing is that you do not need your cable providers cable sticking in the back of your TV to get any TV picture or TV shows.",4,199,negative,0.4951472878456116,0.10673259943723679,0.39812010526657104,0.4951472878456116,-0.3884,0,1856,1,0
Comprehensive list of useful commands: Basic commands Ask for help,"Comprehensive list of useful commands:Basic commandsAsk for help: &#34;Alexa, help.&#34;Mute or unmute: &#34;Alexa, mute&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, unmute.&#34;Stop or pause: &#34;Alexa, stop&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, shut up.&#34;Change volume: &#34;Alexa, set volume to 5,&#34; &#34;Alexa, louder&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, turn up/down the volume.&#34;Media controlsPlay music: &#34;Alexa, play some music.&#34;Queue specific song or artist: &#34;Alexa, play music by [artist].&#34;Play Spotify music: &#34;Alexa, play [playlist] on Spotify.&#34;Play Pandora station: &#34;Alexa, play [artist] station on Pandora.&#34;Play a radio station: &#34;Alexa, play [radio station] on TuneIn.&#34;Play an audiobook: &#34;Alexa, play [title] on Audible,&#34; &#34;Alexa, read [title]&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, play the book, [title].&#34;Resume the last played audiobook: &#34;Alexa, resume my book.&#34;Skip audiobook chapters: &#34;Alexa, next chapter&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, previous chapter.&#34;Listen to Alexa read you a Kindle book: &#34;Alexa, read me my Kindle book.&#34;Set a sleep timer: &#34;Alexa set a sleep timer for 45 minutes&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, stop playing in 45 minutes.&#34;Song information: &#34;Alexa, what's playing?&#34;Music controls: &#34;Alexa, play&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, next.&#34;Restart song: &#34;Alexa, restart.&#34;Add a song to your Prime Music library: &#34;Alexa, add this song.&#34;Like or dislike a song on Pandora and iHeartRadio: &#34;Alexa, I like this song&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, thumbs down.&#34;Time and dateSet an alarm: &#34;Alexa, set an alarm for 7 a.m.&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, wake me up at 7 in the morning.&#34;Set a repeating alarm: &#34;Alexa, set a repeating alarm for weekdays at 7 a.m.&#34;Set a timer: &#34;Alexa, set a timer for 15 minutes.&#34;Set multiple timers: &#34;Alexa, set a second timer for 5 minutes.&#34;Check timer status: &#34;Alexa, how much time is left on my timer?&#34;Ask the time: &#34;Alexa, what time is it?&#34;Ask the date: &#34;Alexa, what's the date?&#34;Ask when the next alarm is: &#34;Alexa, when's my next alarm?&#34;Cancel an alarm: &#34;Alexa, cancel my alarm for 2 p.m.&#34;Snooze alarm: &#34;Alexa, snooze.&#34;Check dates: &#34;Alexa, when is [holiday] this year?&#34;To-do and shopping listsAdd task to to-do list: &#34;Alexa, add 'go to the grocery store' to my to-do list&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, I need to make an appointment with the doctor.&#34;Create a new to-do item: &#34;Alexa, create a to-do.&#34;Check calendar events: &#34;Alexa, what's on my calendar for tomorrow?&#34;Add an event to a calendar: &#34;Alexa, add [event] to my calendar for [day] at [time]&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, add an event to my calendar.&#34;Create a shopping list: &#34;Alexa, add eggs to my shopping list&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, I need to buy laundry detergent.&#34;Check your shopping list: &#34;Alexa, what's on my shopping list?&#34;News and weatherAsk for your Flash Briefing: &#34;Alexa, what's my Flash Briefing?&#34;Check headlines: &#34;Alexa, what's in the news?&#34;Check weather: &#34;Alexa, what's the weather like?&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, will it rain today?&#34; or even &#34;Alexa, will I need an umbrella today?&#34;Get a weather forecast: &#34;Alexa, what's the weather going to be like this weekend?Get traffic information: &#34;Alexa, what's my commute look like?&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, what's traffic like?&#34;Entertainment and foodFind movies in nearby theaters: &#34;Alexa, what movies are playing?&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, what action movies are playing tonight?&#34;Get information on movies playing: &#34;Alexa, tell me about the movie [title].&#34;Discover nearby restaurants: &#34;Alexa, find me a nearby pizza restaurant.&#34;Get operating hours or a phone number for local businesses: &#34;Alexa, find the address for Bank of America&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, find business hours for Harris Teeter.&#34;Get IMDb rating: &#34;Alexa, what is the IMDb rating for [movie or TV show]?&#34;Get casting for a movie or show: &#34;Alexa, who plays in [movie or TV show]?&#34;Find out who an actor is: &#34;Alexa, who plays [character] in [movie or TV show]?&#34;Find an actor's latest work: &#34;Alexa, what is [actor]'s latest movie?&#34;Find out who sings a particular song: &#34;Who sings the song [title]?&#34;Get the names of band members: &#34;Who is in the band [name]?&#34;Get album information: &#34;What year did [band] release [song or album]?&#34;Find popular music from an artist: &#34;Alexa, what's popular from [artist]?&#34;Sample music from an artist: &#34;Alexa, sample songs by [artist].&#34;Find a particular album or song: &#34;Alexa, find [song or album] by [artist].&#34;MathConvert units: &#34;Alexa, how many [units] are in [units]?&#34;Convert units: &#34;Alexa, how many [units] are in 2 [units]?&#34;Basic math: &#34;Alexa, what's 5 plus 7?&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, what's 56 times 33?&#34;Advanced math: &#34;Alexa, 70 factorial.&#34; (Warning: Alexa will list numbers you didn't know existed for about a minute.)Definitions and spellingGet the definition of a word: &#34;Alexa, what's the definition of [word]?&#34;Get the spelling of a word: &#34;Alexa, how do you spell [word]?&#34;SportsCheck the results of a finished game: &#34;Alexa, what was the score of the [team] game?&#34;Ask if a team won: &#34;Alexa, did the [team] win?&#34;Ask when the next game is scheduled: &#34;Alexa, when do the [team] play next?&#34;Find out the results of your favorite teams: &#34;Alexa, give me my Sports Update.&#34;PurchasingReorder essentials from Amazon: &#34;Alexa, buy more deodorant&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, reorder deodorant.&#34;Track packages from Amazon: &#34;Alexa, where's my stuff?&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, track my order.&#34;Order an Amazon Alexa device: &#34;Alexa, order an Echo,&#34; &#34;Alexa, order an Echo Dot,&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, order an Amazon Tap.&#34;Add an item to your cart: &#34;Alexa, add garbage bags to my cart.&#34;Order an Uber or Lyft with their skills: &#34;Alexa, ask Uber to request a ride&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, ask Lyft for a ride.&#34;While listening to music in Amazon Music: &#34;Alexa, buy this song&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, buy this album.&#34;Find new music to purchase: &#34;Alexa, shop for new music by [artist].&#34;Purchase a song or album from an artist: &#34;Alexa, buy [song or album] by [artist].&#34;VoicecastSend current listening to a Fire tablet: &#34;Alexa, send that to my Fire tablet.&#34;Send to a different profile's Fire tablet: &#34;Alexa, show this on [name]'s Fire tablet.&#34;Smart homeAlexa can integrate with loads of smart home platforms, such as SmartThings, Wink, Insteon, Lutron, Belkin WeMo, Philips Hue and many more. Some require you to enable skills, some don't. Here are some of the varieties of commands you can use, although there are dozens moreTurn lights on or off: &#34;Alexa, turn on the lights&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, turn off the living room lights.&#34;Dim the lights: &#34;Alexa, dim the lights to 50 percent.&#34;Adjust temperature: &#34;Alexa, raise the temperature 1 degree.&#34;Set temperature: &#34;Alexa, set the temperature to 72.&#34;Lock your doors: &#34;Alexa, lock my back door.&#34;Close your garage door: &#34;Alexa, ask Garageio to close my garage.&#34;Discover smart home devices: &#34;Alexa, discover my devices.&#34;Pair a Bluetooth device: &#34;Alexa, pair&#34; or, &#34;Alexa, Bluetooth.&#34;Connect to a Bluetooth device: &#34;Alexa, connect to my phone.&#34;Disconnect from a Bluetooth device: &#34;Alexa, disconnect from my phone.&#34;Use IFTTT recipes: &#34;Alexa, trigger [IFTTT recipe].&#34;Profiles and user accountsSwitch profiles: &#34;Alexa, switch accounts.&#34;Check which profile is active: &#34;Alexa, which profile is this?&#34;SkillsEnable skills: &#34;Alexa, enable Jeopardy!&#34;Disable skills: &#34;Alexa, disable Domino's.&#34;SearchGet Wikipedia information: &#34;Alexa, Wikipedia: [subject].&#34;Tell Alexa to continue reading a Wikipedia entry: &#34;Alexa, tell me more.&#34;Ask a general question: &#34;Alexa, how tall is [person or object's name]?&#34;Ask a general question: &#34;Alexa, how many people live in America?&#34;Get a &#34;Game of Thrones&#34; quote: &#34;Alexa, give me a 'Game of Thrones' quote.&#34;Easter eggsAlexa comes chock-full of Easter eggs and jokes -- the list is long. We covered the strange world of Alexa Easter eggs recently, noting some of the more popular or prominent commands that prompt a snarky or humorous response.&#34;Alexa, tell me a joke.&#34;&#34;Alexa, tell me a fact.&#34;&#34;Alexa, beam me up.&#34;&#34;Alexa, set phasers to kill.&#34;&#34;Alexa. Tea. Earl Grey. Hot.&#34;&#34;Alexa, my name is Inigo Montoya.&#34;&#34;Alexa, I want the truth.&#34;&#34;Alexa, party on, Wayne.&#34;&#34;Alexa, show me the money.&#34;&#34;Alexa, what's the first (or second) rule of Fight Club?&#34;&#34;Alexa, surely you can't be serious.&#34;&#34;Alexa, are you SkyNet?&#34;&#34;Alexa, party time!&#34;&#34;Alexa, open the pod bay doors.&#34;&#34;Alexa, when am I going to die?&#34;&#34;Alexa, what is your quest?&#34;&#34;Alexa, nice to see you, to see you...&#34;&#34;Alexa, don't mention the war.&#34;&#34;Alexa, this is a dead parrot.&#34;&#34;Alexa, what is your cunning plan?&#34;",5,200,neutral,0.7843620181083679,0.1549198031425476,0.7843620181083679,0.060718171298503876,0.0942,1,9193,0,0
Best gift my parents have ever received (other than me...and MAYBE my sister. Maybe.),"I gave this to my parents as a gift, as they have never had cable, have never heard of streaming video, still use dial-up internet (crazy noise & all!), & only ever watch movies (aka VHS' & DVDs) from the local library.They're really quite adorable—after 36 yrs of marriage, they've become so much like the other they could be mistaken as twins (I mean, aside from physical features, of course...Dad is balding & mom is all silver, like the moon & the stars, those 2!).Imagine my genuine surprise & delight when they each bought their first cell phones probably only 3 years ago. I wanted to have a party to celebrate, but my sister wisely suggested that we observe them for a while first. And so we did. Phone calls began to arrive at weird times of the day, voice mail messages from mom would come in while she took a bathroom break & call to say she loved me. I know, it was sweet. But the bathroom? Cmon, Mom, that's so unsanitary! Also could she just not do that with a main land line??But that wasn't bad, not even a thought any longer, when the texting began. Jere is my first text from her: &#34;Dear Dautr. Txtng is hrd. Lb u. From mom.&#34;I called her & taught her how to have a normal text convo & even taught her some short phrases like LOL (she originally thought this meant Love Or Leave & was confused after many well-meaning emails, texts, etc., from her own friends & colleagues). She still uses TTYL & TTFN more than anyone I know & no longer signs her name, and so once she could handle those things, I figured she was really ready for something more challenging. My dad also was ready; sneaky him had KNOWN how to text for a long time bc of a former work phone, but refused to do so until I caught him! I text with him all the time now. He might hate it. Poor guy. LOL 😂So after the 1st year, instead of a party, I tried to convince them to each try smart phones instead. This idea was a total dud, however, as my mom couldn't figure out how to type. She complained there was no proper &#34;1-2-3&#34; keypad with the abc's on them —there was only QWERTY—and so I tossed that idea (for now). Since they still could go a few more years w/ their simple phones, I went a completely different route this time.And then it struck me...The all-new 🔥Fire TV stick! My parents upgraded last year from their analog tv to a flat screen w/ an antenna (it's crazy how many changes are happening—all at once!) w/ an HDMI output (Dad: &#34;what the heck is HDMI?&#34; Me: oh Daddy...).So after years and years and even more years of hearing (& even enduring) old reruns of &#34;Batman&#34;, &#34;the Lawrence Welk Show&#34; & soap operas which are surprisingly still popular...I preordered the Fire TV Stick for my parents. I figured the worst that could happen is that they hate it, & I got to keep it or could re-gift it to someone who truly appreciates it! Ha!When I gifted it to them, my mom, who has actually heard of things like Amazon, Netflix & PlayStation (likely bc of me, in all fairness), asked me &#34;but it can't possibly do anything...can it?&#34;My Dad reassuringly patted her arm & said, &#34;Don't worry, honey, if we can't figure it out, we have our own tech support right here!&#34; At this, they both looked at me expectantly.I am a big proponent of teaching a person to fish instead of feeding him 1 fish & having him come back day after day for more. I'm also an introvert & had already expended my energy for the day, so was ready to get home to my own cozy couch & tv for a little &#34;Downton&#34;.And so, I handed my Dad a card (it was his bday🎁, too) w/full instructions for set up & how to use it. I gave them their own username & password (so they don't judge me for my own somewhat &#34;sleazy&#34; selection of movies—anything rated above PG is often too offensive for my parents' beautiful brains!!) & a sheet of instructions on how to get started. I had already put in several movies into the &#34;my Watch List&#34; section, so they wouldn't wander off too much & get mad at me for gifting them smut if they happened to come across anything more sinister than &#34;the Andy Griffith Show&#34; or &#34;I Love Lucy&#34;.I threw in some movies my dad will love (lots of good ole westerns), & movies that my mom will watch w/ happy tears, at the end of which she will thank Jesus for bringing such a great daughter (me, among others) into this world.I even threw in some videos for my incredible grandmother who supposedly hates watching tv...except these particular shows are about her home country of Greece 🇬🇷 & they have proven to be hits w/both her & her day sitter; I've been told it's relaxing & she begins to remember & share some of the old stories...stories I've heard all of my life & know almost as well as I know myself, but stories she has been forgetting lately bc of the dreadful disease of Alzheimer's. (BTW, support your local Alzheimer's chapter or go visit a nursing home & spend some time w/ older, wiser ppl who will let you leave feeling all warm & cozy & thankful inside—both bc you did a good thing & bc that person made your day better than you made theirs.)So. What do I think about the 🔥Fire TV stick🔥? I think that, other than my parents' most major milestones in life, including my birth (obviously), it is a massively wonderful gift that they have loved & will continue to enjoy for many (many) years to come. Because, ya know, as my parents would say, if it works, why even change it???",5,201,positive,0.6360165476799011,0.6360165476799011,0.32711753249168396,0.0368659608066082,0.5992,7,5456,0,1
Busunlimited Reviews the Fire TV Stick,"Review of the Amazon Fire TV StickSince this review is so positive, let me start by saying that I paid “full price” (maybe there was a discount for prime pre-orders) for this product and I am not affiliated with Amazon.SUMMARYIf you are wondering if you should buy the new fire stick, if you are an Amazon Prime customer, the answer is most likely YES. If Amazon is still offering this product for $40, “close your eyes and buy it.” That is, of course, unless you own a very equivalent product like Amazon Fire TV with the audio remote. I own two early version Roku’s and wondered about the wisdom of buying a product that does about the same thing. I do not wonder any more.SETUPAlmost no setup. You plug in the power and plug the Firestick into you HDMI port and place batteries in the remote and it is going. I am an Amazon Prime member and I really like the fact that your account information is already there. You will be able to instantly see you video libraries and watch lists. I also found that my pictures and videos taken with the Amazon Fire were available.SURPRISESI expected to get a new audio interface to the “TV box” and a better interface to Playstation VUE (the ROKU interface does not have many of the features of the Firestick interface). However, there were some unexpected pleasant surprises.The music interface was a wow! I have Amazon prime but not Unlimited Music. If you are a prime member what you get is amazing. Without the unlimited music service you will have a ton of music. I have a “regular” music library that I purchased, and as a prime member I have the prime collection. With Alexa I can voice search over the two Amazon music services (regular Amazon music, and Amazon prime music). The amount of music and “stations” is not unlimited, but it will almost seem that it is. I can ask for a particular song (“play shout”, a type of music (play Jazz) or you can just say “play music” and let Alexa decide. You can even give Alexa the words and she can find the song. If you are a classical music fan this is a field day, since many “complete works” are available for free to you in the prime collection or for as little as 99 cents if you pay the one-time charge for the music.Alexa, was also a surprise. I expected that I would be able to go to modules using voice commands and I can (go to Playstation VUE). It is not very surprising that you can search for Amazon movies and TV via voice control (this takes some practice for more advanced searches). But, I did not realize that you get much more from Alexa. While you cannot do all of the thing that you would be able to do with Echo or Echo Dot, you can do a lot. You can ask Alexa for: A weather report, a stock market report, your customized news briefing, your Amazon order status, what movies are in local theaters, make an addition to your todo list, a list of a particular type of local restaurants, and much more ( notice what happens if you ask Alexa if she knows your name). Alexa can also read a book for you and order supplies for you (via Amazon of course).Alexa has excellent voice recognition. It is the best I have ever used. You can almost forget that ALEXA is not really human, and say almost anything reasonable and most of the time it will come out OK. It does not have to be initially trained and another human can use it without any additional setup. Yes, it does sometimes get things wrong, but this happen far less than I would expect for a total hardware/software cost of less than $40.Alexa, worked well with two people using the voice interface (one male, one female). No special voice training for Alexa was required.INTERFACE with PLAYSTATION VUENow for the bad part. There is a delay when you use Playstation VUE with the Amazon Fire Stick. This is confusing when you are learning to use the Fire Stick and Playstation because you may think that nothing is happening because you did not press “ENTER” hard enough or you entered a command incorrectly, but the only thing that was wrong was the unexpected delay. After I learned to expect the delay, I found it to be only slightly annoying and not a show stopper. However, if you plan to use Playstation VUE and do not feel that you could live with a delay, you might consider Amazon Fire TV (not the Fire Stick) which I am told is faster (but I have not personally verified that it is).The Playstation VUE interface on the Amazon Fire Stick is superior to the one I have with my older ROKU. The Fire Stick interface has advanced selection features that lets you select by category, genre, age rating, channels, popularity, expiration date and content length. The interface also has a programming guide that shows what is playing by date and time. My initial reason for considering buying the Fire Stick was to get the superior interface.INTERFACE with AT&T Directv NOWWorks fine with AT&T Directv NOW. None of the slowness found with Playstation VUE was seen when I used Directv NOW.Multiple Firesticks In One HouseholdI got a second Firestick free with AT&T Directv NOW. I was concerned that having two remotes close together would interfere with each other. I should not have been. Each Firestick seeks and links to its remote. You can bring the “wrong” remote right next the wrong Firestick and it will not respond, but the right one will if it is nearby.",5,202,positive,0.6191802620887756,0.6191802620887756,0.35541921854019165,0.025400487706065178,0.5938,5,5327,0,1
Almost nothing but smiles over my purchase,"Just got on the streaming device bandwagon. I've been using my desktop PC to stream for years now, but sometimes I'd rather not be sitting at my PC battlestation and watching content on the TV in my study so I figured I'd give this a try in order to be able to easily access the same Prime video content on my living room television or even occasionally be able to watch on my study tv while somebody else watches different programming in the living room.Well, I already knew it wasn't going to work well with the router I had, which was a couple years old and was a single user in/out model and decided to go with a Phicomm K3C AC 1900 MU-MIMO Dual Band Wi-Fi Gigabit Router that has a multi core Intel SOC (System ON chip processor) which allows multiple in and out signals simultaneously without having to deal with the wait-go-wait-go signal technology used by most routers. Multiple user MU-MIMO is the key, especially if there are more than one device likely to be accessing internet content at the same time. SO I got a great deal on that router to go with the Fire TV stick and I'm very glad I did.Together, they work flawlessly. Just to verify that many of the complaints I've seen are here WERE due to those users not having capable enough wireless routers, I went ahead and hooked up my old router and although it DID work, I noticed that it would occasionally have to buffer or would drop the signal once in a while. It was ok, but was clearly not how this experienced was designed to work. That's cool though, it was just a test. Put my new router back and have been using it for several days now.Performance is flawless. There is zero lag, ever. There is no buffering BS, at all. I don't even have a top shelf internet connection so it's not because of that. I do have Xfinity (Comcast) cable but I am on one of the middle grade tiers, not one of the top shelf ones. I think I am on a 25Mbps service but usually my speeds are more like 50-60Mbps when I test at Speedtest.net.So anything over 25Mbps connection is probably fine if you are likely to only be connecting a single simultaneous stream at any given time. Something over 40Mbps is probably a good idea for multiple streams. Anyhow, back to the Fire Stick with Alexa voice, which works really well. I don't have any past experience with these kinds of devices even though I am a long time tech geek and enthusiast, but that doesn't matter because this device is totally intuitive. Within five minutes, and without bothering to even look at either of the two small booklets or any online instructions, I was able to get the remote to do pretty much whatever I wanted it to. Easy peasy.We couldn't be happier, at least so far. The only thing I'm not terribly happy about is the fact that it only comes with a 90 day warranty, unlike the first gen Fire stick which had a 1 year warranty. Why would you drop the warranty on your devices from a year to 90 days unless you know there are going to be issues with them. If Amazon had faith in the quality of these devices they would offer a standard one year warranty just like almost every other electronic component out there. Almost every single modern television comes with at least a one year warranty. Same goes for pretty much every DVD and Blue Ray player, home theater systems, computer components like motherboards and graphics cards usually have much longer warranties. Regardless, it bothers me a bit that Amazon reduced the warranty on these but what bothers me more is that THEY don't offer the option for extended warranty THROUGH Amazon.You have to go through Squaretrade for that and I've dealt with squaretrade before on other purchases and found them to be an impossible company to deal with. Squaretrade seems to me to be nothing more than a scam company that will try every possible angle to avoid fulfilling the terms of their warranty agreements. When I called them regarding this device, just to try and get information about whether they paid for shipping in the event that I needed to use the warranty for replacement, the customer service agent started spouting off all the reasons why they were not responsible for replacing my device AND I WASN'T EVEN A CUSTOMER YET. I was just looking for information in CASE I decided, against my better judgement, to invest in the warranty since Amazon doesn't offer one. Needless to say, I will forego that.The other thing I didn't like is that the replacement remotes for the Fire Stick TV with Alexa voice control cost nearly as much as simply buying a new one. So my suggestion would be to take very good care of the remote and receiver. Do not allow kids or pets near them unless replacing one at the rate of 35 bucks a pop is no big deal to you. So my opinion is that there are a few areas where some things could use improvement but that is really only in the area of warranty and replacement parts. As far as function goes, so long as you have a decent enough internet speed and either a good wireless router or a wired connection you can run with an adapter to the device, you should have no issues. Again, I don't know if it will hold up over the long term but I'll come back and update this review once enough time has passed that I can be fairly certain of making an accurate assessment in that area.",5,203,neutral,0.5789661407470703,0.3434426188468933,0.5789661407470703,0.07759120315313339,0.2659,7,5292,0,0
A wireless review from a wired guy,"Before I go into the review and get trolled for not knowing what I'm talking about, which we all know happens. This is my review based on over 20 years of working in music from everything from DJing, some mastering, and even night club staging. Not that it’s been a profession, but more of an extreme hobby and I have gone through some brands throughout those years. With that said, here is what you’re getting with these headphones. Please keep in mind that if you’re looking for something in the range of Grado, Master and Dynamics, then this isn't for you, but don't take that as a reason to pass these headphones up. They perform better than I was expecting for a pair of wireless headphones that only cost $50.Pros: Earbuds1. Bass is deep, which is good for those who enjoy it2. Bluetooth connectivity was very fast, and they auto connect once they come off their case. (Both on Google Pixel 2, Mine and iPhone X, wife)3. Touch controls are simple and easy to remember4. Mic quality is pretty good in windy situations (Great for commuters)5. Build quality rivals more expensive earbudsPros: Packaging1. Well packaged, not too bulky2. Very easy to follow instructions3. Charging case doubles as a battery bank to keep your phone or other music device going4. Comes with a satchel to keep the case and cord safe and together5. Better than average warranty (90-day replacement or full refund), plus a 1 year worry free warranty, and if you register with them you get an additional year. That's 2 Years! My Polk Audio Buckle headset only came with 1 year at 4 times the cost when I bought them new.6. Case quality is good and study.Now that you have an overview of the good. Let’s look at what didn't make them great, which to be honest was very minor and with a few tweaks can make this a very strong competitor for more expensive earbuds. As it stands, they are very good budget ear buds that are just shy of perfect.Missed opportunities: Earbuds1. The bass is good, but not refined or accurate almost like an open port sub box in your car that hasn't been properly tuned and at higher volumes disrupts the vocals and highs enough to drown out classics like Duke Ellington. Now if you’re looking to listen to Skrillex, it’s not all that bad. (Side Note) - I used them both as my benchmarks for this portion.2. Though you connect fast to your phone. The controls are not as fast once your connected. Surprisingly it was still fast. It averaged about a half second of response time with my Pixel 2, but it took slightly longer with my wife's iPhone X .. roughly .78 seconds. This was just on controlling Pause/Play, skip forward and back. Calls were pretty much the same.3. Touch controls worked as they should, but I would like to see volume abilities added.4. The mic works in windy situations, but you do have to do some louder talking though for the noise cancellation to know what’s wind and what’s your voice. You don't want to look like a weirdo yelling ""I'll see you when I get home"" to your significant other.5. The build quality is good, but at the price of being a bit bulky. For example, they're larger than the JBL earbuds that I was considering buying before I got these and that adds on to the discomfort building after a couple of hours of use. Even that them being larger than most, they are surprisingly light and hold on while running on a treadmill.Missed opportunities: Packaging1. The only thing I would point out would be that the case/charger is a bit bulky, but since this is my first time with head phones like this. I guess it’s just something new that I must get accustomed to.Summary:If you want a nice simple workhorse, then this is your best bet. Don't expect it to wow and shock you with the clarity of Beyerdynamic, Master and Dynamics, or even Harmon Kardon for all you audiophiles, and definitely will not beat out Bose earbuds for clarity, (they aren't all that comfy BTW) What you will get a great price point earbud that will do the job as it was intended to over and over again.Oh, and by the way, I've only used wired headphones for as long as I can remember and switching to Bluetooth was not in my timeline at any time for about a hundred reasons, but these helped me see that there is some hope for Bluetooth audio quality. I hope they keep this up and one day they'll be able to produce audio like a corded set that will provide imaging like being center stage. &lt;---- Audio Guys will get that reference.",5,204,neutral,0.7294768691062927,0.08017229288816452,0.7294768691062927,0.19035087525844574,-0.1102,7,4451,0,0
Great deal and works better at streaming then smart Blu Ray player,"Truth be told I'm 40 years old and didn't even know what a Fire Stick was. I Googled A LOT to figure out what it does and why I would need it. For background my family has been w/o good old fashioned cable for probably 5 years. We had it briefly a year ago while in a temporary apt and while I loved the option of recording shows w/the DVR function, I found we basically watched the same 5 shows/channels (HGTV, Food Network, Disney Channel, Discovery, and TLC). So when we moved into a new house a year ago and had Internet hooked up through our local cable company we didn't even consider having cable installed. I think it was $150 to install in each room of our home too (pricey!).So we've almost exclusively spent the last 5 years watching TV through a blu ray player that is a ""smart blu ray"" player with apps that you can stream through. We watch Netflix, Hulu and Amazon (in total about $30/month for all 3) + cable internet that includes a wireless router through Spectrum/Charter for $40/month. We don't have a ""smart TV"", it's at least 5 years old too, and might even be a plasma TV.We got the Fire Stick a few days after Thanksgiving this year and all I did was plug it into the back of our TV in one of the HDMI slots and plugged it into the electrical outlet. I was immediately taken to the home page where I added the apps for networks/stations I knew we liked (NBC, ABC, Fox Sports, HGTV, Food Network, TLC, Disney Jr.). And my husband and I started seeing what we could watch. At first we were SUPER bummed because ALL of the shows we wanted to watch had a ""key"" on them and were ""locked"". When we clicked on the show it said we had to ""activate"" this option at a website, enter a code and then log into our cable provider account. NOTE: Yes there are shows that are ""unlocked"" that anyone can stream, but I would say that doesn't account for a lot (I tried mostly HGTV shows...but you could stream ALL of the Fixer Upper seasons ;)). So I thought man, not really doing much for me. HOWEVER, one big perk was that I was able to stream through the Fire Stick in our upstairs play room, where in the past our blu ray player would tell me there was a network problem (I'm assuming this was because our Internet modem/wireless router was too far away as it's housed in the downstairs and a closed cabinet). So the fact that I could stream our usual Netflix, Hulu and Amazon Prime was a big bonus, and WAY cheaper than buying a ""smart TV"", or video game console that you can stream with or even upgrade the ""smart"" blu ray player.But I kept on digging because I wanted to have access to all shows w/o having to pay a $150/mo. cable bill. And I found out through Spectrum/Charter I can sign up for streaming cable (I do not have a cable box installed in my home) w/my existing Internet account for only an additional $21/month! And now we can watch everything. And I think it's 100x more convenient than traditional cable because you search solely by a network/channel you know you love. Nor do you have to record anything, or wait and see what's playing live. And because I primarily watched Hulu for ""cable"" TV shows (This is Us, Bachelor, Modern Family), I don't need it any more, so for a net difference of $11/month I'm now watching a MILLION times more shows, when I watch and w/the ability to search by the network/channel. We haven't been able to watch even local channels/stations for a year because of our houses proximity to the local towers. We had a digital antenna that my husband tried a handful of times to work in our new house w/no luck.Bottom line: it's great at streaming through your wireless Internet (better than our blu ray player), love being able to look for shows and binge watch by network/station BUT you will need streaming cable from a local provider to unlock the majority of the shows.We also recently received a free Roku because at first I didn't think Spectrum/Charter would work on a Firestick (it took a full 3 days for some reason for Spectrum to ""link"" to our Firestick) and I signed up for SlingTV as well ($40/month for the highest option), and I can 100% say the Roku's interface is not nearly as nice or easy to navigate. I also do not understand SlingTV, you can only watch shows through the SlingTV app as far as I can tell. And it's twice as expensive as my streaming cable option.",5,205,neutral,0.6652022004127502,0.12759952247142792,0.6652022004127502,0.2071983367204666,-0.0796,0,4339,0,0
Trick to Opening Remote at End of Review,"The better half came home from hanging out with friends talking about this thing months ago, probably almost a year ago.Anyways checked it out, and it looked like another Netflix wannabe, so when we ended up discussing it I voted no, we didn't need to spend money on it - we already pay for Netflix, and an Amazon Prime membership, and we can only watch but so many things in a month. We didn't need one more thing. Then Christmas came, and it was perfect size for a stocking stuffer, something the other half had made a big deal about, and it was on sale, so I bought one, and got a big smile from the spouse Christmas morning!Come to find out this little device is more like a gaming system for folks who prefer to watch tv, and movies over playing video games! So now I am humbly declaring I was wrong. Majorly wrong. So wrong we just ordered a second one, and disconnect the WII, & the blue ray/ DVD player - both of which we normally use (besides watching DVD's- we can hook that one up when we want) to watch Netflix, because it automatically (after we entered our account sign in information) accesses the Netflix movie, &TV shows, and places them in the lineup with the others that are available in that category/ genre. You don't even have to switch between this source/ channel, and another one. It works just like a real library lineup - with no separation between publishers. All streamlined, and categorized not just by genre, but also by actors, directors, ECT.Honestly I gotta tell ya - you should get yours now while they're still cheap. It's gonna become really popular, cause it's that cool. So just in case it ends up costing more because people will still want it - get it while it's still less than $50.One thing you do want to be aware of is - IF it says free for 2 weeks, free for 1 month, or free for however long - that's one that will cost you after that period of time. Unless you totally HAVE to have one of those channels - skip it! There's so much content without them you will never run out of GOOD movies/ shows to watch. There's just not enough hours in a year!Also not only do they show the rating the source labeled the movie/show, but they also include the IMDB rating! AND if it's in a foreign language it shows that too! Which are awesome! And saves you alot of searching time!This gadget rocks! I was so wrong! We have it AND Netflix - We need it because we have Netflix, this platform is the best by far, & most of the additional (got to be like 90%+) content is free, plus the ones that are not are easily payable with your existing accounts- like Amazon Prime.We DO recommend the Fire Stick to anybody who might be a little board with Netflix streaming, wants more content, or just a super easy platform for what is thousands (literally thousands) of movies and episodes! Especially for people who don't want to be ripped a new one every month by cable / satellite companies for a tiny selection that's repeated all month long!***********Opening Remote ************Okay, so a lot of people have said the remote is difficult to open, so I investigated with the 2 we own.Here's what I found:I brought the remotes into the light, and put on my magnifying glasses because I personally need them for small details..**Anywho I found I had to run a thin fingernail along the very bottom seam by the arrow up engraving on the back & then went back through the seam with the same nail while pushing up, and the back slide off easy as can be!**There's something about the seal it comes with from the factory that needs to be kind of &#34;unsealed&#34;. It's almost like a suction seal, but was extremely easy to undo, and open.Don't know why it's like that, just know how to remedy, and ...***When I went back later after some use I had to once again fit something into the same seal area, and slide the back up again so I could open it.**Basically the back has to be slid up from the bottom seam rather than by pressure, or force. Don't try pushing down, & then up! It will never work that way, it's not made to do that- you'll just end up breaking it! :)Seriously hope our review was helpful!Love this product as you can see, & I was a nonbeliever!! Lol!",5,206,neutral,0.5278772115707397,0.1445121169090271,0.5278772115707397,0.32761070132255554,-0.1831,0,4188,0,0
Pros & Cons of the new Fire Stick (vs. Roku 3600R),"I own both the new Fire and Roku stick (3600R), below is a short review and honest (personal) opinion on both products.User Interface: the Fire stick has essentially the same UI as Fire TV (which I also own), it is largely divided by content category (Home, Video, TV, Movie, Music, Games, Photo, Apps, etc.), and integrated seamlessly with Prime eco-system. If you are already a Prime member, you will have better experience with Fire stick than Roku. Roku’s UI has the advantage of integrating more contents (Google Store, My Feed, News, etc.). Roku also allows user to make certain changes in Home screen (add/remove/move tiles), unlike Fire stick. However, both UIs are well designed, smooth. It comes down to personal preference.Hardware/Streaming Quality: as far as I can tell, there isn’t much difference, both are powerful devices, almost no lags with either device. One of the attached pictures is a screenshot of streaming YouTube 4K content from Fire stick, the picture quality is stunning (output as 1080p).Remote: I personally like the Fire remote, it is simple (only 7 buttons with a navigation ring), but provides all the functions you will need. I find it is both slimmer and easier to use than the Roku remote. In addition, Fire remote has a voice function, which you won’t find on Roku, this is a big plus. Also note that the Fire stick remote will work with Fire TV but you will have to &quot;unpair&quot; it first (please see the comment made by RoadDog on this review).Voice Search/Alexa: Amazon has greatly improved the search function. One of the main complains of earlier versions of Fire TV/Stick is that Alexa only search Amazon contents, but not 3rd parties’ (Netflix, etc.). However, with the latest software update, the search results now show both Amazon and 3rd party. You can choose from multiple ways to watch a movie (and whether the option is free of charge is clearly indicated).Power Cord: the USB cable came with Fire stick is about 4 feet long, it also comes with an adapter. However, I am using a 3rd party wall charger (iClever BoostCube+ 30W Dual USB Wall Charger with Qualcomm Quick Charge 3.0), and it worked well. In one of the pictures you can see the Fire charger output = 5.0V + 1.0A, iClever output is sufficient. It is a benefit in case you travel a lot, so that you won’t need to bring two separate chargers. One charger with two output slots will be enough for both your phone and Fire stick.App Quality: one of the main reasons that I bought the Fire stick after I bought Roku is because the quality of Playstation Vue app on Fire system is MUCH better than Roku, from my experience there is simply no comparison. Vue app on Fire gives you much easier access to your recorded shows, live programming schedule and channel switching. Roku doesn’t have live programming schedule, and some of my recorded shows are missing. However, quality of other main apps (Netflix, YouTube, ESPN, etc.) are more or less on par between Fire and Roku.Price: Fire stick is ~$9 cheaperHotel/Travel log-in: with Roku, you will need a separate mobile device (phone) to connect to a specific WiFi network established by the stick, then open up a browser and log in (normally with room# and last name). Often it took me several tries to establish the connection. With Fire stick, no need for a separate device, you will go to &quot;Settings/System/Network&quot; and press the &quot;option&quot; button on the remote, an on-screen cursor would appear, which allows you to log in as if you are using a laptop. I found the &quot;Fire&quot; way simpler and more intuitive.Physical Appearance: in fact, this is the only category I’d put Roku on top of Fire stick. The new Fire stick (1.2 x 3.4in) is much larger than Roku (you can see from the picture), it is even larger than the first generation Fire stick. This really surprised me as I thought the trend is to make them smaller. I also prefer that Roku put the power slot at the end of stick, while Fire stick put it right in the middle, which is really awkward.In short, if you are a Prime member and use Playstation Vue, I’d highly recommend the new Fire stick.",5,207,neutral,0.5744960904121399,0.41637885570526123,0.5744960904121399,0.009125077165663242,0.4073,5,4141,0,0
IF you don't know about KODI yet & are thinking of getting this AMAZING STICK- GET IT! WoW! READ......,"I wasn't sure about the whole fire stick thing but I purchased 2 on sale at Christmas time ( $29 ea.!) Well when I got them &amp; went on line to find out more about it- WOW! Okay maybe I've been living under a rock but I have found TV heaven &amp; its KODI !!!!! If you &quot; install&quot; KODI , it makes what is already a Great product- Amazing!!!! Without it, I would not get rid of cable all together as other people have reviewed about. But with KODI, I can 100% see dropping cable, plus not paying for Netflix , Hulu or any other service because by the time your done subscribing to all that junk your pretty close to a darn cable bill!! If you have PRIME than you already get a lot for free on the stick including &quot;Amazon&quot; only series &amp; shows, music etc. But.... KODI allows you to watch your fav series, movies, live tv, all FREE people . So you want to watch the cooking channel, hgtv,comedy, or anything from &quot;The Real Housewives of___ to &quot;Vikings* to &quot;Ghost Adventures&quot; or &quot;Property Brothers&quot;, YUP it's there. You want to watch the news , live, yes you can! Hey want to watch a movie &amp; not pay $8+for Netflix ,PPV etc price, well you can for FREE! Would you like to watch a brand NEW movie that isn't on pay per view ( yet) , well it's on KODI ( FREE) &amp; many that are still in theaters( seriously I couldn't believe it!) ! Today I saw a commercial for the New movie &quot; THE WALL&quot; w/ Matt Damon opens Fri.19th Feb &amp; well I had to laugh I was so shocked , because I watched it last night!!!! To me, it's like the new era of getting bootleg movies( come on you know what I mean 😏) without buying them from some cheap flea market or shady guy &amp; worrying the copy is crap ( u know, when it's someone sitting in the theater with a 📹cam &amp;,you can hear them eating🍿, coughing/breathing &amp; they cover the lens when a movie employee walks around &amp; they always shake the cam like they have Parkinson's disease!?! ) I really can't believe it's this good! YouTube etc has the how to's &amp; what to do's . I'm not tech savvy at all , I use 1 finger to type but it's not brain surgery and I'm sure you can find someone who can do it for you if you think you can't. &quot; my friend&quot; had it done . I have cable now at $165 per month with a $50 discount!!, at the very least I could see going down to the cheapest cable access (for those not ready to cut the cord*) , doubling my internet speed &amp; cutting my bill in 1/2 . With KODI I may drop cable all together &amp; just keep Internet and pay about $50 &amp; have everything I had with my high tier cable package PLUS getting more for much much less..Why would anyone not buy a fire stick? Hey if you already knew all about KODI , great but some people like myself don't &amp; I'm writing this for those who don't know all about it and are wondering if the should get a fire stick or not &amp; what all the hype is about. I seriously had no idea, &amp; im sure there are others that don't know ALL the stuff possible with this little magic stick . And KODI ...I hope I can help even one person ,that like me, wasn't aware of all the new possibilities with this and or what you can get. I'm still blown away myself &amp; I'm so so glad I purchased the fire sticks . Very easy to use, if you can handle a smart phone than you can use the fire stick (navigating thru KODI is like learning to use a new phone, you get the hang of it pretty quickly &amp; start finding all these new awesome things!) Seriously, My Mother hits the mute button on the cable remote &amp; is so lost she has to &quot;CALL ME to fix the tv because there's no sound!&quot; That's not the worst either ☹️ BUT she uses a fire stick ! So I'm sure you'd have little to no trouble learning it.Here's to watching TV again without a $200+ bill a month &amp; you don't even watch 90% of the channels you have to pay for!",5,208,positive,0.8272833228111267,0.8272833228111267,0.13977716863155365,0.032939571887254715,0.7943,0,3921,0,1
Finally I Can Stream!,"The Fire TV Stick works wonderfully. I live in a rural area and for years haven't been able to stream with any device because our internet service wasn't considered fast enough. We got a new satellite internet service with a package that said we still didn't have a fast enough speed to stream, but I'd been able to watch internet provided episodes of network TV through my computer and thought I'd take a risk on the Fire Stick because it was reasonably priced, and if my test failed, I wouldn't be out much money. To my delight, I have been able to stream my Netflix account, and content available from Amazon without any trouble. We've been using the Fire Stick virtually every night for just over a week without issue.Installation and start up couldn't have been easier or quicker. Plug one end of the Fire Stick into an available HDMI port on the TV and the other end into the wall. The power cord to the wall could have been a little longer, but we were able to get it there without an extension cord. The Fire Stick protrudes from the side of the TV a little bit, so if that bothers you, it would probably be best to get an extension cord and maybe tape the Fire Stick down in the back of the TV so that it's not visible, but it didn't bother me, so I haven't tried that. The start-up menu guides you through the setup. It is completely automated, requiring no information except for setting parental controls, and entering the username and password from any other streaming service you have, such as, Netflix, to connect your existing account. The whole process is basically intuitive and has you up and running in minutes.The Alexa Voice Remote works well. I have been able to search without any problems, minus some need to enunciate a little better on a few occasions; for example, when I said &#34;The Wire&#34;, the first result returned was for &#34;fire&#34;, but the screen shows what Alexa heard, so you know whether it understood you or not, and when I repeated the request with better enunciation, it produced the desired results.So far, I only have three minor wishes:1. The home screen is basically well designed, but can get a little cluttered with all the breakdowns in genre choices (Popular movies, Kid movies, Comedies etc.) and can get a little confusing. On the other hand, if you didn't know what you wanted to watch, and were looking for recommendations, it would take longer, so it's just one of those things. Besides, if most of what you're doing is using the Alexa Voice Remote, there really isn't much of a problem.2. I would also like it if when search results were returned, you could tell from the description whether the program was free with Amazon Prime or if payment, or another streaming subscription service is required. Currently, you need to click on the icon for the show to receive a longer description of the program that then also indicates a list of available options for viewing (such as free with Amazon Prime, a cost to rent through Amazon Prime, Purchase only, Netflix, Hulu, Sling, or other subscription streaming service).3. There really isn't a &#34;power&#34; button. When you're done, you switch your HDMI input back to your regular TV, but you don't really turn the Fire Stick off. It appears to turn itself off eventually, because if you exit to watch something else, or turn the TV off, and then return to the Fire Stick HDMI input later, it takes a minute or so to boot up. I'd like to be able to turn it off when I'm done, just because that's in my nature :)I highly recommend the Fire TV Stick if you are interested in streaming media. It is reasonably priced and easy to use.",5,209,positive,0.5626555681228638,0.5626555681228638,0.2984153628349304,0.13892912864685059,0.4237,4,3641,0,1
This Non Tech 71 Year Old Lady Says BUY IT!!!!!!!!,"I am SO GLAD I bought this Fire TV Stick with Alexa. It has literally made my life happier. As I write this review I'm listening to &#34;soft classic rock&#34;. All I had to do was say...&#34;Play soft classic rock&#34; and music started playing. For people like me who are elderly, tech illiterate, perhaps disabled, and who love music, movies, and TV shows, let me explain a few things. I've been looking at this stick for some time now but was scared to buy it. Then one day I said...the heck with it...I'm not stupid...I can read instructions...if it doesn't work for me I can send it back...I have nothing to lose and it's affordable. So I purchased a fire stick...yea me...lol.This is NOT complicated to hook up AT ALL and there are very clear instructions that anyone can understand. The box you get includes power adapter, a cable, and extender cable, the fire stick, 2 batteries for the remote, and an Alexa Voice Remote. It's as simple as can be. First of all the instructions say the extender cable is to improve WiFi and remote performance so I used it. Why not..better is always better..lol. So...I plugged one end of the power cable into the power adapter and the other end of the cable into the fire stick. Then I plugged the fire stick into the HDMI extender cable and then plugged that into the TV. I have a wide screen Sanyo. When you stick your head around the left side of our TV you see three places to plug &#34;things&#34; into. They're called ports...lol. Mine are marked HDMI 1, 2, and 3. I just plugged the stick into port HDMI 1. Last, I plugged the adapter into the wall socket and that was it. That's it. THAT'S IT!!!! That's ALL I had to do. Read the short instructions to connect this fire stick. Turn on your TV and then follow the instructions that appear on your screen. The Fire Stick does the rest.Obviously you can watch movies and TV shows as explained in the description but there's so much more. Ask Alexa what the weather is for the day in your home town or where your kids live across the country. I love music but somehow got away from listening to it over the years. Not anymore. There's always music in our house now. Just turn on the TV and tell Alexa what to play. This time I pressed the button and said...&#34;play soft rock&#34;. Alexa said...&#34;here's a station that plays soft rock&#34;. The first station didn't appeal to me so I pressed the button again and said &#34;next&#34;. I got another soft classic rock station that's been playing for over an hour now. I've been listening to songs I used to love and haven't heard in a long time. How I love &#34;Hotel California&#34;. They call them stations but it only plays music...no commercials or chatter...one song plays after the other. Also a box shows on the screen that gives you the name of the song playing and the artist. You can ask for any kind of music from classical, to rock, to alternative, to show tunes.I'm still learning. I know there's more I can do with this and it will get easier to find exactly what I'm looking for as I play around with it. I bought mine during the introductory promotion for the &#34;All-New&#34; version...think it was $29.95. Now it's $10 more but still worth every cent. Don't hesitate to buy it because you think it's too complicated. They really made a good little device here and it's very easy to use for anyone who has a TV and WiFi which you probably have if you have a computer.",5,210,positive,0.9638746976852417,0.9638746976852417,0.027212291955947876,0.008913091383874416,0.955,4,3434,0,1
"I understand why people cancel cable. Overall, it's a great experience.","Welcome to the 21st Century. I think the technology must be similar to a smartphone; from Amazon, I got aps for the CW, Fox News, NBC. There is no 5.1 Dolby Stereo for programming from these free aps. However, the picture quality is superior to our Comcast on demand (for CW). And several NBC and CW shows I watched in the past were cut by Comcast.Many programming is free from Amazon Prime. I played [[ASIN:B01M2C4NP8 Arrival]]. The picture quality was worse than a VHS cassette; all sort of artifacting, from banding, blurry, no detail: looked like Real Player on dial up modem from the 1990s. I called Tech Support, they said there was a glitch in the program. But I don't know if it stays in cache; it still looks dreadful. [[ASIN:B00I3MQNWG Bosch Season 1]] (only one time it looked terrible; started another time fine) has superior picture and sound to most Blu-rays (shot on Red camera 5K I guess). [[ASIN:B01N9I1J91 Victoria Season 1]] sometimes has distortion but the [[ASIN:B01LXM0S25 Masterpiece: Victoria Blu-ray]] also has issues per the review on Blu-ray.com.(My Internet connection is over 50 Mbps. A good Blu-ray like [[ASIN:B01FV8SVEW She Wore a Yellow Ribbon [Blu-ray]]] is less than 30 Mbps so that's not an issue.)While not sharing different political views, evidently Amazon and Google have a spat. So YouTube ap is gone. But you can download a Firefox ap and voila, YouTube. They haven't banned RT yet and the picture quality is far superior to Comcast cable. And The Arrival trailer is a beautiful picture; no issues unlike the Amazon trailer.Purchased product is superior to purchased Comcast movies; same price. So Fire TV is superior there. For someone who grew up with four channels and an outside antenna, engineering has changed everything. My unit is functioning fine.So if you don't have Amazon Prime, the Fire TV is a good reason to buy it. I only hope that Amazon isn't conserving bandwidth by short-cutting &#34;free&#34; content. I looked at [[ASIN:B01IG0E1F0 Star Trek Beyond]] via free Prime and its picture was OK; don't know why The Arrival was so terrible.(A [[ASIN:B075XN1NZC Roku Express | 5X more powerful HD Streaming (2017)]] review mentions [[ASIN:B00KDSGIPK Pluto TV - It's Free TV]], which I just downloaded. I'll play around with it.To conclude, it's worth purchasing, if only as back up to Cable. With rabbit ears and these free aps, or pay for Sling, I can see how people cancel satellite and cable and save big dollars. My only concern is that Prime TV and Films picture quality does not appear to be equal to paid for content. And the TV aps are like phone aps. There is no Dolby 5.1 sound. But I'll live without it if the shows aren't heavily cut for added commercials, as Comcast Xfinity has done for its on Demand.Addendum: Buying (renting) movies on the Fire Stick is much better than my experiences with Comcast. The movie loads instantly, perfect 1080p picture and Dolby 5.1 sound. In contrast, using Comcast, there were error codes, calls to customer service that lasted over half an hour, and obvious limiting of the dynamic range of the sound track, plus blowing up the movie to 1.78 (though I see the movie in question, [[ASIN:B06XGCLGZS Kong: Skull Island]] is only available via HBO. Well, Black Friday Blu-ray was cheap. My point is that when Amazon video offers a movie, it's a far better experience than what I had with Comcast cable.",5,211,neutral,0.5561219453811646,0.18733014166355133,0.5561219453811646,0.2565479576587677,-0.0692,0,3402,0,0
Comparison between Fire TV and Fire TV stick. Out of the box. Update to come.,"Update:So far I have only had a few issues out of either my Fire TV or the Fire TV stick. If you have the extra money I would definitely go with the Fire TV. It just a bit better all around and if you have quite a few apps that you download like myself, I am worried about running out of space on my Fire TV stick. The Fire TV is quicker on response time and once you use them a bit, you will start to notice it more and more. So, all in all this isn't a bad device and I still rate it at 5 stars, but if you can pony up a little extra cash and are going to put this to good use I would upgrade to a Fire TV. If you are a lite user and don't mind the small difference in delay between the Fire TV and Fire TV stick this would be the device for you. I bought one of each, because I knew I would need a 3rd one and I will be going with the Fire TV.------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------Initial Review:So far I am liking the Fire TV stick. I am just beginning to use this, so I will update a bit more later. My plans are to cut the cable and go with Playstation VUE for my TV subscription. There are trials to VUE and SLING, so my plan is to try them both out for a week and go with the one I enjoy the most. I have watched a few movies since I am a prime member and they have streamed well with great clarity. I was having issues with prime buffering to my smart TV, but I have had very few issues with Fire TV stick. I am running 10 Mbps for my internet service, so I am at the lower limit on what is acceptable to stream HD video. I tried using the USB power cable that came with the Fire TV stick and plug it directly into the USB on the back of my TV and I had issues with insufficiently power being delivered to the Fire TV stick. Some TVs will not supply enough power through the USB to drive the Fire TV stick, so just be aware of that. I do wish this worked with the Echo though. It is nice having Alexa integrated into the Fire TV stick now as it previously was not incorporated. This way I can tell Alexa from my sofa to turn on/off my Wemo switches or adjust the temperature of my Nest thermostats. So far I am enjoy the benefits as I am just scratching the surface. I also bought a Fire TV to compare the two devices. So far my comparisons are below and I will update them once they have been put through a test with the subscription services.Comparison between Fire TV and Fire TV Stick:1.) I was a little hesitant when buying the Fire TV stick, as my brother had an older version and it didn't work too well for him. I can say they must have made a lot of improvements. It is a little slower than the Fire TV, but not by much.2.) The Fire TV does have expandable media slot so if you are needing extra storage space for apps I would suggest the Fire TV.3.) Cord for the Fire TV stick was a bit short for me. Thought it would be a little longer since it needs to plug into the stick which is directly plugged into the HDMI slot on your TV.4.) The Fire TV stick is easier to hide since you do not have the box to deal with. Everything is conveniently hidden behind the TV if you have an outlet behind your TV or plug the USB into your TV (mind you that the USB slot on some TV's will not power the Fire TV stick).",5,212,positive,0.7732873558998108,0.7732873558998108,0.1962374895811081,0.030475184321403503,0.7428,4,3389,0,1
This All-new Fire Stick is a joy to have,"This product is so good that I feel compelled to write this Amazon product review. It was love at first sight. The initial out-of-the-box experience is such a delight. The packaging is clever, compact and &#34;light.&#34; The product came with the Stick, USB power cable, power plug, Voice Remote, 2 AAA batteries and a HDMI extender cable. All these six items were compactly tugged into different compartments that folded up into a box of 6&#34; x 3.5&#34; x 1.25&#34;.There is a slight nuisance with the Alexa Voice Remote. It was not easy to slide the backcover of this remote to place the batteries. To preserve the overall &#34;smoothness&#34; of this gadget, the indent area to grab the backcover was too shallow to slide the cover off for its first time use.Once the Stick is plugged into a HDMI port and powered, setting up the Fire TV Stick is intuitive even for a first time user of the Amazon Fire stick. The set up screen come on my TV with a list of found WIFI SSID. Select my home network then enter my network password. It quickly connected to my WIFI network. I was pleasantly surprised to find that the Stick knows my Amazon account. (A shrewd Amazon marketing lock-in to easily purchase or rent video or audio.) Enter my Amazon password, I was logged into my Amazon account and set up for me to try out Alexa. The whole set up process feels snappy. It was finished in less than 5 minutes.By pressing the &#34;Mic&#34; button on top of the Voice Remote, the TV blinks with a chime, meaning ready to listen. I said: &#34;James Bond.&#34; Quite a few videos were listed with the most recent ones first. This list include freebies as well as those for rent or purchase. I asked Alexa: &#34;List Woody Allen.&#34; The database is quite extensive. Then I asked for &#34;Asian movies.&#34; The list came back was extensive too. Query like &#34;Woody Allen Keaton before 1990&#34; seems to work as well.This morning I tried out Alexa on Prime Music. I said: &#34;Play Bob Dylan.&#34; It started right away. Then &#34;play soothing music.&#34; Alexa came back with a Baroque station, to which I have been listening while writing this review. Integrating Alexa to Fire has allowed me to un-tether my laptop to the TV. In the process, I can stay on my couch to switch between video and music accessing the extensive library of Amazon Prime media. Alexa has proved to be intuitive to use. Its vocabulary seems to be extensive and capable of disambiguating accented pronunciation. While on the Alexa Voice Remote, pressing its &#34;select&#34; button will turn on the TV. However it cannot turn off the TV unless the TV is connected to a smart home device.When I tether my laptop via HDMI to my large screen TV, the laptop's screen resolution only took up half of the TV screen. With Fire Stick, I am now getting the full screen. To take full advantage of Fire Stick/Prime library, I plan to connect my TV audio to the stereo system to get better sound quality through the TV's optical audio port, which is the last remaining audio output for my TV.The All-new Fire Stick is an amazing product bundled with an intuitive voice interface, which integrated well with a speedy search technology over a rich media library. I can comfortably say that for the movie and music lovers, this new Fire Stick is a joy to have.",5,213,positive,0.9700964093208313,0.9700964093208313,0.024447733536362648,0.005455906968563795,0.9646,4,3319,0,1
Fire Stick has successfully replaced my Gen 3 Apple TV and Roku,"This is my second unit (my first is a Fire TV) and I have been using this side by side with AppleTV. I first bought a Fire TV to replace a Roku box in my room that I've had for a few years that was acting weird and every other update either worked or it didn't so I gave up. I thought at first of buying another Roku box but I kept reading reviews that the fan sounded like a jet taking off and that was a turn off. I thought about a Gen 4 AppleTV as I love my AppleTV Gen 3 in the living room and when comparing prices I decided that a box Fire TV couldn't hurt and worked well and replaced that Roku box and I will never miss it. After a few weeks I thought I would try out a Fire Stick just to see if its capable and here I am.The obvious difference between the stick and box isn't much and I could live with either one. Once huge difference is when adjusting the screen size with Calibrate Display option to adjust the scale to match the TV. The Fire Stick tells you to use your TVs overscan and zoom settings to adjust this (see attached pic on review) and the Fire TV box has an option to do that built in. How silly is that? Some TV's either don't have that option or is tough to do for some people. From what I am reading previous version of the Fire Stick had that option. Not a big deal for me as I can set my TV to auto size, but some of you may find that to be a downside depending on your TV's options.I was previously using iTunes on my iMac slowly ripping my DVD collection to there in MP4 format and using Apple TV to play them which was convenient. I thought I was going to miss that option but I installed Plex server on my iMac, pointed it to my movies folder and had it up and running in less than an hour playing movies with the Plex client on the Fire Stick and the Fire TV box. Both are running it well and this Stick surprisingly well.I've been using both the Stick and the Fire TV for YouTube, Hulu, NetFlix and Prime and I have not had any problems that I have found as of yet. I actually prefer the YouTube Fire client over the AppleTV client (which was native on Ver 3). One thing I love is the Netflix on Fire TV has the option of choosing you have setup in Netflix and Roku's version had no such option and we have 3 profiles set up.I didn't think I would ever use Alexa but saying &#34;foreign films&#34; or whatever genre so far seems to work well as there is no real way to pick some genres in Prime on Fire TV, there is a few but not as many as there should be.The question is, would I buy the Fire Stick again? Yes! Do I prefer the box over the stick? It doesn't matter with me now as I haven't came across any limitations of the stick besides the screen sizing that would make me prefer one over the other. I don't have 4K TV's currently so thats not an issue. So if you want to save a few bucks and 4K isn't an issue with you, just go with the stick to start, its more cost effective than any other option and it works well.Pros:- Extra small form factor- No extra cables to have to deal with- Seems to be quite powerful for the stick form factor- Minimalist remote controlCons:- No way to adjust the screen scale to match the TV. Fire TV box has this option- Doesn't use IR so unable to use my current Harmony Remote",5,214,neutral,0.643826961517334,0.18210706114768982,0.643826961517334,0.17406593263149261,0.008,4,3254,0,0
New Fire TV Stick vs New Roku Stick,"I have owned a lot of streaming devices throughout the years. I started with Google TVs, then Android boxes, Chromecast, Nexus Player, Apple TV 4, Roku Stick (3600R), and finally the Fire TV Stick. Out of all the devices I've owned, my favorites are the Apple TV 4 and now this cheap Fire TV Stick. I am getting the new Fire TV Stick to replace my Roku Stick.Hardware:Both come with a stick to be plugged into the HDMI port and a remote. The Fire TV Stick even throw in an HDMI Extension cable. The Roku Stick is thin and long as the Fire TV Stick is shorter and wide. The stick appearance is insignificant because they go in the back of the tv anyways. The remote, though, is important.The Roku remote feels like a toy. It has cheap plastic and doesn't have a good feel to it. The Roku remote layout has the back and home buttons up top, followed by a d-pad with a select button in the middle, then a return and menu buttons, below that is the media back, play/pause, forward buttons. At the very bottom are four buttons for Netflix, Vudu, Amazon, and Google Play. These are basically product placement. It's uncustomizable and unprofessional. Hitting those buttons by accident would bring you to the channel page to download the app.The Fire TV Stick has a harder and better plastic feel. Layout is more intuitive as well. An Alexa voice command up top, followed by a directional pad ring with a select button in the center, below that is the Android standards back, home, and menu buttons, then ends with the media back, play/pause, forward buttons.The Alexa remote is far superior to the Roku.UI:Roku user interface is really really dated. It hasn't been updated awhile and it shows. It's also has a permanent ad spot to the right of the channel selection screen. It doesn't follow the new UI design philosophy of Apple and Google's Material Design. The fonts aren't clean, the purple background is unbearable after awhile as well.Fire TV UI is fresh. However, its main purpose is to push Amazon's ecosystem. It's a great ecosystem, for one price you get free 2-day shipping, video streaming, and music streaming. But if you don't have Prime, then the Fire TV UI is kinda pointless and just one big ad.Mods:Roku has a load tons of channels. But keep in mind they're low quality and niche like the church channels and hindu channels.Fire TV Stick is very limited because it's just a walled off version of Android. You need to side load, which is very easy, to gain access to greater apps. Although getting Kodi pretty much set it apart.Performance:The new Roku Stick, 3600R, is very reliable. It performs admirably.The 2nd Gen Fire TV Stick has 1GB RAM and 8GB storage. It is really fast on Fire TV.Connectivity:Roku Stick has private listening, but you only use it through the iPhone app.Fire Stick bypass the app and offer bluetooth. So you can connect your headphone directly to the Fire TV.Both offers hotel wifi login. Fire Stick is easier to use and doesn't require a phone.Overall, the Fire TV Stick is much much much better than Roku.",5,215,positive,0.6950654983520508,0.6950654983520508,0.3008526563644409,0.004081837832927704,0.691,5,3045,0,1
Tumbs up! Great product 👍🏻👍🏻👍🏻,"Hello everyone, I’m going to write a review in response to the negative ones, since I’m not able to reply to any of the reviews. I am more than satisfied with this device. I am an intermediate when it comes to computers/technology knowledge. Which means I have a lot of knowledge when it comes to computers/technology, but I don’t know everything. I have an Amazon Fire Stick in every room in my home, and I gift every single person I know with a Fire Stick. And I do this just to see their reaction when they realize how much money they can save, monthly, when they no longer have to pay for cable, only WiFi/internet service. I’m saving about $160-$189 monthly. Doing the math...that’s $2,880-3,468 per year. What can you do with that extra money? I’m saving to buy my first home. Next goal will be saving for my son’s first car. The Amazon Fire Stick/Fire TV is the best device in the market now, July 2020. There is nothing impossible in this device, if you have knowledge about the apps, and the ones that offer free tv, free movies, live tv, youtube,local channels, nationwide channels, international channels, worldwide channels and worldwide public surveillance cameras. HBO, PayPerView, Showtime, Stars, any channel, series, news, movies, websites,any family, adult or general channel. Just update the apps each month. Anything a computer can do or anything a cable company has to offer, you can get with this device. It’s like having your phone, computer, social media apps, internet browser, cable company, gps, weather station, radio station, and tv station, all at once,in one device. As long as you have a valid WIFI/internet service connection, and a tv or monitor with a HDMI connection. If you have any app issues, restart your Fire/TV stick, go to settings, apps, manage installed apps, go to the app that you’re having an issue with, clear cache, launch app. If you’re having connection issues, restart Fire Stick, and internet modem, try reconnecting to WiFi. If you’re still having issues, check with your internet provider. That was my only issue, ever, with this device. If you can’t get the remote control or any device to link, If any of your apps, movies, or tv shows are lagging or freezing, anything that has to do with your connection or performance, call your cable company. I had issues with my internet connection. So, I called my cable service provider, Xfinity, (which charges an arm and a leg) resolved my issue and disconnected my cable service. It saved me a lot of money on an almost $300 monthly bill (about $240-$289) And once I switched to Internet only, everything runs smooth. No issues. I couldn’t be happier with this product. I got one of the best internet services that they have to offer, by saving thousands per year, and at the time I got $100 Visa gift card from Xfinity, by choosing an active promotion. Win, win. Now, my bill is about $80-$100 per month. It depends on the taxes or extra fees. For more info contact me at hotchiquita12 @ hotmail .com (remove the spaces, everything together) Please like my review if you found this review to be very helpful. I want to help people understand their Fire/TV Stick. I also want to prevent negative review feedbacks. Thank you!",5,216,positive,0.8750602006912231,0.8750602006912231,0.11058828234672546,0.014351527206599712,0.8607,0,3226,0,1
I own both Roku and the Fire Stick.,"I own both Roku and the Fire Stick. We have 7 smart tv's in our house. All Samsung and we were very frustrated with the performance of the built in smart tv apps. We started out buying Rokus for a couple of the TV's and it was a huge improvement. We eventually decided that we wanted to dump AT&T and just stream all our content via the internet as we watched most of our shows via Netflix, HULU, Amazon Prime, and we have our own Plex Media Server. The deciding factor for buying the Fire Stick was when AT&T released the DirectTV Now service, which as of now is not available on the Roku, but was available on the Fire Stick. Roku will have it in Q1 of 2017.We instantly feel in love with the Fire Stick with Alexa voice control. The remote is simply in design and easy to setup and use. Simply being able to ask Alexa for the weather makes it worth it, but it does so much more. One major reason I love it over Roku is that it makes my Amazon Prime content more readily available. Before because I had to navigate through several steps to even bring up the amazon prime app I used it sparingly, but now it's front and center so I tend to use it more, which adds to it's value and the justification for paying the $99 a year service fee.Second thing I love is the Amazon Fire Stick smart phone remote control app. I was always pissy that Samsung remote apps were just worthless, but the Fire Stick remote app works flawless and even has the Alexa voice control. Often times I'm away from the remote, but I always have my phone in my pocket and it's a huge plus.I also purchased the Digital antenna that is an add on purchase with the fire stick as the DirectTV Now service does not offer local channels, and I wanted to view local news reports. It worked well enough in our upstairs bedrooms, but was not sufficient for the main living room television. I have since purchased a signal line booster to see if that helps, and if not then I will get a larger antenna that I will place in the attic. Either way it's happening as I'm done paying $235 a month for TV and Internet service.All our TV's are WIFI enabled, but unless you're a networking guru and have your house properly wired for wifi coverage you may want to invest in powerline network adapters, which will take your internet over you electrical wires. I use them for a home office in the basement which is far enough from the wireless router that service isn't up to par and they work great.One last thing. The DirectTV Now service is an awesome step in the right direction, but is still having some issues. They are offering an introductory rate of $35 a month for 100 channels (normally $60). As of now during peak times (Mid Afternoon and Evening) it buffers a great deal and locks up, but it's worth dealing with as they will fix the issues and getting the $35 a month intro rate is a big plus. I'm a networking engineer and I trust they will have it fixed soon.",5,217,neutral,0.4848354756832123,0.12911643087863922,0.4848354756832123,0.3860480487346649,-0.2569,4,2929,0,0
Fire TV Stick: Great Way to Watch All Your Favorite Asian Dramas on VIKI and DRAMAFEVER!,"I use streaming players to primarily watch Viki and DramaFever (and of course, Netflix). And I'm happy to tell you that they both work great on the Amazon Fire TV Stick now! (It wasn't always this way, only just a year ago. But I'm happy that they are both available now.)The speed is fast, and video is clear and vibrant, and the sound is good. I think it's superior to the [[ASIN:B01LXUZPQU Roku Premiere+ Streaming Media Player]], which I also own.I really prefer the interface of the Fire TV Stick over the interface of the Roku. The Roku is a great machine, but the interface has always been clunky, despite several upgrades over the years. The Fire TV Stick looks much more sophisticated, and has more convenient options. For example, if you pause a video, you can see which episode you were watching, and an option to select another episode directly from that screen. With the Roku, you always have to get out of that screen in order to find out which episode you were watching, or to select another episode.Also, the Roku uses close-captioned style of subtitles, which is purely text-based. The Amazon Fire TV Stick gives you an overlay style, which shows enhanced text such as italics, and musical symbols (to indicate song lyrics). It just looks nicer.Installing the Viki and DramaFever apps are easy. Just hold down the Voice Remote button and say &quot;Viki&quot; and &quot;DramaFever&quot; and you are on your way!A couple of quirks to the Fire TV Stick:(1) Unfortunately, you need to use the included power supply and plug it in a wall outlet for best performance. You can't just stick the USB directly into the TV (although this works well for the [[ASIN:B01DA0YCNC Roku Streaming Stick (3600R) (2016 Model)]]).I've tried this, and it does power the Fire TV Stick on, but then I get a message saying, &quot;inadequate power supply&quot;, and then it takes forever to &quot;optimize performance.&quot; So it's really just best to find a wall plug. Hope you have one free.(2) The Viki app has some kinks that it needs to work out. If you're playing a Viki video, and you decide to stop watching, so you press &quot;Home&quot; to go back to the Home Screen - the sound from the video you were watching will just continue to play! And if you start playing another video, you will simultaneously hear the sounds of both videos. So what you need to do is to stop the video by pressing the back button before you switch out to use another app.I think this is a problem with the Viki app, and not really a problem with the Fire TV Stick, because this does not happen with any other app that I have tried. I hope that they will fix this at some point. But it's not a reason for me to not recommend the Fire TV Stick.Anyway, this is a great machine, and one of the most economical ways to enjoy Asian Dramas on the big screen. Enjoy!",5,218,positive,0.9769928455352783,0.9769928455352783,0.020342573523521423,0.0026646286714822054,0.9743,5,2838,0,1
Streaming has come a long way...,"So I picked this Fire Stick during Black Friday sale. It seems that the engineers and programmers as Amazon have spent their time well and created a streaming stick that’s easy to use and fully functional.Dispensing with how to plug it in and activate it, if you want to fully utilize Alexa you’ll need to get the Alexa app. Download it to a phone or tablet, log in, and you can enable Alexa skills beyond what’s already set up in the fire stick. That means you’ll be able to do cool things like order pizza or call an Uber from your Alexa remote.You’ll be happy to know that your Amazon account will already be enabled when you get the Firestick, which means you’ll be able to access your prime account from the jump. If you don’t have a Prime account yet, you should consider getting one because Amazon’s video service has become very robust in the last year and easily rivals Their competitors. With Prime and this little stick you’ll be able to tell Alexa “play Zombie by the Cranberries” and she’ll jump right to it, as well as say “Play Iron Man staring Robert Downey Jr.” and Alexa will jump straight to the movie.(As an aside, I decided to subscribe to the Amazon Channel Anime Strike. Their channel list includes HBO, Showtime, Starz, and many others, and I find it easier to manage having HBO for instance by subscribing through Amazon. It’s dead simple, just choose to subscribe from your Amazon account on any device (Including the firestick) and HBO shows up as a channel on the firestick. It’s exactly the same as if you went to HBO’s app and subscribed there, except you don’t need the app to watch HBO)Now for the Cord Cutting fun. There are four services already installed on the firestick and ready to subscribe, those being Sling, Hulu’s live service, PlayStation VUE, and DirectV NOW. (Edit: you have to download PlayStation VUE, but it’s available none the less). Subscribe to any one of these services, put up an Antenna for over the air local channels, and you can throw your cable TV service away. That’s not a joke, nor is it an exaggeration. Sling TV is the least expensive for it’s lowest tier, but you can add more channels as you wish.My suggestions for apps to try when you first set it up are Pluto TV, the NBC app, FoxNow, Crunchyroll, FunimationNow, Crackle, NHK world, PBS, and the ABC app, all of which are free to use.Go ahead and get one of these. It works beautifully and you wont regret it.(Another aside. It’s much better to invest in a streaming device than it is to get a so called “smart tv”. From what I’ve seen so far, TV manufacturers are notorious for letting the app stores become so outdated that the apps on the TV stop working, meaning you’d have to get a new tv if you wanted the apps to work again. Just get a box instead because it’s way cheaper and even if it did become out of date it’s cheaper to replace)",5,219,positive,0.9283534288406372,0.9283534288406372,0.06747138500213623,0.004175164736807346,0.9242,0,2862,0,1
Nice addition to my TV - Battery hungry remote,"Update #2: After weeks of searching for an answer as to what is going on with the Fire Stick seeming to quickly drain even lithium batteries, I seem to have found an answer (or possible two). The problem identifying what helped is that I changed so many things at once, I am not sure what exactly fixed this issue. First of all, I changed all of the available options (through using the Fire Stick controller) to turn off any optional feature I could. This seemed to have immediately fixed my issue, as I have not had to change the batteries since then and its been over a month. But not so fast - I was replacing the batteries in another device using the brand new pack of lithium batteries I ordered for the Fire Stick, and the other device didn't work with new batteries. I tested these supposedly brand-new batteries and found one that was almost dead. It is not inconceivable that when I put the first pair of lithium batteries into the Fire Stick I had a bad battery in that pair as well (from the same pack) - I tested after the Fire Stick stopped working but not before putting in the brand new batteries. I noticed after the batteries failed that one seemed very drained and the other was right at the Red/Green boundary (which suggests one battery was already drained had I thought this through). So I am raising my Fire Stick score back to 5 stars, I love this device and it no longer is eating batteries. I wish I could tell you exactly what to change - maybe in a future update. (My apologies to Amazon for not having figured this out sooner.) I am once again considering changing all my TVs to Fire Stick as it is so much easier to use than the Apps that come with the TV.Update #1: The remote control is going through batteries like crazy... I have never seen a device eat so many batteries. I recently ordered and started trying to use lithium and they are more expensive but drain about as fast as the cheaper alkaline. I also tried NMh rechargeable and those last maybe a day or two. The cost of keeping these thing running is ruining my overall experience - so I like what it does but not feeding it batteries all the time. Downgrading rating to 3 stars.--Very easy to set up, and way easier to use than either my TV controller or my cable box controller. It has really allowed me to make use of my Prime account TV service much better. Extremely Pleased.Note on the voice control: Voice control works but honestly not easier than just using the controller - that or I am too old to learn new tricks. The voice controller will not rewind or advance - I have tried numerous ways. It is often confused when I try to tell it what I want to watch unless the program is on Prime, and sometimes on NetFlix. I no longer bother trying to use voice. It just isn't worth the trouble and aggravation. Perhaps when they ship one that reads my mind it will work better.",5,220,negative,0.5022363662719727,0.03607941046357155,0.4616842269897461,0.5022363662719727,-0.4662,7,2875,1,0
Worth Every Penny,"Watching your favorite shows just got even more enjoyable!Do you find yourself watching your favorite shows from your small phone? Do you keeping having to recharge your computer during those binge sessions of Netflix? The Amazon Fire TV will eliminate all of those hassles for you by putting all of your streaming devices on to your TV. Once installed, you can stream your favorite movies, music, and television directly to your TV without skipping a beat. An added bonus is Alexa, she is the voice command built into your remote that makes ease out of streaming from the moment you open the box. I use the product multiple times a day to stream Netflix, HBOnow, and Hulu. Before I was stuck staring at my phone for hours watching my favorite shows. Now with just a couple clicks, I can sit in the comfort of my living room watching from my TV.Ease: The Fire TV Stick is amazingly easy to install. You simply just insert the dongle into any HDMI port on the back of your TV. Then you connect your stick to your home Wi-Fi and you are off and running. There are hundreds of apps to select from all at the tip of your fingers. You can do anything from streaming TV to ordering Chinese food. It is the ultimate tool for those rainy days, where no one is going outside.Alexa: She is by far one of the best perks of owning this device. Alexa is the genie that lives inside your Fire Stick remote. She grants your wishes by voice command. You simply just press the button on the top of your remote and she will do as you say. You can say &#34;Alexa, watch 'The Walking Dead',&#34; or &#34;Alexa, open Hulu.&#34; She is the perfect tool for learning how to operate the Fire TV Stick. If you are ever lost, she will be there to guide you to where you want to be. She also makes watching on the move easier. If you need to go to the door to pick-up your Chinese food a simple &#34;Alexa, pause,&#34; and you are good to go. Over my time using this product I found myself wishing for more friends like Alexa.Price: For a lot of college kids 35-40 dollars can be a lot of money. However, this device is worth every penny of that. Everything I want and need from a streaming device is now on my TV. This device is simpler and more user friendly than other similar devices on the market, and it comes from a trusted name such as Amazon. The price is well worth how the device changes your watching experienceI fully recommend the Amazon Fire TV Stick to anyone who is in need of an upgrade to their streaming lifestyle. From the moment, you connect the device to your Wi-Fi you are at full capacity to start watching, listening, or streaming at the press of a button, or at the command of your voice. This device is a favorite in my home, and with a purchase will easily fill the same role for you.",5,221,positive,0.966956615447998,0.966956615447998,0.031053006649017334,0.001990389311686158,0.965,4,2786,0,1
The best streaming device in the market !,"This is my 2nd fire stick I have bought for use at home. I love the fire stick over any other streaming device I have tried so far. I additionally have a google chromecast and Xbox at home. However, I find myself reaching over to the fire stick remote every time I want to stream something on TV.Pros:(1) Very smooth and easy-to-use intuitive interface -- device is very fast with little lag in device input. I bought my first Firestick around 2 years ago and it doesn't have any noticeable device slowdown. In contrast, my chromecast has gotten considerably slower since I bought it.(2) Bugs are extremely rare -- maybe once every few months. In contrast, my experience with chromecast has been very bug ridden.(3) Not only you can use the Firestick remote and interface, you can also stream directly from your phone just like chromecast(4) You can stream Amazon prime movies and TV shoes -- a very different library than Netflix. Due to competition, Amazon does not allow prime services to be used on chromecast(5) You can install Kodi app on it if you so desire and use it as a Kodi device. Chromecast does not let you install any app on the device and therefore, the procedure of streaming Kodi is much more complicated using a chromecast(6) WIFI performance is excellent - I rarely encounter any buffering issues. In comparison, my chromecast has suffered from buffering issues since day one(7) Having a separate remote is very convenient. At first, I was skeptical about having another remote occupying space on my coffee table. However, Firestick remote is very useful and you can very quickly access any content. I rarely have to use my phone to cast anything on my Firestick(8) Alexa is a pretty good AI assistant and I like the idea of having voice control on my streaming device(9) Awesome amazon's customer support always ready to help in case anything goes bad with your Amazon deviceCons:(1) Amazon competing directly with Google on several fronts has resulted in Google pulling out its several commonly used services (such as Google play and Youtube) from Amazon devices. However, there are separate non-google apps that let you access these services without much work -- so only a minor issue. Amazon does the same thing by not letting Amazon prime be accessible on chromecast.PS: While it may sound like I am badmouthing chromecast here, it is not true. I am simply comparing firestick to another commonly used streaming device which I have experience with. I loved my chromecast (for 2+ years) before I bought the firestick. However, I think firestick is well ahead in game when compared to chromecast, which needs some catching up to do.",5,222,positive,0.9573736786842346,0.9573736786842346,0.03821273148059845,0.0044135949574410915,0.953,5,2656,0,1
This ROCKS!! :D,"I LOVE MY FIRE TV STICK!!!! I decided to cut the cable cord, as the price was just increasing rapidly, and really without much, nor many changes in offerings. (They had the 30-40(ish) stations, then the exact same stations repeated,only in HD, and the sports channels, (where I spent most of my time!) GO NINERS!!) ;) Then they added some retro-stations. But again, nothing to write home about, and my bill went from $56.-$85-$110.15 in less than 3 years...SOOOO, A BUE BYE cable! And as I have a wireless TV, I didn't need the box that is offered.And the remote is voice activated, so you can say&#34; comedies&#34; etc. and a short list of the different type are displayed. (PLUS, there is NO monthly fee for using the stick! Only the one time purchase price, which is incredibly reasonable.) I installed the Fire Stick, and was quite amazed by all that was offered. ( I also have Amazon Prime,which is not needed to to receive stations, you can pick and choose to suit your needs and no forced stations to watch as cable has!) which also rocks, and they offer so much to pick and choose from, I love that feature. And the picture quality is superb. HD all the way! It also offers many different apps, ie&#34; HBO NOW in which if you have Prime, they offer a 30 day free trial! And HULU Plus,(another 30 day free trial!) Also many of the stations offered by cable, as well as stations for kids, and the basic 3 major networks:ABC/NBC/CBS PLus the sports versions of these stations. And their Prime music has EVERYTHING, every genre as well. (And as one in &#34;the music biz,&#34;) I was thrilled by this. So gang, if you are considering cutting your cable cord, and saving the big bucks, this Fire TV Stick is the way to go!!!! I kid you not!! And if you are a sports spaz like myself, there is a station called &#34;Sling TV,&#34; that has ALLLLL of the sports stations, PLUS The NFL Network!! Along with the regular stations that are not sports related!! HUGE~HUGE PLUS! It has 2 ways to watch, there is an &#34;Orange package that has many stations, plus some sports, and The Blue, that has more, plus more sports. I chose BOTH, The orange and Blue. And together it is only #39.98 a month! (Including The NFL Network!) So you can't beat that with a stick!! Lol....So, please consider this wonderful offering from Amazon. It is SO worth it! I simply cannot say enough good things about this. (Without rambling on more than I have already!) And if you do decide that this isn't for you, (which I honestly do not see happening!) Amazon's Customer Service Representatives are superb, so kind and helpful, no rush, no judgement, just great folks. So, I encourage you to give it a try, I'm sure you will NOT be disappointed. And I am a skeptic!",5,223,positive,0.8783150911331177,0.8783150911331177,0.09757078438997269,0.024114135652780533,0.8542,0,2744,0,1
A Nice Improvement Over The Older Generation,"I upgraded from the 1st generation Fire Stick and the performance is like night and day. If you’re wondering if you should upgrade or not, here are a few main reasons why you should:1. If you notice any lag on the home screen or in any apps2. If you encounter network issues (slow speeds or weak/dropped signals)3. If you experience overheating (can cause lag or shut off Fire Stick)4. If you use the voice remote feature through the app (although you can purchase the voice remote separately)I experienced the first three issues above on a regular basis and the new Fire Stick has yet to show any of them (even after using Kodi or other intensive apps such as TiVo DVR streaming). I actually had the 1st generation Stick that came with the voice remote and rarely use it. The main thing I use it for is to search for an app to download since it is much faster than typing it in. Depending on what you use on your Stick, the voice remote can actually be pretty powerful.Upgrades:Faster processor - Has a quad-core porecessor nowFaster WiFi - Uses the latest AC standard. This is really only helpful if you have an AC router and fast enough internet speeds to utilize the speed increaseBluetooth - Uses the 4.1 standard now instead of 3.0Support for High Efficiency Video Codec (HEVC) (for higher resolution at lower bandwidth)Included in the box:- Fire Stick- Voice Control Remote- Wall Outlet and USB Cable- 2 Amazon Basics AAA Batteries (for remote)- HDMI ExtenderOverall I was very glad that I upgraded from the older generation. If you aren't experiencing issues with your first gen stick then there isn't any need to upgrade. However, if you want a Fire Stick that is faster then definitely upgrade. The new Stick is slightly bigger but not so much that it would cause any inconvenience. I love the Fire Stick and think it's much better than Chromecast or Apple TV. The newer processor also also for better game play if you use the Stick for that.Something to note: My first generation stick with voice remote came with a female to female HDMI adapter instead of an HDMI extender. I like the adapter much more than the extender because it lets me use my HDMI cable to connect the Fire Stick instead of having it plugged in directly to the TV. In my opinion, the HDMI extender doesn't provide enough length if you experience network issues. It's really only good for someone who had a crowded HDMI location on their TV and can't plug the stick in due to its size. The new Fire Stick doesn't come with the adapter so you will need to buy one separately if you want one.",5,224,neutral,0.48018157482147217,0.46527615189552307,0.48018157482147217,0.05454229936003685,0.4107,4,2572,0,0
A Cable Cutter's Dream!,"After much research, I dropped my cable television service almost 2 years ago and installed a good outdoor antenna and wound up with 47 channels of local free television. I was happy, but I REALLY missed my DVR and the ability to record my favorite shows, in order to watch them when I wanted and to fast forward through commercials. So I bought a Tivo and now had 47 channels (ALL of the major networks plus PBS and several independents} and a better DVR than I ever had with cable. That made me happier, but, although we could live without them, my wife missed HGTV , DIY, and a few others and I missed History, National Geographic, the national news networks, and the ESPN channels for watching college football. We did miss those channels , but we did NOT miss them enough to go back to $110/month cable tv.Then about a month ago I first became aware of the Amazon Fire TV Stick and PlayStation Vue..........OH, HAPPY DAY!For a mere $40, the Fire TV Stick has opened up a whole new world of entertainment. I was already an Amazon Prime member which gave me immediate access to a huge library of music, movies, and tv, but then I started exploring the apps that are available and found that there are hundreds of them ranging from useless (to me) to absolutely wonderful. No matter where your interests lie, I cannot imagine you not finding several different (free) apps that will delight you. As you can see, I am both very impressed and very happy with the Fire Stick, but when I combined it with a subscription to PlayStation Vue my cable cutting dream was complete! I subscribed to Vue's Core Slim package ($35/month) and now I have 60+ channels of cable tv, including all of the channels that my wife and I missed, and the ability to record any show that I want to watch later at my convenience. Vue even allows you to fast forward through commercials on the shows that you have recorded.In conclusion: With a good antenna and a Tivo box (both purchased from Amazon) I have all of the local channels and major networks and a full-service DVR on which to record them. With the Fire Stick, Amazon Prime, and PlayStation Vue I have a huge library of music, movies, TV, and 60+ channels of live cable TV (which also comes with a built-in DVR) This setup is NOT equal to cable TV. It is FAR SUPERIOR and the cost per month is HALF what i was paying for cable TV alone. My media joy is now complete.P.S. I received no compensation of any kind for this review. I know it reads like a commercial, but it is how I actually feel. Sometimes when you are lucky, the product lives up to the hype.",5,225,positive,0.5767161846160889,0.5767161846160889,0.3557986319065094,0.06748513132333755,0.5092,0,2591,0,1
I Love Amazon and Alexa.,"The Alexa Voice Remote makes navigating easy. Just ask for what you want and she'll bring it up, and anything that is similar to the request. That feature is not activated by calling Alexa's name. You press a button and ask for what you want. If you have questions Alexa's voice will respond to them. If want you is not available, Alexa will let you know. If you have a Kindle Fire, this is almost like having a big Kindle Fire...not for reading, but in the way Amazon's free apps are downloaded and opened to view. It's not like you just turn on the TV and start watching. The apps/movies/tv shows, including those already installed have to be opened. Many have to be downloaded and those downloads are the same quick speed as the Kindle. In this way it works like a Kindle Fire. Of course, the Fire Stick has many more apps available, both free and to purchase.I don't like having to go to websites to register and get the codes (before allowed to view) for many of the non Amazon apps, but that's their requirements. Many apps that are not for Prime are free, too, but you may be limited in what you can watch. For instance. TCM channel app is free, but it isn't live streaming. They have some pre selected movies available to watch.The Fire stick is so versatile. It can be plug into any flat screen TV. I highly recommend if you're a Prime Member. You can view so many movies on your TV, instead of a computer screen or a small Kindle screen. You can play many games, too. There are many free lifestyle apps;, cooking, massage, educational, exercise,etc. You can live stream Network Channels, but there is a fee. I know ABC is 5.99 monthly. You can purchase premium channels from Amazon for a monthly fee....HBO, Starz, Showtime, etc...Their monthly fee is cheaper than the TV providers after their few month trial period is over.I wouldn't consider this a replacement for Uverse, Cable, etc...but it can be for some. Originally, that's what I was looking for, but we still like live streaming TV. My last Comcast bill was well over 200. I was able to go with one of the cheaper Uverse plans and reduce our bill by 100 bucks per month. I'm pleased about that. You will need internet/wifi from some provider for the Fire Stick. The Stick works on HDMI1. Set up is fast and easy. Last thing, I don't know if it's just my TV, but the volume on the TV increases dramatically when actually using the Fire Stick. When you turn it off, the volume goes back to normal for your TV. This could be good for anyone that has difficulty hearing.",5,226,neutral,0.6156929135322571,0.36944571137428284,0.6156929135322571,0.01486139465123415,0.3546,0,2536,0,0
"Works great, and the first unit we have bought that works on the 5 GHz band","We cut the cord for cable/satellite a little over a year ago, and since I have been looking for a system that had minimal buffering. We currently have an android TV box and a Roku 3 which both had pros and cons.Our router is at the opposite end of the house, and is over 40 feet from the TV with multiple walls between. Both are capable of using the 5 GHz band, but neither got a reliable connection.Both would connect to the 2.4 GHz band, but disconnected and buffered often. For both, we decided to use an Ethernet connection using the electrical wiring. This was better, but still a lot of buffering. At first, I blamed our internet service provider, but our download speeds on speed test was very good.I was a little hesitant to try the Fire TV Stick since it used only WIFI, and our experience with the other units on WIFI was not good. At the price of $39.99, I decided to give it a try. Setup was easy, but it took a little time to download all of the apps and to enter user names and passwords for each. Initially, I connected it to the 2.4 GHz network thinking that it was too far from the router to get the 5 GHz band. At this point, I wasn't happy with the Fire TV Stick at all. The picture was grainy and the colors were dulled. Since I know that such devices will revert to SD video when the bandwidth is not fast enough, I decided to try the 5 GHz band. Surprisingly, on this band the picture was crystal clear and there was no buffering.We have been using the Fire TV Stick for about 4 days, and, so far, buffering in nonexistent. The voice commands using the remote are extremely helpful. Any app can be launched by voice command, and the search function to find programs by the various criteria works very well. At this point, it looks like the search function works primarily with Amazon Prime Videos rather than across all apps. I would like a feature for volume control that this doesn't have and the android TV box does. It would also be nice if the voice search was across all apps as it is on the Roku 3. It would also be nice to have the option to download additional apps for movies and TV. If this option is available, I have not yet found it.In spite of the couple of inconveniences mentioned, I would highly recommend this device if your router is close for the 2.4 GHz band or supplies the 5 GHz band. Since our TV viewing is uninterrupted with buffering, I can live with controller the volume with a different remote. As for downloading additional app, we probably have more available on this unit than we will ever make use of .",5,227,neutral,0.7545531988143921,0.16390162706375122,0.7545531988143921,0.08154522627592087,0.0824,5,2559,0,0
Excellent product!! Much better than Google Chromecast!,"I have used Chromecast v1.0 prior using this prior stick and was looking for a new streaming device after my Chromecast died(which started with casting issues).I was a bit skeptical in buying Fire stick as was not sure if it was going to be as good and simple as Chromecast, but, I have to admit that this product has exceeded my expectations to an extent that I now think choosing Chromecast was a mistake for me earlier.Below is my detailed review:User Interface:I have read in online reviews that Roku provides the best user interface, but, I haven't used Roku so cannot comment. But for sure the Alexa remote and the experience of using the Fire TV interface is 10 times better than using Chromecast.I like the simplistic approach of the remote with fewer buttons and still getting all of the jobs done in an efficient way. Alexa voice controlling is a sweet addition the device and fun to play around and is bang on target for most of the things like - Weather, directions & normal search operations.After using the Amazon remote I realized that how much effort I was putting to switching between apps on my phone to case on Chromecast, with the remote switching between apps is effortless.Casting & Screen Mirroring:I always had this question in my mind before buying fire stick if it will support casting like Chromecast. But I was happy to discover that it same casting options are available through my apps on Android and also it directly mirrors the entire phone/tablet.The best part is I can even extend/mirror my Windows 10 laptop display wirelessly.Picture Quality:I have a LG smart TV and also used Chromecast, but, after switching to fire stick I realized that the videos have overall better dynamic range, better sharpness and color.The same videos from my SMart TV apps and Chromecast appeared to be little dull compared to Fire stick.This might just be my observation, but, thought it was worth mentioning. Please not I have not used Roku so it is out of this comparison.Performance:The stick is lightning fast plays the contents with hardly any buffering delays. Switching between the apps is seamless.Please note, I have limited apps installed at this pont, but, will have to see how this device ages with more apps installed.Overall, I am extremely satisfied with this product and worth every penny. Strongly recommended and definitely deserves 5 star rating.",5,228,neutral,0.5616165399551392,0.31034642457962036,0.5616165399551392,0.12803703546524048,0.1823,5,2380,0,0
Fire Stick vs. Chromecast (also with their respective digital assistants),"This is another one of those products that I wish I bought a LONG time ago. I thought I was just fine with using my Playstation 4 as my streaming device. There's nothing *wrong* with that per say, but it's a pain to make sure your controllers are constantly charging, and it's not primarily a streaming device so it doesn't have the most friendly layout for streaming.For the price of the Fire Stick (and there are frequent sales) it is a really easy purchase to make. I have used a Roku before (a long time ago) and also have a Chromecast currently, so I can compare it a little bit. There are already a lot of reviews on what exactly this does, so I'm going to tell you the major pros and cons of the Fire Stick vs. the Chromecast.Fire Stick:-If you have an Amazon Echo you can use voice control with your fire stick-Very easy to access Amazon Prime titles. A lot of people really dislike the Fire Stick interface, just a heads-up. They find it cluttered and difficult to get through. I actually like it, but just a warning.-Controller is very slender and sleek but it's very annoying if you lose it and that's easy to do (although there is a Fire Stick app which is pretty nice)-You can screencast most things, but NOT YouTube (owned by Google, competitor), so that is really annoying, especially for someone like me who uses YouTube a lot.Chromecast:-Works great with the Google Home obviously (I own the Echo and Google Home)-Best with Android of course.-You control all your streaming from your phone, there is no controller. The upside is that you never lose the controller and it's very unique...downside is you are reliant on your phone and the battery on your phone.-Screencasts YouTube, of course, and while you can screencast HBO Now, you can't screencast HBOGo! That is really stupid, especially considering that HBO Go is for people paying for HBO in addition to a large cable/satellite bill.Overall, they are a bit different and I use them for different things. I prefer my Netflix/Hulu/Amazon etc. streaming with my Fire Stick, screencast YouTube with Chromecast. I also have both a Google Home and Echo, and both are good for different things. Spotify Premium works with either the Echo or Google Home, but for the Google Home you also have the option of Google Play Music (which I switched to recently) which is a huge bonus. I don't really prefer one over the other...they are just different!",5,229,negative,0.47787848114967346,0.14021840691566467,0.38190314173698425,0.47787848114967346,-0.3377,5,2411,1,0
"The Best ""Little"" Content Streaming Devices on the Market.","What is there to not like about these devices? I've now ordered 5 of the Fire TV Sticks. One was a birthday gift to my daughter given today. With a good, decent speed internet connection and WiFi /router (I have TWC Spectrum 200 mbps down speed cable gateway/router), the display clarity is absolutely fabulous on &#34;just&#34; 1080p HDTV's. two Sony Bravias 60&#34; and 46&#34;, one Samsung 46&#34;, and a new 49&#34; TCL Roku HDTV (love the TV not the Roku part so much). So I just set up my 4th FTVS on it. The amount of content, in my opinion just blows away, Chromecast, Roku, or any Apple streaming devices. I also have 2 decent Sony Blu-Ray players with wired and wireless internet. The FTV sticks' resolution is far better than either WiFi or Ethernet on my Blu-Ray players. The Blu-Rays are constantly buffering. The FTVSs almost never, and when it does rarely happen, it's more like a hiccup.I'm fortunate to have both Amazon Prime (had it almost since the beginning of Prime) and a decent number of TWC premium movie channels. Had more premium channels before the stinking, ill advised purchase of Time Warner Cable by Charter Communications. I'm fortunate to be grandfathered into TWC programming instead of Charter/Spectrum as long as I keep the bulk of what I have (CATV, internet and digital telephone).Anyway, back to the FTVStick. They are awesome. My daughter was astounded when she saw all the content she could get. I had been trying, at least since Black Friday's sale last year (same pricing going on right now), to convince her to order one. She and her husband have a Chromecast. After they installed the FTVS today she remarked that had she known it had all the content it has, she would have bought one long ago. My son also lives in the same house that we rent to them all, and I convinced him to buy a FTVS when they went on sale about a month or so ago ($5 more than current sale price). I'm told he hasn't had a chance to install his yet.Besides the phenomenal amount of content and clarity of display resolution, they are so easy to maneuver and operate. I love the feel of the relatively small size of the remote with not too many features. I guess the only downside with that size is that one needs either an accessory for volume and a few other typical remote functions or you always have to have either the TV remote or a universal type remote from your &#34;friendly&#34; cable or satellite provider at your side/lap/nearby.",5,230,positive,0.9331883192062378,0.9331883192062378,0.06187336519360542,0.0049382890574634075,0.9283,0,2461,0,1
Wonderful Television and Music Experience,"I recently cut the cord and had my cable television disconnected. I ordered two of these Amazon Fire TV Sticks, one for my television in my living room and the second one for the television in my bedroom. I actually ordered these tv sticks several months ago and had not got around to installing them since I thought it would be a difficult process. I do not have a smart tv and I am no expert on technology so I was worried that I would have problems installing the fire tv sticks. I had no trouble at all installing the sticks. All you do is plug them in to your televi and follow the directions that pop up on your screen. I was shocked and pleasantly surprised at how easy it was to use these fire tv sticks. I had them installed and television shows going in just a few minutes. I can watch every program that I used to watch through my cable tv provider, Comcast/Xfinity, only without the huge bill. I have high speed internet which allows me to stream movies and tv shows. I am somewhat of a news junkie and was worried about whether or not I would be able to watch the news. I get CBSN, Fox News and CNN all free. I do not get my local news and I miss it. However I can do without my local news in order to save over $100.00 per month. I also decided to purchase HULU for $4.99 per month for extra shows and movies and shows. I got a special price on HULU for $4.99 per month for one year. Normally it is $7.99 per month which still isn't bad considering the huge amount of movies and shows that you get! So with the Amazon Fire TV Sticks I actually have better television viewing than I had with cable Television and am only paying $4.99 per month to watch practically any show or movie that you can think of. You can purchase additional channels such as HBO, Netflix etc. I am on a fixed income and need to keep my bills as low as possible but I am truly happy with the programming that I have and see no need to add additional channels. I love music and thanks to my fire tv stick I now can listen to all of my favorite songs through my television. Also you get youtube, facebook and many other apps that I haven't checked out yet. If you are on the fence about cutting the cord, dont be! I am so glad that I got away from cable television and it was much easier to do than I thought! My only regret is that I didn't do this sooner! I highly recommend Amazon Fire TV Sticks and am extremely HAPPY with my purchase.",5,231,negative,0.5492178201675415,0.03546346351504326,0.41531872749328613,0.5492178201675415,-0.5138,0,2425,1,0
Incredible Performance,"This little thing, and it is tiny, outperforms a smart tv with a wired ethernet connection to our router. This thing is fast. Gone are the days of the little spinning widgets, the testing, the waiting, the loading, and the buffering. I can resume playing a movie instantly, like it's been sitting there, queued up, and waiting for me.My internet connection is 75 Mbps fiber, and my experiences will differ from others, but this works better than any other connected device we have. Some specifics I'd like to touch on:1. Packaging. It's easy to get into, it's very well designed. I wouldn't normally sign the praises of boxes and bubble wrap, but they did a good job here. You won't need kitchen shears, and box cutters to get to the goodies inside.2. Connection. Took me about a minute, (I had to reroute a power strip so the included USB power supply cable would reach.3. Setup. It came preconfigured for our account, and other than selecting our language, and connecting to our network, there was nothing else that needed to be done, (other than installing apps, which I will get to).4. Installing apps, like Netflix, and Vevo. Quick, and easy. Netflix didn't even require that I run back and forth to my computer to get/input a device specific code. I just entered user ID, and PW, and it was up and running.5. There have been several reviews of the firestick running hot, or not connecting to it's remote. Mine runs pretty cool...barely warm, and has had no problem with syncing with the included remote. I ran my firestick for several hours playing 1080P HD movies, it remained cool. I swapped batteries in and out of my remote several times, and it has never failed to sync with the firestick.6. Alexa. If I were to deduct anything from this review, this is where it would happen. I didn't, as I'm not yet fully familiar with the device, and any complaints I might have might very well be because I've not yet fully explored Alexa's functionality. Initial impression is that it does not understand simple phrases that it should....like &#34;Home&#34;, or &#34;Go Home&#34;. There does not seem to be a way to launch Netflix so that we can select from our saved profiles. I'm still learning though, and won't take away a star because of a possible ID-10-T error.Overall, this is a product worth a five star review.",5,232,positive,0.9057947993278503,0.9057947993278503,0.08096589893102646,0.013239273801445961,0.8926,7,2320,0,1
What should be a easy 4 star or perhaps better is a single star ...,"Ok, I will admit and stand corrected, the Browser option to use YouTube through the Fire Stick's etc is actually pretty decent, it adds another step to access Youtube that is the Browser and voila it's there just like it would have been with the Fire Stick Now what remains to be seen is if Google decides to shut down those access points as well???I'm still pleased with my Roku purchase, and will if the need arises replace the other Fire Sticks's I have with Roku rather than to be used as a pawn in the BIG sandbox where Google and Amazon are dickering like little grade school kids, the big difference is they are taking our money and and showing little regard for those of us who have helped them earn Billions!!!!!!For those who haven't purchased or are considering, YouTube is no longer available on the firestick you now get the sleazy work around through a browser, which remains to be seen if Google shuts those downSave yourself the grief, purchased a Roku at Sam's club yesterday, first off the remote is far superior you have tv control for volume and off and on.Secondly they're is no YouTube BS it's there as well as all the other streaming apps including Amazon.It's faster and seems to connect to WiFi with a better signal.As for Amazon, everything under the sun doesn't doesn't mean picking and choosing merchandise, I think that's false advertising as well when I bought the 5 sticks YouTube was part of the package, I think Amazon should buy them back.Simply put, this is why the government regulates BIG biz cause they use their size and clout to screw the consumer over in the end and can't play like big children in the same box.What should be a easy 4 star or perhaps better is a single star because of the typical BS associated with BIG companies aren't happy making Billions and argue over who is and isn't doing the other justice.Before you buy, beware it would appear YouTube will not be available January of 18, for me after buying several cancelling my DirecTV service I thought I'd have all my entertainment wrapped up on a little stick behind the TV.If YouTube is part of your viewing regime, might want to look elsewhere, if something changes I'll gladly repost a new review, otherwise it's pretty crappy the word doesn't get out much before the service doesn't work, Good Job Amazon and Google.....",5,233,positive,0.7584830522537231,0.7584830522537231,0.22206807136535645,0.019448844715952873,0.739,5,2333,0,1
UPDATED REVIEW: good little cable-cutter's streaming device,"UPDATED REVIEW: A gentleman from Amazon's Customer Service team called regarding my original review- kinda nice knowing Amazon stands behind Fire Stick the way they do with their Kindles. To make a long story short, he gave some advice and I followed it. I performed a factory reset, started with a fresh connection, and voila! It's working considerably better. So...Is this the best device ever? No. But is it a great device at a low cost with a good feature-set that offers a rich cable-cutter experience? Absolutely. And is it worth the full price? Yes. Yes it most certainly is. The fact I got mine on Prime Day for one half the normal price just puts an even bigger smile on my face.OLD REVIEW: I purchased this latest-generation Firestick on PrimeDay with the anticipation of having a nifty device for when I travel that enables me to use hotel TVs to watch what I want without a lot of headaches. Mind you, I &#34;cut the cable&#34; 11 years ago, using XBMC and my 1st gen XBOX, then later jumping to Roku devices and various PCs since. So I can honestly say I'm very underwhelmed. I spend more time rebooting my Firestick than watching it. It locks up every single time when I &#34;power it up&#34;- and the sad thing is I have yet to bring it on the road. I don't have a frame of reference other than my Roku, Roku 2, Roku 3, etc- and while the Roku updates sometimes have bugs, I can watch shows with confidence. My current primary TV has both the Firestick and a Roku Express plugged in, and the Firestick- while nifty with Alexa- locks up and crashes regularly, and when turning the TV on, I usually have to reboot the Firestick 2 or 3 times. If I had been stuck paying full price, I'd be all about a refund, or at the least a replacement. Since I paid PrimeDay price, I'll monitor another couple weeks, and if it keeps up this erratic behavior, I'll be returning for a refund.The bottom Line: I cannot in good faith recommend the Firestick at full price or recommend it it as an alternative to the more-reliable Roku- especially when the Firestick has the power and financial backing of Amazon behind it. I expect more for the money.For those who are on the fence- if you can pick one up on sale and already have another streaming device, give it a shot- it IS worth $20.",5,234,positive,0.9412083625793457,0.9412083625793457,0.0521901473402977,0.006601519417017698,0.9346,7,2284,0,1
What’s there not to like?? The future of television technology.,"What can I say?? Amazon is taking over! I just love my Amazon products. I now have a fire stick on every televisions I own. I also have given them as gifts. The set up is seemless if you already have an Amazon account. As soon as I plugged it in, it started and transferred my account to it without having to re entering all my information on every one I install. The voice remote is something I can’t do without.l either. All my old fire sticks are being replaced in my home due to wanting the voice activation. It is great for elderly peeps. Just say what you want to watch and it will find it for you. Another option I love, is the ability to add your Apps that need subscriptions. Such as Showtime, HBO, Gaia, etc. the fire stick allows you to order the subscription and charge your amazon account instead of having to log into each app individually.It was becoming a real pain to have different app accounts and all of them having your credit information. This way Amazon makes it so simple to add and delete apps all on Amazon. Billing is simple with everything on Amazon charged to whatever payment options you have on file. I got rid of all my Apple TV and Roku for this very reason. No more codes to enter. You can’t go wrong with the fire stick. It’s an everything in one unit device. I order my Amazon items from the fire stick also. For friends and family, I will keep buying them as gifts. Also, they are linked to all your amazon products that are linked to your account, like show, echo, etcFor the money, you can’t beat it. I have been without cable now for five years and I only put the apps that have the programs I like to watch. It’s really cheaper than cable/satellite hands down. And everything on cable you can access using their Apps. Thanks Amazon for such great products. There are too many good things to mention. One more thing to mention, the Bluetooth capability is awesome too. I connect my headphones at night to allow my spouse to sleep without noise from the tv. The only thing i would suggest is having the power cord longer. It’s hard to plug in if your outlet is more than four feet away. It also uses the HDMI port to connect to the tv or laptop. The size makes it nice to pack and take on vacation or business trips. It would be nice if it can be powered by batteries. Thanks again Amazon!!",5,235,positive,0.9155468940734863,0.9155468940734863,0.06472122669219971,0.019731825217604637,0.8958,5,2329,0,1
BRILLIANT INVESTMENT FOR YOUR TELEVISION!,"I have been using this Fire TV Stick for months now and all I have to say is, its the best investment iv'e had in my tv in such a long time.Here are the reasons why it is a great investment: - No longer have to worry about a cable bill or satellite tv bill, yearly contracts, cable boxes and all that junk ever again. Just plug into your USB in the back of your tv, and or anywhere where you can put a USB stick, and turn on. You literally have complete control over everything you watch. - You can pick and choose what you want to spend on apps and most are free to use (like CNN, NBC news, Cartoon Network and a few more).Sling Tv, or more recently, DirectTv App are good apps if you want a cluster of all cable channels, like AMC and such. Yes, some apps you do have to pay for, like Hulu and Netflix, but with what you get on both those, it still works out to be cheaper then Cable tv.Personally I use Sling tv, it's cheap and there is no contract, and even better it has all the channels I watch on regular cable, just with out all the other stuff that you don't watch. You can add certain channels if you like with your Sling tv, like Comedy, Sports and such, and then take them of when your done.Apps I have on my fire stick is, Amazon Prime (paid for one year, $99), Sling Blue ($25 per month, streaming on three devices at once). - The Alexa voice remote is fantastic! and easy to use, especially when you are looking for something, you don't have to go through all the apps looking for it, does it for you.It does take a little to get used to, especially if you are very used to cable tv, like AT&T U-verse and such, where you just turn it on and there is all your channels. BUT...you most certainly do get used to it after a few days or like me about a week or two lol!IF you don't like contracts, paying a Sh**t ton monthly on cable tv, and willing to learn and be patient with getting used to something like this, I would highly recommend it. Being a single mother, I like to have certain luxuries in life, like having tv shows I like to watch, and simply can not afford a high a$$ bill each month, wondering how on earth did it get to that much when I barely even have the tv on, the fire stick to me is fantastic and affordable.",5,236,positive,0.9693147540092468,0.9693147540092468,0.02444279193878174,0.006242456380277872,0.9631,0,2243,0,1
"Works great with Direct TV now, and free same day delivery","Amazon is freaky fast!! I’ll get to that.Amazon prime is great for streaming. We have been cord cutters for a long time now. We relied on a smart tv, Xbox one, and an Android box for our TV watching. The Android box thing is just about over. So we decided to partially re-cord, with Direct TV now (internet based TV, not satellite, there is no dish involved). We can get 60 channels for a good price. Direct TV will even throw in a free compatible streaming device. (In 2 or 3 weeks)Well none of our current devices work with DTVnow, and we were falling behind on our super hero shows on the CW. So I saw the Amazon fire stick with free same day shipping, ON A SUNDAY, seriously!!! I had to buy this, just to see how same day, Sunday worked out. I ordered the fire stick Sunday morning about 10ish. Sunday afternoon an Amazon delivery driver was walking up my driveway around 4:30ish. How is this even possible?!?! Amazon is crazy good at customer service!!So I throw the fire stick in our Vizio smart tv. Which really is not all that smart. It’s a few years old, and has always had internet connection issues. I should have put a fire stick in it years ago.The fire stick came loaded with a setup video, and a helpful tutor. I went through the setup quickly and loaded my TV apps, including Direct TV now.Within a few minutes I was streaming Episode IV of Earth X from DC Legends of tomorrow for my family via DTVnow, with commercials. Now we could have watched it on KODI, with out commercials. But the stream would have been all glitchy, and rather crummy. It would have been low definition. The fire stick provided smooth, glitch free, HD viewing of our favorite CW show. Well technically that would be Flash, then Arrow, then Legends, but Earth X was a cross over 4 part series, from those three shows, and it started with Supergirl.I am still getting used to the fire stick and the Alexa remote, so I’ll have to update my review with all of those details.If you are in need of a great streaming device, to replace something that is not working so well anymore, and you need it fast, you can not beat Amazon’s same day shipping. It’s worth the price of admission just for that!!I wish Amazon offered a TV package similar to DTVnow or Hulu plus. It would be great to keep it all in one.",5,237,positive,0.9290839433670044,0.9290839433670044,0.06380389630794525,0.007112143095582724,0.922,4,2290,0,1
One of the best decisions of my life!,"Getting the Fire TV stick and cutting the cord from cable is one of the best decisions of my life. The product itself is incredibly easy to use. 1. Take the Fire TV stick out of the box 2.) find your HDMI port(s) on the back of your TV 3.) plug in the FIre stick 4.) allow it to find your WiFi network and login and connect 5.) press the home button on the Fire TV stick and let it synch up to your TV and voila, you're in business! Navigation on the device is pretty much like an iPod with a directional &#34;wheel&#34; and only 6 buttons needed to get you moving through your apps. The content is delivered in a Netflix-like format with &#34;boxes&#34; you select to choose which app you'd like to watch. One of our favorite features is the Alexa voice control. We use it to request music, movies, get local forecasts, find out sports scores, etc. It's fun to use and makes navigating that much easier.As far as channel/content availability, I had done some analysis on the cable channels we actually watched out of all those offered. I found we had about 73 unique channels offered, by the time you got rid of duplicates (I don't care if that means some were HD versions of the others...the content doesn't change just because it's in HD!) Of those, I found we watched about 40 on a sometimes to regular basis (some of those being sports channels which are seasonal). Between the content we receive as Amazon Prime customers, the channels we get with Sling TV and HBO Now and Netflix, plus a digital antenna to pick up local stuff, there isn't a single channel missing from our current lineup. In fact, we've actually got a ffew others we didn't have before that we really like (such as AXS TV which has concerts, interviews with musicians, etc. that we enjoy). Adding up the monthly cost of Prime, Prime Music, Sling and HBO Now, we are still $50 a month cheaper for TV service than we were with cable. Plus now we've got channels we actually watch and aren't paying for 100 more that we couldn't care less about.If you're considering making this move I encourage you to do so...you won't be sorry! It was so liberating calling TimeWarner/Spectrum/whatever the call themselves at this very moment to ask them how to return our equipment because we didn't need them any longer!",5,238,positive,0.9539827704429626,0.9539827704429626,0.04083237424492836,0.005184834823012352,0.9488,0,2280,0,1
Love my Firestick! Buh-bye overpriced Comcast!,"I cancelled my over-priced, ($125+) bloated Comcast cable package after receiving an email from Amazon reminding me that my Prime membership included movies, TV shows etc. I was never happy with Comcast: I had the top-of-the-line package, yet it didn't include shows/movies I wanted to watch: so I wound up paying $2.99 per episode or varying prices for movies &#34;on demand.&#34; Thumbs down. In addition, Comcast has a monopoly in my rural area. (I live on the side of a mountain in the middle of nowhere.)I'm so happy with Firestick! The user interface is set up to make it easy to discover delightful new things to watch via your TV: like the Deutsche Welle videos (short, well-crafted newsy videos on interesting subjects). And I can't believe Alexa is built in. I often ask for the &#34;weather&#34; and &#34;news&#34; just so I can have the fun of using Alexa. And I love asking Alexa to play specific music.The Firestick has given me control over what I want in the form of entertainment -- that feeling is a value add. I also signed up for a SlingTV trial, which enables me to watch TV shows live. So I didn't miss the finale of &#34;The Strain&#34; on FX. (Yay.) (Note: Your Firestick comes with a generous amount of free SlingTV - an extended trial. So wait until you receive your Firestick to sign up for Sling.)Note: On the second day of using Firestick I experienced some buffering and a message displayed indicating that I had inadequate bandwidth. I couldn't watch anything at all. After googling around I found a helpful post by a techie on this issue. Seems Comcast, back at their Skyrim headquarters, were throttling back my Internet speed (as ISPs are wont to do). Instead of the top line speed I'm paying for, I was throttled down to 23 Mbps. (Hmnn, I wonder if they can detect defecting users starting to stream from Amazon?) This throttling is something ISPs sometimes do to put you on a data diet, particularly at the end of the month. I signed up for something called IPVanish, which makes it look like my ISP is in California, instead of New England, and 'poof' - no more buffering issues, and my speed tripled.So my line-up now is: Firestick + SlingTV + IPVanish. (My only regret is not having done this when Firestick came out.)",5,239,negative,0.8730258941650391,0.011614612303674221,0.11535944789648056,0.8730258941650391,-0.8614,0,2257,1,0
My Fire Stick won't connect and says: connected with problems,"Ok so I love my Fire stick, but I just wanted to post something about an issue I encountered with it and was unable to find an answer to online- anywhere. I came home from a week vacation, and got an error message saying it was not connecting to the internet. When I checked the connection in the settings, it said 'connected with problems'- and I had no other recourse, or settings to do anything about it.So if you go online, the community will tell you to disconnect it. I disconnected it about 15 times, by first unplugging, then pushing on the little home/house button allowing me to restart, then unplugging the actual HDMI cable. You name all the different ways to disconnect it, I did it, and nothing worked.So I went to option B in the community, which said to restart your router, but I knew it wasn't a router issue since all my other devices were connected and worked fine. I still thought I would try- it did not do a thing for me.I continued to research online, and it seemed the problem was I had purchased one of those plugs you can control thought your Alexa, to turn on and off an unrelated device near by, and that this could create interferences. Apparently the Fire works on you 5 GHz, and if another 2.4 GHz is near by, it creates issues- which those little plugs are. So I tried to move the online plug further away to see if that would fix it... nothing.At this point, I am 2 days into my problem, and no way near a fix, and there is nothing online to help me. From what I had read over the two days of searching, when you go on vacation and don't put your device on SLEEP by pushing SLEEP after you hit the Home button for 6-8 seconds- you can end up in this situation. For most people, they can fix it by restarting their fire and/or router. Nothing worked for me, SO here is the fix. If you have another TV with another HDMI port or another Fire connected, bring the one that is NOT connecting to the working location, and it will connect automatically. Once connected, unplug it, and replug it in the location that was causing you trouble, and TA-DA! It works again. And next time you go on vaca, don't forget to set your Fire on Sleep Mode (Push Home button a long time) before your turn off your TV.",5,240,negative,0.5938612818717957,0.10279823839664459,0.30334046483039856,0.5938612818717957,-0.4911,2,2229,1,0
Performs perfectly using Wi-Fi hotspot!,"I've hesitated to purchase a stick for a very long time, thinking it would not work in my situation. I finally broke down & bought one on Cyber Monday & boy, why did I wait so long? I'm in a rural area with no internet or cable, other than satellite. Satellite doesn't work for me either - too many trees, no signal. I am using an AT&T Velocity wi-fi hotspot device for my internet, with an 8-device maximum. The Fire TV Stick performs beautifully! I typically have 5 devices running - an Echo, Echo Plus, Fire HD8 Tablet, Cell (Samsung Galazy) & the Fire Stick - and get this, on ONE BAR of service! Amazing! I also have a Phillips Hue A19 smart bulb connected to the Echo Plus, but it doesn't show up as a device on wi-fi, so it must connect directly to the Echo Plus built-in hub. (My first smart home item). I rely heavily on reviews, so hopefully this review will help those with internet challenges. The stick does work with a wi-fi hotspot, even with 4 other devices connected & one bar of service! Occasionally, I do have issues with slow connection, but I don't believe that has anything to do with the Stick, but rather my AT&T wi-fi service. It will usually correct itself in 20-30 minutes. I'm sure it's just a signal issue & comes with the territory in a rural area. The stick was breeze to set up & I also really like the simplicity of the remote--no fumbling around with a gazillion buttons in the dark. And Alexa voice control is just awesome & fun as well. Really great to be able to watch movies on the flat screen now, rather than on a tablet. I can't say if the stick will work properly using a cell phone as the hot spot as I haven't tried that. My cell phone service inside my house is iffy, so I usually have it connected to wi-fi, which gives me better service. Oh, & I do turn off the Fire stick when not in use -- connected to a surge protector, so I just cut the power so it doesn't count as a device on my wi-fi. I am totally happy with the Fire TV Stick & highly recommend. Everyone's situation can be different, but if you want to try using the Fire Stick with a wi-fi hot spot or you cell, I would say go for it, give it a try, it works great for me. I figure if it doesn't work out, you can always return it.",5,241,negative,0.6866462826728821,0.05597745254635811,0.2573763430118561,0.6866462826728821,-0.6307,4,2240,1,0
"I was a bit hesitant at first since I live in a rural area where internet speeds aren't the greatest, its rated at 3mbps","I decided to cancel my satellite tv service after 10 years. My bill eventually climbed from the normal $60ish/month to over $100 when all of my credits expired. Retention dept wouldn't offer me enough to stay with their service so I fired them! I bought the fire stick and ordered prime. I was a bit hesitant at first since I live in a rural area where internet speeds aren't the greatest, its rated at 3mbps. And speed tests back this up. I was most worried about buffering issues. My worries were put to rest immediately. In the two weeks I have had the fire stick, I have yet to have any program on prime, buffer, ever! And the most amazing thing is the picture quality is 1080, my satellite service was only 720. For the price of the fire stick coupled with prime for a year, the total cost less than a 1 1/2 months of satellite service. Without all of the commercials.Edit: I've been using the fire stick for about 2 months now. I think its the best thing I bought in a long time. Again, my internet speeds are only 3 mbps and the stick works flawlessly. I also have the latest roku streaming stick which I was given. There is no comparison between the two, the fire stick is way faster when scrolling thru menus, etc. And the voice remote on alexa kicks butt over the roku's clicking the arrows to manually type in any kind of search. There is still the issue of having to unplug the fire stick from time to time to get it to start up, that mainly happens when the fire stick sits for extended periods of non use. But overall, if my stick broke tomorrow, I would replace in a second without any regret.The only slight issue with the fire stick I've had, is about once a week the stick wont wake-up when turning on the tv and pressing the home button on the stick. Pressing the fire sticks home button is suppose to wake it up. So I have had to un-plug the stick and plug it back in to get it started. This could be a hassle if the tv's hdmi port isnt easily available. I ordered a longer hdmi extension cable for a few bucks to make it easier to reboot if necessary. Also so I could have easier access to the stick so I can put it a different tv in my house.",5,242,negative,0.7823216915130615,0.015561165288090706,0.20211713016033173,0.7823216915130615,-0.7668,4,2164,1,0
Fast. Nice interface.,"My TV worked fine, but it wasn't a smart TV. I purchased a Sony Blu-ray player with smart capabilities, but it was slow and clunky and often crashed. I endured this for several years thinking that this was normal smart capability. I thought the poor performance might be do to the lousy internet we have were I live. Hoping it might help, I was resigned to buying a smart TV, but then I decided to give Fire TV Stick a shot. I was able to purchase it for only $24.99 which pretty much finalized my decision. The problem was NOT my internet.Setting up the Fire TV Stick was extremely easy. The interface works great and the response time is phenomenal - even with the lousy internet we have living in a rural area. The remote is smaller than expected and very basic, but has all the buttons you need plus the voice control. I dozed off while watching a move from Amazon Prime. I press the microphone button and said, &#34;rewind 30 minutes&#34;. Bam! The movie picked up 30 minutes earlier. I'm very happy to say that the remote does not have any of those dedicated buttons that you often hit accidentally and they send you off to Netflix or where ever causing you to spend ten minutes navigating back to where you were.I installed the PLEX app on the Fire TV Stick (only took a minute) and access movies stored on my laptop which runs the PLEX Media Server. This works great too. This to has a beautiful interface. I get cover graphics for each movie plus a synopsis - all pulled from the net. So much better than casting movies to my TV through my 'smart' Blu-ray player.I still have some playing to do with this new toy, but so far I am pleasantly surprised and very happy with it. I highly recommend it if you don't already have a smart TV or your unsatisfied with its smart performance. What are you waiting for?I only use Fire TV Stick to access movies via Amazon Prime (works great) and movies stored on my laptop. I installed the PLEX app on the Stick (only took a minute) and run the PLEX Media Server on my laptop. This works great too. Much better than having to cast movies from my laptop to my Blu-ray player.",5,243,negative,0.6756157875061035,0.049439478665590286,0.2749447822570801,0.6756157875061035,-0.6262,4,2121,1,0
I love this thing but...,"it wasn't love at first sight. The makers of electronics seem to think the user knows a lot more than I do and send minimum instructions of how to set them up. I'm in my 70's and don't have any kids or grand kids nearby that I can call to come over and set stuff like this up for me. I read the instructions, put the parts together, and plugged it into one of the HDMI ports on my TV. I selected that input and ....nothing. A setup screen is supposed to come up when the unit is powered up but all I had was a blank screen so I tried another port but the result was the same. I went back to the port I have my DVR plugged into while I went online to look for some help. I didn't find any. I unplugged everything and plugged back in again and...nothing. After much cursing and throwing my hands up I took a break and set up my Echo Dot. After more cursing I got it going and quit while I was ahead.After a great supper, I did prepare it myself, and a couple of glasses of wine my blood pressure was back to normal and I was relaxed so I decided to try the Fire TV Stick again. I read the instructions again, laid them aside, and unplugged everything, plugged it all back together, and....nothing. So it was back to cursing and throwing my hands in the air and to top things off I couldn't find the instructions I just had in my hands, maybe it was the wine. The one thing I did differently this time was I didn't go back to the port my DVR was on. While I was searching for the instructions, which I haven't found to this day, the set up screen came up. I entered my Amazon account information and I was connected. The first thing it had me do was download some Apps. I have a Netflix account so that was the first one I selected. There are loads to choose from and you can go back later if you want to. I don't know if it's normal or my Sony is different but when I select the port the Fire TV Stick is plugged into nothing happens for several seconds, making me think that it isn't working, but all I have to do is be patient and it comes up. Now I can watch Netflix and Amazon videos on the big screen instead of my computer. Happy times are here again.",5,244,negative,0.567608118057251,0.0317080095410347,0.40068382024765015,0.567608118057251,-0.5359,6,2155,1,0
"The Amazon Fire TV Stick is easy to use, portable, and affordable.","I purchased the Amazon Fire stick while shopping on black Friday. My purchased included the Fire Stick, Alexa voice remote, power adapter, 2 AAA batteries, and an HDMI extender. I have been a loyal Apple TV user for years, but after my recent purchase of the Fire Stick I don't think I'll ever go back. It is cheaper and easier to navigate than my Apple TV was. It has a better connection and better quality picture no matter the TV or where I am. The Amazon Fire TV Stick is easy to use, portable, and affordable.Ideal UserThe Fire Stick is ideal for people who do not have a smart TV, but have access to high speed internet. It is perfect for people who wishes to access streaming services such as Netflix, Hulu, or Amazon Prime. It makes cable obsolete with access to apps like Sling TV, HBO, and CNN.Easy to useIt is easy to navigate from start to finish. You do not to be tech savvy to use this device. They give you step by step instructions so you are streaming your favorite shows and movies in no time. First you plug your fire stick into your TV’s HDMI port. When it turns on it will ask you to connect to your wireless internet. It will then take you to your home screen and you are ready to download your favorite applications.PortableYou don’t need to buy multiple devices for each room any longer. The Fire Stick is very portable room to room, house to house, and even hotel to hotel while on vacation. It also comes with an HDMI extender to improve your Wi-Fi connection, that works very well.FeaturesAnother great feature of this device is Alexa. Alexa is an intelligent personal assistant designed by Amazon. She can do anything from playing your favorite music, answer a question you are unsure of, and even order you a pizza. It can do just about everything the Echo and Echo dot can do without buying an extra device.The Fire Stick is cheaper than buying a smart TV, cable subscription, and an Apple TV. It has better connection and picture than any streaming device I have ever used. It is affordable and unbelievably easy to navigate. Every household could use one.",5,245,positive,0.8452159762382507,0.8452159762382507,0.1478460729122162,0.0069379061460494995,0.8383,4,2087,0,1
Glad I got Fire Sticks- good results on 802.11ac,"I purchased two for our home and set them up in a few hours- I bought a HD 8 Fire tablet last month and I liked the amazon interface so much, that I sprung for Fire Sticks- even with a 10 day wait to get them .Compared to my Roku3, the Fire Stick has a superior picture and much better voice search. . Both of them (and my Roku) are set up on the 5ghz Wifi ac band on my router. There is entirely too much signal pollution from neighbor's wifi routers to use 2.4ghz channels and expect to have good results. I did a scanner check in my neighborhood last year and I have over 20 strong SSIDs on 802.11n. I found that setting up my 2.4ghz router for 802.11g only, not on the 802.11n protocol, solved all my computer Wifi problems. I can still get 30mbs download speeds on 802.11g, with no more download hangups! Everyone in my area seems to be on 802.11n ( that is how they come setup) and most are using 2 channel mode for double bandwidth, which only exacerbates the signal crowding for all. If you are having trouble with your Fire Stick, then try running inSSIDer program and see if your router isn't on the same channel as a strong neighbor's signal. - or maybe it's your own wifi printer! Getting good streaming video, might entail going into your router menu to set a fixed channel that doesn't have interference.We cancelled our Comcast cable last month and I put up a good outside antenna. We have 2 HD Tivos for recording OTA live TV and the Fire Sticks for streaming video. I can actually afford to get a movie channel now! . Amazon Prime, Netflix, one movie channel and live TV on our Tivo DVRs gives us more than I had on cable and I'm not paying for sports channels that I never watched. I would also say that 10% of my streaming content comes from Youtube., with an occasional oldie movie on the side loaded TerrariumTV app.One final note, the wallpaper images are gorgeous. I find it restful to just let the Fire Stick go into pause mode, while I am on my laptop or reading a book. I am not done with Roku- I am getting a new 2017 model, TCL Roku TV next month, so I can get 4K HDR streaming content-",5,246,positive,0.8135458827018738,0.8135458827018738,0.1720186471939087,0.014435511082410812,0.7991,0,2114,0,1
$40 gives you Apple TV performance,"I've owned many set top boxes and media players over the last 4 years and this one is the best one in terms of value and performance I have ever owned. The Fire TV Stick is fast. Like buttery smooth when you are zipping around the interface there is almost no delay when you click a button and that action is done on the Fire TV.The Fire TV Stick with Alexa makes my old Roku HD 1080p look slow and outdated. I got the Roku back in 2012 and at the time it was a great value in a small emerging streaming market, but now it is slow. Pressing a button on my Roku by comparison takes a few seconds before the device responds to the input.I enjoy the build quality of the remote. It has clicky responsive buttons that have a nice crisp feel when pressing them. My favorite thing about the remote is the Alexa integration. The voice recognition is amazing and makes it great to find things quickly on the Fire TV.The Fire TV supports my favorite apps ESPN, YouTube, and FoxSportsGo. These apps are all super smooth and if you are upgrading from an old streaming box you will notice the fast animations that these third party apps have. The ESPN app is very polished and supports replay options and live streaming options perfect if you a cable subscription you can use it to watch your favorite sports.The price for the Fire TV is amazing to say the least. The Fire TV Stick is easily as fast and responsive as Apple's Apple TV or other streaming devices. You get this zippy performance for just $40, which is still something I think about a lot. The performance of a $100 machine is easily now accessible in a compact $40 package. The Fire TV Stick does 1080p which is the standard for HD TVs right now. The normal Fire TV, the $90 box, can support 4K, so if you need to have an Ultra HD streamer you'll need to step up to that model.I can't say this any clearer. If you are hesitant on buying this streamer don't be. It is worth the $40 and then some with its fast user interface and Alexa integration. Amazon is clearly on the top of the streaming market with this new Fire TV Stick.",5,247,positive,0.9539930820465088,0.9539930820465088,0.038581181317567825,0.00742572033777833,0.9466,4,2081,0,1
"""This TV is on FIre.... ""  (sang like Alicia Key's song)","I don't know what took me so long to get this product ...actually I do know.. I wanted to hear from everyone before I committed. It's not for cost... it's more for expediency. I am not tech savvy..don't have a lot of time to fuss with something and I definitely am not the type to package things back up and send it back for a refund... So after my disastrous attempt with the Chrome Stick ($35 and it would not sync with my tv and wasted an hour of my life and I didn't bother to return it to Best Buy) I took my time, read some reviews and was 80% sure I wanted to buy this product.... I got this product for an incredible price of $29.99 within 3 days. I lucked out.. I actually clicked on an Amazon email which was very unlike me, I opted for the one-click check out button before I changed my mind... you know how you overthink a purchase... ? yea you do... Just buy this one. I would pay more for this product. It was so easy to install it was ridiculous. The voice command acuity is so good, it's ridiculous. It's so affordable it's ridiculous. First class packaging and instructions and it came with batteries! So for tech savvy people, read the tech savvy reviews... there are a lot of them... I don't know who KODI is but I'm going to explore that when my tech savvy friend comes over.. btw, my tv is far from smart but I'd call it &#34;slightly unaware&#34;. So my tv was Peter Parker turned Spiderman and the radioactive spider bite was the Amazon Fire TV Stick. So far I've been able to access Amazon Videos, Amazon Music, Netflix/HBOGO/Showtime Anytime/Bravo/AMC/Hulu (subscription required)/ and a bunch of other stuff I have yet to explore. great product.. seemed to have even improved the tv image... Alexa makes Siri seem mentally challenged. You guys that complain about the connectivity due to wifi, please, get high level wifi... why wouldn't you. No issues for me there as I opt for the most expensive and fastest wifi I can get so that the world is at my fingertips. I've been playing around for a month.. so far so great and I hope to not retract any part of my enthusiastic review. Thanks a lot Amazon!",5,248,negative,0.8186336159706116,0.018778221681714058,0.16258814930915833,0.8186336159706116,-0.7999,0,2127,1,0
I'm annoyed by all the technology for interface everything as usually ...,"When I installed it I couldn't believe I hadn't gotten one years earlier. I'm annoyed by all the technology for interface everything as usually seems expensive and hard to negotiate AND will become obsolete when things like ports change -- e.g. USB-A versus USB-C, cords, and probably platforms (Android, whatever)I plugged into the HDMI port at the back of my not new flatscreen tv. (2009 maybe?). I expected a long, long process of getting it to recongize this or that and interface and it just worked instantly BOOM. Negotiate Netflix and Hulu and Prime back and forth with out having to download apps -- you can download countless but I don't need or bother.There is one thing I hope they fix. In the platform when you negotiate moving from thing to thing -- hulu to netflix say -- you can search in Prime and it will show you if the show or moving is available on Netflix and Hulu. SOmetimes what comes up is an auto rental (which you can do too and I suppose that's a big feature for people who do that). Anyway, sometimes it asks for you to pay when I already have access to the media for freeIt now has a Webbrowser (when this feature is on a TV, the TV is a lot more expensive and i'm sure the webprowsers suck). I tried the webbrowser once and it worked fine but I wouldn't ever really use it that way. But for people who will, maybe I'd give the browser a 5 out of 10, but like I said I suspect it will be way better than the TV versions.I got on one of those holiday sales where they drop the price a third -- I think 39$. So I cannot tell you how i am amazed how this works. 5 years ago havin all these things together would probably cost $1000 with a device to do this part and other to do that part and so on.There was ONE creepy thing. I bought one for a friend as a gift and when I was at her house setting it up, it immediately started up with my name -- i.e., addressed me. I looked down at myself like &#34;Can it see me?!&#34; Obviously they programmed it before sending it to me somehow through the packaging. Just seemed a little Big Brother",5,249,negative,0.7377243638038635,0.03521900251507759,0.2270565927028656,0.7377243638038635,-0.7025,0,2064,1,0
